<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-AFRICA-VICTIMS-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR VICTIMS' KIN, THE BAD NEWS IS SUDDEN AND SHOCKING  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING for all needing)  
 (SUBS to refine, add info)   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Friday mail brought a flimsy letter from Africa to the home
of Delbert and Mary Olds in Panama City, Fla. It was from their
daughter, Sherry, and inside the envelope was a Post-It sticker. It
read, ``Will E-mail you soon.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday evening, two Air Force officers arrived with another
letter. It informed the family that Sherry Lynn Olds, a senior
master sergeant with the Air Force, had died earlier in the day
after a terrorist bomb exploded outside the U.S. Embassy in
Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a beautiful girl,'' said Pat Casey, the victim's aunt,
who spoke for the parents. ``She was very special to her parents.
It is a devastating loss to them.''
</P>
<P>
   For the families of the victims in various parts of the country,
there was no good way to learn the bad news. The phone rang before
sunrise at Bonnie Hobson's home in Lamar, Mo. Her son, Sgt. Kenneth
R. Hobson, Jr., 27, had been killed. Her daughter-in-law, Debbie,
was calling from Nairobi, sobbing uncontrollably.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the telephone call that did not come that worried friends
and relatives of Molly Huckaby Hardy, 51, a State Department
employee from Valdosta, Ga. They had seen the bombings on
television. ``When we hadn't heard from her, we knew something had
happened,'' said Marsha Bates, a childhood friend of Ms. Hardy's.
``If she could have crawled to a phone, she would have let us know
she was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The American death toll was not yet clear, but by Saturday
night, the State Department had identified five of the victims.
They are Master Sergeant Olds; Hobson; Ms. Hardy; Sgt. Jesse N.
Aliganga, 21; a Marine from Tallahassee, Fla.; and Arlene Kirk, 50,
a Defense Department budget officer who had just returned to
Nairobi from home leave in South Bend, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department also released the names of four other
Americans killed: Prabhi Kavaler and Michelle O'Connor of the
General Services office; Tom Shah, an employee of the political
section; and Jean Dalizu, an employee of the Defense Attache's
office. The Associated Press added two more: Jay Bartley, son of
Consul General Julian Bartley, and Louise Martin of Atlanta, an
employee of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martin worked for the health agency in Kenya with her
husband, Douglas Klaucke. She would have turned 46 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Bryson of Lawrenceville, Ga., said of Ms. Martin, her
sister: ``I still don't believe it's real. She died in a country
she loved, she died doing the things she liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kirk and her husband, Robert, 50, a project development
officer for the U.S. Agency for International Development, had
planned to extend their stay at home for several days, said Ms.
Kirk's sister, Katherine Wright, from South Bend.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Kirk worried that her bosses wanted her back to work
sooner, her sister said, so the couple and their 14-year-old son,
Robbie Jr., flew back, arriving in Nairobi early Friday morning.
``They were both exhausted,'' Ms. Wright said. ``She went home and
then was rushing to get to work. She went to work late. We think
she went into work just before the bomb went off.''
</P>
<P>
   During her six weeks in South Bend, Ms. Kirk cared for her
elderly parents, Frederick Arthur, 84, and Mary, 83. ``She was busy
trying to get them enrolled in some exercise classes,'' said Ms.
Wright. ``She took them to the doctor. Their health is not that
great.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of six children, Ms. Kirk met her husband at
Indiana University. After graduating from Indiana University
business school, they went to South Africa, where Kirk taught
democratic principles to township mayors. During the next 25 years,
they worked for the federal government in various positions in
Botswana and Egypt and, for the last three years, in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   The couple lost a young daughter, Kamilah, to cancer in 1992.
Their oldest child, Maisha, 23, attends Tuskegee University in
Alabama. Family members said the couple planned to move back to the
United States next year. ``It's a bitter pill to swallow,'' Ms.
Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   After a State Department career that spanned more than two
decades, including posts in Brazil and Laos, Ms. Hardy had told
friends and family that she also planned to return to the United
States, possibly next June, to work as an instructor for State
Department employees. Her childhood friend, Ms. Bates, described a
woman who loved the adventure of her job. Her family had recently
received letters and photographs of her remodeled home in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just loved being there, I think,'' Ms. Bates said. ``She
found it a beautiful place. Molly was fun-loving, just great _ an
intellectual that everybody liked.''
</P>
<P>
   While working in Laos in 1973, Ms. Hardy became pregnant, Ms.
Bates said. Like other civilian employees, she was ordered to
evacuate, and her only child, Brandi Plant, was later born in
Washington. Ms. Hardy and her former husband were later divorced.
Her last visit to Valdosta had come in April 1997 to attend the
funeral of her sister, who had died when her car collided with a
dump truck that had crossed the center line of the roadway.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, Ms. Hardy apparently had a potential brush
with danger. ``A plane went down in South Africa that Molly was
supposed to have been on,'' said Ms. Bates, noting that Ms. Hardy
ended up catching a different flight.
</P>
<P>
   While riding on the second flight, Ms. Hardy called to tell her
mother and daughter not to worry. When a similar call did not come
on Friday, her family feared for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeant Olds had returned to Nairobi in June after spending two
months in Birmingham, Ala., taking courses to qualify for a
promotion to become a chief master sergeant. Her aunt, Ms. Casey,
said that Sergeant Olds passed the test and was expected to receive
her promotion in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeant Olds had joined the Air Force out of high school,
following the footsteps of her father, who is now a retired civil
servant. Ms. Casey described her niece as a ``free spirit'' who had
also served in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   During her coursework in Alabama, Sergeant Olds also spent a
week with her family in Panama City, engaging in her favorite
hobby. ``Shopping,'' said her aunt with a gentle laugh. ``That
sounds very strange, but that was her favorite pastime.''
</P>
<P>
   On one shopping spree, Sergeant Olds purchased boxes of corn
meal and grits _ the ingredients of some of her favorite Southern
dishes _ and mailed them to her address in Nairobi. She often sent
her family presents of African jewelry, amber and carved wooden
games.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sergeant Olds, Hobson joined the military as a ticket to
see the world. ``He knew there was more to life out there, and he
was determined to see it,'' said his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in a modest blue house behind a sturdy old maple
tree, he was known as a talented and popular boy. He loved to
debate world affairs and play tennis, act in school plays, go
hiking, cook gourmet meals and paint.
</P>
<P>
   Hobson, the son of a Vietnam veteran, dreamed of retiring from
the Army at age 37, attending culinary school and then opening a
bed and breakfast, his mother said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
