<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PHONE-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC WORKERS ON STRIKE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thousands of workers at Bell Atlantic walked off the
job Sunday morning as the telephone company and two unions failed
to reach agreement before the workers' old contract expired at
12:01 Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The workers began their strike after a day of tense talks
between Bell Atlantic and the two unions, the Communications
Workers of America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers. The two sides voiced optimism Sunday morning that they
might still be able to reach an agreement on Sunday and thus keep
the strike very short and the disruption to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to keep negotiating,'' Jeffrey Miller, spokesman for
the communications workers said just after midnight. `` The talks
haven't really broken off. We just ran up against the deadline, and
our members are adamant that they're not going to work without a
contract. So therefore we're on strike. We hope to keep negotiating
and work out a settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The strike by 85,000 workers is not expected to disrupt normal
telephone service for Bell Atlantic's 26 million customers from
Maine to Virginia. But the strike will cause delays in reaching
directory assistance, in making operator-assisted calls, in
contacting business representatives and in having telephone service
repaired or new lines installed.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said the main sticking point was the union's
efforts to get Bell Atlantic to stop expanding its nonunion
subsidiaries and to stop moving work done by unionized workers into
those subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said: ``The main problem area remains that whole area of
the jobs of the future at Bell Atlantic and whether there's going
to be good high-skill high wage jobs or whether the jobs of the
future are going to be marginalized and substandard.''
</P>
<P>
   The union also said that shortly before midnight it reached a
tentative agreement with Bell South. The settlement, reached in
Atlanta, averted a strike that was scheduled to begin Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that the phone company workers have a long tradition
of walking out as soon as their contract expires, unless a new
agreement has already been negotiated. He said repair workers and
operators began picketing this morning at a Bell Atlantic building
at 40 West Street in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Phone company and union officials said that two sets of
negotiations were held Saturday in New York City and in the
Washington area. The negotiators have been seeking to reach a
single contract, although there will be some separate contract
language for employees who worked for Nynex and employees who
worked for Bell Atlantic, before the two companies merged.
</P>
<P>
   In attacking Bell Atlantic's growing use of nonunion operations,
officials in the communications workers union complain that
two-thirds of the new jobs added by Bell Atlantic over the past
three years have gone to nonunion workers, who are generally paid
less than the unionized workers. The nonunion workers do
telemarketing to sell phone company services, handle some accounts
and install advanced phone lines for Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   According to union officials, one of the company's nonunion
subsidiaries, Bell Atlantic Plus, based in Norfolk, Va., has 700
employees and is seeking an additional 1,400 employees. Union
officials said that Bell Atlantic had transferred some work done by
unionized workers to that new subsidiary, a move the union fears
will jeopardize the job security of union members.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic officials defend these new subsidiaries on the
ground that they have lower labor costs that unionized operations
</P>
<P>
   Other issues of contention include wages, Bell Atlantic's use of
forced overtime, its employing temporary workers and the terms of a
long-delayed financial package to encourage workers to take early
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   To step up pressure on the phone company, thousands of Bell
Atlantic workers staged a wildcat walkout for two-and-a-half hours
on Friday throughout New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, the communications workers reached a tentative
agreement with Southern New England Telecommunications, which
provides service to most of Connecticut, averting a strike against
SNET that was to begin today.
</P>
<P>
   In that contract, SNET agreed to give the 6,300 unionized
workers an 11 percent raise over the 32-month contract and to
eliminate any obligation for them to pay premiums toward their
health insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
