<HEADLINE>
(HLW)  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add new items, call attn to 1STLDs and NYT Page 1
changes)  
 (Eds., also filed in `v' category)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors, The New York Times moved the following stories on
Saturday for its Sunday editions in connection with the terrorist
attacks on the U.S. embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam:
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBINGS (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Volunteers continued a slow,
desperate effort Saturday to save people still trapped under tons
of rubble from a terrorist attack on the U.S. Embassy here, as
American medical teams and FBI investigators began to arrive in two
East African capitals. The death toll from the simultaneous
car-bomb explosions, here and in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, rose
above 90 people and is likely to rise even higher. Streams of
wounded overwhelmed the city's hospitals, where more than 500
people have been admitted and more than 4,200 treated in less than
two days. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (Subbed with 1STLD)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton said on Saturday
that the United States would not shirk from its role as world
leader as a result of terrorism, even though Americans are prime
targets and the capture of terrorists can take decades. By Jeff
Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   (Subbed with 1STLD)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-HOSPITAL (Nairobi, Kenya) _ The grievously maimed and the
walking wounded filled the wards, corridors and intensive-care beds
at Kenyatta National Hospital here Saturday, and doctors, nurses
and technicians were strained to their limits as they struggled to
treat the victims of the car-bomb attack on the American Embassy on
Friday. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   (New story, unskedded; added to NYT Page 1 later editions)
</P>
<P>
   (Subbed with 1STLD)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-VICTIMS (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ After a confusing
scene at the Nairobi airport Saturday morning, three injured
employees of the U.S. embassy in Kenya were flown to Pretoria on a
South African military airplane as other bombing victims awaited
medical approval to be transported.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-SOLDIER (Nevada, Mo.) _ Restless in a little Missouri
town set to a safe but predictable rhythm, young Kenneth Hobson
could scarcely wait to grow up and start chasing adventure. ``He
wanted to see the world,'' said his mother, Bonnie Hobson, sitting
on a porch suddenly filled with flowers of condolence. Word came
early Friday that her 27-year-old son, Sgt. Kenneth Hobson Jr., who
has a wife and a 2-year-old daughter, was one of 11 Americans
killed in the terrorist attack on the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi,
Kenya. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   (Replaced on NYT Page 1 by AFRICA-HOSPITAL)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-VICTIMS-LIST (Washington) _ A list of Americans killed in
the bombing near the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya, as provided
Saturday by the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   (New story, unskedded on earlier budgets/advisories)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-VICTIMS-U.S. (Undated) _ For bombing victims' kin, the
bad news is sudden and shocking. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   (New story, late add; unskedded on earlier budgets/advisories.
Replaces EUROPE-AIRCON on NYT Page 1)
</P>
<P>
   (Subbed with 1STLD)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-TANZANIA (Dar es Salaam) _ A team of U.S. antiterrorism
experts arrived here Saturday night to start sifting through the
rubble from the badly damaged American Embassy for clues as to who
bombed the building on Friday. More American investigators were
expected on Sunday, officials said. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (New story, late add; unskedded on earlier budgets/advisories)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-MORTUARY (Nairobi, Kenya) _ A Nairobi mortuary lets in
the living to search for the dead. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (New story, late add; unskedded on earlier budgets/advisories)
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times News Service
</P>
