<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4886 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-RAIDERS-T     08-09 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-RAIDERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS SLAM STUMBLING COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys flashed back to the woeful days of
1997 last night at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In a 16-3 exhibition loss to the Oakland Raiders, a handful of
mental bloopers and a lack of production in some key positions
reminded fans how far coach Chan Gailey's crew still has to go this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman ran for his life and Emmitt Smith had nowhere to run
behind the first-team offensive line; the Cowboys went
three-and-out in their first four possessions that netted minus-6
total yards.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, ends Kavika Pittman and Greg Ellis underscored a
first-team unit that provided no pass rush, and allowed the Raiders
to sprint for 176 total yards in the first quarter alone.
</P>
<P>
   The lousy elements, which included a fumbled punt, botched snaps
in the shotgun, and two penalties for illegal formation, combined
to compromise any momentum built from what had been a productive
training camp for Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a poor showing for us,'' Gailey said. ``And it proves
to me that we have a lot of work to do. I knew we did. But this
just proves it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard night had by all on the offensive line came as somewhat
of a surprise, because the unit had shown promise with the addition
of rookie Flozell Adams, the improved conditioning of Nate Newton,
and the improved strength of center Clay Shiver. But against a
Raiders defense that ranked last against the run and the pass in
1997, it suffered a meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   The misery began on the Cowboys' first offensive play. A mixup
in the middle of the line, a line that included Adams making his
first start at guard in place of the injured Everett McIver,
allowed former Cowboys defensive lineman Russell Maryland to run
untouched through the middle to bury Aikman. Two plays later,
Raiders tackle Darrell Russell plowed through the Cowboys middle to
force Aikman into a incompletion from his own end zone.
</P>
<P>
   With little time to throw against the stunting Raiders
defenders, Aikman completed was 1-of-6 passing for 6 yards. His
night mercifully ended after he was sacked a second time _ this
time by linebacker Greg Biekert _ who blew by the overwhelmed
Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came after us pretty good with some of the types of
stunts and blitzes that you see in the regular season,'' Newton
said. ``But I'll make no excuses. Those are the things we work on
in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The running game was equally inept. Smith gained 3 yards on four
carries. Chris Warren had two carries for 7 yards. And Ernie Mills,
who is the favorite to start at wide receiver with Michael Irvin,
failed to catch a pass for the second consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman and Ellis have also been shut out this summer in a key
statistic, sacks registered. Neither came close to quarterback Jeff
George last night, as Raiders tackles Pat Harlow and Lincoln
Kennedy provided sturdy pass protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get off the ball as well as I should have,'' said
Pitman. ``My strength is my quickness and speed and when I don't
have it those big lineman can get on me and it makes it tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The only pressure the Cowboys could muster was with the blitzing
Randall Godfrey, who got to George once. Yet this strategy cost the
Cowboys when George correctly read a blitz and tossed a 33-yard
touchdown pass to Terry Mickens, who was so wide open, because of a
Cowboys mixup in the second-team secondary, that he practically
fair-caught George's pass.
</P>
<P>
   Pittman left the game with a sprained left ankle. The severity
of his injury is unknown. Any missed time would deplete the club's
depth at a position that is primarily manned by Ellis, Pittman, and
free agents Hurvin McCormack and Herman Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked bad,'' said Irvin. ``You're going to have setbacks
in training camp. You hope they're baby steps. The step back we
took today was a giant step.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
