<HEADER>
A4887 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LAD     08-09 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDESI CLEARED TO PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Glenn Hoffman has used up more than his share of
lineup cards in his short career as Dodgers manager, adjusting to a
never-ending string of injuries. But he was all too eager to tear
up the lineup card Saturday less than an hour before the first
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   And he was more than happy to scribble Raul Mondesi's name in
the No. 3 slot on the new lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, out the last two games and parts of the previous two
with a lower back strain, was cleared to play by the Dodgers
medical staff after an MRI and bone scan showed no serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   He was designated day-to-day in the early afternoon, and Hoffman
figured to have his center fielder back by perhaps Tuesday. Mondesi
joked to reporters early in the day that he might play Saturday
night. ``Pinch hit, you never know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, he stopped joking and started taking hacks in an
indoor batting cage in front of Hoffman and team trainers and
declared himself ready to play. Team officials were loath to argue
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman thus had his preferred 3-5 hitters _ Mondesi, Gary
Sheffield, Eric Karros _ for the first time since Tuesday. Mondesi
replaced Trenidad Hubbard in center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good news. Very good news,'' Hoffman said of Mondesi's medical
report.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively speaking, it was about the best news he's had in a
week in which both Jose Vizcaino (torn ligaments, right ankle) and
Ismael Valdes (strained stomach muscle) were reported to be behind
schedule in rehabilitating their own injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real concerned. Backs are real tricky,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi was relieved when tests taken late Friday came back
negative Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was nervous,'' he said. ``The doctors said it was
nothing serious. After that, I felt better. My mind just cleared.''
</P>
<P>
   And his back? ``Much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: Lakers forward (and now free agent) Rick Fox took a
break from the NBA lockout to participate in Saturday's annual
Hollywood Stars game. A player rep for the union, Fox said
negotiations with the owners look bleak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it this way: If it keeps going the way it's going,
I'll be shooting `Oz,''' he said, referring to his part-time acting
job on the HBO series.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers pitcher Darren Dreifort, asked if he'd play in the Stars
game: ``You gotta be a star. I just play for the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   Multimillion: The Dodgers passed the 2 million mark in
attendance Friday night, surpassing the mark for the 25th straight
season and 33rd time in history, the most by any major-league team.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes progresses: Valdes threw on flat ground for about 10
minutes for a fourth straight day and increased his velocity.
Hoffman called the outing encouraging but offered no timetable for
Valdes to throw off the mound. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
