<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TUMBLE BUT INCREASE LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ This must be the the Rangers' month.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox dealt the Rangers their first August loss,
yet the American League West leaders extended their lead to three
games over the second-place Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the Chicago White Sox's doubleheader sweep of the
Angels earlier in the day made last night's 11-1 loss to the Red
Sox at The Ballpark in Arlington easier to digest.
</P>
<P>
   At least it beat the steady diet of knuckleballs Red Sox
right-hander Tim Wakefield fed the Rangers during his eight-inning
appearance. Wakefield (14-5) surrendered only one run on seven hits
and two walks for his third consecutive victory and eighth in his
past 10 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a pitch you don't get to see every day,'' Rangers
first baseman Will Clark said. ``It's one of those things you
really can't get in a groove with or get used to hitting because
you just don't see it very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing the Rangers aren't seeing very often are quality
starts from right-hander Aaron Sele, who surrendered seven runs on
10 hits and two walks. Sele (13-9) failed to pitch at least six
innings for the third time in six starts since representing the
Rangers at the All-Star Game. He is 1-4 with an 8.04 earned-run
average in his past five appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Sele's latest downfall began with the game's third pitch. Red
Sox right fielder Darren Bragg _ who entered the game 4-for-7 with
a double, two home runs and two walks in his career against Sele _
sent a 2-0 fastball 418 feet for a leadoff home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I needed the ball down, I kept getting it up,'' Sele
said. ``When I needed it inside, it was right over the plate. It
was just a case of me not making it very difficult for them to hit
the ball. I got behind a lot, and then I would put it right over
the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Consecutive two-out singles by left fielder Troy O'Leary and
designated hitter Mike Stanley gave the Red Sox a two-run lead
after the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Sele retired the first two batters in the second inning, but
Bragg collected a two-out single and scored on the ensuing home run
by third baseman John Valentin. It again would be a case of Sele
failing to locate his fastball on an 0-1 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was missing with some pitches up in the zone a little
bit,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``I just don't think
tonight we threw enough quality strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who failed to record an out in the fifth inning, departed
with a four-run deficit and the bases loaded. Reliever Al Levine
allowed all three inherited runners to score.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored their run in the sixth inning. First baseman
Will Clark reached on a one-out single and advanced to third on a
double by catcher Ivan Rodriguez. Only a two-out single by right
fielder Roberto Kelly separated the Rangers from a shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield afterward called the Red Sox's victory ``a very big
game.''
</P>
<P>
   It terminated their two-game losing streak and the Rangers'
six-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Rangers chose a most opportune evening in
August to lose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
