<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4891 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-Astros-Phillies-H     08-09 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-Astros-Phillies-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Error, hit batter in 9th lift Astros
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Rookies don't catch many breaks. When they do, it's usually of the
painful variety.
</P>
<P>
   A tough first season got a little tougher for center fielder
Richard Hidalgo on Saturday night. Philadelphia reliever Mark
Leiter hit Hidalgo with the bases loaded in the ninth inning as the
Astros staged one of their familiar comebacks, earning a 7-6 win
before 42,523 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The two-run, ninth-inning rally was the Astros' second of the
night. Earlier, two home runs helped erase a 5-1 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The injury did not appear to be serious. Hidalgo, 23, will be
evaluated before today's series finale against the Phillies. He
missed 40 games earlier this season after separating his right
shoulder in a collision with the outfield wall at Denver's Coors
Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not too bad because it didn't hit me in the knee,'' said
Hidalgo, who was hit on the right leg and had a noticeable limp
after the game. ``I'm sore, but I'll be able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo was filling in for regular center fielder Carl Everett,
who has missed the last two games with a strained left quadriceps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what we're going to have,'' manager Larry Dierker
said of his center-field options for today's game. ``It's going to
be one of those get-here-and-see-how-everyone-feels type lineups.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Astros were feeling pretty good after
rallying for six runs in the final four innings for their 18th
final at-bat victory this season.
</P>
<P>
   The victory boosted the Astros' lead over the Chicago Cubs to 6{
games in the National League Central with their 34th
come-from-behind victory this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros trailed 5-1 in the sixth and 6-5 in the ninth after
Bobby Estalella put the Phillies back in front with his second home
run of the game, a solo shot off Doug Henry.
</P>
<P>
   Estalella, who had only two hits in his last 29 at-bats and was
batting .152, went 3-for-4 with two home runs and three RBIs. He
also homered in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Henry picked up his eighth victory _ all of them coming in last
at-bat victories for the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros down 6-5, Bill Spiers led off the ninth inning
with a double down the left-field line and Derek Bell, whose homer
in the seventh had tied the score at 5, singled to put runners at
the corners with none out.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell, who extended his hitting streak to eight games,
drove in Spiers with a fielder's choice ground ball and reached
second base on a throwing error by third baseman Scott Rolen. Rolen
was trying to stop Spiers, the tying run, at home and his throw
sailed far wide of Estalella.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter intentionally walked Moises Alou to load the bases before
throwing a sinker that hit Hidalgo in the leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the whole thing was ugly,'' Leiter said. ``That guy
(Spiers) has got to be hitting .500 against me. He does that all
the time. I can't make a better 0-0 pitch as far as the sinker goes
without throwing a ball, and he hit it right down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That changed the whole situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolen said, ``I made a bad throw and it cost us the game. We got
the play that we wanted and we were going to go home but I made a
bad throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bagwell of the Astros' late heroics, ``It's not something
we want to continue to do because chances are you're not going to
do it often. We've had some luck. The main thing in a comeback win
is the leadoff guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the leadoff guy gets on you always have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean Berry began Saturday's rally with a two-run pinch homer in
the sixth inning off Phillies starter Carlton Loewer. Bell's solo
shot in the seventh, his 17th, came off reliever Wayne Gomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was gone as soon as I hit it, but I was so excited I
couldn't slow down,'' Berry said. ``You know what they say about
speeding up the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros starter Jose Lima didn't pitch a complete game, as he had
in his previous two starts, but he overcame a rocky start to keep
the Astros in striking distance. Lima pitched six innings, allowing
five runs and six hits while striking out seven.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia jumped out to a 4-0 lead off Lima on Estalella's
first homer and a three-rally in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Rolen and Rico Brogna led off the fourth with singles and
former Astro Bob Abreu walked. Mark Lewis hit a sacrifice fly for
one run, Estalella doubled one in and Jon Zuber's RBI grounder made
it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Abreu hit his eighth home run of the season _ a solo shot _ in
the sixth inning to make it 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   The six-inning outing by Lima was only the third time in his
last 10 starts he failed to pitch at least seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   He was named National League Player of the Week on Monday after
allowing only two earned runs and striking out 16 in consecutive
complete games against Florida and Pittsburgh. He was bidding to
become the first Astros pitcher to throw three straight complete
games since Doug Drabek in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I gave up the home run, I told myself to keep the ball
down and keep the team in the game,'' said Lima, whose RBI single
in the fourth pushed across the Astros' first run. ``I think six
innings is good for the bullpen. They can do the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
