<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT AVOIDS SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD _ The best thing about women's tennis is the
second-ranked player whose tense victory over Monica Seles on
Saturday set up a Toshiba Classic final against Mary Pierce today,
giving our hero a chance at back-to-back tournament championships,
since she beat Steffi Graf and Venus Williams last weekend at
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing is the fact that unless you follow the sport
closely, you know all about Seles, Pierce, Graf and Williams but
you have no idea who I'm talking about.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about women's tennis is Lindsay Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing is the fact that because she is not the focus of
glamour photographers or lunatic fans, because she's merely
articulate but never boastful, and because her most eye-catching
decoration isn't hair beads but the little cross on her necklace,
No. 2 in the world gets about as much attention as No. 102.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about Lindsay Davenport is that she wouldn't
dream of complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the position I'm in,'' said Davenport, who defeated
Seles 6-4, 2-6, 7-5 at the La Costa Resort &AMP; Spa. ``I don't really
love the spotlight. I don't want a great deal of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old Newport Beach resident, who will be in Manhattan
Beach for the Acura Classic starting Monday, is the Stealth Bomber
of women's tennis.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy for a second-ranked player to avoid detection by
press and public radar. It's not easy for a 6-foot, 2{-inch woman
to get lost in a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But when Davenport puts her mind to it, she can accomplish
anything.
</P>
<P>
   She yearns for the days, earlier in her five-year professional
career, when she could wander among the back courts during idle
hours, watching other players.
</P>
<P>
   She's a little too well-known to do that now without attracting
a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it when I'm eating and people come up to me,''
she admits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's nothing compared to the crowds some of her rivals
attract.
</P>
<P>
   Women's tennis, and even men's tennis to an extent, discovered
years ago that sex and soap opera sells. Never, though, has the
emphasis been on appearance and personality to as embarrassing a
degree as it is now.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are to blame, journalists are to blame and the tennis
industry is to blame. The attitude is: If people watch in part
because of Graf's legs (guilty), Martina Hingis' mischievous grin
(guilty) or Pierce's pout (guilty), that's better than if they
didn't watch at all.
</P>
<P>
   There's a gossipy tennis magazine, Tennis Match, that makes
Tiger Beat look like The Economist. As far as Tennis Match is
concerned, Anna Kournikova and Patrick Rafter are Hall of Fame
shoo-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport is the antidote to all that.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, during Wimbledon, an English tabloid published
a photo of a perspiring Davenport next to a photo of an equally
disheveled Meatloaf. One of those ``Separated at Birth?'' jokes. If
that struck most readers as cruel, picking on Davenport's generous
physique, it seemed to affect her not at all.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, since 1995 Davenport has shed 25 pounds. She
admits a weakness for her mother's beef Stroganoff, but jokes that
she has learned how to share.
</P>
<P>
   She's No. 2, and she looks harder. She says the leaner body is
quicker on the court, though ``I'm never going to be Arantxa
(Sanchez Vicario) or Amanda Coetzer'' when it comes to speed.
</P>
<P>
   As it also happens, Davenport's rise was overshadowed by the
arrival of the Hingis-Williams-Kournikova generation of teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   It says a lot about Davenport that she doesn't complain when
they get all the magazine covers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all exciting, they're all outspoken and they all have
distinct personalities,'' she said of the younger women. ``They're
very much out there, kind of in your face.... They're all really
confident, like, `Hey, I'm the best.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty quiet. I keep to myself. I really like it at the
Grand Slams. The first couple of days I'm not bothered by the press
at all. All the other players are the favorites. But then I wind up
in the semifinals.''
</P>
<P>
   Since climbing to No. 2 in February, Davenport has drawn within
587 ranking points of No. 1 Hingis, a margin she could wipe out at
the U.S. Open, which starts Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a modest seven-match winning streak on her beloved hard
courts since she was knocked out of Wimbledon in the semifinals by
Nathalie Tauziat, Davenport thinks this Open might bring her first
Grand Slam tournament victory.
</P>
<P>
   Root for her because of what !ital!won't!off! happen if she
wins.
</P>
<P>
   To those who have made fun of her body and her old immobility,
she will speak no I-told-you-sos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'd ever come up to someone and say, `This is to
you guys!''' she said this week. ``I think if I win a Grand Slam,
I'll probably go in the room and say (to herself), `I did it!'''
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room, it will surprise nobody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's just a balanced person,'' Seles said Saturday.
``She has a normal life. She's not just tennis, tennis. You can
talk to her about other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``(From) the players, she definitely has a lot of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   For once, the other players are worth listening to. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
