</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Cowboys' offense sputters against Raiders
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IRVING _ Despite last year's horrific outcome, the Cowboys came
into this season with only a few starting jobs up for grabs. After
Saturday night, most of them should be.
</P>
<P>
   If last year's 6-10 record still gives Cowboys fans fits,
Saturday night's 16-3 preseason loss to the Oakland Raiders should
give them nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Chan Gailey's new offense didn't sputter; it died. The
Cowboys' first team ran a grand total of 12 plays in four
possessions, taking them one minute into the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came after us pretty good with some of the types of
stunts and blitzes that you see in the regular season,'' guard Nate
Newton said.
</P>
<P>
   Which wouldn't seem to bode well for the upcoming regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make no excuses,'' Newton said. ``Those are the things
that we work on in practice _ and we have a lot more work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to determine which part of the Cowboys' game looked
the worst.
</P>
<P>
   They had a total of minus-six yards with the trio of Troy
Aikman, Emmitt Smith and Michael Irvin in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman completed only one pass in six attempts for a total of
six yards.
</P>
<P>
   Smith carried four times for three yards.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin had only one catch for six yards.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line allowed two sacks.
</P>
<P>
   There was one fumble.
</P>
<P>
   There were no first downs.
</P>
<P>
   And that was all in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like anything but the same offense that was touted
last week after scoring a touchdown on its second possession
against Seattle. The first-teamers also scored against Oakland in
Thursday night's scrimmage in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a poor job of handling the blitz,'' Gailey said. ``We
did not run the ball effectively. It was just a poor showing for us
and it proves to me that we have a lot of work to do. I knew we
did, but this just proves it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' offensive line, which was still without guard
Everett McIver, was manhandled. Former Cowboy Russell Maryland
easily broke through against center Clay Shiver to sack Aikman for
a loss of eight yards on Dallas' first play of the game. Aikman was
later sacked in the shotgun formation as Greg Biekert got past
rookie Flozell Adams to knock Aikman for a seven-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Cowboys surrendered too many big plays. On the
Raiders' first possession, Jeff George connected with free-agent
acquisition Terry Mickens on a pass of 18 yards. Olanda Truitt then
burned Darren Woodson for a catch of 43 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' second-team secondary didn't fare any better as Truitt
later slipped by Kenny Wheaton for a catch of 24 yards. Mickens
went deep for a 33-yard catch, then trotted into the end zone with
the nearest Dallas defender a good 15 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   It was a comedy of errors, beginning on only the third play of
the game when Woodson was flagged for illegal contact. The Cowboys
then drew whistles on their first and second possessions for
illegal formations as they struggled to get the right personnel
into the right places for their new plays.
</P>
<P>
   It was second-team quarterback Jason Garrett who eventually led
the Cowboys to their only score, a 22-yard field goal by Richie
Cunningham, the scapegoat last week after missing the game-tying
extra point against Seattle. The Cowboys' second team scored on its
first trip downfield after Garrett completed his first four passes
to spark a nine-play, 40-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   The halftime statistics were embarrassing. The Raiders had 253
net yards to Dallas' 46. The biggest distinction came in passing
yards, where Jeff George and Rice-ex Donald Hollas combined for 202
yards. Aikman and Garrett threw for only 23.
</P>
<P>
   As for the positions that were up for grabs, nobody made much of
a case for themselves. The Cowboys are still looking for a No. 2
receiver, but a woeful offense made it difficult for anyone to
stand out. Billy Davis caught back-to-back passes from Garrett for
14 yards in the second quarter. Ernie Mills was shut out and Jimmy
Oliver left the game with injured ribs after his only catch, which
netted 13 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The other hottest contest is at free safety, where Omar
Stoutmire is battling George Teague and Wheaton. Stoutmire was
beaten by Mickens, but later redeemed himself by batting away a
long pass at the Dallas 40. Wheaton also was burned on a pass and
Teague played sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys scrimmage the Saints on Tuesday night in Shreveport,
La., then travel to Mexico City for an exhibition game against the
Patriots on Aug. 17. They travel to St. Louis and Jacksonville for
their final two preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good wakeup call for us,'' Gailey said. ``No, this
was a bad wakeup call for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
