<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4894 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SIDEBAR-T     08-09 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SIDEBAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS NO CLOSER TO ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said his football team
faces more questions in 1998 than at any time since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Two games into the preseason, the Cowboys are still looking for
answers.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the team seemingly took a step backward
with an uninspired effort in last night's 16-3 loss to the Oakland
Raiders at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Any progress made in the preseason opener against the Seattle
Seahawks and in the past week of practice was seemingly lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proves we got a lot of work to do,'' Cowboys coach Chan
Gailey said. ``We've got to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's collective ``we'' was directed at the entire team, but
it especially held true for the areas the Cowboys had the most
questions going into training camp: at right guard, second receiver
and defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Mammoth second-round pick Flozell Adams, the rave of training
camp since taking over for injured starter Everett McIver, looked
like an untutored rookie.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a few missed assignments, the 6-foot-7,
335-pounder was embarrassed by Greg Biekert when the Raiders'
linebacker beat him inside for a sack on Cowboys quarterback Troy
Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   Adams' spotty play and McIver's absence from practice the past
week after he sustained a cut on his neck in a dorm incident have
raised more questions about the offensive line. McIver remains the
starter. But it's unclear how much the layoff has impeded his
development and the line's cohesiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders took advantage of the lack of continuity with
several successful blitzes and stunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things we work on in practice, and we have a lot of
work to do,'' Cowboys guard Nate Newton said.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive ends Greg Ellis and Kavika Pittman have yet to prove
that they can rush the passer in the NFL. Neither came close to the
quarterback last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are looking to address the problem with a free-agent
addition.
</P>
<P>
   The battle at second receiver between Billy Davis and Ernie
Mills proved inconclusive for the second consecutive week. Mills,
signed as a free agent during the off-season, is considered the
favorite because of his familiarity with Gailey's offense from his
days in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   But after looking great in training camp, Mills has disappeared
during the preseason games. He went without a catch against Seattle
and duplicated the performance against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has had minimal impact as well. His two catches for 14
yards last night give him four for 23 yards in two preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also hoped to take a look at former TCU speedster
Jimmy Oliver as a possible replacement for Herschel Walker at
kickoff returner. However, Oliver's presence was brief.
</P>
<P>
   After returning one kick 17 yards in the first quarter, Oliver
sustained bruised ribs on a reception and didn't return to the
game. The injury added to concerns about Oliver's durability.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver has yet to play a down in the NFL after being drafted by
the San Diego Chargers in 1995. He missed his rookie year with a
separated shoulder. A knee injury sidelined him in 1996. He was
released in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
