<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4895 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HENRY-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-09 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HENRY-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros reliever Henry feasts on team's ability to score in last
at-bat
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Doug Henry has acquired a nickname that's not particularly
flattering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry's the `Vulture,''' Astros manager Larry Dierker said
after his team beat the Philadelphia Phillies 7-6 on Saturday night
in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, a righthanded reliever, entered a tie game in the ninth
inning and gave up a home run to a .200-hitting rookie catcher,
Bobby Estalella.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros came back to score two in the bottom of the
ninth, giving Henry his eighth victory of the season _ all
delivered in the Astros' last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the nickname ``Vulture,'' which in baseball parlance is a
reliever who picks up what others have left for him, without having
to work hard for his meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could argue with him,'' Henry said when informed of
his new nickname. ``I don't want to be a vulture. But I can't argue
with him tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker actually is happy to have a vulture because it means his
team is coming from behind, snatching victory when it appears lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``You often find one on a team that comes back to win a lot of
games,'' he said. ``I remember in '86 we had Charley Kerfeld. And
then another year we had Juan Agosto.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker is beginning to think of Henry as a good-luck charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he comes in, we score runs,'' Dierker said. ``Some games
he hasn't pitched well and we still win. Some games he's pitched
well and he hasn't gotten the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Henry, a free-agent acquisition in the offseason, has
been effective. He has a 2.92 ERA and has held opponents to a .210
batting average. His only problem has been home runs: nine in 52
innings.
</P>
<P>
   He throws reasonably hard _ 92 mph _ but he has a tendency to
use the fastball too often and to leave it too high.
</P>
<P>
   Estalella had pounded a fastball for a home run off Jose Lima in
the third inning, so Dierker was expecting Henry, 34, to try a
different strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking he'd throw some breaking balls to Estalella,''
Dierker said. ``But he threw four straight fastballs and one of
them went out.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry didn't think it was the wrong strategy; he just didn't put
the pitch where he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   With the count 2-1, he said he ``was trying to throw a fastball
away, and it ran up and in. It was a terrible pitch. It was so bad
he shouldn't have swung at it. He should have let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   He let it go, all right. Over the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made some excitement for the fans,'' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. The Astros rallied, as they often do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting on the bench, the maddest guy in the stadium,''
Henry said. ``But if you keep these boys in the game, they're going
to find a way to win. We've gotten to quite a few closers this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   This time their victim was Mark Leiter (6-3), who has saved 20
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just happened to be at the right place at the right time,''
Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   But he wanted the record straight on his 8-2 mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've only vultured two wins all year,'' he said,
referring to games in which he's given the opponents a lead and
wound up claiming the win.
</P>
<P>
   It also should be pointed out that while his teammates often
help Henry, he has been brilliant at bailing his fellow pitchers
out of jams. Of the 26 baserunners Henry has inherited, he has
allowed only six to score.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that when he's in a game, the Astros usually
win it. On a baseball team, a vulture is no albatross.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
