<HEADLINE>
SMITH VISIT POSTPONED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Defensive end Fernando Smith, who was released
by the Minnesota Vikings this spring, has postponed his visit to
work out with the Cowboys until tomorrow. Smith worked out with the
Washington Redskins yesterday and was scheduled to visit the
Cowboys today, but moved the workout back a day to tomorrow because
of scheduling problems, his agent, Jeff Durand, said.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones is expected to meet Smith in Wichita
Falls. If the workout goes well, Jones has indicated that he would
rework several contracts in an attempt to fit Smith under the
salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Durand said his client wants to play for a team that would give
him a chance to start. He also said Smith would not accept a
contract offer less than the $1.3 million he was scheduled to earn
with the Vikings this season.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he had surgery to repair a hernia, which limited his
effectiveness in 1997, Durand said. Since word of the hernia
operation became public, Durand said the Vikings have considered
re-signing Smith, who had his finest season for the club in 1996
with 65 tackles, 9.5 sacks, three forced fumbles and two fumble
recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was misdiagnosed,'' Durand said, ``I don't think anyone
knew what was wrong with him. The Vikings want to talk to him. And
there is no animosity here. But they are on the list like the rest
of the clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Redskins, Smith already has visited Jacksonville,
Atlanta, Chicago, and New Orleans. Durand said several of these
clubs have told him they would meet Smith's asking price. He said
his client probably won't make a decision until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kevin Lyons Sanders makes impact In his first game action of
the preseason, Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders wasted no time
making an impact. On last night's first snap against the Raiders,
Sanders, often criticized for avoiding contact, lowered his
shoulder and dropped the Raiders' Napoleon Kaufman for a loss with
a solid hit on a flare pass to the left flat.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, recovering from off-season ankle surgery, was held out
of the preseason opener against the Seattle Seahawks on July 31 and
the contact portion of Thursday night's scrimmage against the
Raiders as a precaution. He played the first three series and was
not tested by Raiders quarterback Jeff George.
</P>
<P>
   _ Andy Friedlander Woodson looks rusty In his first preseason
action of the year, Cowboys Pro Bowl safety Darren Woodson looked
out of place during the first series of last night's game. After
committing an illegal contact penalty on the third play, Woodson
was beaten by Raiders receiver Olanda Truitt for a 43-yard
reception two plays later.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joel Anderson Raiders rookie sees action Raiders first-round
draft pick Charles Woodson made several brief appearances last
night. Woodson, who is competing with six-year veteran James Trapp
for the starting left cornerback position, deflected one pass.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joel Anderson Hemsley impresses Second-year linebacker Nate
Hemsley had an impressive series of downs on a goal-line stand late
in the second quarter. The Raiders had a first down from the 2-yard
line, but Hemsley was involved in three consecutive tackles that
forced the Raiders to settle for a 20-yard field goal. Hemsley, a
member of the Cowboys' practice squad last season after being
signed as a free agent out of Syracuse by the Tennessee Oilers,
left the game in the third quarter after sustaining a sprained left
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joel Anderson Oliver down on his luck Former TCU receiver
Jimmy Oliver, who has endured a string of injuries in his first
three NFL seasons, was taken to the locker room for X-rays after
sustaining bruised ribs. Oliver was injured on a reception. He did
not return to the game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joel Anderson Dawson in home state Dallas native and former
University of Texas kicker Phil Dawson made a homecoming of sorts
yesterday evening. Dawson is in a three-way battle with incumbent
Raiders kicker Cole Ford and veteran Greg Davis for the starting
position. Dawson connected on an extra-point in the first quarter,
but missed a 47-yard field-goal attempt in the third.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joel Anderson Penalty problems After struggling with penalties
against Seattle last week, the Cowboys had their problems again
last night, drawing five flags in the first half, including two for
illegal formation on consecutive third-and-long plays in the first
quarter. Both were declined after the Cowboys failed to make the
first down. In addition, the Cowboys were called for late-hit
personal fouls against Darren Hambrick and Harold Gragg.
</P>
<P>
   _ Andy Friedlander Shotgun blunders The much-discussed shotgun
formation misfired time after time last night, leading to fumbled
snaps by reserve quarterbacks Jason Garrett and Josh LaRocca from
center Steve Scifres. Another Garrett fumble was negated by an
Oakland penalty, and Troy Aikman had to pick a low snap from Clay
Shiver off his shoetops.
</P>
<P>
   _ Andy Friedlander McIver to practice Cowboys guard Everett
McIver, who sustained a deep cut in a training-camp dormitory
incident on July 29, will return to practice for the first time
tomorrow. He will not play in Tuesday's scrimmage against New
Orleans in Shreveport, La., the Cowboys said, but is expected to
play in the Aug. 17 exhibition game against New England.
They said it.
``Ya'll \Rthe media\S are working harder than the police to put me
in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin, reacting to reports he was
involved in the dormitory incident where guard Everett McIver
sustained a neck wound.
</P>
