<SLUG> BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LOVE LOST FOR BONDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Barry Bonds might be a three-time National League
Most Valuable Player, but he also is baseball's most hated player.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds started a bench-clearing brawl last week between the San
Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies by charging the mound
after he was struck by a pitch from Ricky Bottalico. During the
fight, both sides said Bonds is just a bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies took exception to Bonds stealing second base in the
fifth inning with the Giants leading 9-2 in a game they'd
eventually win 15-3.
</P>
<P>
   After Bonds and Bottalico were ejected, Bonds exchanged words
with Phillies ace Curt Schilling on his way back to the Giants
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were exchanging words,'' Schilling said. ``But I wasn't
saying anything his teammates weren't saying about him on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   One Phillie said Giants right-hander Danny Darwin told him that
he hated coming out in defense of Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy (Bonds) is a first-ballot Hall of Famer,'' Schilling
said. ``No doubt. But when you don't play the game right, bad
things happen. And he deserved what happened. There's no excuse for
anybody at this level to play the game the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that the Giants had blown big leads in each
of the first two games of the series. Bonds, in fact, did note
exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only the fifth inning and they'd come back on us two
days in a row,'' he said. ``Where do you draw the line? For the
first five innings, you play the game out. After that, you give the
other team common courtesy.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't matter to Phillies reserve infielder Alex Arias, who
was ejected after taking a few steps toward the mound after he was
struck by a Kirk Reuter pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitcher's got to do what the pitcher's got to do,'' Arias
said. ``If he's told to throw at me, I don't care. It was Barry who
started the whole thing. No doubt he's a great player. But do you
want to be great piling up stats that don't mean anything? I'm sure
half his stolen bases came that way. I've never had respect for
that guy. Ever. Even though he's a great player. He's a stats guy.
That's all he's worried about.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Phillies rookie catcher Bobby Estalella got in on the Barry
bashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to look up to these guys, but what he did today makes
you not want to respect him at all,'' Estalella said.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, Bonds described anybody who ripped him as
``chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody has a problem with me,'' he said, ``I'll give them
my phone number. We can meet in person and handle it.'' &QL; 
BLAH, BLAH, BLAH
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza has told at least two teammates that he's finished
with the New York Mets, and will leave as soon as the season is
over. Piazza has been booed loudly for failing to live up to the
public's expectations after the Mets won nine straight following
Piazza's acquisition on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, when contract negotiations broke off, Piazza was
hitting only .208 with runners in scoring position, and he wasn't
in the top ten among NL hitters in home runs, RBI or slugging
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   This week Piazza has turned so sour he distanced himself from
virtually all his teammates, with the exception of John Franco and
Al Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   Said one teammate: ``(Piazza) basically told me to have fun
without him next year.''
</P>
<P>
   This obviously is no longer a problem for the Dodgers, who
offered a six-year contract worth $85 million before trading him
May 15. But as Piazza turns 30 in September, he is another year
older without a championship. That has made his place as one of
baseball's most feared hitters seem a little hollow. He is not
expected to get anything near the money the Dodgers offered.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was angry with the Dodgers then and he is mad at the Mets
now.
</P>
<P>
   New York never made much of an attempt in the last 2{ months to
begin negotiations with Piazza. They kept waiting, trying to
determine whether Piazza's presence would jump-start the Mets into
the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   He did that, but more importantly, the Mets wanted to see if
Piazza's presence would bring fans to the park. The Mets were
averaging 20,000 a game before Piazza arrived; 27,000 a game since.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, last week, Piazza and the Mets officially put an end to
the talks that never really started, tabling the matter until after
the season. GM Steve Phillips said, ``we decided to wait, at Mike's
request.'' &QL; 
TROUBLE IN CLEVELAND
</P>
<P>
   While the New York Yankees went after Seattle left-hander Randy
Johnson to keep him away from Cleveland, the Indians really needed
him. Now he's in Houston and Cleveland's pitching staff is in
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the All-Star break, the starting rotation of Jaret
Wright, Bartolo Colon, Dave Burba, Charles Nagy and Dwight Gooden
was one of the team's strengths. But fatigue and injuries have
become a problem. The Indians are especially concerned that
youngsters Wright and Colon may have been overpitched in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Since the break, Colon, who had five complete games in the first
half, has pitched eight innings only once. In Wright's last two
starts, he has allowed 14 earned runs in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired,'' said Wright, who will start today at Tampa Bay.
``I don't know what having a dead arm means. I'm just tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooden went into the break strong but was 0-3 in his next four
starts and the Indians were actively shopping him before the
deadline. Chad Ogea was ready to take Gooden's spot in the rotation
but developed a sore knuckle on the middle finger of his right
hand.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened to acquiring Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   According to GM John Hart, Seattle asked for Burba, reliever
Paul Shuey, infielder Enrique Wilson and Brian Giles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not tear the heart out of our major-league club to get
a guy who would be here for only 60 days,'' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   But when Houston acquired Johnson for prospects, Hart said: ``We
were baffled. Whenever we talked to Seattle it was about a
major-league trade for star-quality players. We barely talked about
prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart would have liked to have had that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was nowhere for us to pick up a deal because we'd
hardly ever talked about prospects with the Mariners,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hart said the Mariners tried to pit the Indians and Yankees
against each other to drive up the price for Johnson. ``But neither
team blinked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted Johnson. But I haven't lost a minute of sleep because
of the price being asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Wonder how he will feel in the postseason. &QL; 
TRADE QUESTIONED
</P>
<P>
   There appears to have been some panic involved in the Cubs'
trading last year's No. 1 pick Jon Garland from Kennedy High School
to the Chicago White Sox for middle reliever Matt Karchner. They
also traded right-hander Todd Noel, their top pick in 1996, along
with one-time starting third baseman Kevin Orie and right-hander
Justin Speier (son of Chris Speier) to Florida for Felix Heredia
and a minor-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts are saying that was too much potential for not much
talent. Heredia is 22 and made a reputation by throwing 51/3
scoreless innings last year in four World Series appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Karchner, on the other hand, is 31 and has been on the DL in six
of the last nine seasons, including once this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs need for relief pitching is critical. They entered the
weekend with a 2{ game wild-card lead, then dropped the first two
games of the series in St. Louis 16-3 and 9-8. Now, the Cubs' lead
has been cut to a half-game over the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox seemed overwhelmed that they could land Garland
for Karchner. In his White Sox minor-league debut last Monday,
Garland allowed two hits and struck out 11 in six innings for
Single-A Hickory (N.C.).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people I've talked to in other organizations are
impressed with Jon,'' GM Ron Schueler said. ``Everybody I talked to
(after the trade) said, `I had no idea he was available.' They just
couldn't believe they would part with the kid. I hope he's as
special as they think he is.'' &QL; 
JACK WILL BE BACK
</P>
<P>
   The Reds offered manager Jack McKeon a one-year contract
extension Monday _ over the phone. McKeon, who says he wants to
stay, was surprised by the call and wanted to wait to accept until
this weekend when he and GM Jim Bowden could sit down and talk.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt both men will make sure they're still on the same page
in terms of the rebuilding process. Both know they must continue to
build with young players, but McKeon wants to make sure there are a
few veterans in the mix. Bowden will likely advocate playing more
kids next year.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon has a reputation for being good with young players, and
some, like 24-year-old rookie Sean Casey and 24-year-old Dmitri
Young, agree. McKeon stuck with both even when Casey struggled at
the plate (1 for 29 before a short trip back to the minors after
his eye surgery) and Young had trouble learning to play left field
when Casey took over in Young's natural position, first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a fine manager for us,'' said Young, who thought
Tony La Russa wasn't patient enough with young players like him
last year in St. Louis. ``He's been a great influence on me. He
gives you a chance to play and learn from your mistakes. It's a
learning process for all of us. You've got to be patient, and he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are watching the Reds because of the All-Star break
trades that sent top prospect Paul Konerko and left-hander Dennis
Reyes to Cincinnati for closer Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Konerko has since been sent to the minors, but Reyes was
recalled from Triple-A this week and has won his first two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Where do they fit into McKeon's plan? Too soon to tell.
</P>
<P>
   There are many in the Reds' clubhouse who think McKeon's
reputation for patience is undeserved. He has been harder on some
players _ like 25-year-old second-year pitcher Brett Tomko, deposed
first baseman Eduardo Perez and 25-year-old third baseman Aaron
Boone _ than his favorites like Casey and Young.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon says the criticism reflects the job of dealing with 25
personalities. ``That's natural,'' he says. ``You've got 25 guys on
a team, maybe 17 or 18 like you and five or six (you) don't.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon says he's been patient this year, but as the kids grow
up, his tone may have to change a little. He says he's had some fun
this year, though it has often been a tough season. ``I try to be
understanding to a point,'' he said. ``Sometimes I get riled up and
have to bite my lip. Sometimes I want to jump on them, but the more
they play, the fewer mistakes they'll make. I don't know if there
will be more pressure next year, but I wouldn't expect to be as
patient. I'd be disappointed if some of the same mistakes went on
next year.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
This week's series between Florida and the Dodgers will be more
than a homecoming between Gary Sheffield, Bobby Bonilla, Charles
Johnson and Jim Eisenreich and what little remains of the Marlins
championship team. Florida's Mark Kotsay, who grew up in Santa Fe
Springs, has bought 110 tickets for Tuesday's game at Dodger
Stadium, and 110 more for Wednesday night's game. He's also rented
a city bus to take them all to the games. &QL; 
ROTISSERIE WATCH &QL; 
The White Sox's Albert Belle leads the major leagues with 17 homers
(in 26 games) since the All-Star break. He has 35 homers and 97
RBI, which puts him on a pace for 50 homers and 138 RBI. The White
Sox records are 41 homers by Frank Thomas in 1993 and 138 RBI by
Zeke Bonura in 1936. &QL; 
STAT OF THE WEEK &QL; 
Astros second baseman Craig Biggio didn't play in Wednesday's game,
his first day off after 494 consecutive games, which was the
second-longest active consecutive-games streak in the majors (well
behind Cal Ripken's ongoing record of 2,593 entering today.) On
Saturday, Biggio, who last missed a game on July 31, 1995, was in
the on-deck circle in the seventh inning, but manager Larry Dierker
sent up Brad Ausmus instead. &QL; 
THE BUZZ &QL; 
Right-hander Orlando Hernandez has lost 15 pounds in two months,
causing concern among Yankees officials. El Duque reported to the
big leagues at 218 pounds but dropped to 203 during last week's
West Coast trip. Hernandez, a heavy smoker, will see a specialist
this weekend in New York, although coach Jose Cardenal believes the
problem can be traced to stress: Hernandez left two daughters and
most of his family in Cuba when he defected on a raft last
December. &QL; 
QUOTABLE &QL; 
``There's nothing wrong with my arm. There's nothing wrong with my
arm. Print that. There is nothing wrong with my arm.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Cubs rookie Kerry Wood, after he was routed by Arizona on
Wednesday amid reports that he had a tired arm. If Wood, who starts
Tuesday in San Francisco, stays on track, he will face Houston's
Randy Johnson on Aug. 22 at Wrigley Field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
