<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DROUGHT TAKES HEAVY TOLL ON FISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB HOOD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fish kills such as one discovered last week on the Nueces River
near Corpus Christi might become even more common statewide if
prolonged hot temperatures and lack of rainfall continue to lower
the levels of lakes, rivers and streams, Texas Parks and Wildlife
Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are beginning to see fish kills pop up all around the
state,'' said Larry McKinney, the department's senior director for
aquatic resources. ``In most instances, they have been caused by
low oxygen levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The water levels on many freshwater lakes have dropped eight to
10 feet since mid-March, and many rivers and streams have dried up
or become shallow pools, forcing fish to crowd into smaller areas
where they face steadily declining oxygen levels.
</P>
<P>
   Hit hardest by the drought have been Falcon and Amistad
reservoirs, on the Rio Grande River. Falcon is 90 percent empty _
more than 51 feet below its conservation pool elevation, or full
level. Amistad, which when full spreads across 67,000 acres, has
shrunk to 21,000 acres, about 6,690 acres smaller than the size of
popular Lake Fork in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   So far, most of the fish kills have occurred in rivers and
streams, where water flows have ceased. Fish kills on major
freshwater lakes have not reached a critical stage statewide,
officials said, but they have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The Nueces River fish kill involved species sought by anglers,
including flounder, according to biologist Ken Rice, who is
monitoring the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found southern flounder, striped mullet and thousands of
Gulf menhaden,'' said Rice, a parks and wildlife department
biologist. ``Basically what happened is that there has been no flow
from Lake Corpus Christi above the area,'' Rice said. ``Then there
was a discharge from a waste-water unit into the river, causing a
big algal bloom. With no tidal movement or flow, the nutrients
began to collect and not mix in. The big algal bloom just sucked up
all of the oxygen.''
</P>
<P>
   Another creek in the Rio Grande Valley has also experienced the
deaths of menhadens, and some ranch country lakes, such as those
behind San Jose Island, have experienced deaths among fish stranded
by lowering water levels, Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Since July 4, the death of an estimated 1,800 largemouth bass at
Sam Rayburn Reservoir was blamed by the department on heat-related
stress, which possibly occurred after fish were released into
warmer-than-usual waters by anglers.
</P>
<P>
   Another freshwater fish kill occurred at Lake O.C. Fisher near
San Angelo, where mostly rough fish such as carp began dying in the
North Concho River on the extreme upper reaches of the lake a few
weeks ago. That fish kill began to spread to the main lake,
however, as levels of dissolved oxygen began to decrease, killing
game fish, including sand bass.
</P>
<P>
   Fish kills are expected annually, especially during hot, dry
summers in areas of West Texas where such weather conditions are
more common than elsewhere in the state. However, biologist Joan
Glass of Waco said those deaths, which normally occur in inlets and
small streams as levels begin to dwindle, started showing up about
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always expect to see some die-offs during the summer in
small streams,'' Glass said. ``But they usually don't start
happening until after August. This year, they started showing up
about one month early.''
</P>
<P>
   One area that is being closely monitored is the Canadian River
north of Amarillo. Home of the largest population of Arkansas River
shiners in the United States, a fish proposed to be added to the
endangered species list, the Canadian River has no flow and has
dried to pools.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said some fish species are more tolerant to river flow
variations and are able to bounce back when the flows return.
</P>
<P>
   Many area lakes have suffered from a lack of rain. Lakes
Grapevine, Whitney and Lewisville were five to eight feet above
their full marks March 18. This week, Lewisville's level had
dropped more than three feet below its full capacity, Whitney's
level had fallen 51/2 feet below full, and Grapevine stood at
almost three feet low.
</P>
<P>
   Although low water conditions have created water hazards such as
stumps, rocks and sand or gravel bars that a few months ago were
far enough under the surface for safe boating, fishing success has
actually increased on some lakes by concentrating the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they predict that more fish deaths will occur if
hot, dry conditions continue through September, especially in
tributaries and rivers.
</P>
</TEXT>
