<HEADLINE>
TYSON'S VALUE TO BOXING WELL-DOCUMENTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOEL ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Tyson, the one-time ``Baddest Man on the Planet,'' has
experienced more triumphs and tragedies than a year of daytime
dramas.
</P>
<P>
   He's an ex-heavyweight boxing champion and million-dollar
moneymaking machine for former promoter Don King. He's also a
convicted rapist, and the man who bit Evander Holyfield on the ears
in a heavyweight title fight.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of his many conquests and controversies, Tyson
is the sport's greatest attraction since ``The Greatest of All
Time,'' Muhammad Ali, boxing insiders and fans say.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson sparked another drama last month when he applied for a
license to box in New Jersey. His boxing license was revoked after
he gnawed Holyfield's ears in their heavyweight title rematch in
June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the New Jersey hearing, Tyson lost his composure amid more
than 40 minutes of questioning. He accentuated the outburst with an
expletive.
</P>
<P>
   Such sensational and provocative behavior expands the list of
compelling arguments against licensing his return. But consider
this:
</P>
<P>
   Boxing without Tyson means ``marquee'' matchups such as George
Foreman vs. Larry Holmes, two middle-age, overweight heavyweight
champs from the '70s and early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing without Tyson yields less than half the pay-per-view
revenue than it does with him.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing without Tyson means that celebrities and gentry alike
won't plunk down $1,500 for a ringside seat at Caesar's Palace.
Pay-per-view operators gleefully charge $49.95 for the show. Even
nonboxing fans are eager to catch whispers of Tyson's return.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps boxing ``does'' need this man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings interest into boxing,'' said Jeff Pomeroy, publicist
for Showtime Sports and Event programming. ``Not many boxers can
bring in many other people besides the fight fan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is ``the'' box office draw in boxing,'' said Ferdie
Pacheco, analyst for Showtime's Championship Boxing series.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers seem to bear out that statement.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson and Holyfield's second fight in the MGM Grand Garden, the
highest grossing fight in boxing history, raked in $14 million at
the gate and $2 million in pay-per-view sales, said Marc Ratner,
executive director of the Nevada State Athletic Commission. The
commission revoked Tyson's license for a year.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the Holyfield-Michael Moorer match four months
later at the Nevada-Las Vegas campus earned $5 million to $6
million at the gate and $600,000 to 700,000 in pay-per-view sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's staggering ... He's the biggest draw the sport has,''
Ratner said. ``When Mike fights, it's a front-page story, whereas
most other fights are just on the sports page.''
</P>
<P>
   When estimating Tyson's financial worth to boxing, consider that
in his first fight after being released from prison, Tyson earned
$25 million _ the largest purse ever at the time _ to fight the
less-than-formidable Peter McNeeley.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson fought six times in that two-year period for no less than
$10 million, earning a total of $140 million _ including $30
million to fight Holyfield twice.
</P>
<P>
   According to lawsuits filed against King, Tyson's former
promoter, 50 percent of Tyson's purses and contracts with Showtime
TV and MGM Grand Hotel-Casino came to $106 million.
</P>
<P>
   Said promoter Scott Sherman: ``A promoter can make money with
Tyson. He's important to boxing in that he's very controversial.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Tyson manager Bill Cayton said he agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's important to the boxing business,'' Cayton said.
``He's by far the top-seller in pay-per-view history.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pomeroy: ``When Mike is fighting, the world watches.
There's not many boxers who can bring the ratings he can.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Pomeroy, Tyson has been a part of seven of the top
10 pay-per-view events in history.
</P>
<P>
   How is Tyson's immense attraction explained? If he's so
undesirable to so many people, why do they continue to watch?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because people like train wrecks,'' Pacheco said. ``I've yet
to see anyone turn off TV because they didn't like someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Charley Steiner, an ESPN boxing analyst, said interest in Tyson
is not because of his fighting skill, or because he is a fan
favorite. Instead, it's because of ``a morbid curiosity about
Tyson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know what he's going to do,'' Steiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Pacheco added, ``He hasn't shown that he has the capacity to
take stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Steiner said Tyson is not the fighter he once was, making him
less important to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be the greatest attraction in all of sports,'' Steiner
said. ``But he's not as good a fighter anymore. People will tune in
to Tyson no matter what. Sadly, even Joe Louis was an attraction
past his prime. With Tyson you never know what you're going to get.
Who would have thought Tyson would be in this predicament now?''
</P>
<P>
   But can he be replaced?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody needs anybody. We are all replaceable. Life goes on,''
said Angelo Dundee, who trained Ali and Sugar Ray Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the sport survived the loss of Ali, Ratner noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened after Muhammad Ali?'' he said. ``The sport will
go on. The sport has to be bigger than its athletes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
