<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT HELP, THESE ANGELS HAVE NO PRAYER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels appear to be a team ready to fall apart. If
the Rangers can survive the next two weeks against the Yankees, Red
Sox and Indians, they could win the American League West going
away.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, disappointed that general manager Bill Bavasi failed
to make a significant move before the deadline, took another shot
when popular first baseman Cecil Fielder was designated for
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Fielder had been in a slump lately but he's a veteran with
playoff experience and had emerged in his first season with the
Angels as an important clubhouse leader. His departure upset
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things \RFielder\S does in this clubhouse
that people don't know about,'' catcher Phil Nevin told the ``Los
Angeles Times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taking away our best leader. He's the only guy who's
been through the wars of the World Series and won it. They brought
him in here to hit and for his leadership, and he's done both. I
don't know what else he could have done for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Fielder was a big part of the Angels winning 22 of 28 in June,
as he hit .295 with 12 homers and 29 runs batted in. But he was
batting .214 with three homers and 12 RBI in 25 games since.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, trying to shake things up, brought up third baseman
Troy Glaus from the minor leagues and moved Dave Hollins to first.
Fielder signed with the Angels to be their designated hitter, but
Tim Salmon is limited to that duty because a foot injury prevents
him from playing the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are in the division race because of what they did in
June. But outside of that month, they are 38-47 and have definite
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday, their starting pitchers had a combined earned-run
average of 4.81 and only Chuck Finley, 8-5 with a 3.06 ERA, has
kept the rotation from falling apart. The Angels were hoping to
trade for pitching help in Tim Belcher or Juan Guzman before the
trade deadline. Instead they settled for Jeff Juden, and they're
hoping Ken Hill can have an impact when he comes off the disabled
list at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill, 8-5 with a 5.15 ERA, didn't exactly inspire confidence
when he tried to deflect that pressure, saying, ``Who knows? I
could pitch worse.''
</P>
<P>
   A trade for Belcher is a possibility. He would have to clear
waivers but the Angels have the right to claim somebody before any
team with a better record, and it's unlikely a team out of
contention would claim Belcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have a terrific outfield with budding superstar Darin
Erstad, Jim Edmonds and Garret Anderson. But their infield is
mediocre, especially without Fielder, and the best they could do to
help their catching was pick up Charlie O'Brien from the White Sox.
He's on the disabled list with a bad thumb.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we have to do some things to shake things
up a little bit,'' Salmon said. ``This team needs to do something
to get it turned around. Everybody knows how badly we need to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody except Disney, apparently. The entertainment giant
that runs the Angels seems content to concentrate on marketing and
promotion and not to worry about the product. There has been talk
they'll pursue Mike Piazza in the off-season, but the Disney track
record makes that seem laughable.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the Rangers barely fought off the late-season
charge of the Seattle Mariners to win the division. This season,
even as tight as things seem, they could win it without a fight
unless the Angels do something to get their snoozing franchise
turned around.
POP UPS
Tribe troubles
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians have serious concerns about their starting
rotation. Going into the weekend, pitchers Jaret Wright, Dwight
Gooden, Bartolo Colon, Charles Nagy and Dave Burba were a combined
6-12 with a 5.62 ERA since the All-Star break. The Indians are
particularly concerned that Wright and Colon might have pitched too
much in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   There are few alternatives beyond reliever Steve Karsay. Chad
Ogea, who has been on the disabled list twice this season, was
optioned to Triple A, where he has developed a sore knuckle on his
pitching hand.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians pursued Randy Johnson but general manager John Hart
said the Mariners wanted Burba, reliever Paul Shuey, infielder
Enrique Wilson and outfielder Brian Giles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not tear the heart out of our major-league club to get
a guy who would be here for only 60 days,'' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   Hart said the Mariners tried to pit the Yankees against the
Indians, ``But neither team blinked.'' Hart said he was surprised
that the Astros got Johnson for prospects, something he hardly
talked about with the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers fans should watch the Indians carefully, particularly if
the Red Sox win the wild card. If the Rangers and Indians win their
divisions, the team with the better record will play the Red Sox in
the first round. The loser gets the New York Yankees. If the Angels
win the wild card, the Rangers will play the Indians in the first
round.
Piazza unhappy in NY
Mets catcher Mike Piazza seems determined to get out of New York as
a free agent at the end of the season. He has been booed by fans
and criticized severely by the local press for not driving in more
runs. He's also not happy the Mets haven't made an effort to
re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a tough town,'' Mets assistant general manager
Omar Minaya said. ``But we're going to try and re-sign him.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza isn't talking but teammates have been telling New York
writers that he's gone. There's also the belief that the Mets gave
reliever John Franco a two-year, $6 million extension to soften the
blow of Piazza's departure.
Padres go all-out
</P>
<P>
   The Padres showed again what a crucial season this is for them
by acquiring pitcher Randy Myers from the Toronto Blue Jays on
Thursday. The deal, for two minor-leaguers, committed them to $12
million the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres are hoping their terrific season convinces voters to
approve a $411 downtown million ballpark in November. The Padres
should win the National League West, but getting Myers the day
after he blew a save against the Rangers was done with an eye
toward postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Myers gives the Padres a good left-handed reliever to go with
closer Trevor Hoffman. The trade also keeps him away from the
Atlanta Braves, who are desperate for relief pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, because the Braves have a better record, had first
shot at claiming Myers off the waiver wire. They were worried that
if they didn't claim him, Atlanta would. That could have been the
difference should the teams meet in the postseason.
The Buzz
</P>
<P>
   Tigers general manager Randy Smith offered closer Todd Jones and
center fielder Brian Hunter to the Braves for troubled outfielder
Andruw Jones and was turned down. ... Pat Gillick is expected to
step down as Orioles general manager at the end of the season and
manager Ray Miller is campaigning for assistant GM Kevin Malone to
get the job. But Reds general manager Jim Bowden is also being
mentioned as a possibility. ... Power pitchers still create the
most excitement. Boston loves Pedro Martinez, the Astros are
ecstatic about getting Randy Johnson and Cubs rookie Kerry Wood has
been a huge hit this season. But Greg Maddux, on his way to a fifth
Cy Young Award, remains the best pitcher in baseball...
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals are a troubled franchise. None of the
prospective owners has offered the minimum $75 million purchase
price. Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt, who everybody was hoping would save
the franchise for Kansas City, has offered $52 million, with $25
million contingent upon improvements to Kauffman Stadium. ... The
Montreal Expos are encountering difficulty in getting a new
stadium. They sold fewer than 5,000 personal seat licenses in a
13-month period. They were hoping for 12,000 to 13,000. ...
</P>
<P>
   Cubs manager Jim Riggleman and general manager Ed Lynch had
their contracts picked up for 1999. But when Lynch included two
former No. 1 draft picks, pitchers Jon Garland and Todd Noel, in
deals for relievers Felix Heredia and Matt Karchner, it was a sign
he knows he must win soon or else. ... The Reds are close to
signing manager Jack McKeon to a one-year contract extension,
believing he is the best man to oversee their youth movement. ...
</P>
<P>
   Indians outfielder Brian Giles was sidelined last week after
being bitten five times in the left leg by what is believed to be a
spider. ... The second longest active consecutive games played
streak ended when Astros manager Larry Dierker sat Craig Biggio on
Wednesday night. Biggio, who had played in 494 consecutive games,
said, ``I took a lot of pride in it. I'm not going to lie and say I
wasn't disappointed it came to an end.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Yankees pitcher Orlando Hernandez has lost 15 pound since coming
to America, saying he has had trouble acquiring an appetite for
American food. His brother, Livan, was the opposite when he
arrived. He scared the Florida Marlins when he binged on Burger
King food before learning what a salad is. ... Phillies pitcher
Curt Schilling struck out at least 10 batters in 10 of his first 16
starts, but just twice in his past nine. During that stretch he is
3-4 with a 4.97 ERA. ...
</P>
<P>
   Devil Rays pitchers Tony Saunders and Bryan Rekar are the latest
to complain about Tropicana Field, which is a lousy facility. But
manager Larry Rothschild wasn't happy with the complaining, saying,
``If there are people who don't want to play here, all they have to
do is come in here and I'll give them their check and we'll get
them out of here. If they truly feel like they don't want to be
part of what we're trying to build here, then we'll do the best we
can to accommodate them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
