<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS EXPECT TRIO TO SPARK DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Willie Shaw, the Raiders' new defensive coordinator, Charles
Woodson, Eric Allen and Darrell Russell represent more than merely
the recent Heisman Trophy winner, a six-time Pro Bowl cornerback
and a future standout at defensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   They represent ants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in the ghetto,'' Shaw said to a reporter days before
the Raiders played the Cowboys in an exhibition game last night.
``And when I came home at night and turned on the light, the
roaches would scramble for cover. But the ants never stopped
marching. If you brushed them off the counter, they just climbed
back up and kept marching.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I want, players that just keep coming at you. I
don't want roaches, looking for excuses and blaming others.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Raiders coach Jon Gruden appointed Shaw to clean up a
Raiders defense that was always running for cover in 1997. The
Raiders allowed more yards rushing and passing than any team in the
NFL. They were 28th in points allowed.
</P>
<P>
   If we continue with Shaw's crude example, the roaches are
leaving Oakland. Malcontent defensive lineman Chester McGlockton,
troubled cornerback Larry Brown and aging cornerback Terry McDaniel
were released after the season.
</P>
<P>
   In their stead is Woodson, expected to win a starting cornerback
job; Allen, who came by trade from the Saints and is expected to be
the other starting corner; and Russell, the No. 2 pick in the 1997
draft who coaches say can be a star at defensive tackle after
spending his rookie season out of place at defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of roaches in the league,'' Shaw said. ``We're
going to be the ants.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Raiders, in the AFC West this season,
Denver and Kansas City are the anteaters. Bring on the Browns The
Cleveland Browns franchise can begin stocking players in February
to prepare for the 1999 season. The club can sign at least 30
veteran players from other NFL rosters in what is being called an
access draft. They'll be given 14 selections in the regular 1999
draft, including the first pick in each round, and a second pick in
rounds two through seven after all teams with a 1998 regular-season
winning percentage of less than .500. They will also get the final
selection in round seven.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the team needs an owner. The league is reviewing
applications from several bidders. The price is expected to near $1
billion. And if we're talking money alone, the favorite to own the
team is Alfred Lerner, 65, chairman of MBNA Corp. credit card
company.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner, who has teamed with former 49ers general manager Carmen
Policy, has a net worth that has been estimated at $2.5 billion.
His first job was selling furniture that paid him $75 a week. He
was a minority partner with Art Modell in the former Browns
franchise, and the deal to move the team to Baltimore was made on
Lerner's private jet.
</P>
<P>
   The other candidates to own the Browns are lawyer Larry Dolan,
67, whose ownership group includes entertainer Bill Cosby and
former Dolphins coach Don Shula; Cleveland Indians owner Richard
Jacobs, 73; Howard Milstein, 47, a New York real-estate developer
and part-owner of the New York Islanders whose partnership includes
Cowboys director of player development Calvin Hill and former
Browns wide receiver Paul Warfield; Thomas Murdough, 59, founder
and chairman of Cleveland-based toymaker Step 2 Co. who has asked
Michael Jordan to join his ownership group; and real-estate
developer Bart Wolstein, 71, who is backed by Hall of Fame running
back Jim Brown. Briefly The Tennessee Oilers announced recently
that they will change the team's name before the 1999 season. Club
owner Bud Adams will pick the name after a statewide advisory
council sorts through suggestions from fans statewide and after a
review by the NFL. ``The fans have shown us some tremendous
support,'' Adams said. ``They deserve this. We will have a new name
in 1999. It will truly be a Tennessee name.'' The name change will
mean a new logo and team colors. ... If you were not one of the 10
people in this region who checked out the Bengals-Giants preseason
game last night, you missed an oddity. They played the game at
Giants Stadium on grass. Real grass. The Giants and Jets will play
home games on the natural surface for the remainder of the
preseason schedule. The surface of Giants Stadium has been
artificial turf since it opened in 1976. Stadium officials one day
want to see whether the grass can withstand the rigors of a
Northeast winter. More than 6,000 plastic trays of grass weighing
1,100 pounds each were laid on the stadium's artificial surface.
The grass will be removed at the end of August in preparation for
the regular season.
</P>
</TEXT>
