<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DON'T FEAR BRACKET CREEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL and T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major League Baseball's luxury tax will not prevent the Rangers
from absorbing additional salary during the season's remaining
seven weeks, general manager Doug Melvin said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   President Tom Schieffer expects the Rangers' 1998 payroll _
which also includes signing bonuses, incentives attained and player
benefits _ to approach $65 million with the July acquisitions of
right-handers Todd Stottlemyre and Esteban Loaiza, third baseman
Todd Zeile and shortstop Royce Clayton. Those four additions
escalated the payroll approximately $2.78 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Rangers _ barring further additions _ expect to
avoid the luxury tax, assessed against the major leagues' five
highest payrolls. Avoiding the luxury tax, though, will not come
``at the expense of winning,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a level where you've got to be careful, though,'' he
said. ``It depends on the who the player is and what kind of impact
he would have.''
Trade upset Tatis
Fernando Tatis is trying to get over being traded by the Rangers
and adjusting to life with the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I get mad about it,'' Tatis said. ``When I first
heard about the trade, I couldn't believe it. I was in shock. ... I
didn't want to get traded. I wanted to play in Texas. But you don't
know where you're going to be in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatis and pitcher Darren Oliver were traded to the Cardinals for
pitcher Todd Stottlemyre and shortstop Royce Clayton on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I feel a stranger here,'' Tatis said Friday night
after getting three hits in the Cardinals' 16-3 victory against the
Chicago Cubs. ``I still hope the Rangers win. I hope they make the
playoffs and win the World Series because that's what we were
looking forward to doing.''
Replacing Stevens
Matchups will dictate how manager Johnny Oates utilizes the at-bats
that usually would go to designated hitter Lee Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers placed Stevens (strain, right oblique muscle) on the
15-day disabled list yesterday and purchased the contract of
outfielder Warren Newson from Triple-A Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   The reserves _ outfielders Roberto Kelly, Mike Simms and Newson,
infielders Luis Alicea and Domingo Cedeno and catcher Bill Haselman
_ will share the load.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to play everybody,'' Oates said. ``Everybody has
contributed, and this is a way to keep everyone sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who entered last night hitting .429 (3-for-7) with one
home run during his career against Boston right-hander Tim
Wakefield, started in right field. That allowed Oates to utilize
right fielder Juan Gonzalez as his designated hitter.
Searching for Angels
Right-hander Jeff Juden, whom Anaheim acquired Friday from
Milwaukee, will join the rotation, Angels manager Terry Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen, though, whom Juden (7-11, 5.53) will
replace. The candidates include right-hander Steve Sparks, Omar
Olivares and Jason Dickson and left-hander Allen Watson.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers, who received $20,000 and a player to be determined
for Juden, exposed the hard-throwing 6-foot-8 right-hander to
waivers because ``he just wasn't getting the job done,'' Brewers
manager Phil Garner said. Nevertheless, the New York Yankees also
claimed Juden.
Farm report
</P>
<P>
   Triple-A Oklahoma (Pacific Coast League): The RedHawks (61-53)
swept a double-header of seven-inning games from New Orleans on
Friday. Right-hander Terry Clark and left-hander Ricky Pickett
pitched complete games for the 4-1 and 4-0 victories, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Double-A Tulsa (Texas League): Left-hander Corey Lee (8-8, 4.87)
surrendered only three hits, but he allowed five runs and issued
six walks in 72/3 innings as the Drillers (62-57) lost to Arkansas,
5-2.
</P>
<P>
   Class-A Savannah (South Atlantic League): The Sand Gnats (58-62)
beat Columbus, 5-4, as second baseman Jason Romano went 3-for-4
with a run batted in and scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   Pulaski (Appalachian League, rookie): The Rangers (19-29) beat
Princeton, 11-7. Center fielder Corey Wright went 3-for-5 with two
triples and two RBI and scored four times.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Coast (Gulf Coast League, rookie): The Rangers (24-19) beat
the Pirates, 16-2. Left fielder Cody Nowlin went 2-for-5 with four
RBI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
