<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BATTERS FIND RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Faced with the prospect of taking on Texas's
All-Star starting pitcher, Red Sox batters practically raced each
other to the plate in an 11-1 win over the Rangers Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Aaron Sele's name evokes something less than fear
from those who know him best.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Bragg led off against his former mate with a home run _
the first time this season a Red Sox hitter has opened a game by
going deep. An inning later, John Valentin hit a two-run homer, and
Sele was gone before the end of the fifth as the Red Sox won at The
Ballpark in Arlington for the first time in five tries this season.
</P>
<P>
   Bragg, Jimy Williams's choice to lead off with Darren Lewis
being given the night off, homered again in the eighth inning off
Rangers reliever Al Levine, capping the biggest offensive night of
his career. He went 4 for 6, scored four runs, and hit two home
runs in a game for the first time. Bragg singled in the second and
doubled in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Bragg came to the plate in the ninth with a chance for a fifth
hit, but Rangers third baseman Todd Zeile made a diving stop and
threw him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already tough to live with,'' said Sox designated hitter
Mike Stanley. ``He told us he's not making enough money to do this
every night. I told him if he did do this every night, he would
make more money.''
</P>
<P>
   All in jest, of course, as the victory did wonders to raise the
level of levity in the Red Sox clubhouse. Stanley, Mo Vaughn, and
Nomar Garciaparra had three hits apiece as Boston broke loose for
18 hits after scoring just 10 runs in its last four games. The Sox
ended the AL West-leading Rangers' six-game winning streak and now
hold a 7 1/2-game lead over both Anaheim and Baltimore in the
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Wakefield, meanwhile, assured the Red Sox of returning home
with a winning record on this 14-day, 12-game trip, shutting out
the Rangers through five innings while his teammates built an 8-0
lead against Sele and Levine. The win gave Boston a 7-4 record on
the trip, with only Sunday night's game here left to be played.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a long road trip,'' said Wakefield, who despite
a game-time temperature of 94 degrees pitched eight innings,
allowing just seven hits and two walks. ``It's wearing on a lot of
guys, especially me. I'm looking forward to going back to Boston.
This was huge, especially this late in the year, that we've picked
up as many wins as we have on this trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The win was Wakefield's eighth in his last 10 decisions and 14th
of the season, only two shy of his career best in 1995, when he
went 16-8. That puts him within talking distance, at least, of the
first 20-win season of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The last knuckleballer to win 20 in a season was Joe Niekro of
the Astros in 1980. Wilbur Wood of the White Sox, who won 20 or
more in four straight seasons (1971-74), is the last American
League knuckleballer to win 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be nice, but I'm not thinking about that right
now,'' Wakefield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it's possible,'' said Stanley, assessing Wakefield's
chances at 20 wins. ``You talk to anybody around the league _ when
we were in Seattle I heard Jay Buhner say he was so glad he didn't
have to face him. He'd rather face Pedro Martinez. When he's going
this good, nobody wants to face him.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sele, who opened the season 8-2 and was 12-5 when
selected to the All-Star team, has lost four of his last five
decisions, none of which have been pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Bragg has been Sele's principal tormentor on the Red Sox. He's
batting .600 (6 for 10) against the righthander with three home
runs and two doubles. In his first at-bat Saturday night, he leaped
on a 2-and-0 fastball, driving it onto the putting green beyond the
center-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen him pitch,'' said Bragg. ``We know what he's got.
When he makes his pitches, he's tough. But he fell behind me a
couple of times and threw me pitches to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   One out after Bragg's home run, Vaughn followed with the first
of his three singles and came around on singles by Troy O'Leary and
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin made it 4-0 in the second, following Bragg's single
with his 14th home run.
</P>
<P>
   Sele's night came to an abrupt end in the fifth, which opened
with singles by Vaughn and Garciaparra. Pitching coach Dick Bosman
paid a visit to the mound, but his advice obviously went unheeded
as Sele walked O'Leary on four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, who had three RBIs Saturday night in his best game
since being reacquired, greeted Levine with a two-run single that
made it 6-0, and Donnie Sadler's double brought home O'Leary with
the seventh run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I needed the ball down, the ball was up,'' Sele said.
``When I needed the ball in, the ball was out over the plate. This
was just a case of not making it very difficult for them to hit the
ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
