<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-CREW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREW CRUSH REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Two Revolution rejects in Columbus Crew
uniforms contributed to New England's worst loss of the season
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Stern John, a 21-year-old Trinidadian striker, scored twice and
Andy Williams, a 20-year-old Jamaican, sparked the midfield as the
Crew took a 6-1 victory before 13,712. Both failed Revolution
tryouts, John before the 1997 season and Williams in December.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have the worst record in Major League Soccer,
with 19 points in 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night they contributed to their downfall by failing to
build on their positive play in Wednesday's 3-0 victory over San
Jose. They failed to play through Colombian midfielder Oscar
Pareja, partly because of the small Ohio Stadium field, and also
because of their tendency to lose patience.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Crew solidified their third-place Eastern
Conference standing, improving to 30 points in 21 games. The
Revolution could not match the midfield magic of Williams, the
striking dynamics of John and US national team forward Brian
McBride, or the defensive organization of the Crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an old-fashioned spanking and because of our record,
it gets magnified,'' Revolution coach Thomas Rongen said. ``Every
team is a recipient of a spanking like this. We got our asses
kicked in all departments.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution will likely have to win in regulation time at
Tampa Bay Friday to remain in playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go forward,'' Rongen said. ``What else can you do?
I've seen games like this before because we become very
helter-skelter, and that havoc can lead to a lot of goals. We felt
good going into the game. We made two lineup changes, but that was
not the reason for what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution were missing two starters from the San Jose game
_ Mike Burns (right hamstring) and Janusz Michallik (left foot
sprain) _ but the others who had keyed that victory were
ineffective. They might have had difficulty adjusting to the field,
but that does not explain the effectiveness of Williams, who was
making his home debut.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Farrell scored the first goal, curling a 30-yarder from
the left into the far upper corner as goalkeeper Ian Feuer held his
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's dribbling set up a corner kick by Robert Warzycha
that was headed in for a two-goal lead by John in the 32d minute.
</P>
<P>
   Nine minutes later, New England's Richard Goulooze and Dahir
Mohammed failed to connect on a clearance, and McBride headed in
another Warzycha corner for a 3-0 halftime edge.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution had several chances but did not seem as dangerous
as the Crew.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Dooley headed in a short corner from Williams early in
the second half, and Rob Smith and John stretched the Columbus
advantage to 6-0 before Raul Diaz Arce scored his 16th goal of the
season in the 89th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one area that surprised me was dead-ball situations,''
Rongen said. ``We had strength and players who are very good in the
air in the game. But they scored on corners, and that changed the
course of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Revolution can match the creativity of the Williamses
of the MLS, they are going to struggle. Williams, who played for
Jamaica in the World Cup after attending the University of Rhode
Island, performed with confidence and poise and constantly
frustrated the Revolution. Williams disoriented the Revolution with
quick touches and changes of direction, and his teammates
responded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
