<SLUG> BC-BBN-LEBRETON-COL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAN REACTION TO JOHNSON IS ASTRO-NOMICAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With the great left-hander pitching, the Astrodome was
sold out. Hotel rooms were scarce. The city was abuzz.
</P>
<P>
   I remember it like yesterday. We were kids. My best friend's dad
had just driven four of us for six hours in a Plymouth Fury without
air conditioning. We trudged from ``No Vacancy'' sign to ``No
Vacancy'' sign for two hours, until we found a far-too-princely
room at the posh Shamrock Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   My friend's dad was still wincing as he came back to the car.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, that June 22, 1966, night still represented
the largest regular-season crowd ever to witness a baseball game in
the Astrodome. The audience, we all knew, wasn't there so much to
see the still-expansion-pained Astros, but to view first-hand lefty
Sandy Koufax and the star-studded Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   But so has been the journey of the starship Astros.
</P>
<P>
   For 36 years, they have been the other guys. It was their
siblings in the 1962 expansion, the New York Mets, who rose from
futility to snatch the Cinderella slipper before the Astros. It was
the Astros who were always headed to Virginia. It was the Astros
who lost Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   In June of this season, Astros players marveled at the nightly
crowds that flocked to see Mark McGwire of the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``But let me tell you the big difference tonight,'' first
baseman Jeff Bagwell said, as he stood at his locker before
Friday's game with the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, people are coming to watch one of our guys.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-10, and armed with the wingspan of a left-handed
pterodactyl, Randy Johnson is a lot to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes before game time Friday, Johnson slowly walked to
the bullpen to begin his pregame warmups. Suddenly, bodies began to
rise from their seats and a crescendo of applause started to rain
down. Johnson was getting a standing ovation _ just for leaning
over, stretching.
</P>
<P>
   In the field-level seats, Carol Weatherly of Lake Charles, La.,
sat with her boyfriend and her 9-year-old son, Thomas. They had
driven from Louisiana that afternoon. They had trouble finding a
hotel room. They, too, were there to see a sensational left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas held a freshly printed Randy Johnson pennant and Carol
clutched a folded navy blue T-shirt with Johnson's lanky silhouette
and his nickname, ``The Big Unit,'' loudly splashed across the
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been Astros fans since the Jose Cruz and Terry Puhl
days,'' Weatherly said. ``We come once every year in June.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Weatherly and her boyfriend Jim heard on the radio that
Johnson was pitching Friday, they looked at one another and said,
``We have to go.'' She called the doctor's office where she works
and faked a sore throat and fever.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson Fever. Houston never felt so good.
</P>
<P>
   Even to the Astros players, his coming had seemed like a dream.
Outfielder Moises Alou went to bed early on the night of the
trading deadline, July 31, and didn't hear about the deal with
Seattle until he got on the team bus the next day in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Sure, right,' '' Alou recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Craig Biggio had given up the vigil and turned
the TV channel. The hotel alarm clock read 12:15, 15 minutes past
the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up,'' Biggio said. ``Then somebody called me and said,
`Well, you've got Randy Johnson.' I said, `Get outta here!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The deal was so staggering _ the players figured that Johnson
would be dealt to the Yankees or Indians _ that two days later in
Pittsburgh, they found it odd to believe that the stork-like No. 51
wearing an Astros uniform was actually one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the attention I'm getting is kind of embarrassing,''
Johnson confessed Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Astros fans were just as curious. The crowd to watch his
Astrodome debut Friday, 52,071, broke the record as the largest to
ever see a regular-season Astros home game. At 9 a.m., there were
fans standing in the rain outside the Astrodome, waiting to buy the
few remaining tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Astrodome vendors stocked 15,000 additional hot dogs in
anticipation of the big crowd. In the dome gift shop, racks of new
shirts hung waiting. For $190, you could get the official home
jersey, replete with Johnson's name and number. For those with a
more Marlinesque budget, there were eight new styles of Johnson
T-shirts. Three colors of caps. Souvenir picture baseballs. And the
pennants.
</P>
<P>
   There were peanuts but, curiously, no elephants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd call it a little bit of a circus atmosphere,'' Johnson
observed.
</P>
<P>
   After his route-going, five-hit, ovation-studded outing, Johnson
was quick to embrace a broader perspective. Though the reception as
he went to warm up made him ``feel like a rock star,'' Johnson
stressed later that his new team is not a one-man gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little overwhelmed by all the attention this has
gotten,'' he said, humbly. ``But whether I'm here or not, the fans
should be coming out and supporting this team, because this is a
championship-caliber team.''
</P>
<P>
   He had heard the stories about Houston attendance, too, it
seemed. The Astros have been the class of the National League
Central this season, but before Johnson arrived, they had performed
in front of a home crowd in excess of 40,000 only five times.
</P>
<P>
   Astros fans, Houstonians say, are waiting for the playoffs. Or
they are waiting for the year 2000, when the downtown,
retractable-roofed The Ballpark at Union Station will open its
gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Bagwell. ``Fan support has been better
this year. You've got to win. But even if you're winning during the
regular season, don't automatically assume that they're going to
come out and watch you play.''
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, it has been suggested that Johnson was acquired
more as an Astrodome drawing card than anything.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson half-winced. ``If that was the case,'' he said, ``then
I'd almost feel like a freak show.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that he is the center of all this commotion seems to
unsettle Johnson. He says he's a quiet, shy guy _ ``People say I'm
a loner'' _ and doesn't like to call any attention to himself.
</P>
<P>
   But he tried to go out to dinner Thursday night in Houston and
soon found himself signing autographs. He also attempted to browse
The Galleria anonymously. For obvious reasons, that didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got a haircut, so it couldn't have been the hair,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, his new teammates have welcomed him warmly. Since when
don't we all love a circus, Biggio suggested?
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a No. 1 horse here,'' Biggio said. ``Now we've got
one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unique,'' said fellow pitcher Jose Lima. ``That's why
he's The Big Unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting quietly at his locker after Friday's dominating shutout,
Johnson was gracious to his former team, the Seattle Mariners,
thanking the fans and praising the likes of Junior Griffey and
Edgar Martinez. But the talk about the contract, Johnson admitted,
had become a season-long distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like night and day,'' he said. ``Now I can focus.
Not that I wasn't trying to focus in Seattle, but there was a lot
going on. I feel bad for the fans and for my teammates back there,
because there was _ not a dark cloud _ but something hovering over
the team all year. Where is he going to go? Is he going to go?
</P>
<P>
   ``But that part is over now. I'm a Houston Astro. I'm proud of
putting this uniform on.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, like the Astros franchise, longs for the elusive. He
says the ultimate would be a World Series. No one Friday night
dared remind him that, for want of a fat contract, Johnson left
what was supposed to be a Series contender in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The night was too filled with history, too illuminated by
flashbulbs, to dwell on that. Johnson lingered for nearly an hour,
answering a handful of reporters' questions, taking care to say the
right things.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of history in this dome,'' the lefty said. ``You
feel pretty excited about pitching on the same mound where some of
the people I've looked up to have pitched _ people like J.R.
Richard and Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching out there tonight was very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The night had been a loud reminder of what the Astros had done.
They had pulled off the trade deadline's most technicolor coup.
</P>
<P>
   They are armed for the Braves, for the Padres, maybe even for
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe just for the circus.
</P>
</TEXT>
