<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-CHAMPIONS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNORS HURT; LECONTE, GOMEZ IN FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
 TOURNEY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ Jimmy Connors, the No. 1-ranked player on the
Nuveen Tour for players age 35 and older, dropped out of the Sprint
PCS tennis tournament at Babson College Saturday night, minutes
before he was to face No. 4 seed Andres Gomez in a semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy has plantar fasciitis,'' said Glen Hunt, the event's
trainer, describing the soft tissue inflammation of Connors's left
foot. Connors reported the injury Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Connors earns $12,500 for reaching the semifinals. The
tournament winner will get $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Guillermo Vilas, who had lost to Connors in a quarterfinal
Thursday, was originally pegged as Connors's replacement, but tour
officials could not locate Vilas, so No. 3 seed Mansour Bahrami,
another quarterfinal loser, went against Gomez _ and lost before
1,782 fans, 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez will go for the championship Sunday against Henri Leconte,
who defeated Johan Kriek, 7-5, 6-4, before 1,337 in the afternoon
session of the hardcourt tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Leconte, who turned 35 July 4 and was playing his first American
event on the Nuveen Tour, used a clever service-return game to
frustrate the serve-and-volley game of Kriek.
</P>
<P>
   The key to playing Kriek, according to Leconte, is to not simply
sock his serves back at him. ``He plays solid and has a nice
game,'' said the Frenchman, a 1988 French Open finalist who last
month won his first senior tournament, in Aland, Finland, with a
three-set win over Bjorn Borg. ``He loves to hit the ball, so you
have to mix it up. You have to spin, throw in a lot of slices, go
with the topspin, and you have to change the pace all the time. He
loves to win when you hit the ball hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Kriek was having problems with the serves themselves.
``If I had served better, I would have won,'' said Kriek, who
reached the Nuveen Masters Championship final last year. ``He was
ripping on my second serve. I served in spurts _ well for two or
three games and then I had a bad game. When you think too much
about your serve, there's no rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   The first set had five breaks, three by Leconte. ``We didn't
serve very well,'' Leconte said, ``with the balls flying towards
Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   The final break was in the 11th game. Leconte went ahead, 0-40,
and after he missed on a backhand return that floated wide, Kriek
double-faulted, making it 6-5. Leconte served for the set for the
second time, this time successfully.
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, Kriek surrendered another key break, in the
fifth game. Leconte took the game by belting a forehand into the
open court, prompting a forehand from Kriek that was long.
</P>
<P>
   That opened the door for Leconte to take the match in straight
sets, and he finished the job in the 10th game, belting a forehand
winner up the line and following it with a backhand volley winner.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Connors has had to drop out of a
Nuveen Tour event. In March, at the Masters Championship in Naples,
Fla., he dropped out because of upper respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
   Connors has won three Nuveen tournaments this season: the Trigon
Champions in Richmond, Va., the BTI Champions in Raleigh, N.C., and
The Challenge in Newport Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Connors cofounded the Nuveen Tour in August 1993 _ he sold his
ownership interest last year _ and has played since its inception.
He has won 30 senior events following a regular men's tour career
in which he captured 139 singles titles. At one point, he was
ranked No. 1 on the men's tour for 268 weeks. Last month, he was
inducted into the International Tennis Hall of Fame in Newport,
R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Connors is expected to begin treatment immediately so that he
can compete in the Nuveen Tour's next event, the Citibank Champions
Aug. 11-16 in Purchase, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``My foot's not good,'' Connors said from his hotel room, ``and
hopefully in a couple of days it will give me a chance to play in
New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
