<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS RALLY IN NINTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _Raul Mondesi's return boosted the Dodgers' hopes
Saturday, but it was Eric Young's clutch hitting that lifted their
spirits when Mondesi and the rest of L.A's designated run producers
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers headed into the bottom of the ninth inning facing a
1-0 deficit and a potentially morale-crushing loss to the
Pittsburgh Pirates. But a better-late-than-never offense arrived at
Dodger Stadium around 10 p.m., with Young delivering a
game-winning, one-out RBI single to clinch a 2-1 victory before
what was left of a crowd of 45,187.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably would have been hard to bounce back the next day.
That would have been a tough loss,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a potentially devastating loss turned into a positively
inspiring victory, as the Dodgers won their second straight to move
within four games of the Chicago Cubs in the National League
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you lose 1-0, it would have been a tough loss,'' said
Dodger starter Dave Mlicki. ``Anytime you can win in the bottom of
the ninth, it's a good feeling. Everybody leaves the park with a
good feeling, everybody's excited to come back (the next day).''
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki felt pretty good despite failing to get a decision. The
right-hander pitched seven-plus strong innings, giving up four
hits, four walks and one earned run.
</P>
<P>
   He was matched pitch for pitch by Pirates right-hander Jon
Lieber, who saw his eight innings of solid work go to waste when
relievers Jason Christiansen (2-3) and Mike Williams surrendered
the clinching hits.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros led off the ninth with a single up the middle off
Lieber. With one out, Adrian Beltre singled off Christiansen, and
Charles Johnson drove in the tying run with a single to shallow
right field.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates intentionally walked Roger Cedeno to load the bases,
and Young _ hitless until that point _ made them pay with a single
to shallow right center off Williams, making a winner of Dodgers
reliever Antonio Osuna (7-0).
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers didn't expect they would need a come-from-behind
victory when manager Glenn Hoffman put together the lineup card.
Mondesi, recovered from a sore back, returned from a two-game
absence and returned the heart of the Dodgers lineup to full
strength for the first time in four days.
</P>
<P>
   But 3-4-5 hitters Mondesi, Gary Sheffield and Karros managed
only two hits in 12 at-bats. Mondesi's presence was felt mainly on
defense, and not always for the better.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi went 1 for 4 with three strikeouts, was caught stealing
on the back end of a double play and made a pair of aesthetic
catches in center field. But he also committed a costly throwing
error in the sixth inning that allowed the Pirates to take the 1-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   With the game locked in a scoreless tie and no outs in the sixth
inning, the Pirates' Tony Womack walked, then stole second. A
Johnson pickoff attempt skipped into center field, and Womack,
barely hesitating, headed for third, testing Mondesi's cannon arm.
But Mondesi misfired, and the throw bounced past Beltre and into
the Dodgers dugout, sending Womack home and providing a 1-0 lead
that nearly held up.
</P>
<P>
   ``To lose that way,'' Mlicki said, ``would have been a tough
thing to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleared to play less than an hour before game time, Mondesi's
sore lower back survived a pair of running, lunging catches. In the
fourth inning, Mondesi made a charging snag of Jose Guillen's
sinking liner into shallow center field, then doubled Kevin Young
off first base to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi followed with a highlight-reel catch in the fifth,
making a sliding grab of Lieber's line drive into left-center field
to end that inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman admitted some trepidation, especially since it was
Mondesi, not the medical staff, who gave the back a passing grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking to see if he got up,'' Hoffman said of the two
catches.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers managed 11 hits despite the scoring struggles and
had a scoring opportunity snuffed in the eighth inning. With two
outs and Mark Grudzielanek on second base, Sheffield hit a 320-foot
foul ball, but left fielder Al Martin made a flying, Fosbury-flop
catch in the first row of seats to end the inning and the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also had a chance in the fourth inning, when Mondesi
led off with a double. But Sheffield struck out and Mondesi was
gunned down by Jason Kendall on the steal attempt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
