<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4967 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     08-09 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Aug. 16.)  
 (HLW)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; TRAIL FEVER: SPIN DOCTORS, RENTED STRANGERS, AND THUMB
WRESTLERS ON THE ROAD TO THE WHITE HOUSE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Lewis. Vintage, $14.
</P>
<P>
   In reporting on the 1996 presidential campaign, the author
details the nearly farcical demands of politics in the television
age and discovers more wisdom and bravery among those at the bottom
of the political food chain than at the top. The result is
``deeper, funnier and more edifying'' than the usual insider
account of life on the hustings, Phil Gailey said in the Book
Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REALITY AND DREAMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Muriel Spark. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $12.
</P>
<P>
   A hopelessly spoiled film director is tempted to play God, with
ruinous results _ not for him but for his extended ``family.'' Dame
Muriel Spark, through the voice of her all-knowing narrator, is
``as relentlessly observant of human habits and unguarded moments
as she has ever been,'' Penelope Fitzgerald wrote here last year.
An earlier novel,  &UR; THE GIRLS OF SLENDER MEANS &LR;  (New Directions,
$10.95), follows the escapades of a varied group of young women
living at a ladies' hostel in London after the Allied victory in
Europe. In 1963 our reviewer, Virgilia Peterson, praised the
author's ``absolute pitch in dialogue, her economy of style and her
sedulous avoidance of sentiment.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEWS OF A KIDNAPPING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Gabriel Garca Marquez.
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Edith Grossman. Penguin, $13.95.
</P>
<P>
   The 1982 Nobel laureate in literature chronicles the brazen
series of crimes committed by Pablo Escobar's Colombian cocaine
cartel as it sought to undermine efforts to extradite Escobar and
his fellow drug lords to the United States. Last year our reviewer,
Robert Stone, said the author had ``a quick eye for the
illuminating detail and a capacity for assembling fact.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TUMBLE HOME: A NOVELLA AND SHORT STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Amy Hempel. Scribner, $10.
</P>
<P>
   This slender collection features minimalist stories about
parenthood, death and breakups, written as if assembled from
fragments of conversation. ``Hempel writes with an effortless wit
... showing us the larger shapes of our lives by capturing their
most fleeting and fragmentary moments,'' Elizabeth Gleick wrote
here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TWENTIETH CENTURY: A PEOPLE'S HISTORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Howard Zinn. Harper Perennial, $15.
</P>
<P>
   In this abridged version of ``A People's History of the United
States'' (1980), which has been updated into the Clinton years, a
scholar takes sides with the losers, the downtrodden and the
underdogs, arguing that too much history is written from the point
of view of governments and elites. In his review of the original,
Eric Foner found the approach to be limited, but said ``Zinn writes
with an enthusiasm rarely encountered in the leaden prose of
academic history.'' The same publisher has reissued  &UR; THE AMERICAN
CENTURY: VARIETIES OF CULTURE IN MODERN TIMES &LR; , by Norman F. Cantor
($16), a sprawling guided tour of the century that was first
published in 1988 and has also been revised and updated. In
managing to cram in just about every notable trend, event and
discipline, this is an ``opinionated, idiosyncratic and thoroughly
entertaining'' survey, Hal Goodman said here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CARSON VALLEY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Bill Barich. Vintage Contemporaries, $14.
</P>
<P>
   Set against the shifting economic landscape of the wine country
of northern California, this love story centers on a troubled young
woman who returns from New York and has an affair with the manager
of her father's vineyard. In 1997 our reviewer, Linda Gray Sexton,
admired the author's ``easy grace'' and ``elegant sleight of
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LADY WHO LIKED CLEAN REST ROOMS: THE CHRONICLE OF ONE OF
THE STRANGEST STORIES EVER TO BE RUMOURED ABOUT AROUND NEW YORK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By J.P. Donleavy. St. Martin's Griffin, $9.95.
</P>
<P>
   Jocelyn Guenevere Marchantiere Jones, a fresh-mouthed
43-year-old Scarsdale matron and Daughter of the Confederacy, finds
herself slipping down the social ladder after her husband deserts
her for a bit of ``fresh flesh.'' Her travails make for a ``rich,
ribald and touching creation,'' Nina Sonenberg wrote here last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NOEL COWARD: A BIOGRAPHY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Philip Hoare. University of Chicago, $18.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on both careful research and gossip, the author
maintains that the public image of Noel Coward as a languid
hedonist was a fiction _ the actor, playwright, songwriter and
world-class wit was driven by an intense passion for fame. ``One of
the many merits of ... Hoare's book is to remind us of the man's
self-discipline, his rigorous professionalism and his courage,''
Miranda Seymour wrote here in 1996.  &UR; IN GHOST OF A CHANCE: A
MEMOIR &LR; , by Peter Duchin with Charles Michener (Random House,
$16.95), the last society bandleader tells the bizarre story of how
he was left by his father, the bandleader Eddy Duchin, to be raised
under the privileged wing of Averell Harriman. In 1996 our
reviewer, George W.S. Trow, called this a ``brave and stylish''
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CALCUTTA CHROMOSOME: A NOVEL OF FEVERS, DELIRIUM &AMP;
DISCOVERY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Amitav Ghosh. Bard/Avon, $6.99.
</P>
<P>
   This mazelike thriller about weird science projects and global
mind control begins when a computer programmer in 21st-century
Manhattan stumbles onto the damaged ID card of a former colleague
who disappeared in Calcutta in 1995. Last year our reviewer, James
Saynor, called this ``a finely carved mystery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
