 AM-NYT-BUDGET
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Aug. 10:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questions or reruns: (212) 556-1927. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken (E-mail:
hewarn(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   The evening supervisor is Pat Ryan (E-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   The late supervisor is Sam Weiss (E-mail:
saweis(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Technical problems: &LR;  Peter Trigg.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA BOMBINGS:
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-BOMBINGS (Nairobi, Kenya) _ American diplomats, soldiers,
intelligence officers and law-enforcement personnel from around the
world streamed into Nairobi on Sunday to shore up a shell-shocked
American Embassy, secure the shattered mission and search for clues
in the terrorist bombing that killed at least 190 people and
injured more than 4,000. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-VICTIMS (Nairobi, Kenya) _ African families grieve for
those lost in the bombings. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-EMBASSY (Nairobi, Kenya) _ A reconstruction of what was
happening inside the American Embassy when the bomb went off. By
Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S. (Washington) _ Albright, Cohen, Berger, Pickering on
the Sunday talk shows; plus Washington developments on the
bombings. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-TERROR (Washington) _ Questions about the blasts, most of
them unanswered: what did the terrorists want; why they did it; why
they did it in Africa; what it means; why no credible group has yet
stepped forward to take credit. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-EVACUATE (Landstuhl, Germany) _ Injured Americans and
Kenyan Embassy employees arrive in Germany for medical aid. By
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-TANZANIA (Dar es Salaam) _ Investigation developments in
Dar es Salaam. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-VICTIMS-U.S. (Undated) _ The U.S. victims and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INTERNATIONAL:
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-RWANDA (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ A pilot's account gives
the lie to the official Rwandan story of non-involvement in latest
fighting in the Democratic Republic of Congo. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (Undated) _ The U.N. Special Commission suspends arms
inspections of new sites in Iraq after Baghdad's decision to halt
cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-U.S. (Washington) _ The United States hopes that, with
a new president in Colombia, relations will improve. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ The new Palestinian Cabinet is
approved. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-POLITICS (Bangkok, Thailand) _ Post-election
intimidation of the opposition continues. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   NAPALM-DISPOSAL (Deer Park, Texas) _ Four months ago, after
local residents and politicians screamed bloody murder, a train
carrying 22,000 gallons of napalm en route to an Indiana disposal
facility was abruptly halted and turned back to California, where
it had been moldering since the end of the Vietnam War. In July,
another toxic waste company inherited the napalm disposal contract.
But this time the company, GNI Group, is situated along Houston's
heavily industrialized Ship Channel, one of the globe's largest and
densest concentrations of petro-chemical facilities. The result was
that very same shipment of napalm eased its way into Texas three
weeks ago with only the briefest flurry of complaint.
</P>
<P>
   HATTERAS-LIGHTHOUSE (Cape Hatteras, N.C.) _ The U.S. Park
Service wants to move the Hatteras Light, the candy-striped tower
that is the most recognizable lighthouse in America, to save it
from the ever-advancing sea. But residents and business owners in
this part of the Outer Banks say that moving the lighthouse will
destroy its character, and hurt tourism. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PHONE-STRIKE (New York) _ Developments in the Bell Atlantic
strike.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INQUIRY (Washington) _ As the Starr inquiry continues,
we take a look at how it evolved from a land-deal investigation
into a sex inquiry; and talk to prosecutors about the way Starr
handled the transformation. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   Tentative.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-POLITICS (Washington) _ Republicans go home for summer
with divisions as deep, though not as vocal, as last year's. Fault
lines between social conservatives and business conservatives get
deeper and mess up all kinds of legislation. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Dateline TK) _ Commentary by Bob Herbert;
details later.
</P>
<P>
   William Safire and Anthony Lewis are on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moving later: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET -- A rundown of culture, lifestyle, sports,
and special section stories; will move by 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER -- A list of stories being considered by
New York Times editors for Page 1; will move at 4:30 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT -- Stories scheduled for Page 1; will
move by 7 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT -- A description of the front page layout of
the first edition of The New York Times; will move at 7:30 p.m. ET.
</P>
