<HEADER>
A5053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAR-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT     08-09 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR MOVIES: THE HORROR AND HONOR OF A GOOD WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Restoring the nation's heroic image of itself probably wasn't
what Steven Spielberg had in mind when he was preparing and
directing ``Saving Private Ryan.'' It's more likely that he simply
wanted to make an accurate, entertaining movie about a war the
country could be proud of. The film was to be a tribute to the
courage and sacrifices of those American soldiers who, along with
(mostly unacknowledged) Allied forces, swarmed up the beaches of
Normandy on June 6, 1944, to begin the final phase of World War II
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The completed movie is all Spielberg could have hoped it would
be, and more. Once again he has made a connection to the American
public of almost messianic proportions. Among other things, he
seems also to have fulfilled a national longing that maybe even he
wasn't aware of: to wipe clean the collective American conscience
after the trauma of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing he has even revived a type of patriotic war movie
you might think went out of fashion for all time with ``Heartbreak
Ridge.'' That was Clint Eastwood's gloriously foolish attempt to
celebrate the 1983 American landings on the sleepy little island of
Grenada as the equivalent to the invasion of Iwo Jima.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, war movies for every occasion: gung-ho
movies designed to keep the home front united behind the fighting
men, peacetime war movies that are all rousing action and
adventure, and the occasional pageantlike spectacles, exemplified
by ``The Longest Day,'' that re-create the war as a huge,
impersonal diorama, populated by Hollywood A- and B-list actors
representing historical personages and the little guys who are
history's pawns. The rarity: the maverick movie that shows the
waste of war (``All Quiet on the Western Front,'' from 1930, and
``Paths of Glory,'' 1957).
</P>
<P>
   As melancholy and as skeptical as those two films are, neither
comes close to dramatizing the dubiousness of war as it's seen in
the best of the Vietnam movies, but they have something going for
them that no other American war movies ever had: They are about a
war that was lost even before it got going, that was waged in
behalf of a cause never made comprehensible and that promised a
victory impossible to achieve. The war itself was a bestial
metaphor for all wars, even those that are won.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Saving Private Ryan,'' war is good again.
</P>
<P>
   Gone as if by absolution are the nightmare memories of our
involvement in Southeast Asia. So, too, apparently, are the
memories of four haunting, shame-inducing films made about that
war: Oliver Stone's ``Platoon'' and ``Born on the Fourth of July,''
Stanley Kubrick's ``Full Metal Jacket'' and Brian De Palma's
``Casualties of War,'' the only profoundly angry antiwar films ever
produced within the American filmmaking establishment.
</P>
<P>
   It was not an accident that none of these films was made until
the second half of the 1980s. By that time, Vietnam was behind us,
and one could recognize the idiocies of that war without feeling
guilt that one might be betraying the troops. They were
exceptionally good films, respectfully received, but maybe more
important, they also served as a kind of public penance. (Try as
John Wayne did with his 1968 cry from the heart, ``The Green
Berets,'' not even he could persuade Americans to swallow the idea
that Vietnam was the last chance to stop a communist assault on
Southern California.)
</P>
<P>
   How war movies are accepted by the public reflects the times in
which they're released. ``The Green Berets'' flopped because
audiences in 1968 were more into flowers than defoliation. Even
``Heartbreak Ridge'' was something of a disappointment considering
the enormous popularity of its star. But that was in 1986, in the
high-flying, luxe-loving Reagan era. If audiences at that time had
any image in their minds of Grenada, it was of a pretty little
Caribbean island where you might once have headed if you couldn't
get reservations on Mustique.
</P>
<P>
   The box-office success of ``Saving Private Ryan'' sends out
mixed signals, and mixed signals are the order of our day. The
first hour tells us that war is insupportable, while the remaining
two remind us of our moment of glory.
</P>
<P>
   Most people _ certainly those of us who were in World War II _
go along with the idea that in particular circumstances war can be
a reasonable, even moral response. What's astonishing about
``Saving Private Ryan'' is the unqualified praise that has greeted
a film that, with adjustments, could have been made 50-odd years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   True, the dialogue is realistic in a way that no World War II
audience would have tolerated. It's also true that, near the
beginning, there's an extended battle sequence of such merciless
detail and intensity that it would have been judged un-American
while any war was being fought.
</P>
<P>
   After that, for all of its blood and guts, ``Saving Private
Ryan'' depends increasingly on the sorts of comforting narrative
formulas that have made war movies such an enduring genre. The
ending is a second elaborately staged battle sequence, but one very
different from the first. A small, poorly equipped American unit
defends a strategic bridge against a much larger, far better
equipped German force. Though the mood is desperate, the manner
realistic and the body count high, the conclusion is a
soul-satisfying triumph, almost miraculous in the way of something
in a fantasy war film like ``The Guns of Navarone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' even suggests _ without irony, if
obliquely _ that Mom and apple pie were what Americans were
fighting and dying for.
</P>
<P>
   The mission at the center of the film: the assignment of eight
soldiers, still stunned that they survived the carnage of Omaha
Beach, to find and remove from harm's way one Pvt. James Ryan,
whose three brothers have been killed in action.
</P>
<P>
   Ordering the mission is no less than the Army's kindly, sober
chief of staff, Gen. George C. Marshall. On the first or second day
after the general helped to start the biggest, riskiest military
operation in the history of the Western world, his Washington
office is as serene as that of the dean of a small New England
college on a midsummer afternoon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When Marshall gives his aides their instructions, it's clear
that he has been browsing through his Bartlett's, as may be his
wont. He sends the aides off after quoting the letter Abe Lincoln
wrote to Mrs. Bixby, a mother who lost five sons in the Civil War:
``I feel how weak and fruitless must be any words of mine which
should attempt to beguile you from the grief of a loss so
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Words like that, which can't be mocked, load the scene with
secondhand feeling. Yet Lincoln's letter could be another,
subliminal reason why ``Saving Private Ryan'' is being found so
irresistible. Here we have evidence that the world's most powerful
country has a heart. The nation is being run not by scalawags and
rascals, the kind Henry Adams wrote about in his still-pertinent
1880 novel ``Democracy,'' but by towering father figures, men firm
of purpose, measured in their conduct, who grieve as we grieve.
</P>
<P>
   We're back watching the kind of movie Hollywood turned out with
a patriotic vengeance after Pearl Harbor. Among such films: ``The
Sullivans'' (1944), about the five brothers from Waterloo, Iowa,
who were lost when their light cruiser, the Juneau, was sunk. ``The
Sullivans'' is not an overt war movie. There are no big battle
sequences. Instead, it concentrates on five prototypical small-town
boys and how they grow up in Small Town, USA, eventually to give
their lives for their country.
</P>
<P>
   The gallantry of the Sullivan family is one of the inspirations
for ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Indeed, Capt. Miller (Tom Hanks), the
officer who leads the mission to find the young man, is initially
sarcastic about his objective, which he sees as a time-wasting
public-relations gesture when there's a war to be fought. But,
being a good officer, he follows orders. As it turns out, he
continues to fight the war nobly even while carrying out the
mission.
</P>
<P>
   To call ``Saving Private Ryan'' antiwar is wishful thinking.
After all, it recalls the good war. No matter how graphic World War
II movies are, they inevitably celebrate war by softening through
sanctification the pain and suffering of those fighting the war. No
bridge is too far, no sacrifice too extreme for these fighting men.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty is that movies glorify whatever they focus on.
It's the curse of their Midas touch. Movies can replicate the
surfaces of things, sometimes, like ``Saving Private Ryan,'' with
astonishing verisimilitude. Yet, without the doomy context of what
we know about, say, the Vietnam War, they don't often capture the
smell, taste, feel, boredom and sense of utter, no-way-to-get-out
desolation.
</P>
<P>
   Some World War II novelists succeeded in doing this by climbing
inside individual characters and isolating their experiences: I
think of Norman Mailer (``The Naked and the Dead'') and James Jones
(``The Thin Red Line''). But reading is a private matter, far more
personal than the communal activity of watching movies. Good
writers take you down dark corridors of the mind no cameras can
penetrate. When you read, you travel solo, carrying only your
secret luggage.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly 30-minute battle montage that helps to open ``Saving
Private Ryan'' is a singular piece of filmmaking: a magnificently
photographed and edited sequence that initially looks as if it had
been composed of documentary clips, shot by perhaps a dozen or so
anonymous cameramen at Omaha Beach on D-Day, but only now liberated
from the censors.
</P>
<P>
   Each split-second image is seen as if out of the corner of the
camera's eye. Bullets, bodies, panic, confusion. A face looks
startled one moment and is dead the next. Through the chaos of
bewildered soldiers and beached equipment, a man in mid-distance
lurches across the sand, carrying his severed arm. The din is
unimaginable, its Gotterdammerung effect augmented by the digital
sound, which separates every skull-blasting thud, whine, crack,
whoosh and boom.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way Omaha Beach must have looked and sounded. So it
goes for five minutes, 10 minutes, 15 minutes and on.
</P>
<P>
   But then you, too, begin to suffer your own kind of shell shock.
You are, after all, watching a movie. You can see the red exit sign
at the side of the screen. You smell the aroma of the simulated
butter on the popcorn being wolfed down by the person next to you.
You become conscious of the editing, of the technology of the aural
effects, of the fact that the gruesome images aren't much different
in degree from those featured in commonplace, R-rated slasher films
made for teen-agers. There are just more of them, packed more
closely, and, unlike those in slasher movies, you're supposed to
believe them.
</P>
<P>
   This is also a way to escape the emotional effects of what you
have been experiencing. It doesn't necessarily diminish the art of
it. Not until you have seen the rest of the film do you realize
that nothing that comes after this montage is really worthy of the
aspirations of the people who put the sequence together. ``Saving
Private Ryan'' is otherwise a gung-ho movie wrapped in reassuring
truisms.
</P>
<P>
   It restores our self-image, but does it have anything to do with
our values, with the content of our lives as we live them today?
Not much. It shows us as we might like to be. Meanwhile we sit in a
gaudy meeting house where desires are instantly gratified, and
death has no consequence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' is a shrewdly, sometimes boldly
conceived entertainment film, but it's no more antiwar than the
dear old ``Sullivans.'' It's anti-getting shot, maimed,
dismembered, disemboweled, blown up and killed.
</P>
<P>
   In an imperfect world, that seems to be the most we can hope
for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERCASH-ART-1     08-09 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERCASH-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERCASH'S LESSON IN WEB SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER WAYNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1994, when the World Wide Web had no commerce to speak of, a
group of computer and credit card-processing experts banded
together and formed a company built around high-security technology
for safely transferring money on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The product failed to find a market. Yet, four years later, the
company, Cybercash, has survived by adapting to the less
sophisticated but far more flexible security technology that was
eventually embraced throughout the Web. And though it is still in
the red, Cybercash has managed to take its stock public and to grow
by merging with a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   The history of Cybercash offers a vivid example of how difficult
it can be for any company to steer proprietary standards into the
unpredictable currents of the Internet _ even when the technology
in question is widely acknowledged to offer a superior product. It
is also a lesson in survival.
</P>
<P>
   That survival has exacted a price. When it became clear that
revenue for the second quarter, which ended on June 30, would be
lower than expected, the company, which is based in Reston, Va.,
laid off 20 percent of its staff, including one founder who
volunteered to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining group of about 200 has sharpened its focus on
areas that already produce revenue. It has moved development of
more ambitious technologies for the next century to the back
burner.
</P>
<P>
   Cybercash's original product was a ``digital wallet,'' a piece
of software intended for home computers, with the idea of keeping
bank accounts and credit card numbers handy and secure. No one
would need to enter a credit card number to buy something because
the wallet would keep it encrypted.
</P>
<P>
   To further reduce fraud, the wallet would hide credit card
information even from merchants, making the system in some ways
more secure than standard retail transactions.
</P>
<P>
   But users shunned the product and gravitated toward a simpler,
nonproprietary alternative known as Secure Sockets Layer, or SSL, a
straightforward system intended to scramble all data passing
between a customer and a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   SSL did not provide any of the digital wallet's sophisticated
features for electronic commerce, but it did offer adequate
security for most transactions. What is more, it was flexible
enough to encrypt everything, including entire Web pages that held
sensitive data.
</P>
<P>
   In a nimble move, Cybercash modified its back-office processing
software for merchants to handle orders generated by SSL. Although
the company did not generate the revenue it had hoped to make with
the wallet concept, it did grab a piece of the action for handling
transactions between online merchants and their banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very nice service,'' said Michael Salim, president of
American Data, a North Carolina company that rents Web space to
retailers and resells Cybercash's processing services to his
customers. ``It really makes the use of credit cards easy.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Salim said, Cybercash's original wallet, which
denominated deposits on hand as virtual coins, ``operated with some
funny money; no one liked that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Loftus, a senior vice president of Cybercash, said the
company was trying to build on that sort of response. But she said
that instead of abandoning the wallet concept, the company would
alter the wallet's design and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, it was a container for electronic cash,'' Ms.
Loftus said. ``Going forward, we're going to concentrate on making
the buying experience easy, consistent and secure.''
</P>
<P>
   The new wallet, she said, would be more tightly integrated with
the browser and would not require the customer to spend any extra
time to install it.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Condon, Cybercash's chief operating officer, said one
important lesson in the company's evolution had been that the
consumer generally was not greatly concerned about security because
the banks and the merchants pay losses incurred in fraud or theft.
The consumer, he said, was primarily interested in convenience and
in saving time.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants and credit card companies, on the other hand, are
eager to reduce fraud. In an SSL-based system, a user can type any
credit card number, including a stolen one. In such cases, it is
the merchant, not the credit card company, that sustains the loss.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Cybercash will introduce a new generation of
its wallet later this month. Designed to the greatest degree
possible to be transparent to the consumer, it will also
incorporate the new Secure Electronic Transaction standard, or SET,
that is being pushed by the credit card industry.
</P>
<P>
   All the sophistication is aimed at reducing credit card fraud by
distributing electronic identification files known as certificates,
which act like driver's licenses or passports. The certificates
allow computers to generate digital signatures that the credit card
companies hope will weed out the most common types of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, introducing any new standard is filled with danger. In
this case, the most serious challenge will be finding ways to
distribute the certificate files to everyone's home computer. So,
while the next version of Cybercash's wallet product will be
engineered to use certificates, Condon said, the feature will not
be built in.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the company is investing money and resources in
the back-office software that generates most of its revenue. On
April 30, Cybercash completed a merger with a onetime competitor,
IC Verify, a company built on credit card services for
brick-and-mortar merchants. IC Verify had recently begun expanding
into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Goldberg, a former IC Verify executive who is now a
Cybercash vice president, said that the goal of the companies'
merged operations was to provide merchants with a single tool for
transaction processing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Today, she said, many traditional merchants are opening Web
sites, and she expects that in the future, Web-only retailers like
Amazon.com might open stores, in much the same way that J. Crew
migrated from catalogs to shopping centers. The merged version of
Cybercash is aiming to unify its product line to dominate both
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also expanding its solutions for making it easier
to pay recurring bills on time. The costs for companies to mail
credit card, phone and utility bills each month is substantial, and
Cybercash intends to provide a simple, one-step tool that will
allow customers to go to a Web site, examine their bills and then
authorize payments.
</P>
<P>
   One of Cybercash's strongest assets is its perceived leadership
in these kinds of secure transaction technologies. Michael
Schneider, a vice president at IMC On-Line, an Atlanta-based
company that rents Web space, said the availability of Cybercash
was often crucial in persuading businesses to choose his service.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love the idea of the technology,'' he said, ``and they
get all caught up in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a catch: Most merchants, he said, discovered that
their sites did not generate enough business to justify the cost.
``For four or five transactions, having a separate statement, it
just wasn't worth it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schneider predicted that more businesses would eventually
adopt the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merchants are scared about the transactions coming in and
knowing whether they're bogus or not,'' he said. ``They're scared
about the unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Cybercash, it is fear of the unknown that drives
sales of security technologies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
