   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CASTRO _ CUBA-CASTRO _ MIAMI _ Summer is always the time for
feverish speculation about the health of aging Cuban President
Fidel Castro, who turns 72 on Aug. 13, and this summer is no
exception. Just a few weeks ago, a Cuban doctor-turned-defector
living in Costa Rica claimed that Castro suffers from a fatal brain
disorder. There was a barrage of similar ill-health rumors last
summer, some even announcing Castro's death. But, if anything,
Castro appears more robust than ever. He appears to be traveling
more these days than at any time in his 39 years in power. He
continues his commitment to communism, even as he's been striking a
conciliatory tone towards President Clinton. (Emling, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   POVERTY- WASHINGTON _ Poverty in the United States may be more
of a trap door than a revolving door, with Americans falling into
poverty for months at a time during any year, only to pull out
again at a later point, according to a new report from the U.S.
Bureau of the Census. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   GA-RUNOFF _ ATLANTA _ What's the expected voter turnout for
Tuesday's primary election runoffs? Only 22 percent of registered
voters cast ballots on July 21. With the governor's race all but
decided, will two hotly-contested runoffs for lieutenant governor
generate much interest? Any hot metro county races?( Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PBP-SMOKE (Developing, with photos) _ West Palm Beach, Fla. _
The anti-smoking Truth Train and GROSS bus arrive in south Florida.
The bus will go to Deerfield Beach and Boynton Beach; the train
will stop in Okeechobee and West Palm Beach. Both will have rallies
with conscripted schoolkids. Both groups will also be here Sunday
before moving on. (Bennett/Warejcka, Palm Beach Post
</P>
