<HEADER>
A5067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-MSTATE-COX     08-09 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MSTATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldogs are underdog threat in SEC
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The four-year contract extension Jackie Sherrill received at
Mississippi State last year was a surprise to some throughout the
SEC ranks. After all, the Bulldogs played themselves into position
to win the SEC West with late consecutive road wins at Auburn and
Alabama, but then fell to inferior opponents Arkansas and Ole Miss,
playing themselves out of a bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   In seven seasons in Starkville, Sherrill has a 41-37-2 record,
including a mediocre 24-30-1 mark in the SEC. But in reality, last
season may have been Sherrill's best coaching job at Mississippi
State, considering the tragic drowning death of star running back
Keffer McGee shortly before preseason camp started a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the death and a rash of injuries to several starters,
Sherrill rallied his squad to a 7-4 record. That's the main reason
the Bulldogs enter this season as a darkhorse in the SEC West.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be our best team at Mississippi State,'' Sherrill
says.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs will be led by arguably the SEC's most underrated
player in senior tailback James Johnson. Johnson, a former
junior-college star who was thrust into the starting role last
season by the death of McGee, became just the fourth back in school
history to rush for more than 1,000 yards. In 11 games, he rushed
for 1,069 yards and 12 touchdowns on 217 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming in, Coach Sherrill was telling me, 'Well, you know
we've got Keffer McGee,''' Johnson said. ``Obviously, I didn't
expect to make that kind of an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson figures to play an even more prominent role this season,
following the departure of tailback Robert Isaac, who started eight
games last year. Johnson, who started just four games as a junior,
weighed as much as 238 pounds last season. But he started a diet in
the offseason and worked with a State track coach to improve his
speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the back of his mind, he thought he had to get big to play
in the SEC,'' Sherrill said. ``Now, he's down to 228 pounds and
only has four-percent body fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson should benefit from one of the league's largest
offensive lines. All-SEC candidate Eric Allen returns at center,
along with senior Anthony Kapp at right tackle and seniors Craig
Moore and Randy Thomas of East Point at guards. Promising sophomore
Floyd ``Pork Chop'' Womack takes over at left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the most athletic offensive line we've had,''
Sherrill said. ``We'll still be very big and strong, but this
offensive line can run.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill is hoping returning quarterback Matt Wyatt also will
run more. Wyatt was the SEC's worst-rated quarterback last season,
completing just 45 percent of his passes with only six touchdowns
and 15 interceptions. Sherrill hired former State quarterback John
Bond as a graduate assistant in the offseason to help with the
quarterbacks' mobility. Wyatt could be pushed by redshirt freshman
Wayne Madkin and true freshman Brandon Butler in two-a-days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quarterback has to be a better player,'' Sherrill said.
``I called Matt in before spring practice and told him it's his job
to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Bulldogs lost their top three playmakers from
last season _ end Greg Favors of Atlanta, safety Eric Brown and
cornerback Izell McGill of Rex. State used a 4-2-5 alignment last
season, but coordinator Joe Lee Dunn has switched to a more
conventional 5-2-4 this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers Barrin Simpson and Jamaal Dinkins and JUCO defensive
linemen Darius Brown and Alvin McKinley will be counted on heavily.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday: South Carolina
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
