<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      08-09 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTENTIOUS LAWMAKERS APPROVE ARAFAT'S CABINET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Palestinian lawmakers voted Sunday to approve a new
cabinet appointed by Yasser Arafat, but only after two days of
vocal debate in which a loud minority criticized what they called
his disdain for the Legislature's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-28 vote brought a tense conclusion to a long dispute
between Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and the Palestinian
Legislative Council, whose members had urged him for more than a
year to make far-reaching changes in order to combat corruption and
mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat instead announced last Wednesday that he had decided to
keep his cabinet, or executive council, virtually intact, and it
was that decision that won endorsement Sunday. But the episode has
ignited an unusually public airing of dissent by Palestinian
lawmakers at what many regard as Arafat's high-handed style and his
inattention to his government's flaws.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of Arafat's cabinet, including Hanan Ashrawi, a
prominent international figure, have resigned over his cabinet
action. And as it became clear that Arafat would nevertheless win
the day, one critic, Hassan Khadr, a member of his Fatah
organization, nearly set off a brawl at a legislative council
meeting this weekend. Khadr proposed sarcastically that lawmakers
might just as well go one step further and declare the Palestinian
leader ``God of the Palestinian people forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since a parliamentary probe last summer found evidence of
widespread graft and waste within the Palestinian Authority,
lawmakers had been pressing Arafat to dismiss ministers suspected
of corruption. But none of those ministers were dismissed as part
of the changes he announced, whose main effect was to add 10 new
members to what had been an 18-member cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the new members were chosen from the Legislature,
where they continue to hold seats and where their votes helped
Arafat to win a clear majority Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's critics have called the cabinet expansion a transparent
attempt to co-opt his critics. But some of the newly appointed
ministers contend that it reflects Arafat's recognition of the need
for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opposed all of the mistakes of the executive authority, and
now we will struggle to correct the way,'' said Saadi al-Krunz, the
new industry minister, who had served on a parliamentary committee
that compiled a report on high-level corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat did not attend the session.
</P>
<P>
   Those who called on lawmakers to reject the new government
included Mrs. Ashrawi, who served as spokeswoman for the
Palestinians during the 1991 Middle East peace conference in Madrid
and who had been minister of higher education since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggled for a long time to get the voters' confidence,
and for the Palestinian Authority to respect the Legislative
Council, and now we should respect ourselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Khadr, the Fatah member who ridiculed Arafat during Saturday's
debate, told reporters after Sunday's vote: ``This is a very
dramatic end to a great political institution. I feel very let
down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
