   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   CLIMATE-DISEASE (Undated) _ Scientists have long theorized that
climatic changes related to global warming could unleash new
outbreaks of diseases like malaria, dengue fever, cholera and heat
stroke. But with the modest amount of warming experienced so far,
they have been unable to produce much hard evidence. But in the
belief that 1997 and 1998 may provide a taste of what is to come,
those who pay attention to the health effects of climate are now
pulling together data about weather-related illness and death in
recent months. While most of the evidence is circumstantial,
consisting of correlations and coincidences, it suggests that amid
all the scientific smoke there is some fire to be concerned about.
By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-MUSEUM (Mashantucket, Conn.) _ A new museum, opening
Tuesday, will celebrate the Mashantucket Pequot Tribal Nation's
resurrection. The Foxwoods Resort Casino, now the state of
Connecticut's largest individual source of revenue, allows the
Pequots to live like sheiks, with tribal housing and free college
tuition for all. The casino also supplied $193 million _ roughly
four months' take from the slot machines _for the museum. The
Pequots, once denied loans even for salt-box houses, are rich. Now,
they want respect.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-LONGS (Winnfield, La.) _ The stories of politics and
pig hunts are a little worn from use here in the birthplace of
brothers Huey and Earl Long, a bit like the final line of an
oft-told fairytale that a child shouts out even before the book is
closed. No one knows those stories better than family, and as about
50 Long relatives gathered on Sunday for an old-fashioned family
reunion, the people who hold tiny pieces of that legacy fit them
all together, to form legend. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PHONE-STRIKE (New York) _ Developments in the Bell Atlantic
strike.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-SMALLSTOCKS (Undated) _ While the larger, well-known
stocks of companies like Coca-Cola and Philip Morris have been
battered for much of the last month, the stocks of smaller
companies have suffered much more. The Dow Jones industrial
average, a large-stock gauge, fell about 9 percent from its high in
mid-July, while the Russell 2000 index of small stocks fell nearly
20 percent from its high in April. A study by Salomon Smith Barney
showed that the vast majority of small issues, with market values
of less than $250 million, had fallen 45 percent on average from
their peak through Aug. 4. The mounting evidence has prompted some
Wall Street analysts to talk about a darker side of the bull market
and even to suggest that a bear market is in the offing. By David
Barboza. With graphic and photo.
</P>
