A5077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WWII-RUSSIA-MUSEUM-NY     08-09 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-RUSSIA-MUSEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WASHINGTON, MEMORABILIA OF WARTIME RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (js) 
 By MELISSA McNAMARA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of Hitler's uniforms and the Soviet flag that
flew over the Reichstag after the fall of Berlin are among some 500
World War II artifacts on display for the first time in the United
States in a new exhibition at the Ronald Reagan Center for
International Trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``World War II Through Russian Eyes'' includes photographs,
documentary film footage, battlefield maps and personal mementos of
those Russians who fought and died during the war. The exhibition,
which is free, is the result of a collaboration between Kermit
Weeks, president of the Historical Artifacts Museum near Orlando,
Fla., and Col. Alexander Nikonov, director of Moscow's Central
Armed Forces Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Also being shown in this country for the first time are three
Soviet documentaries made between 1941 and 1945. ``The Great
Patriotic War,'' an eight-part series directed by Roman Karme;
``The Battle for Berlin,'' a two-part series; and ``The Siege of
Leningrad'' will run continuously during the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Siege of Leningrad,'' directed by Alex Temin, includes
rare scenes of the composer Dmitri Shostakovich, who was nicknamed
the ``Fireman of Leningrad,'' conducting his Symphony No. 7 before
a malnourished, frostbitten audience in that beleaguered city.
These films were widely shown in the Soviet Union during the war,
but have been kept in the Moscow museum since then. Many of the
cinematographers involved died in battle.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors enter the exhibition, designed by Alexander Okun,
through a 50-foot ``tunnel of history'' in which paintings and
photographs, along with replicas of Leningrad street signs and
soldiers' bunkers, recreate the atmosphere of the war years.
</P>
<P>
   Original game pieces that Russian soldiers carved from wood to
entertain themselves and even a handmade marionette of Hitler, used
to entertain Soviet troops, are also on display. Mark Talisman,
director of the exhibition, said the artifacts provide Americans
with ``new insight into the depth of the war and the way in which
it touched every Russian family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With this exhibit,'' he added, ``history has come full
circle.'' Talisman said the show would go to New York after it
closes here on Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Nikonov said some artifacts, like the swastika flag that
belonged to Hitler's personal guard unit, have not left Moscow
since the war. ``Americans and Russians were partners during World
War II,'' he said, ``and now, more than 50 years later, we are
partners once again in exhibiting and viewing this history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
