<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5080 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABYBANDS-COX     08-09 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABYBANDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hospitals testing various security options
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Modern technology enables doctors to detect a baby's
sex within weeks of conception, save the life of high-risk newborns
and perform other feats for infants that would have been unheard of
20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What it can't do is guarantee that parents take their baby home
from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Baby switching and snatching rarely occur. But hospital
officials admit that no technology exists to eliminate the
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent publicized switch, at the University of Virginia
Medical Center, attests to that.
</P>
<P>
   There have been four baby switches and seven abductions in
hospitals since 1995, when the Joint Commission on Accreditation of
Healthcare Organizations in Chicago began tracking them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone wants to commit a criminal act, he or she will find
a way to do it,'' said Dr. Henry Schaeffer, chairman of the
American Academy of Pediatrics' Committee on Hospital Care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't conceive of a system that's going to be foolproof
unless you literally handcuff the baby to the mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals have, however, adopted ways to protect babies.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford Long Hospital in Atlanta lets mothers and babies room
together at all times. The hospital doesn't have a nursery. ``It's
just to make sure that those types of things don't happen to the
babies,'' said Rashel Stephenson, a Crawford Long spokeswoman.
``It's absolutely impossible for someone to get out of the unit
with the baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Many facilities use identification bracelets that are
pre-stamped with numbers to reduce the possibility of tampering.
Two bands are placed on the baby and one on the mother. If the
bands are cut or torn apart, they cannot be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to make sure Mama sees the banding done,'' said Patsy
Hammonds, clinical coordinator of Piedmont Hospital's newborn
nursery in Atlanta. ``The bracelets are checked on every visit to
Mama's room. If that baby and Mama don't match, the baby comes back
to the nursery.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last year or so, many metro hospitals have installed
another protective device to safeguard newborns.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``Baby LoJack'' after a car anti-theft system, the
device is similar to one used for merchandise in retail stores.
Alarms sound and elevators stop working when a baby is taken to a
restricted area.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Northside Hospital, which delivered 13,000 babies in
1997, has increased the number of closed-circuit cameras around
rooms with mothers or babies. It also requires those with access to
delivery areas to carry special cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way you can use the nursery is to provide an access
card, and that provides an audit trail of who's coming into the
nursery,'' said John McDonald, Northside's security director.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledges there is no 100 percent guarantee the system
would prevent a staff person from switching babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's difficult. Anytime you're an insider, you have
information that other people don't know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best safeguard against swapping, advises Schaeffer,
is to look for identifying marks on the baby immediately after
delivery, such as a dimple or birthmark.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Schaeffer said correctly identifying a baby could be
tricky, especially after a long, hard labor. ``If I brought you a
baby two hours later I'm not sure you would necessarily know if
there were no real distinguishing characteristics.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
