   MARKET-SMALLSTOCKS (Undated) _ While the larger, well-known
stocks of companies like Coca-Cola and Philip Morris have been
battered for much of the last month, the stocks of smaller
companies have suffered much more. The Dow Jones industrial
average, a large-stock gauge, fell about 9 percent from its high in
mid-July, while the Russell 2000 index of small stocks fell nearly
20 percent from its high in April. A study by Salomon Smith Barney
showed that the vast majority of small issues, with market values
of less than $250 million, had fallen 45 percent on average from
their peak through Aug. 4. The mounting evidence has prompted some
Wall Street analysts to talk about a darker side of the bull market
and even to suggest that a bear market is in the offing. By David
Barboza.
