<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN DINING ITALIAN, TALK THE GOOD TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you have a favorite Italian restaurant, try this phrase on
your waiter when he delivers an order of ``polmone in umido.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Da quanto tempo e morto questo?''
</P>
<P>
   Boy, that waiter will think you're smart. However, the chef may
attempt to remove your necktie with a meat cleaver. Because the
English interpretation of the above phrase is, ``How long has this
been dead?'' Since you have just ordered stewed veal lung, that
question may be essential to your survival.
</P>
<P>
   And survival is what Rick Steves teaches. An Edmonds, Wash.,
travel writer, tour leader, PBS television celebrity and the author
of several pocket language guides, Steves has a grasp of varied
dialects. He also has a sense of humor. As his student, you can
only hope the food servers you encounter are also of a jolly
disposition.
</P>
<P>
   Another helpful phrase Steves offers, to anybody visiting a fish
restaurant in Italy, is this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Solo la testa, per favore.'' You are asking the waiter to
bring you ``just the head, please.'' What you will probably get is
an astonished look from your food server.
</P>
<P>
   Steves is blessed with a disarming smile. That must be
particularly helpful when he concludes his meal abroad by asking in
Italian, French or German, ``Do any of your customers return?''
</P>
<P>
   However, his phrase books also show you how to make new friends.
The chapter on ``chatting'' includes the foreign translations of
these helpful exchanges:
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just be friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you like a massage?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Darling, will you marry me?''
</P>
<P>
   See? Steves eliminates a lot of non-essential dialogue. That may
be why every third American we encounter while touring aboard seems
to be clutching one of the 16 guide books he has written.
</P>
<P>
   With just such a traveling aid, we located a classic cliffside
hotel in Sorrento charging less than $80 a night for a double room
with breakfast served on a terrace overlooking the Gulf of Naples.
</P>
<P>
   In his guidebook Steves advised that the hotel is located in a
neighborhood ``drunk with character.'' It was not another Rick
Steves joke. But until we checked in, we suspected he might be
directing us to a neighborhood full of drunken characters. In which
case we had made a pledge.
</P>
<P>
   No massages!
</P>
<P>
   Fagioli con Tonno
</P>
<P>
   1 14-ounce can white beans
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One-fourth cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 red onion
</P>
<P>
   1 7-ounce can solid pack white tuna
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh sage leaves
</P>
<P>
   Drain and wash the beans. Dry, plunk them into a bowl and add
the oil and vinegar. Mix in the sage leaves and let sit for an hour
or so while you reconsider that pledge about massages.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile peel and thinly slice the onion. Chill in ice water
for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   OK, divide the beans onto four plates as an appetizer (or two
plates as a main dish). Divide the tuna also, then top with onion
slices. If you want, you can drizzle each dish with a bit more oil
and vinegar. Add salt if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Mussels and Pasta
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces pasta pieces, cooked
</P>
<P>
   1 anchovy fillet
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon capers
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon oregano
</P>
<P>
   One-eighth teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 14-ounce can chopped tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds mussels
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   I used small penne for this dish, but you could use bow-ties or
any pasta of similar size. Cook until barely done in salted water,
wash with warm water and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   In a cooking pot heat the olive oil. Chop together the anchovy
fillet and capers and add to the pot along with the garlic, oregano
and cayenne. Cook one minute, then add the tomatoes, wine and
washed mussels. Cover and steam 10 minutes, until the mussels open.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the shells from most of the mussels and discard. Return
the mussels to the pot along with eight or nine unshelled but
opened mussels. Add the cooked pasta and simmer five minutes. Add
salt if needed and serve the mussels, pasta and sauce in bowls to
three or four guests. And pass some crusty Italian bread for
dunking.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember one thing. If you want some mussels in Italy you
order ``cozze.'' If you mistakenly ask for ``muscolo'' you will get
a Sicilian weight lifter in a tight T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, and in case you do order stewed veal lung, the
guidebooks advise that the Italian phrase for ``yuck'' is ``che
schifo!'' And in France you turn your head to one side and explode
with an indignant, ``Pouah!''
</P>
<P>
   Bon appetite!
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
