<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5101 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-MUSEUM-ART-2TA     08-09 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-MUSEUM-ART-2TAKES(750)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEQUOTS BUILD MUSEUM WITH CASINO RICHES AND WRITE THEIR OWN
HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: New England)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET, Conn. _ A scent machine spews eau de smoky
campfire, and an escalator ride through a fiberglass glacier
includes geologic crunching and a 30-degree drop in temperature.
But in this museum built with a blank check, the final display is a
rickety yellow trailer with a shower head out back and a dented
kettle on the stove.
</P>
<P>
   It was in just such trailers that the remnants of the
Mashantucket Pequot Tribal Nation spent a dozen hungry years
repopulating a nearly abandoned Indian reservation _ only to become
millionaires with an Oz-like casino so tall it twinkles with red
lights to ward off airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   That teal-and-plum castle, Foxwoods Resort Casino, is now
Connecticut's largest individual source of revenue and allows the
Pequots to live like sheiks, with tribal housing and free college
tuition for all. The casino also supplied $193 million _ roughly
four months' take from the slot machines _ for the museum, opening
Tuesday, which celebrates the tribe's resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   The Pequots, once denied loans even for salt-box houses, are
rich. Now, they want respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not just doing this to pay back what happened to native
people,'' said Theresa Hayward Bell, the museum's executive
director, who once lived in one of those trailers. ``This is
something that native people should always have been able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And, oh, what $193 million can do. The nation's museum
professionals are watching with awe _ and envy.
</P>
<P>
   Furs and replicas of tools, bones and a soapstone bowl are put
out where visitors can touch them; when they're worn, they'll just
be replaced. Base boards are slate, inlaid with Indian basket
designs. Display cases are solid elm and ash instead of the museum
norm, laminated plywood.
</P>
<P>
   A diorama of a caribou hunt, 50 feet in diameter, is accompanied
by a touch-screen program that allows an exploration of the
strategy of the kill. One life-size caribou seems to lunge with
shock and fear as an Indian spears him in the right side with a
flint-tipped spear (reusable, the program explains). Convincing ice
and moss roost in crevices of the boulders. A cook fire glimmers,
waiting for the first slabs of meat.
</P>
<P>
   In a 22,000-square-foot Indian village nearby, real water rushes
in the riverbed, and a computer linked to 110 speakers constantly
remixes the sounds of dogs, geese and crickets. The 50 trees have 5
million green polyester leaves, hand-painted with yellow, ivory and
bronze. To recreate the perfect American chestnut tree, artisans
traveled to Wisconsin to make a latex mold of a 23-footer.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, a 185-foot tower of stone and glass soon will give
visitors a pilot's eye view of the cedar swamp that sprouted the
largest casino in the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   W. Richard West, the director of the Smithsonian Institution's
National Museum of the American Indian, said the Pequots' museum
was tremendous poetic justice for ``a people and a culture that had
been left for dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pequots were, historically, one of the most potent
political and military forces on the East Coast,'' he said. ``Now,
they've come full circle. No one can say the glory of native
culture is a past phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Williams, the acting president of the American
Association of Museums, said it is a rare luxury for a group to
have nearly unlimited resources and the chance to build an
institution from scratch. ``They've done everything,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Banging down finishing touches this week, workers said they
never expect to work on such an opulent job again. Jim Spillson, a
carpenter, stroked the hangings and cases as if he were in church.
``Big bucks,'' he said, rubbing his thumb against the inside of his
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian village, designed to recreate the scene on a summer
afternoon in 1550, is encircled by a 600-foot mural, blown up from
a photograph of an oak and hickory forest. Fifty-one life-size
figures, each molded from sketches and measurements made of living
native Americans, weave mats, fashion arrows and fish.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the men sport elaborate geometric tattoos, which would
have been made by pricking soot and charcoal into their skin. Two
gulls hover over a garbage mound of shells.
</P>
<P>
   A recreated farmstead, like the ones Pequots built when furry
animals became scarce, includes a two-acre orchard where the stone
paths and manicured trees unintentionally evoke a formal English
garden. The log cabin is so snug that one construction worker, John
Melgey, joked that it was nicer than his own house. ``This is
comfy,'' he joked. ``I've been looking for a place.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The museum, though, is much more than a physical triumph. With
its Mashantucket Pequot Museum and Research Center, the tribe is
renewing the truism that the victor writes the history. This time,
it just took awhile.
</P>
<P>
   Pequot, translated for centuries in European histories as
``destroyer,'' here is rendered as ``the people of the shallow
water.'' Instead of conquering tribes that competed in
wampum-making, the Pequots now are on record as having ``gained
control of neighboring Native groups.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum sits within sight of Foxwoods and its 5,567 slot
machines, 24 restaurants and three hotels.
</P>
<P>
   At the museum, a visitor's journey begins in a model of the
glacier that once covered the reservation, and ends with displays
heralding the two elderly Pequot women who found themselves alone
on the reservation in the 1970s, holding the land for the
descendants who would engineer the tribe's comeback. With the
modest dream of self-sufficiency, they cut wood, grew lettuce and
boiled sap. And then they tried bingo.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and fall, the Pequot tale will be soaked up by 60
school groups consisting of more than 2,000 pupils.
</P>
<P>
   With the slogan ``Our Legacy Is Yours,'' the museum is being
advertised with posters at Metro-North commuter rail stations in
the New York City suburbs, and on buses in Providence, R.I.
Advertising is running in magazines like Smithsonian, Yankee and
Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $10 for adults and $6 for children, and the tribe
projects annual attendance of 350,000. The museum gives the
550-member tribe a chance to lure youngsters and other nongamblers
to the reservation, but that could cause problems with the Pequots'
neighbors. Already, many resent the 175 buses and 50,000 people
that the casino draws to the area each day.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the expensive technology, Pequot officials are eager to
portray the museum as a home for serious scholarship, and a place
to dispel stereotypes about Indians from European histories and
Hollywood portrayals. Indeed, the museum was dreamed of long before
the tribe went into the gaming business: The collection has its
roots in the archeology, genealogy, oral history and other
information gathered during the process of gaining sovereign status
from the federal government, which was completed in 1983. The first
casino opened in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's 150,000-book research library emphasizes the 20th
century native American experience. ``We want to provide the tools
to allow people to write the books, make the videos and write the
poems that will introduce people to the truth about native
Americans,'' said Cheryl Metoyer, the museum's Director of
Information Resources.
</P>
<P>
   James Wherry, an anthropologist who has served as an adviser to
the Pequots' Tribal Council for 15 years, wrote in a tribe history
that the museum was planned with the aim of ``debunking some of the
more odious popular misconceptions of Pequot history and culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum also is a chance for the Pequots to ease tensions
with their modern neighbors, who are resisting the tribe's effort
to annex new land for the reservation. Several local officials,
used to battling the tribe in court and at zoning hearings, said
they were pleasantly surprised to receive invitations to Monday's
ribbon-cutting ceremony for the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal Chairman Richard (Skip) Hayward, who once curled up on
the floor during a lobbying trip to the Bureau of Indian Affairs in
Washington because he could not afford a motel room, will introduce
a video greeting from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Johnson, the mayor of Ledyard, a town of 15,000 that
surrounds the reservation, said many of his constituents resent
what they consider the ``special privileges'' that the federal
government has conferred on the Pequots. But Johnson said he
believes the museum will be a big step in improving relations.
``They're here and we're here, and we're going to have to live with
each other for many years to come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wherry, the tribal adviser, said area residents would be
mistaken if they thought the Pequots were interested only in good
will, though. ``Some of these town folk still think of the tribe in
the old ways,'' he said. ``They long for the good old days when
they could depend on the tribe for low-cost farm labor. This is our
answer. The Pequots have arrived.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
