<SLUG> BC-BOEING-FIGHTER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING WOULD ASSEMBLE FIGHTER JET IN ST. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Joint Strike Fighter, one of the biggest military
procurement projects ever, will be assembled in St. Louis if The
Boeing Co. wins the competition over Lockheed Martin in three
years, the Post-Intelligencer has learned.
</P>
<P>
   Some parts could be built in Seattle and shipped to St. Louis
for final assembly, though that is still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department currently plans to buy nearly 3,000 of
the stealthy strike fighters by 2020 at a cost of $219 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some military experts have said the program could be worth as
much as $300 billion when potential foreign sales are included.
Lockheed Martin executives have described the project as a ``must
win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest defense program out there in the entire
world,'' said Bert Cooper, a military aircraft analyst with the
Congressional Research Service in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Where Boeing would build its fighter should it win the
competition has been the subject of much speculation because of the
promise of thousands of aerospace jobs the project would mean.
</P>
<P>
   California has lobbied hard behind the scenes to have the
winning fighter entry built in that state, where the aerospace
industry has been hard hit by defense consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement that Boeing has picked St. Louis for assembly of
the Joint Strike Fighter is expected soon, and could be made
Thursday when Boeing will reveal the next round of its facilities
consolidation, sources said. Boeing is streamlining its commercial,
space and defense facilities in the wake of last year's merger with
McDonnell Douglas and the acquisition of Rockwell International's
military and space business.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also is expected to announce Thursday that it will start
another next generation 737 production line at the under-used
Douglas factory in Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year's merger with McDonnell Douglas, St. Louis has
become the headquarters of Boeing's military aircraft and missile
systems. Boeing builds the F-15 Eagle, the F-18 Hornet and the F-18
Super Hornet in St. Louis, as well as the T-45 Goshawk jet trainer
and the re-manufactured Harrier II Plus for the Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Without new foreign orders, the F-15 production line will shut
down next year, and the F-18 Hornet line in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If Boeing wins the Joint Striker Fighter competition, St. Louis
would have the two biggest U.S. fighter projects well into the next
century. The Navy will buy a minimum of 548 of the new F-18 Super
Hornets. The first operational Super Hornet is scheduled to be
delivered later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is now building two demonstration Joint Strike Fighters
that will compete against two from Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Although sections of the demonstration fighters are being
fabricated in Seattle and St. Louis, final assembly is taking place
at Boeing's plant in Palmdale, Calif., which is also where the
rollout, ground testing and first flight will occur.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent flight testing will be at nearby Edwards Air Force
Base, and later at the Navy's Patuxent River test facility in
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The first Boeing demonstration fighter should be finished by
late 1999 or early 2000. The second should roll out of the Palmdale
plant a few months later.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is scheduled to select the winning design in spring
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin is also building its two demonstration fighters
in Palmdale, at its famed Skunk Works plant. Lockheed Martin
executives have not said where the Joint Strike Fighter would be
built if the company beats Boeing. Lockheed Martin now builds its
F-16 fighter at a huge plant in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Intended to serve the Air Force, Navy, Marine Corps and British
Royal Navy, the Joint Strike Fighter will be the first fighter
required to perform such multiservice roles.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy wants a fighter that can land and take off from an
aircraft carrier. The Marines and Royal Navy want a fighter that
can replace Harrier jets, which are capable of short takeoff and
vertical landing. The jet must also be stealthy so it can evade
detection by air or ground radar.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office has estimated the research and
development costs of the project at $22 billion. The actual cost of
each plane would be $28 milion to $38 million in fiscal year 1994
dollars, depending on the version.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Boeing beat out an entry from McDonnell Douglas to
join Lockheed Martin in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Many military experts believe that the project is so important
to the overall U.S. defense industry that there will be no
winner-take-all decision by the Pentagon. Boeing and Lockheed
Martin will share the lucrative contract, these experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Even Norman Augustine, the recently retired chairman of Lockheed
Martin, told reporters at last year's Paris Air Show that he
thought both Boeing and Lockheed Martin would emerge as winners in
the fighter competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
