<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: GETTING MORE PROMOTIONAL TIME FROM TV; USING TV SETS TO
TRACK PEOPLE AND PETS; LIVE TV IN AIRPLANES; THREE-DIMENSIONAL TV 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if there were not enough commercials already, an Israeli
inventor has patented a system to squeeze even more promotional
time out of every moment a television set is turned on.
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Tsuria, of Shoham, Israel, won a patent for inserting what
he calls ''informational messages'' into the small pockets of empty
air time created when television channels are switched.
</P>
<P>
   His invention is intended for one- or two-way pay-television
systems that rely on cable, satellite or television networks or any
combination of those. Such systems offer dozens of channels,
sometimes as many as 150.
</P>
<P>
   When a viewer scrolls through the channels, it takes the
television set's decoder about one second to tune in each new one.
No picture or sound is transmitted during this interval, which is
known as zapping time.
</P>
<P>
   Tsuria believes that when a viewer scrolls through many channels
at once, an unpleasant and unproductive amount of zapping time
results. He proposes to fill that time with messages.
</P>
<P>
   His invention includes a decoder to receive an incoming
television signal, a multichannel display and a channel changer. A
predetermined message can be sent with the television signal. When
the system senses that a channel is being changed, the message
signal is decoded and displayed during the zapping time.
</P>
<P>
   Tsuria intends for the message to be somehow associated with the
channel involved _ either the one that was being viewed when the
channel changing commenced or the one being tuned in. But his
patent does not specify whether the message should be commercial,
promotional or public service.
</P>
<P>
   Tsuria received patent 5,786,845 and assigned it to News Datacom
Ltd. in Berkshire, England, which is a subsidiary of News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Set to Check on Fido's Whereabouts
</P>
<P>
   Television owners may soon be able to use their sets to track
people, pets and vehicles. James Reynolds of San Jose, Calif., has
patented a system that uses land-based or satellite radio
navigation systems like the Global Positioning System to pinpoint
people or objects and display their location on a television map.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds' system needs a television cable company and phone line
to make it work. A radio transmitter is attached to a vehicle or
pet, or carried by a person, and sends a signal to the navigation
system. The signal can include longitude, latitude, altitude,
velocity and time. The data are then transmitted via a
communications service provider to a local television cable
company.
</P>
<P>
   A person at home who wants to find a pet, a relative or a car
driven by someone else can call the cable company and request the
location information. Soon a map is displayed on that person's
television set, with an icon representing the sought-after person
or object on the image to show the exact location. Reynolds
received patent 5,774,825.
</P>
<P>
   With Dish on the Plane, Fliers Can See TV Live
</P>
<P>
   It is common for planes to offer in-flight entertainment that
includes taped episodes of television shows and newscasts. Soon,
however, passengers may be able to watch live television. Richard
Sklar, Lawrence Girard, Ralph Phillipp, David Frankenback, Dickey
Berry and Jim Williams have won a patent for Raytheon's Hughes
Aircraft Co. of Anaheim, Calif., that uses an antenna mounted on an
airplane to pick up satellite television transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   The antenna picks up signals that are part of a direct broadcast
satellite system, the network used to transmit television signals
to the popular 18-inch dishes set up outside about 7 million homes
across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A controller and interface unit steer the antenna and lock it
onto a satellite's RF signals. Those RF signals carry television
channels and are decoded to turn them into video and audio signals.
The signals are routed to monitors inside the plane so passengers
can watch live programming.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors received patent 5,790,175.
</P>
<P>
   Taking TV 3-D From Inside the Set
</P>
<P>
   Watching television is still a passive activity, in spite of all
the hype about interactive TV. Sheldon Zelitt of North Gower,
Calif., hopes to enhance the experience somewhat with his invention
of three-dimensional television that does not require broadcasting
pictures in strange colors or wearing funny glasses.
</P>
<P>
   In his patent, Zelitt says he produces his 3-D images from a
two-dimensional display by ``varying the apparent distance of the
image from the viewer on a pixel-by-pixel basis.'' He inserts an
optical element next to each pixel. Each element is elongated so
that light can enter at different points. The place where the light
enters determines the illusion of the visual distance of its pixel
partner.
</P>
<P>
   The same technology can be used for computer monitors, film and
still photography, Zelitt says. He received patent 5,790,086.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
