<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Aug. 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will develop along much of
the East Coast from Maine to South Carolina on Monday as a pair of
jet-stream disturbances approach. With ample moisture in place
through a deep layer of the atmosphere as well as weak winds aloft,
thunderstorms will persist long enough in a few areas to induce
local flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, isolated thundershowers will plague the upper
Tennessee and Ohio valleys and the southern Great Lakes states as a
cold front advances southward.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the cold front, bright sunshine and lowering humidity
levels will grace the Upper Middle West and northern Plains.
Temperatures will still be quite warm behind the front, especially
in the Dakotas and Montana where highs will be in the upper 90s in
some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine and hot conditions will also scorch much of central
Texas and Oklahoma as high pressure at 18,000 feet builds over the
region. High temperatures will eclipse 100 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   A compact but vigorous disturbance will spawn showers and heavy
thunderstorms with gusty winds and hail from eastern Kansas to
central Arkansas. Additional thunderstorms will percolate in the
torrid air over Florida and along the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Copious moisture associated with the remnants of Tropical Storm
Frank will aid in the development of showers over the deserts and
plateaus of the Southwest and Rocky Mountains. Meanwhile in the
Pacific Northwest, low clouds will cling to the coast while
sunshine and seasonable heat dominate east of the Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Upwelling
</P>
<P>
   When this month began, the temperature of Lake Ontario near
Rochester, N.Y., was hovering near its seasonal peak of 70 degrees.
By early Saturday, the water temperature had plunged to a bracing
46 degrees. The profound chill came from waters that were drawn
from deep below the surface of the lake. An unusually persistent
air flow from the south has been pushing the surface waters of Lake
Ontario toward the northern shores. In order to compensate for the
northward flowing water, cool water has been rising from below
along the southern side of the lake in a process called upwelling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
