u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-EVACUATE-697-N     08-09 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-EVACUATE-697-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
15 WOUNDED IN NAIROBI BOMBING ARE FLOWN TO GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-VICTIMS, AFRICA-EMBASSY,
AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-TERROR, AFRICA-TANZANIA) 
(ll) 
 By CRAIG WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDSTUHL, Germany _ Fifteen people seriously wounded in the
bombing of the American Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya, were flown to
hospitals in Germany on Sunday by the United States Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 evacuees were a Marine Corps guard, nine civilian State
Department employees and five Kenyan staff members. The only
patient identified by military officials here was Mary Ofisi, a
46-year-old examiner who worked in the financial management center
on the first floor of the embassy. Ms. Ofisi, a Kenyan, said in an
interview in the U.S. Army Regional Medical Center here that she
heard three explosions on Friday morning before she found herself
on the floor with a thick, warm liquid _ her own blood _ covering
her face and upper body.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found myself, I was down under chairs, pieces of
computers, and I called to my friends and there was no sign,'' she
said. ``I knew then that I was alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Her left eye was covered with gauze, her face was cut and
scratched and her voice trembled as she said that she believed that
most of her closest co-workers had died. She and the other blast
victims were met by military ambulances at Ramstein Air Base when
they arrived at 12:10 p.m. after a 9{-hour flight on a gray Air
Force C-141B Starlifter.
</P>
<P>
   Another Kenyan employee of the embassy who was also on the
flight was carried, attached to intravenous tubes, on a stretcher
by 10 Air Force crew members to an Army helicopter for transfer to
a German university neurosurgery clinic in Homburg for intensive
care of his head wounds. The others all rode in ambulances the few
miles to the Army medical center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took these 15 because they were the most critically
injured,'' said Col. Lawrence Whitehurst of the Air Force,
commander of the 86th Medical Group at the base.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehurst said other victims who had been flown from Nairobi to
South Africa for treatment needed more immediate care.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said none of the Americans were able and
willing to talk with reporters on Sunday night. None of the 15 were
in danger of dying, officials said, but several were taken to the
emergency room for surgery for wounds like thigh and hip fractures,
punctures from shrapnel and eye damage.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ofisi said the U.S. ambassador in Nairobi told her on
Saturday that she would be flown to Germany for an operation to
repair fractures around her eye. Mrs. Ofisi said she had heard
three explosions on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sounded like gunshots,'' she said. ``The first was a big
noise, and we thought a tire had burst, and then immediately there
were two short ones.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``I feel good that the Lord spared my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Decisions on where to send embassy personnel from Kenya and
Tanzania are under the control of the United States Central
Command, based at McDill Air Force Base, Fla., the U.S. military
authority for operations in Africa below the Sahara, Whitehurst
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Russ Turner of the Air Force, chief flight surgeon of
the medical team that accompanied those who arrived on Sunday,
said, ``This is a seriously, seriously injured group of people who
are very traumatized, mentally and physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Scores of the 43,000 American military personnel stationed in
Ramstein, Landstuhl and nearby Kaiserslautern lined up in an
auditorium near the commissary on Sunday to give blood for the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   The plane that brought them had flown 172 units of blood,
transfusion and intubation equipment and other medical supplies to
Kenya on Saturday. Another C-141B sent from Ramstein with more
medical equipment and blood supplies on Saturday night is expected
to return by Monday with a few additional wounded victims.
</P>
<P>
   Turner described the wounded Marine guard who was brought here
as a hero in the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young marine was very severely injured,'' he said. ``He
got temporarily patched up and then signed himself out against
medical advice to go back and help others who had been hurt. There
were just heroic efforts on the ground.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
