<HEADLINE>
SLUMP IN SMALL-COMPANY STOCKS UNNERVES WALL ST. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., Ill.)  (ART ADV: A graphic and a photo are being sent to NYT
graphics/photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204, 1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Max Rodel, a 55-year-old chemist and investment fanatic, is
agonizing over his stock portfolio and feeling a bit rotten about
the way his small-company stocks have cratered in the last few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been absolutely miserable, not only for the last few
weeks but for the last few years,'' he said in a bout of
frustration. ``I'd invested in small caps for years and done well.
But I'm having a very bad year investing, one of the worst in 25
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Rodel, who works part time, took a few days off from
his consulting practice in Mill Valley, Calif., last week to glue
himself to CNBC financial news and to peruse his subscription of
Oberweis, a newsletter about small-company stocks. But as the stock
market swooned, he watched helplessly as some of the stocks in his
portfolio plummeted as much as 80 percent from his purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on? While the stocks of large, well-known companies
like McDonald's and Boeing have been battered for much of the last
month, the stocks of smaller companies have been hit even harder.
For instance, the Dow Jones industrial average _ a gauge of larger
blue-chip stocks _ has fallen 9 percent from its high in mid-July,
while the Russell 2000 index of small stocks has dropped 19 percent
from its high in April.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a study by John Manley, a securities analyst at Salomon
Smith Barney, showed that the majority of really small-company
issues _ 5,464 stocks with market values of less than $250 million
_ had fallen 45 percent on average from their peak through last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence has prompted some Wall Street analysts to talk
about a darker side of the bull market and to even suggest that a
bear market is in the offing. Despite solid gains in many blue-chip
issues, they say, the broader market is much sicker than many
investors realize.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just semantics, just a word game,'' said Gail Dudack,
chief investment strategist at Warburg Dillon Read. ``Most everyone
owns stocks, and no one wants to hear the words bear market. But
this is a bear market that's been working its way from the bottom
up, and that's classic.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, few on Wall Street are willing to view the recent
selloff as the prelude to a stock market crash, noting that the
economy is still growing and that foreigners continue to be eager
buyers of American stocks. Meanwhile, many analysts simply see a
new paradigm _ powered by baby boomers pouring money into
retirement plans _ that favors index funds of the big blue-chip
companies over small-company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, sharp declines in smaller stocks have not always
infected the broader market, and on Thursday and Friday both the
small and big stocks rallied, ending one of the nastiest selling
bouts in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But the downturn in small-company stocks is difficult to ignore.
Their weakness can be glimpsed in what market analysts call the
advance-decline line, a measure of how many stocks rise versus how
many fall over a given period. In the 30 days ended last Tuesday,
9,394 more stocks fell than rose, one of the worst performances in
a decade.
</P>
<P>
   That selloff caused blue-chip stocks to decline nearly 10
percent from their records, a sizable drop that analysts generally
consider a market correction. A bear market is defined as a 20
percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the misfortunes of smaller company stocks have
any greater significance in the current bull market, their weakness
has many on Wall Street paying heed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this says is that the bull market has become increasingly
narrow,'' said Claudia Mott, who tracks small-company stocks at
Prudential Securities. ``There's so much to be said for the
bargains in the small-stock sector, but the money is going into the
big names.''
</P>
<P>
   How bad is it? According to analysts, the performance gap
between large and small stocks is approaching the levels of the
Depression. The disparity, however, is not new. Since early 1994,
stocks of big companies have vastly outperformed stocks of smaller
companies. In April 1997, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index had
risen 19.8 percent in the previous 12 months, but the Russell 2000
index of smaller stocks had fallen 5.1 percent _ creating a spread
of about 25 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Early last week, the chasm between small and large stock
performance widened once again, to 17 percentage points. And
perhaps more important, the Russell dropped into negative territory
at its low on Wednesday, showing small stocks down 8.7 percent on
the year while the S&AMP;P 500 was up 11.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is close to the largest spread we've seen since October
1929 and October 1937,'' said Theodore Aronson, an analyst and
principal at Aronson &AMP; Partners, a money management firm in
Philadelphia. ``You can drive the proverbial truck through that
spread.''
</P>
<P>
   Such disparities exist despite studies that have shown that
smaller-company stocks generally outperform blue chips over the
long haul. In his book ``Stocks for the Long Run,'' Jeremy Siegel,
a professor at the Wharton School of the University of
Pennsylvania, says that going back to 1925, small stocks have
produced a compound annual return of 12.5 percent compared with 11
percent for the S&AMP;P 500. To be sure, Siegel and other studies note
that if the data exclude certain unique periods, large stocks
outperform smaller stocks by a narrow margin.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller-company stocks have also had a relatively strong track
record in earnings growth. Ms. Mott of Prudential said smaller
companies outpaced larger companies in earnings growth for five
consecutive quarters, a trend expected to continue well into 1999.
In the second quarter of 1998, she said, small companies had profit
gains of about 10 percent, compared with just 2 percent for S&AMP;P 500
companies.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, smaller-company stocks are at or near historically
low valuations. So investors are paying relatively little per share
for each dollar of earnings growth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cheap as the shares may be, investors want to see appreciation
over time, and over the last few years investors like Rodel have
watched their shares slip and slide while blue chips have soared.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for underperformance are many. But chief among them
seems to be the growing popularity of index funds that mimic the
performance of the S&AMP;P 500. Millions of investors, eager to ride
the bull market of blue chips, have tied their fortunes to such
indexes.
</P>
<P>
   Portfolio managers, fighting a losing battle against the index
funds, often find themselves riding the same stocks, trying to keep
pace, which creates a kind of blue-chip buying frenzy. And
foreigners, increasingly eager to invest in American companies, are
buying into the safest, most heavily traded stocks.
</P>
<P>
   This has helped push blue chips to record highs. In fact, much
as happened with the Nifty Fifty stocks of the 1970s, buying power
is being concentrated in an ever smaller group of stocks. For
instance, in the first half of this year, the top 10 stocks in size
in the S&AMP;P 500 had an average gain of 24.9 percent, while the
smallest 200 gained just 6.5 percent, on average.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of buying does not sit well with Jim Oberweis Sr.
Since 1976, Oberweis, whose office is in North Aurora, Ill., has
run the Oberweis small-stock newsletter and a mutual fund that
boasts an annualized return of about 25 percent over the last
decade. This year, however, his portfolio of small stocks is
lagging badly behind the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have clients scratching their heads saying, `Why do I go
through the effort to find good companies with good earnings and
then they don't do well?''' he said. Meanwhile, ``Coca-Cola is
selling at 50 times earnings with revenues growing 7 percent.
That's asinine. It may be a great company, but it's not a great
stock.''
</P>
<P>
   For many on Wall Street, the debate over small stocks comes down
to this: Is this a new era in which investors simply favor blue
chips in a global marketplace, despite higher prices and concerns
about Asia, or are investors signaling a bearish downturn by
retreating from a broad segment of the stock market?
</P>
<P>
   If history is any guide, the deterioration in small stocks
usually signals a sharper downturn for the broader market. In 1929
and 1972, small-company stocks began to deteriorate well ahead of
larger stocks, until the market behemoths collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   There have been exceptions, notably in 1997, when sharp
slowdowns in smaller stocks did not lead to a bear market, but
analysts say that more often than not, bear periods follow broader
meltdowns. And although this bull market _ now one of the longest
in history, having begun in October 1990 _ has defied many
historical markers, a growing number of analysts are concerned
about its longevity, particularly now that earnings growth has
slowed drastically for big companies.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Farrell, a longtime analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., noted
last week that some 70 percent of all over-the-counter stocks were
down 30 percent or more from their all-time highs, and he said this
weakness was a sign of bearishness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only a bull market in the sense that the big major stocks
haven't come down 10 percent,'' he said. ``But if you were told 50
percent of your portfolio was down 40 percent, it would be hard to
argue you weren't in a bear market.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more, once-bullish market commentators like Ralph Acampora,
a technical analyst at Prudential Securities who once predicted the
Dow would reach 10,000 by 2000, are turning bearish. Acampora's
bearish words on CNBC last Tuesday helped send the Dow plunging
299.43 points.
</P>
<P>
   But Aronson said that despite the bearish signals, nothing was
exact in the global marketplace, which depends on emotions as much
as calculations. ``None of these statistical relationship are
anything approaching `E equals MC squared,''' he said. ``There's no
formula. A lot of it is market psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Rodel, he is going to wait and hope that this is not the
onset of a bear market, but a cycle that could end with small
stocks taking back a leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have friends who only invest in the S&AMP;P 500 funds, and they
kind of tease me,'' he said. ``But I think I'm going to stick to my
guns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
