<HEADLINE>
PENN &AMP; TELLER'S NEXT TRICK: REVIVING THE VARIETY SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Penn &AMP; Teller's Sin City Spectacular,'' a variety show
premiering Monday on the FX cable channel, won me over before the
talking dog.
</P>
<P>
   But every good variety program needs a showstopper act, and Todd
Oliver and his stubby-legged mutt, Irving, are the stunner Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Left My Heart in San Francisco'' has been sung better, but
rarely outside the human species. At least it seems the dog sings
and talks. Never mind, just see it for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   When Irving started recalling how he'd spent his day, I was off
the chair and on the floor. See, it's not all (set ital)that(end
ital) hard to amuse a critic.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Carey, Lou Reed and Rob Schneider are on the show too.
Also, an acrobatic troupe, the Pavlovics.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Penn &AMP; Teller, a couple of brainy entertainers
who happen to be the Grand Guignol of modern magic.
</P>
<P>
   For the next several weeks, at least, ``Penn &AMP; Teller's Sin City
Spectacular'' _ the show is taped at the Luxor in Las Vegas _ will
try to revive a TV genre that's as old as Milton Berle's ``Texaco
Star Theater.'' The variety format is so antiquated that it seems
new again.
</P>
<P>
   Penn Jillette and his publicly silent partner, Teller, have
shaped the weekly series as a sort of homage to the variety shows
of the Ed Sullivan era. That means respect for the specialty acts
as well as the headliners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was just wonderful to have a plate spinner and
James Brown on the same show in Ed Sullivan's time,'' Jillette said
in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping there are some people (who) would like to see a
show that treats everybody in show business with respect and is, at
the same time, funny.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a decent goal. And, at least in the first show, nicely
realized.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Penn &AMP; Teller's Sin City Spectacular'' isn't Sullivan
redux. Big Ed might have spun on his axis and breathed flames if
he'd seen this ``really big shoe.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn and Teller indulge us with a cheesy showgirls-and-neon
opening. When Schneider makes his appearance, it's in the guise of
Dean Martin, saying, ``You know, most of your kids' music you
listen to today is crap, and I'd like to sing some of that crap for
you right now.'' Carey learns a trick that involves Teller's caged
head and hungry rats.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the ``Sexual Magic'' number, with Penn belting
suggestive lyrics while Teller beds down with a lightly attired
showgirl for a scorcher of a card trick.
</P>
<P>
   Clever stuff, mind you, but we aren't talking Topo Gigio.
</P>
<P>
   Irving the conversational dog, however, works clean. He'd do
Senor Wences proud. S'all right? S'all right.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
