<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-EMBASSY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANCE, AND LUCK, IN BOMBING AT U.S. EMBASSY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-VICTIMS, AFRICA-U.S.,
AFRICA-TERROR, AFRICA-EVACUATE, AFRICA-TANZANIA) 
(ll) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ An Air Force employee lost a chance to spend
Thursday night in Amsterdam, and lost her life when she went to
work on Friday. A 21-year-old Marine guard would probably have
lived if he had been at his post, in the front of the U.S. Embassy.
But he had just gone to get money for the weekend at the cashier's
office, in the back of the embassy, and was killed.
</P>
<P>
   By design, terrorist attacks are ruthlessly indiscriminate. The
blast that tore through the embassy here was no exception, taking
and sparing lives at will as it shattered the belief that any U.S.
outpost could be a low-security risk.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Kenyan victims had gone to the embassy early Friday
morning with the hope of getting a visa or job.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, timing blessed the embassy's most senior
diplomats, who were attending their weekly meeting in the
ambassador's spacious office on the embassy's fifth, and top,
floor, where the blast's impact was the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``That saved my life,'' said William Barr, the embassy's chief
spokesman, who had been thinking that he might slip away a bit
early on Friday, for a round of golf at the Muthaiga Club, the
fabled colonial hangout.
</P>
<P>
   For unknown reasons, Julian Bartley, the embassy's general
consul, was not at the meeting, as he would normally be. On Sunday,
he was the last of the dead American diplomats to be identified.
His son, Jay, a university student who had a summer job at the
embassy, was also killed in the blast.
</P>
<P>
   At the senior officers' meeting, one main item of discussion was
security. The senior diplomats tossed around ideas on how to impart
to this summer's new arrivals at the embassy the need for prudence
in this mile-high capital on the Equator that has been gripped by
street crime, while avoiding a siege mentality that would keep them
locked behind high walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rather ironic,'' Donald Mackenzie, regional director
for the U.S. Agency for International Development, recalled on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to tell them, `Kenya is really a marvelous place,
you can enjoy yourselves,''' said Mackenzie, who first began to
appreciate the country as a Peace Corps volunteer here 28 years
ago. ``This has traditionally been a place with a low terrorist
threat.''
</P>
<P>
   But at 10:35, as the meeting was nearing the end, there was a
loud thud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some one next to me said, `That's an explosion,' '' recalled
Paul Peterson, who arrived here only three weeks ago, as the State
Department's regional security officer. ``I knew instantly it was a
bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   About 10 seconds later came the second, and far more powerful,
blast _ the one that tore through the embassy, leveled the building
next door, and blew out every window to the top of the 22-story
Cooperative Bank building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the first one out of the room,'' Peterson said. ``I saw
bloody people everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened is still far from clear. It appears that a vehicle
loaded with explosives drove into a parking lot behind the embassy.
There have been reports in the local papers that gun shots were
heard before the explosions, but these have not been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The blast knocked Mackenzie, who was sitting near a window, out
of his chair, and he suffered minor cuts on the back. He picked
himself up, and quickly followed the others out of the room. They
started down the stairwell, now without any light. And with the
walls crumbling, debris turned the stairs into something more akin
to a slide, Mackenzie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dust was just horrible,'' he added. ``A lot of us were
fearing that we could not go on breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, there was no panic, not even screaming inside the
embassy, several diplomats recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But there was random death.
</P>
<P>
   Among the unfortunate were those embassy employees who, with the
weekend approaching, had gone to the cashier's office and the
Citibank branch to get money. They are located in the back of the
embassy, on the first floor, which took the brunt of the blast.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Jesse Aliganga, a Marine sergeant from Florida,
was killed, said Peterson, the embassy security officer.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a strike at Kenya's commercial banks, the secretary
for Barr, the embassy spokesman, asked for time to go from their
offices, about a half-mile from the embassy, to transact business
at Citibank.
</P>
<P>
   ``She went down and she didn't come back,'' Barr said. He asked
that her name not be published because the Kenyan government had
not released the names of the Kenyan victims.
</P>
<P>
   Fate also dealt cruelly with Arlene Kirk, an Air Force employee
at the embassy, and Robert Kirk, who worked for the Agency for
International Development. The couple were returning to Nairobi
from vacation. Their flight from Amsterdam was overbooked and the
airline asked for volunteers to forgo their seat, in exchange for
some money and a free night in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   The Kirks decided to take it, Barr said. But by the time they
got to the counter, enough other passengers had volunteered. So the
Kirks got on the flight, and returned to work on Friday, where Mrs.
Kirk was killed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
