A5125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-SCAMS-NYT &LR;      08-09 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SCAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS TARGET ENTERTAINMENT-RELATED INVESTMENT SCAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is too late to invest in ``Titanic,'' but how about a chance
to invest in the films of Lyman Dayton, a producer and director who
won prestigious awards at the Cannes Film Festival and whose
previous projects gave investors profits of 500 percent?
</P>
<P>
   That sales pitch attracted plenty of investors, according to the
Federal Trade Commission. But while Dayton was real, his supposed
awards were not. The returns to investors in his films were far
smaller and substantially more investors were allowed in than the
sellers had claimed. While Dayton was not charged with wrongdoing,
the commission has won more than $12 million in judgments from
several telemarketers who sold the film partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many Americans track weekend box-office grosses
with a fervor matched only by their obsession with the stock
market, investment scams have found a new and apparently fertile
field: entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, state and federal securities regulators have
filed a growing number of enforcement actions against individuals
and companies that have sought to raise money for investments in
film, television or other entertainment projects.
</P>
<P>
   Now, intent on fighting back even harder, regulators are joining
forces. On Tuesday, senior officials from the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the Federal Trade Commission and the North
American Securities Administrators Association, a group of state
regulators, will announce a joint crackdown on fraudulent
investment opportunities in the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people selling these investments read the headlines and
glom onto whatever is hot,'' said Mark Beauchamp, a spokesman for
the state regulators group. ``We've seen deals involving supposed
movies, television shows, cable investment opportunities,
infomercials and theme restaurants. There's a fair bit of it out
there, and they're selling it through the Web or through
old-fashioned boiler room tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   While regulators say they have seen isolated cases of
entertainment-related fraud over the years, its prevalence, and the
amount of money its perpetrators have been able to raise from
investors, has increased markedly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The deals recycle many of the usual tactics of investment fraud.
Sometimes, state regulators shut down an operation in one state
only to see it move to another. Last year, Wisconsin regulators
undertook an enforcement action against a film company called
Desert Gold Partners of Hollywood for selling unregistered
securities. The action followed similar filings against the same
company by regulators in Texas, Iowa, Kansas and Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Other entertainment ventures appeal to gullible investors who
see them almost as charitable causes. Regulators in Arizona and
Arkansas recently brought actions against an outfit called kidZtime
TV, which was accused of selling unregistered partnership units in
a company that claimed it would obtain the broadcast rights to
nonviolent children's programing on cable television systems.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has also sharpened its focus on entertainment ventures
that end up defrauding investors. The commission is pursuing
regulatory actions against former insiders at First National
Entertainment, which produced a feature-length animated film called
``Happily Ever After'' that fell far short of the returns it had
projected.
</P>
<P>
   ``People read how motion pictures like `Titanic' make $1
billion,'' said David Cohen, supervising attorney in the
enforcement unit of the Wisconsin division of securities. With oil
and gas prices cheap, investment opportunities in that
traditionally fraud-ridden field are less attractive. And
regulators have been fairly successful at alerting investors to the
dangers of high-technology ventures, like wireless cable deals.
Therefore, Cohen said, ``I guess they need something else to
sell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 1835EDT &QL; 
