<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      08-09 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEC Takes Close Look at Accounting of Web Deals
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission may be voicing subtle
warnings about the unusually high prices of Internet industry
stocks by reviewing how acquisitions are accounted for on the
buyers' financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent example is America Online, which was not able
to release its quarterly and full-year earnings last week, because
it is still wrestling with the SEC over the accounting for two
recent acquisitions. The issue is how much of the price the online
service paid for the acquisitions can be written off now vs. how
much must be deducted over many quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble in Paradise for Alaska Men
</P>
<P>
   Even a labor of love can have its problems. Alaska Men, a
magazine whose mission is to advertise the state's plentiful supply
of bachelors to spouse-seeking women around the world, is in a
legal battle over its control, and publication has been suspended
since winter. But thanks to the Internet, matchmaking has not been
completely stymied. The publisher has set up a Web site for the
magazine and hopes to resume printing soon.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Brown Hires New Yorker Colleague
</P>
<P>
   Editor Tina Brown, the former editor of The New Yorker, has
chosen one of her longtime colleagues to be executive editor of her
new magazine at Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   Crackdown on Entertainment Fraud
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many Americans track box-office grosses with a
fervor matched only by their obsession with the stock market,
securities regulators have filed a growing number of enforcement
actions against individuals and companies who have sought to raise
money for investments in film, television or other entertainment
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Cybercash's Lesson in Web Survival
</P>
<P>
   Cybercash, a company built on a technology for transferring
money on the Internet that failed to find a market, has survived by
adapting to the less sophisticated security technology widely in
use. Yet the company's history shows how difficult it can be for
any company to steer standards into the unpredictable currents of
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Home in Silicon Valley
</P>
<P>
   Steven Ballmer, newly elevated to president of Microsoft,
announced last week that his company would set up a satellite
headquarters in Mountain View, Calif., in Silicon Valley. Not lost
on anyone is the fact that Microsoft is moving into the hometown of
Netscape Communications, whose struggle with Microsoft is at the
heart of the government's antitrust suit against Ballmer's company.
</P>
<P>
   The Web's Built-In Marketing Force
</P>
<P>
   Like franchising without the franchises, companies on the Web
are using affiliate networks to do their marketing for them.
Affiliates earn commissions just for enticing online shoppers to
click to another company's site to buy something. Many
entrepreneurs see it as the perfect way to capitalize on the
medium's capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Suit Filed Over Nerve Gas Report
</P>
<P>
   Cable News Network and Time magazine have been hit with the
first lawsuit filed in response to their joint report in June
contending that the U.S. military dropped lethal nerve gas in Laos
in 1970.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
