<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIAPOLITICS-NYT &LR;      08-09 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAS VOTING IN CAMBODIA REALLY FAIR? NEW DOUBTS 
</HEADLINE>
 POLITICS-NYT  (ll) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ As bargaining continued over the shape of a
coalition government in Cambodia, new reports emerged on Sunday
that the ruling party, headed by the apparent winner of last
month's election, Hun Sen, has been harassing political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch, the monitoring group based New York, issued
a statement saying it had found evidence of ``a wave of reprisals
and threats by officials or security forces affiliated with Hun
Sen's Cambodian People's Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no one had been killed, it said, members of Hun Sen's
party were forcing members of opposition parties to flee their
villages by threatening and sometimes shooting at them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it said, some members of the ruling party who had
failed to deliver the vote in their areas last month were also
being threatened by fellow party members. Separately, an official
of the International Republican Institute, a private group
affiliated with the American Republican Party, which helped monitor
the election, said on Sunday that the group was still receiving
reports of a variety of electoral abuses and was withholding
judgment on the fairness of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   These statements added to a growing sense of unease about the
quality of the election, held on July 26, in which Hun Sen's party,
according to the official count, won a majority of seats in
parliament, but not the two-thirds needed to form a government.
</P>
<P>
   But the election committee that organized the balloting, and is
conducting the count and hears complaints about abuses, is
controlled by Hun Sen's party, as are most municipalities, police
departments and other government agencies around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The accumulating reports of abuses suggested that in a number of
instances _ and perhaps in a systematic way around the country _
the governing party had employed its powers to manipulate the
election's outcome. But it was impossible to tell whether any such
manipulation affected the overall result, as the second and
third-place finishers, Prince Norodom Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy,
have complained.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Grove, the director of the International Republican
Institute's Asia division, offered an assessment of the voting, the
mood two days later and the current situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I clearly saw the enthusiasm and euphoria on election day,''
Grove said. ``By Tuesday morning, this euphoria had turned into
despair and now, I am hearing from my Khmer friends, that despair
is turning to anger.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Washington, Grove said he had
witnessed the unannounced removal of ballot boxes from a precinct
to the central counting center at 4 a.m. on the night after the
election, and had been illegally barred from observing what became
of them.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, a number of foreign diplomats based in Cambodia
have commented that there are no true democrats in Cambodia's
competition and that there is no guarantee that the parties of
Ranariddh or Sam Rainsy would have acted any better if they had Hun
Sen's power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 1846EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
