<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5141 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     08-09 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     AN HOUR WITH PHIL HARTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Paul Hartmann &LR; ((cq)), brother of the late comedian  &UR; Phil &LR; 
 &UR; Hartman &LR; , has asked Dr.  &UR; Gene Schoenfeld &LR;  to review and interpret
toxicological reports and medical records of  &UR; Brynn Hartman &LR; , who
killed her husband and herself. Her body was found to contain
evidence of cocaine, alcohol and Zoloft.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld, who often serves as a forensic consultant on the
effects of psychoactive drugs, says he was stunned when Hartmann
came to his San Francisco office carrying a small wooden box of his
brother's ashes.
</P>
<P>
   The Hartmann family is large, explained Paul, and each of Phil's
siblings was given a portion of the c &LR; remains. ``I thought you
might want to be with Phil for a while,'' said Paul, handing the
box to Schoenfeld to hold during their conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul has since returned to Southern California with the little
wooden box,'' says Schoenfeld. ``I was truly pleased and deeply
touched by this encounter.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; ABCS FROM AARDVARKS, BATS AND COUGARS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Allen &LR;  and  &UR; Linda Anderson &LR; , publishers of the Minneapolis
newsletter Angel Animals and a forthcoming book on spiritual
lessons taught to humans by animals, will present a San Francisco
workshop Monday for the Learning Annex. Among the stories that have
appeared in their inspirational newsletter:
</P>
<P>
   ``A Rabbit Helped Me Take My Next Spiritual Step'', ``Learning
Patience From My Cockatiels'', ``How a Fish Connected Me to My
Spiritual Ministry'' and ``A Cat Showed Me How to Get Pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MATTERS OF PRINCIPLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Food for the party  &UR; Kim Basinger &LR;  and  &UR; Alec Baldwin &LR;  threw for
the Clintons last week in the Hamptons was supplied by 24 local
restaurants, one of which was planning a contribution the
animal-loving Baldwins couldn't accept. The hosts became ``very
upset,'' reported the New York Post, when they learned that foie
gras -- made from force-fed ducks and geese -- was on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin called someone high up in the Democratic Party and
insisted that the delicacy not be served.
</P>
<P>
   - The California Cigar Association and the San Francisco Giants
co-hosted a $15-a-head pregame cigar party Friday night to
celebrate what CCA president  &UR; Nick Nikkah &LR;  referred to as ``the
perfect melding of two American pastimes: baseball and the
enjoyment of a fine cigar.'' The CCA describes itself as a
``statewide association dedicated to combat unnecessary laws''
about cigar smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Lest the pro-cigar event lead people to the conclusion that the
Giants are pro-tobacco, fans at Monday's game will be given flyers
educating them about the evils of chewing tobacco. Ten thousand
will be handed out.
</P>
<P>
   Although smoking is banned in the stands at 3Com Park and team
trainer  &UR; Mark &LR;   &UR; Letendre &LR;  is heavily involved in the campaign
against chewing tobacco, the Giants have no official anti-tobacco
policy, the team's  &UR; Blake Rhodes  &LR; told Personals.
</P>
<P>
   - Before Sunday's Pretenders and B-52's concert at Shoreline
Amphitheatre, lead singers  &UR; Chrissie Hynde  &LR; and  &UR; Kate Pierson &LR; 
sponsored a signature drive for a petition urging the University of
California to cancel experiments in which monkeys will be subjected
to deafening levels of sound. Learning of &UR; Paul &LR; 
 &UR; McCartney &LR; 's recent letter asking that the experiments be called
off, Hynde had written to UC officials last week to add her voice
to his plea.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Heidi Fleiss &LR; , the Hollywood madam serving time in the
federal prison in Dublin, says in an interview to be broadcast
October 19 on A&AMP;E's ``American Justice'' that's she's bitter that
 &UR; Charlie Sheen &LR; , a former client who testified against her, was
``treated like a superstar.'' She went to jail, she said, while he
signed autographs for FBI agents. ``I don't know,'' said the
feminist entrepreneur. ``It's a man's world.''
</P>
<P>
   - Friday's item about  &UR; Princess Diana &LR; 's dress came from Good
Housekeeping, not Vanity Fair.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Dogs are considered property, but cats are not. They're like &LR; 
 &UR; squirrels. A horse would be considered property and anything &LR; 
 &UR; larger than a dog would be considered property.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Art Carbonel &LR;  of the California Highway Patrol in Monterey,
where an ordinance about collisions between animals and cars is
under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
