single mother who worked as a clerk at the Ufundi Cooperative
Savings and Credit Society. Her brother, Frederick, a father of two
young boys, also worked at the bank. He is missing and presumed
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Friends described Miss Ndolo as a talkative and independent
young woman who liked to go dancing in Nairobi nightclubs and
enjoyed her single life. She had been pleased to discover that she
was pregnant last year. Her baby boy is three months old.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was happy about the baby,'' her father, Michael Opondo
Ndolo, a retired civil servant, said as he waited for his
daughter's body to be loaded into a hearse. ``She had a plan of
opening a small shop, a boutique.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the sentiment of many grieving family members here,
Ndolo said the American Embassy should be moved far from the center
of town.
</P>
<P>
   Naftali Muyonga, a senior official in the Foreign Ministry, came
to the morgue to take care of arrangements for his brother-in-law,
Moises Ashton Mwani, who was a high-ranking civil servant in the
Teachers Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Mwani, 50, was killed by shrapnel from the blast as he sat in a
meeting on the fourth floor of a building next to the Ufundi
building, Muyonga said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we fail to understand is why the terrorists should pick
on a peaceful country like Kenya,'' Muyonga said.
</P>
<P>
   At about noon, Omukhani and his friends carried the body of his
wife, Elizabeth Akino, out of the morgue on a stretcher and into a
van. Half her face and head had been destroyed by shrapnel. The
hearse took the body to a funeral home in Nairobi's center, to keep
until the family can collect enough money to transport her body to
western Kenya for burial.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Akino's death was a heavy blow for her family. She has two
children, an 8-year-old boy, Marvin, and a 3-year-old girl. Her
husband has been on strike from the Kenya Commercial Bank for a
week, along with thousands of other bank employees. The striking
workers were dismissed by management last week, and it is unclear
if they will be allowed to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be worried,'' Omukhani said. ``I don't know my fate
as of now. I'm just wishing that all will go well and I'll go back
to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Akino's older sister, Tereza Okidi, 45, said she was worried
the family would not have enough money to support the children. Ms.
Okidi, a former secretary, said she had recently started a small
restaurant in a marketplace. But she has two grown children of her
own, both unemployed, and her earnings will not stretch far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to start life with these small children,''
she said. ``I can't neglect my sister's children. I can't run from
the responsibility. It has found me and it is mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friends and relatives described Ms. Akino as a strong,
athletic woman. She played semiprofessional volleyball for the
Kenya Commercial Bank team for several years before she gave it up
to devote herself to her children, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Nairobi, Ms. Akino was the sixth child in a family of
nine. Her father was a mechanic. She attended public schools and
finished high school, but never had enough money to go to college,
relatives said. She was studying typing and shorthand and dreamed
of becoming a secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, she had grown more religious. She loved gospel
music and spent much of her spare time working with women's
organizations and church groups. Though she was not garrulous, she
had many friends. Her desk at work was a magnet for people on their
coffee breaks, so much so that her boss sometimes complained.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Akino and her husband and children lived in a one-room
apartment in a barracks-style public housing project in Bahati, a
working-class neighborhood. She talked often to friends about her
desire to move into a bigger house, buy a car and have a third
child.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of the tiny home are decorated with banners from
volleyball tournaments. There is a showcase with trophies on one
wall. Her husband is also a player, for the Kenya National Team.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, her family and friends met in her home to
share stories and talk about funeral arrangements. Several fought
back tears as they gathered outside on wooden benches under a gray
sky. They prayed together first and then began to talk in low tones
about what was needed for a respectable funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was my best friend,'' said Danae Tirop, 28, who also
played for the bank's volleyball team. ``She was the maid of honor
at my wedding. She was warm, generous, kind, understanding. She
always thought of her children first.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tirop's eyes welled up.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that Friday, I actually wanted to go to see her,'' she
said. ``But I decided to wait until after lunch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
