<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUBIOUS DATA ON SAVINGS AREN'T WORTH WORRYING ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: If the news that America's savings rate hit a record
low recently stimulated your caring glands, you're misallocating
your anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   It has become fashionable to fret about America's grasshopper
tendencies even as the ants get the worst of it. It could be argued
convincingly, in fact, that the transformation of the erstwhile
Asian dynamos into zombies was caused by too much savings. Those
economies ended up with more savings than could be used
efficiently, which led those running the financial system to
channel the excess into wasteful investments.
</P>
<P>
   This is always the problem. Savings may be the raw material of
investment, but unless the resources are allocated to the highest
and best use, savings won't translate into prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Although Americans persist in beating themselves up because the
national savings rate isn't higher, it's quite possible the savings
rate has, for the time being at least, outlived its usefulness as
an economic statistic.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy is driven by personal consumption, which fuels
two-thirds of the country's growth. In Japan, the comparable figure
is almost 10 percent lower. This helps explain why Japan's economy
is sputtering while America's is thriving.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is caught in what some economists might call a liquidity
trap. Bankers call it pushing on a string. Japan's policy-makers
seek more consumption to stimulate growth and design policy to
encourage consumer spending. Japanese fears about the economic
future, however, prompt more savings and less consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Would America want to trade its anemic savings problem for
Japan's inadequate consumption problem? Probably not, given the
realities of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there is good reason to doubt the validity of the
savings statistic. The level of mutual fund assets recently topped
$5 trillion, an increase of nearly 1,700 percent over the last 16
years. Smart Money recently noted that employer-sponsored 401(k)
plans, which weren't widely available when the decade began, now
are used by 25 million workers who are sitting atop some $1
trillion worth of 401(k) investments.
</P>
<P>
   These sorts of statistics wouldn't seem to reflect any serious
lack of interest in saving for a rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of statistical cognitive dissonance, a number in
the most recent savings story didn't compute at all. The article
quoted a Federal Reserve estimate that nearly 60 percent of all
families don't own stock, which means they haven't benefited from
the bull market of the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Without disputing the numbers outright, it's probably a
reasonable guess that a significant number of these families
include workers whose pension funds are substantially invested in
stocks. If so, it means these workers probably feel less pressure
to save for their retirement and thus are more active consumers
than otherwise would be the case. As consumers, of course, they
help generate the economic growth that has been a key factor in the
stock market surge.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Social Security money each month transfers money from
a generation that might save it to a generation that almost
certainly will spend it. The generation providing the money thus
feels less need to save because of the expectation that Social
Security also will supplement their needs when they become elderly.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is worrisome, perhaps, but the result so far is an
economy that serves society's needs better than any other in the
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
