<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SAFE IN THE CENTER OF TOWN AND FAR FROM THE SPRAWL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Our home for the first six months of marriage was a
rented cottage well beyond the city's edge.
</P>
<P>
   The property was bounded on one side by a railroad track, and on
two others by meadows where quail whistled and the rank grass was
interlaced with rabbits' runways.
</P>
<P>
   An interstate highway passed by a quarter mile to the east, but
it was screened by trees, out of sight and almost out of hearing.
</P>
<P>
   That was the road my new bride and I both took to our work in
town. It was a trip of 25 minutes or a bit more at rush hour. We
complained about the time it took, and about beginning and ending
our days with that hectic drive.
</P>
<P>
   The truth, however, is that the volume of traffic the highway
carried was not so great. Neither was the hazard. Drivers behaved
civilly then, and the term road rage had not even yet been coined.
</P>
<P>
   A morning errand the other day took me past that place where we
once lived.
</P>
<P>
   The open fields are gone _ that whole area having become, in
effect, an immense industrial park. The great undistinguished
buildings have a mechanical and inhuman aspect. And that is only
the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   For far out past that sprawls the residential development _
treeless subdivisions to the horizon and beyond. More highways have
been built, all interconnecting, to carry the automobiles of the
grim legions who make their twice-daily passages from and to the
cookie-cutter warrens of exurbia.
</P>
<P>
   It had occurred to me to notice my watch, so that I might
compare the time of travel with the trips of that earlier year.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sense of fever and fury on the road. Cars weaved in
and out, changing lanes like shuttles in a loom. Horns blared. A
man went past me with his face set in a scowl, jaw thrust out,
gripping the wheel like someone choking snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the drivers were chatting on their car phones. Others
were applying lipstick or eye shadow. All this while the flow of
traffic proceeded practically bumper to bumper, sometimes at a
crawl, sometimes a full 15 miles an hour over the speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   And that journey that formerly had taken 25 minutes, sometimes
less, now required a bit over 40 minutes. Meantime, at the sides,
road construction crews were at work, slicing off a part of the
hillside to make room for more lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Our home is in the city now. In the rush hour, I need 15 minutes
to get to the office. Other times of the day, I can make it in 10.
</P>
<P>
   I realized in that moment, as I was borne along in the careening
mob, that nothing under heaven could persuade me to live as those
people live. And I also received what I believe to be a powerful,
if not very original, insight.
</P>
<P>
   It is that the very machine which has destroyed the cities _ the
automobile _ may in the end turn out, ironically, to be their
salvation.
</P>
<P>
   The time must eventually come when there will be no place left
to lay new pavement. The numbers of vehicles, expanding
exponentially, will overwhelm the road builders.
</P>
<P>
   As traffic of outlying areas degenerates toward gridlock, the
danger and the fury will become intolerable and unmanageable. And
it will occur to the exurbanites, as it has to me, that no one
should have to live that way.
</P>
<P>
   The flow to the outermost edges will be reversed. People will
look once more to the place they left, the center, and with their
return will come new vitality.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the farthest suburbs could stand empty. A hot wind will
blow across that asphalt desert, as if it were some abandoned
station on the planet Mars.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that may not ever actually happen. But as Brett Ashley
says in the final line, ``Isn't it pretty to think so?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
