<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5168 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     08-09 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
In this instance, bronze is beautiful
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ If the Dream Team had been here, Rudy
Tomjanovich would have gone home with a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dream Team had been here _ Grant Hill, Gary Payton, Tim
Hardaway and the rest of the big-name NBA stars _ the outcome would
have been a foregone conclusion. The United States would have won
by 20, 30 or 40 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dream Team had been here, the only questions would have
been who among them would cause the first international incident
and whether Nike, Reebok or Adidas won the sneaker wars.
</P>
<P>
   The World Championship of Basketball ended with Yugoslavia
edging Russia 64-62 for the gold medal and Rudy T's American
Dreamers whipping Greece 84-61 for a third-place finish, which was
anything but a bronze bust.
</P>
<P>
   The night after they lost a stunner to Russia in the semifinals,
blowing a 10-point lead, the Dreamers were reeling from the
emotional blow. Yet in the fragile hours when it still hurt like an
open wound, they were beginning to look at the overall picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the greatest basketball experience of my life,'' said
David Wood, 33, who has played for 13 pro teams and eight NBA
franchises. ``It was an honor to play for my country. I never knew
what it was like to be an Olympic athlete, and now I do. This will
always be very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition was genuine
</P>
<P>
   It was special because of the circumstances that brought them
together for a 4{-week whirlwind tour through four countries as
this disparate group of European exiles, Continental Basketball
Association lifers and one college star stepped into the breach
left by the Dream Team's absence.
</P>
<P>
   It was a question that dogged their every step, a shadow they
could never hope to outrun: Wouldn't the Dream Team have done
better?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it would have. But that is not to say it would have
been a better experience for those involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Dream Team, the talent level, of course, would have
been overwhelming,'' Tomjanovich said. ``With that team, you're
talking about detail work, getting plays just right, trying to do
this and that and, at the same time, entertain everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's almost a no-win situation. If you win by 15 or 20,
people want to know why it wasn't 25 or 30. In spite of the
disappointment, in a lot of ways, this felt more satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just the point. It was more satisfying seeing a committed
coaching staff take mediocre-but-devoted players from the depths of
America's basketball talent and mold them into a team that became a
legitimate threat to win the title.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy T's staff fought the odds of playing against veteran
national teams that have been together for years and a deck that
was stacked against them. First, the NBA stars abandoned them.
Then, some of the bottom-dwelling life forms known as player agents
sabotaged their effort, persuading experienced former NBA players _
i.e., Byron Scott and Dominique Wilkins _ to pass on invitations as
a show of support for the union.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, what did U.S. fans miss without the Dream Team,
except a gold medal that would have come from overkill in place of
true competition, like using a sledgehammer to swat a mosquito?
</P>
<P>
   Testament to Rudy T
</P>
<P>
   In order to feel ahead of the rest of the world hoopswise, must
we always gas up the Enola Gay for another bombing run? Truth is,
if an air of superiority is all we're looking to get out of these
affairs, we can feel smug having scared the bejabbers out of the
tournament field with a roster that included none of America's
roughly top 500 players.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, this was big. The job he did under these circumstances makes
Rudy T the front-runner to be the U.S. Olympic coach at Sydney in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamers always will remember the last three minutes against
Russia, the misplays, the bad calls. It's a fact of life at this
level. This is a different, quicker, more partisan, and in some
ways, better game than the NBA. No dancing girls, mascots, blaring
music or whoring for the corporate dollar with a promotion during
each timeout. It is just basketball with national flags, chanting
and thick cigarette smoke. Also, offenses are always on the attack,
even if not as skilled.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamers played hard, running their legs and not their
mouths. There was none of the trash-talking or crotch-grabbing
demonstrated by Derrick Coleman and Larry Johnson in 1994. There
was little ego, certainly none of the Dream Team conceit.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys got as much out of what they have as any team I've
ever been around,'' Rudy T said.
</P>
<P>
   No gold. Just an experience to be bronzed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
