<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POVERTY-COX     08-09 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POVERTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Third of nation flirts with poverty, census study finds
 &HT;    By Scott Shepard
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Poverty in the United States may be more of a
revolving door than a trap door, with nearly one-third of Americans
falling into poverty for months at a time only to pull out later,
the U.S. Census Bureau reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The report used seven different economic measures designed to
provide a ``video'' look at poverty instead of the more traditional
``snapshot.'' It concluded that while some Americans are mired in
chronic poverty, for most, poverty is ``a transitory condition,''
sometimes lasting no more than a couple of months in any given
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who experience poverty generally escape it within
a few months,'' said Mary Naifeh, author of the report.
</P>
<P>
   Naifeh, comparing 1993 and 1994 survey data, found that 30
percent of the U.S. population was poor for at least two months,
but only 5 percent was poor continuously for the full 24-month
period. She concluded that while ``poverty rates may suggest to
some that poverty is a chronic condition, the reality is quite
different.''
</P>
<P>
   She found that 41.8 percent of Hispanics and 40.2 percent of
African Americans slipped into poverty for at least two months
during the study period, compared to 18.3 percent of whites. People
in families headed by a single female had the highest poverty rate
of any group, 48.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The average number of months spent in poverty was 4.5 over all,
with whites averaging 4.2 months; African Americans, 6 months;
Hispanics, 5 months; and single female households, 7.2 months.
</P>
<P>
   Children had the highest ``entry rate'' into poverty: 4.4
percent of those ages 0-17 who were not poor in 1993 fell into
poverty during 1994. The entry rate for those age 18-64 years was 3
percent. Among retirement-age adults, only 2 percent slipped into
poverty from one year to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Naifeh also found that 21.5 percent of central city dwellers
experienced poverty during the study period, compared to 17.5
percent of ``nonmetropolitan'' residents and only 10 percent of
those living in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The statistical poverty threshold, based on after-tax income and
the number of adults and children in a family, is adjusted each
year by the federal government. In 1993, it was $14,654 for a
two-adult, two-child family. In 1994, it was $15,029 for the same
family.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty experts cautioned that the new Census data could be
easily misinterpreted as suggesting that the United States, now in
the eighth year of unprecedented economic growth, does not have a
significant poverty problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always known that there's a lot of mixing and churning
going on,'' said Robert Haveman, an economics professor at the
University of Wisconsin-Madison and an associate of the
university's Institute for Research on Poverty. ``And the way we've
traditionally measured poverty has taken that into account.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question is whether upward mobility is occurring any
faster now that it has in past economic periods,'' said Jared
Bernstein, an analyst at the Economic Policy Institute in
Washington. ``And every indication is that appears to be
unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past 15 years, the rate of people moving out of poverty
has been relatively unresponsive to the growth of the economy,
according to Bernstein. Further, in the robust economic expansion
of recent years, the national poverty rate has dropped only 1.1
percent, from 14.8 percent in 1992 to 13.7 percent in 1996, the
latest year for which complete Census data are available.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
