<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. CHIEF TRIES AGAIN TO PERSUADE IRAQ TO SUBMIT TO ARMS
INSPECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan summoned his special envoy in
Baghdad for talks this weekend and sent him back with a message
asking President Saddam Hussein to end Iraq's refusal to cooperate
with arms inspectors, Annan's spokesman said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The envoy, Prakash Shah of India, had several private meetings
with Annan over the weekend in Lisbon, where the secretary general
is on an official visit, said Fred Eckhart, the U.N. spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Annan's actions lent his authority to efforts to prevent a new
crisis over U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq from getting out of
control.
</P>
<P>
   No active weapons searches have taken place in Iraq since it
said on Wednesday that it would no longer cooperate with
inspectors. Only the maintenance of long-term surveillance
equipment installed at Iraqi sites is being permitted.
</P>
<P>
   That type of surveillance was to have been the next stage in the
monitoring process, after Iraq had been declared free of banned
weapons and sanctions had been lifted, but Iraq appears to be
trying to move itself to that stage by fiat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspections in respect of the commission's disarmament
responsibility are temporarily suspended,'' Janet Sullivan, a
spokeswoman for the U.N. Special Commission, the weapons inspection
agency, told Reuters in Baghdad on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials and diplomats say it is difficult to see how the
more intrusive inspections can be resumed unless Saddam Hussein
sees some gain in reversing his order.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has demanded an immediate lifting of sanctions. At the same
time, Saddam Hussein has been building support in the Arab world
and among some members of the U.N. Security Council for
circumventing the embargo imposed in 1990 if the United States and
Britain, both of which have veto power, insist that the sanctions
stay in place until outstanding questions about Iraq's prohibited
weapons programs have been answered. The next major sanctions
review is in October.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its stand in the crisis early this year, the Clinton
administration has conspicuously not threatened the use of force to
win Iraqi compliance with inspections. American military strength
in the Persian Gulf has been reduced since the end of the last
crisis, which was defused by Annan with a visit to Baghdad in
February.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has chosen instead to focus on
weakening Saddam Hussein by aiding rebellious Kurds in a
semiautonomous region of northern Iraq, victims of two decades of
persecution that human rights groups define as genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Kurds were attacked with chemical weapons in the
mid-1980s. Many others were forcibly moved from their homes, and an
unknown number were shot and killed.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has moved troops into the Kurdish region in recent days,
and some experts on the region say Kurdish leaders may need the
promise of military support if they are to be prevented from
seeking a deal with Saddam Hussein rather than face another Iraqi
campaign against them. They say that the Kurds do not have a hope
of toppling Saddam Hussein and that the only potentially effective
rebellion might be from Arab clans in the Iraqi heartland.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Wedgwood, an expert on international organizations at Yale
Law School and the Council on Foreign Relations, says in a
forthcoming article in the American Journal of International Law
that the last crisis with Iraq teaches that without a stronger
threat from the United States, statements and demands from the
divided Security Council will not have much effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``In international politics, multilateral diplomacy without a
unilateral commitment to enforcement is unlikely to be effective,''
Ms. Wedgwood wrote. She recalls Annan's remark in Baghdad in
February, when the Persian Gulf bristled with American and British
warships.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do a lot with diplomacy, but of course you can do a
lot more with diplomacy backed up by firmness and force,'' Annan
said then, just after extracting a pledge of cooperation from Iraq.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Iraq, aware of American reluctance to threaten force this time,
is trying to portray the current crisis as the fault of the United
States. A letter to the Security Council last week from Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz, Saddam Hussein's spokesman to the
outside world, characterized the sanctions as ``the injustice
created and maintained by the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Some officials and diplomats from the Middle East say they
suspect a link between Iraqi belligerence toward the United States
and an increasingly acquiescent environment for a new round of
terrorism by Arab militants. Even governments friendly to the
United States are under intense pressure from radicals because of
the deadlock in peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   While stopping short of suggesting a direct relationship between
the Iraqi crisis and the bombing of American embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania on Friday, an official said Arabs had been warning for
months about a generally poisonous atmosphere toward the United
States spreading in the Arab world, fueled by the Iraqi crisis and
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Arab League accused Richard Butler, executive
chairman of the U.N. arms inspection agency for Iraq and its chief
arms inspector, of overstepping his mandate in continuing to demand
a fuller account of weapons programs from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butler's actions exceed his duties, since Iraq has fulfilled
all its commitments concerning weapons of mass destruction,'' the
Arab League spokesman, Talaat Hamed, said in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   Hamed said the league's secretary general, Esmat Abdel-Meguid,
was in contact with Annan. ``Abdel-Meguid wants the Iraqi file
completely closed,'' Hamed said.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, interviewed Sunday by CNN, said Saddam Hussein always
tried to characterize the standoff over sanctions as an issue
between him and the United States, while the conflict was instead
with the Security Council, which demands a real accounting for
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't cook the books,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that in talks last week, which he broke off on Tuesday
after repeated Iraqi refusals to discuss outstanding issues, Iraq
had been rattled by the recent finding of traces of VX nerve gas in
shell fragments after years of denying that it had ever filled
warheads with the chemical weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the degree of protection that Tariq Aziz was running on
the biological program was a miracle to behold,'' Butler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
