<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5186 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BOMBINGS-550(2     08-09 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BOMBINGS-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL INQUIRY BEGINS AS KENYA DEATH TOLL NEARS 200 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Israel)  (See also: AFRICA-VICTIMS, AFRICA-EMBASSY, AFRICA-U.S.,
AFRICA-TERROR, AFRICA-EVACUATE, AFRICA-TANZANIA) 
(mk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ American intelligence officers and
law-enforcement personnel from around the world streamed into
Nairobi Sunday to search for clues in the terrorist bombing that
killed at least 190 people and wounded nearly 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   A mother and son were found alive Sunday in a bank building
damaged in the blast, and rescuers were continuing an excruciating
search for survivors, using pickaxes, shovels, crowbars,
sledgehammers and their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Here and in Washington, a global investigation into the nearly
simultaneous attacks on the U.S. Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania
began to take shape. Some evidence may come from videocameras
mounted on the roofs of both embassies, although officials in Kenya
and Tanzania said they were not sure whether the cameras had
recorded the explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said their investigation was likely to reach across
Africa and the Arabian peninsula to Afghanistan, looking into
terrorist networks with bases in at least four countries and into a
need for stepped-up security at vulnerable American diplomatic
posts around the world. In Washington Sunday, senior Clinton
administration officials said they would ask for more money to
improve security at American embassies worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said they feared that forensic evidence from
the bombing might have been destroyed in the frantic search for the
wounded and dead in the wreckage left by the powerful explosion.
Only Sunday did American investigators begin to secure the site of
the blast and begin a painstaking search for evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are conflicting priorities,'' a senior American official
here said. ``One is removing survivors and removing remains.
Another is gaining evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli rescuers found a mother and a son unharmed Sunday on the
20th floor of the Cooperative Bank of Kenya building adjacent to
the embassy. Lt. Col. Oren Loefler, a spokesman for the Israeli
rescue team, told Reuters that the boy, who he said was about 12,
had been in the apartment at the time of the explosion, and that
his mother had entered afterward to find him. They waited there for
two days, too frightened to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers said that Sunday afternoon, at least one woman,
named Rose, was still alive in the wreckage of the Ufundi House, a
seven-story office building next door to the embassy. The rescuers
strained to hear her as they clambered over a 40-foot-high pile of
debris containing dozens of bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is alive,'' said an Israeli officer, Alon Seren. ``She is
stuck in a difficult place, and it is very dangerous for us to
rescue her.''
</P>
<P>
   But as darkness fell, the voice of Rose fell still, and rescuers
were not sure if she was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The rescuers were bringing out the dead, one every 20 minutes.
``We have pulled out bodies with our bare hands,'' said Meital
Hallawi, another member of the Israeli team. ``We are just like
robots,'' she said. ``We can't have any feelings if we want to
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Olumola, 38, a cashier at Ufundi House who had left the
building to run a quick errand when the bomb went off on Friday
morning, helped Kenyan Red Cross workers identify the bodies.
``They have just found a friend of mine,'' she said. ``There are 28
more people in there, they say. I knew some of them. I passed them
by at work.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The chance of a terrorist assault on the Nairobi embassy was
rated as slim by officials at the State Department and the CIA,
according to Paul Peterson, the embassy's regional security
officer. Security risks at American embassies are ranked as low,
medium, high and critical by those analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said that ``Nairobi was low'' _ so low that the
embassy, one of the largest American diplomatic outposts in Africa,
shelters diplomats from the U.S. mission in neighboring Sudan,
where the CIA had warned of a possible attack in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five FBI agents, 11 officers from the CIA's
Counterterrorist Center and scores of military intelligence
officers and State Department security experts arrived in Nairobi
Sunday. Among those arriving to reconstitute the embassy was a
State Department officer, Charles Slater, who had just flown in
from London and said his wife had been maimed in the explosion at
the American Embassy in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   At the embassy here, not a single room was untouched by the
blast. A slightly tattered American flag hung limply from the roof
Sunday, surrounded by twisted metal, a ruined satellite dish and a
disabled security camera.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion, which destroyed ``the brain center of the
embassy,'' in the words of Peterson, came from a vehicle that
breached a thin layer of security at the rear of the building.
Embassy officials said the vehicle had apparently been driven past
a manually operated barrier staffed by an employee of the
Cooperative Bank of Kenya to the edge of a ramp leading to the
embassy's underground garage.
</P>
<P>
   There, a few feet from the first-story windows of the embassy,
the vehicle exploded with a force that hurled a maelstrom of flying
glass and debris over a 10-block radius in downtown Nairobi,
damaged buildings 500 feet away and shattered thousands of lives.
As of Sunday evening, 190 people were known dead _155 people who
were outside the embassy and 35 who were inside.
</P>
<P>
   Among the embassy's staff, 12 Americans were confirmed dead
Sunday night. ``There will be 12 coffins going back tomorrow,''
said Chris Scharf, an embassy spokesman. Twenty-four Kenyan
employees were dead, and uncounted dozens were missing, American
officials said. The death toll represented roughly one of every
five Americans in the building at the time of the explosion, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy held a private memorial service Sunday for employees
who were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Prudence Bushnell, who had been giving a speech at
the Cooperative Bank building down the street from the embassy at
the moment of the explosion and was slightly wounded, toured the
ruins of the mission Sunday, walking stiffly, with a slight limp, a
split lip and an expression of mourning.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She emerged, looking devastated, briefly stopping to touch a
rosebud on a memorial bouquet standing by the embassy's entrance
before she drove away. Around her, grim-faced security personnel
and edgy Marines sent from Saudi Arabia stood guard.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to use the ruined embassy, its staff and the new arrivals
from the FBI, the CIA, the State Department and the Pentagon have
decamped to the headquarters of the U.S. Agency for International
Development, where the investigation is being headed by Joseph
Melrose, the ambassador-designate to Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The information being analyzed by the investigators Sunday
included a witness' report, not yet independently confirmed, that
three men described as Arabs were seen stealthily videotaping the
embassy building on Monday, an American official said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI forensic technicians, State Department security experts,
Navy Seabees and Fairfax County, Va., firefighters detailed to the
State Department's Office of Foreign Disaster Assistance began
combing the embassy building Sunday, looking both for signs of life
and clues to the crime. Among the firefighters' ranks were veterans
of the team that rushed to Oklahoma City after an Army veteran blew
up the federal building there _ a case successfully closed with a
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials said Sunday that the investigation of
this bombing could take months or years. And they voiced fears that
amid the rubble and chaos, clues from the crime had been lost in
the search for the wounded, the missing and the dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
