<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5188 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-STRIKE10-CO     08-09 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-STRIKE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth settlement may mean future changes for workers
 &HT;    (EDS: May be used as a sidebar to any BellAtlantic strike story.
Moving on (f) financial and (a) general news wires.)
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The 11th-hour settlement that averted a strike against
BellSouth offers raises and increased pensions, but includes an
effort to reshape the way the union and the phone company do
business with each other.
</P>
<P>
   In the tentative, three-year pact that covers 48,000 of
BellSouth's 86,188 employees, the Communications Workers of America
won a 12.39 percent wage increase and a potential bonus of 2.5
percent in the deal's last two years. The company also said it
would soften its practice of forcing employees to work overtime,
agreeing to rely first on volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   But for the union's graying membership, retirement benefits were
also key, and BellSouth agreed to a substantial boost in pension
payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``These have been the tough issues all along, and they stayed
tough until the end,'' said Noah Savant, assistant to the vice
president for the CWA district that covers the nine-state BellSouth
turf. ``I think both sides worked extremely hard to get an
agreement, but of course a deadline always puts pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Intriguingly, the deal calls for formation of a ``joint
operations board'' that would include union and company officials
from six BellSouth units.
</P>
<P>
   The board could examine bonuses for employees, rules for union
jobs and training that would let workers shift to better positions.
The idea is to give workers better job opportunities and the
company more flexibility. For example, the board might recommend
that job descriptions for a truck driver or technician be revised
if the work could be done more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth Vice President Dick Sibbernsen said company success
depends on ``employees being willing to work in new ways and CWA
being willing to partner with the company.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of arrangement may be critical in the next few years
for BellSouth, which began life in the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T with a
virtual monopoly on local telephone service through most of the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the $21 billion-a-year company faces competition in
wireless, international operations, data services and local phone
service to businesses, as well as residential service in some
places.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, BellSouth is champing at the bit to get approval for
entering the competitive market in long distance telephone service,
and BellSouth agreed the CWA can represent workers in its long
distance unit.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications analyst Jeff Kagan said the new board may
help BellSouth minimize what he says is the disadvantage of having
a union. ``The phone companies of the future will look nothing like
phone companies of the past and the unions are set up to operate in
the phone companies of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But Larry Michel, economist at the Economics Policy Institute,
said union wages are not the only factor in rising prices. A union
can be an advantage to a company that needs a stable and skilled
work force, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the contract to take effect, the deal must still be ratified
by union members The deal calls for members to get a $500 ``signing
bonus'' for ratification.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's agreement contrasts with the strike called by the
CWA against Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's workers were ready for a walkout, too, and despite
the optimism of both sides, it went down to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   But by 11:30 p.m., the 40-person BellSouth team led by Tom Posey
and the 30-person CWA squad headed by Vice President Jimmy Smith
had put the finishing touches on a deal.
</P>
<P>
   As the word was passed to CWA Local 3204, which accounts for
4,000 BellSouth workers, local president M.M. Smith said he was
relieved. ``You are not ever really anxious to do a strike. It's
just something you might need to do to achieve what you need to
achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
