<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5190 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATE-SALE-COX     08-09 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-SALE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shop 'til the state drops $19.2 million in sales taxes
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) general news and (f) financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Angie Francalancia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida lawmakers have such a deal for
you: Buy clothing, shoes and similar items costing $50 or less and
save at least 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The state-sponsored sale _ actually, it's a week without sales
tax _ begins at 12:01 a.m. SaturdayAug. 15 and ends midnight Aug.
21. As always in sales, some restrictions apply _ and it's a
one-shot deal.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, all essential clothing and shoes are tax-free for the
week. The state's list of essentials includes aprons, adult
diapers, baseball caps and choir robes.
</P>
<P>
   Items excluded from the tax-free list include backpacks,
scarves, athletic cleats and neckties.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature came up with the tax-free week as a way to
return money to taxpayers in a year that finds the state flush with
cash from an $11 billion settlement with tobacco companies and a
healthy economy.
</P>
<P>
   It was set during the back-to-school shopping season and limited
to items costing $50 or less to ensure that ``Joe Lunchbucket''
benefits, outgoing House Speaker Dan Webster, R-Orlando, has said.
Notably missing from the tax-free list, however, are back-to-school
items such as barrettes and classroom supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Republican-led legislature, known for supporting
big business, will remind voters of the tax-free week come election
time.
</P>
<P>
   State finance officials estimate the state will lose $19.2
million in sales tax during the week _ meaning people across
Florida will save that amount by not paying the 6 percent tax on
each item they buy for $50 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a $50 blouse, keep the $3 in sales tax. Shoppers can buy an
unlimited number of eligible items at $50 and below without paying
tax. But items costing more than $50 will be taxed on the whole
amount. For example, a shopper buying a $75 pair of pants will pay
the full $4.50 in sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   No splitting pairs
</P>
<P>
   Also, a store cannot split items typically sold together _ like
a pair of shoes or a suit _ to sell each piece at or below the $50
mark. Store coupons that reduce the price to $50 or below can be
used to get items tax-free _ rebates and manufacturer coupons
cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers can take advantage of the tax break in other ways. For
example, any items put on layaway before tax-free week and taken
home during the week will not be charged the tax. Or a shopper
could start a layaway on merchandise during tax-free week and the
stores will not ring up the sales tax, even though the items will
be picked up after the week is over.
</P>
<P>
   The $19.2 million the state expects shoppers to save is a
minuscule fraction of the $12 billion in annual sales-tax revenue.
Some local jurisdictions with sales taxes, such as Okeechobee
County, which adds 1 percent, and the St. Lucie County School
District, which collects a half-cent on the dollar, will forfeit
that money as well. Statewide, local governments will lose $2.7
million of the $19.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be pretty hard to quantify what our portion is. I
don't think it's going to impact us negatively,'' St. Lucie School
District Finance Director Mike Averyt cq said. ``It's only one week
out of 52.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida retailers are hoping it will be a big week, with
shoppers flocking to the stores the way they did in New York when
that state tried a sales-tax exemption on clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you run a sale, you hope to make a buck,'' said Dave
Roberts, governmental affairs vice president for the Florida Retail
Federation. ``We don't know how it's going to be here. We think it
will be a good week of sales. Will that benefit us with all the
administrative costs? We hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paul McConnaughay, owner of Johnson's Men's Shop in Lake
Worth, said, ``I don't think it will mean much for us. I'll
probably have to explain it to each one of the customers.''
</P>
<P>
   New York merchants were similarly skeptical when legislators
tried the state's first tax-free week in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting pummeled by the competition from the border
states _ New Jersey, Connecticut and Massachusetts _ that have no
state sales tax on clothing,'' said Ted Potrikus, vice president of
the Retail Council of New York.
</P>
<P>
   New York retailers fell in love with tax-free week, which raised
their sales threefold in some cases, Potrikus said. Statewide,
sales grew to $421 million last year from $238 million in January
1996. Shoppers saved nearly $32 million, according to a New York
Department of Tax and Finance study.
</P>
<P>
   Two big differences
</P>
<P>
   But there are two big differences. Florida's neighboring states
don't have the tax exemptions that New York's neighbors do. And New
York set the limit at $500 for tax-free items, drawing huge crowds
to shop for bigger buys.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-school sales already will draw crowds into the stores,
but industry analysts said they don't know how many more people
will wait to begin shopping on Saturday. Palm Beach County's public
schools open Aug. 19, and Martin and St. Lucie county public
schools resume Aug.18 _ all in the middle of tax-free week.
</P>
<P>
   National chains, including Target, JCPenney and Kids R Us, have
been advertising back-to-school sales for two weeks (cq based on
Aug. 9 run date.).
</P>
<P>
   ``We did move an ad we had running the previous week, and we
also have special signs made up that say this is a tax-free item,''
said Scott Lerner, senior store manager at JCPenney in the Palm
Beach Mall. ``But our advertising officially kicked off July 26.''
</P>
<P>
   While a nationwide analysis shows that August is the
third-biggest sales month behind November and December, holiday
peaks have been flattening in recent years. Shoppers are likely to
have begun buying school clothes during the summer months,
according to the study by the International Council of Shopping
Centers.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Revenue has had meetings throughout the
summer to give retailers information about what is and isn't on the
tax-exempt list, but attendance has been skimpy, said John Merchant
of the department's Palm Beach County office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent out a list of tips outlining the tax-exempt items to
everyone with a taxpayer identification number,'' he said. ``We've
offered to do training for some of the big chains, like Wal-Mart,
but their officials said they thought the list was pretty
self-explanatory.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Department of Revenue officials have set up toll-free
lines to answer questions from shoppers and merchants: (800)
850-7847 and (800) 367-8331 for hearing-impaired from 8 a.m. to 9
p.m. Monday-Friday, 9 a.m.-9 p.m. Saturday and noon-6 p.m. Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   National retailers that have been through the New York
experience aren't worried about preparing for Florida's tax-free
week. Some, like Macy's, will give sales clerks additional
training. Others will put the burden on their computer programmers
so cash registers simply will ring up items without the tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``You work so hard to train your people on a daily basis as to
how you run your programs,'' said Ed Goldberg, government and
consumer affairs vice president at Macy's. ``There's a major
training issue for people to be taught for a one-week period. I
really wish it was as simple as pressing a button.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the cost to do the training . . . is far worth it,'' said
Goldberg, adding that Macy's New York stores had a 300 percent
increase in sales the first time New York exempted clothing from
sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's and other stores have adjusted their advertising
schedules to promote sales next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we learned is to make sure the consumer understands that
tax-free is going to take place,'' he said. ``We're going to beef
up that promotional calendar.''
</P>
<P>
