</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-RUNOFF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Runoff election a likely snooze for Georgia voters
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the summer sizzles, voter enthusiasm fizzles. And
the scarcity of big-name races doesn't help as candidates try to
lure the faithful back for one more round of balloting in Tuesday's
runoffs.
</P>
<P>
   With the governor's matchup decided but for the formality of
Tuesday's election, and only a handful of other races left hanging,
the apathy that marked last month's primary elections is expected
to return with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   The rough-and-tumble campaigns waged by most statewide
candidates who resorted to negative ads and personal attacks also
may have turned off many potential voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Secretary of State's office isn't making a specific
prediction, but officials there suggest that turnout is likely to
dip into the ``mid-teens,'' down from the nearly 25 percent of
Georgia's 4.1 million registered voters who cast ballots three
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   If history is any guide, they're probably right. Generally,
about half the voters who participate in the primary return to the
polls to help settle runoffs. Two years ago, the 33 percent primary
turnout dwindled to roughly 17 percent. And in 1994 _ the last time
Georgia's governor and lieutenant governor seats were up for grabs
_ the 25 percent primary turnout plummeted to 11 percent in the
runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Those who do show up this year will decide who represents both
the Democrats and the Republicans in the fall lieutenant governor's
race, the Republican contest for attorney general and the
Democratic race for state labor commissioner. Scores of local races
also are on the ballot throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat's nomination for governor will appear as a
contested runoff on the ballot, but that's only on paper. Lewis
Massey, the second-place finisher who forced the runoff, suspended
his campaign and tossed his support to frontrunner Roy Barnes,
making Barnes the de facto nominee. Guy Millner's position as the
Republican gubernatorial nominee was affirmed in a recount last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Heated local contests may be the best hope for spiking turnout
upwards in some areas. A spirited contest between homeowners
advocate Sam Olens and incumbent county commissioner Gordon Wysong,
author of Cobb's anti-gay rights resolution, may energize voters.
Similarly, the runoff between Gordon Joyner and Horacina Tate for
Ralph David Abernathy III's Senate seat may lure Fulton voters back
to the polls. In Cherokee County, runoffs for two county commission
seats forced by slow-growth forces also are hot tickets.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall dearth of voters may be good news for candidates
like Democrat Mary Margaret Oliver and Republican Clint Day, both
of whom can count on a well-defined and motivated voting base to
return to the polls as they vie for their respective party's
nomination for lieutenant governor. For Oliver, it's women and
voters in Atlanta's liberal communities. For Day, it's Christian
conservatives
</P>
<P>
   In what have become two of the most acrimonious contests this
election season, Day faces Fulton County Commission Chairman Mitch
Skandalakis for the GOP nomination and Oliver is pitted against
Albany lawmaker Mark Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. David Ralston of Blue Ridge, Ga. faces former
lawmaker Kip Klein for the Republican nomination for attorney
general. And Michael Thurmond, the architect of the state's welfare
reform plan, is up against state Sen. Steve Henson of DeKalb County
for the Democratic nomination for labor commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
