<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5198 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-U.S.-500&AMP;ADD-N     08-09 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-U.S.-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDING SOUGHT TO BOLSTER SECURITY AT U.S. EMBASSIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-VICTIMS, AFRICA-EMBASSY,
AFRICA-TERROR,AFRICA-EVACUATE, AFRICA-TANZANIA) 
(js) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senior Clinton administration officials, vowing
again to track down the terrorists who bombed two U.S. embassies in
East Africa last week, called on Sunday for an expanded budget to
fortify American diplomatic installations abroad against a growing
threat from terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the attacks on the
embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, in which
12 Americans were killed, pointed up larger security problems many
of the 280 American embassies and other diplomatic installations
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried, in a systematic way, to upgrade the embassies
around the world by making sure that the perimeters are secure,
that they have barricades, barbed wire, a variety of things to try
to secure the buildings,'' she said on the NBC News program ``Meet
the Press.'' ``But it is a very hard job and we do not have the
resources for it.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``We are going to be talking about how to increase
the resources.'' Albright cited no dollar figures, but other
administration officials have said that billions of dollars would
be needed if the government hoped for a significant improvement in
security standards at most embassies.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Albright repeated President Clinton's pledge that the United
States would track down those responsible for the bombings, no
matter how long it might take.
</P>
<P>
   ``The memory of the United States is very long, and our reach is
very far,'' Ms. Albright added.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's call for more money to improve embassy
security came as a former deputy director of the CIA, who led a
State Department panel that studied the issue, said the bombings in
East Africa showed that the department had failed to meet security
standards it had supposedly adopted in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't learn lessons very well,'' said Bobby Ray Inman, a
retired admiral who led the experts panel for the State Department
during the Reagan administration. ``We need to do everything we can
to provide protection for those who are representing us abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the State Department has been given less than
one-third of the money that would have been required to modify or
build embassies meeting the standard set in 1985. Between 1986 and
1990, the State Department required $2.7 billion to upgrade its
embassies, but Congress appropriated a total of about $880 million.
</P>
<P>
   While the State Department insists that it is eager to make
security improvements, many department officials were relieved that
the money was not approved in full, believing that compliance with
the Inman standards would have turned some diplomatic compounds
into nearly inaccessible fortresses.
</P>
<P>
   The embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam had not been modified
to comply fully with the security standards called for by Inman's
1985 report, which was requested after a terrorist attack the
previous year against the American Embassy in Beirut, Lebanon, in
which 16 people died.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Inman said he was ``a little cynical after too many years of
watching a process where there's greater eagerness to solve a
problem when you have been attacked'' but little enthusiasm later,
``after time goes on and the attacks haven't been repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview from his home in Austin, Texas, Inman said the
attacks in East Africa were predictable, given that security
standards at some large embassies in the Middle East and elsewhere
in the world had been improved dramatically to meet the so-called
Inman standards, leaving embassies like those in Kenya and Tanzania
as ``softer targets.''
</P>
<P>
   His panel, he said, forecast the problem. ``We recognized that
as some buildings became more secure, terrorists who were looking
to carry out attacks would start looking elsewhere _ they would
start looking for softer ones,'' he said. ``I believe that's what
happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen said Sunday that he believed
Congress would move to increase spending on embassy security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that they would evaluate the needs of the State
Department,'' he said on ABC's ``This Week.'' ``It's correct that
not all of the money that has been requested by the president for
increased securities has been funded.''
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, said on the
CBS News program ``Face the Nation'' that it was impossible to
guard against all terrorist attacks ``unless you build fortresses,
but obviously in the wake of an incident such as this, additional
efforts will be made.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
