<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5206 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS10-COX     08-09 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Linebacker position cuts may mean special teams additions for
Falcons hopefuls
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When it comes time to start shaping the Atlanta
Falcons' final roster, the toughest cuts may come at linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   There are nine players in training camp at that position, and
the Falcons will keep six to eight. The hard part is several
players who might not play well enough to make the team on
linebacking skills alone happen to be good special teams players.
That's important.
</P>
<P>
   ''Probably, the linebacker position is as competitive as any on
the team this year,'' said assistant head coach/defensive
coordinator Rich Brooks. ''And with special teams in the mix, it's
going to be complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   The three men who finished last season as starters -- middle man
Jessie Tuggle (5-foot-11, 230 pounds), weak 'backer Cornelius
Bennett (6-2, 240), and strongside 'backer Henri Crockett (6-2,
251) are holding ground so far.
</P>
<P>
   Crockett isn't going anywhere. He's a middle linebacker at heart
and by trade. Injuries necessitated his move to the middle in
Friday's 31-16 preseason loss to Tennessee, and despite practicing
there just one day, he performed above expectations in three
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   When Tuggle's contract ends after the 1999 season, Crockett will
quite likely be the man in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle, 33, and Bennett, 32, both had good seasons last year.
Due to their ages, coaches must keep an eye on their legs. Also,
both men will count $3.45 million against the salary cap _ the two
highest totals on the team, and a combined 13 percent of the team's
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be difficult, and perhaps imprudent, to trade or
waive either one. Even if they were cut, Bennett would count $1.25
million against this year's cap, Tuggle $933,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the issue of who would play in their spots. In
Tuggle's case, it might well be Crockett, although backup middle
men Eddie Sutter (6-2, 239) and Ruffin Hamilton (6-1, 238) were
doing some good things before suffering hamstring injuries last
week. Neither played against the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   In Bennett's case, the backups are third-year man Craig Sauer
(6-1, 240), who has 21 career tackles, and rookie first-round draft
choice Keith Brooking (6-2, 244) The thought of either starting at
the beginning of the season, when it is hugely important the
Falcons start well to avoid another season where fans refuse to buy
tickets, is daunting.
</P>
<P>
   Sauer also has taken some snaps in the middle. Brooking
eventually will get a look on the strongside.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Crockett on the strongside is 12th year man David Brandon
(6-4, 238), who was the starter before breaking his leg in the
fourth game last season. Brandon, too, is 33.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Crockett and Brandon is third-year man Ben Talley, (6-3,
248) a Griffin native who was a fourth-round pick of the Giants in
1995. Under coach Dan Reeves, and current Falcon linebacker Don
Blackmon, Talley was going to compete for a starting job when he
shredded his knee on the first day of training camp in '96. He
missed that entire season, and was cut by the Giants last summer,
playing no football in '97.
</P>
<P>
   Rosters must be reduced from 80 to 60 after the third preseason
game, and down to 53 after the final preseason game. If cuts were
made today, Talley and Hamilton probably would be first to go.
</P>
<P>
   Talley is not as fast as some, and Hamilton, who is a tad
undersized, hasn't played much as a pro, including five games for
the Packers in '94, none in '95, when the Packers waived him, and
none in '96, when the Falcons reached an injury settlement with him
upon waiving him. He had just two tackles and six special teams
tackles last year, playing outside.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon, who along with Talley, Tuggle and Bennett is considered
a one-position linebacker, could be next on this list.
</P>
<P>
   But there's time for impressions to change, and injuries could
have some say in all this, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm satisfied with everybody's progress right now,'' Blackmon
said. ''With the live action (of preseason games), they'll start to
separate.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
