<HEADER>
A5211 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APVTOUR-COX     08-09 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APVTOUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good memories for Kiraly
 &HT;    By Jon Gallo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Karch Kiraly said he needs to come to Alanta more
often. Every time the San Clemente, Calif., resident has dropped in
for a visit here, he's left with a lot more money in his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at the Miller Lite Beach Challenge at MetLife Park in
Atlanta was no different for Kiraly and partner Adam Johnson. After
an undefeated run, the top-seeded team will return to California
sharing $10,416 after beating Brent Frohoff and Rob Heidger 15-12
in the final of the Association of Volleyball Professionals event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still haven't figured out what's special about this city,''
said Kiraly, who has never lost in the five tournaments he's played
here, including the 1996 Olympics. ``But every time I come here,
good things always seem to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the final, Kiraly's winning streak was in
jeopardy, as Heidger's back-to-back blocks against Johnson gave his
team a 9-5 lead. But Johnson and Kiraly went on a 4-0 run and tied
the score when Kiraly's spike over Heidger found the back line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get down, we never panic, and that's really
important,'' Kiraly said. ``We just kept our composure and played
like we were capable of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   After regaining the lead 12-9, Frohoff and Heidger then fell
apart for good. Johnson and Kiraly ran off six straight points to
capture the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we just needed to start making plays,'' said Johnson,
who had three of the team's final five kills, including the
game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   The loss ended an upset-filled tournament run for Frohoff and
Heidger. To get to Sunday's final, the duo knocked off the
third-seeded team of Brian Lewis and David Swatik (15-4),
fourth-seeded Franco Neto and Roberto Lopez (15-9), sixth-seeded
Bill Bouilianne and Ian Clark (15-4) and 10th-seeded Aaron Boss and
Albert Hannemann (15-9).
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the best I've played in a long time,'' said Frohoff,
who missed all of last season because of a knee injury. ``But it's
disheartening because we had two leads against the best team in the
world and blew them both.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's win makes it 4-for-4 for Kiraly in tour stops here:
with Kent Steffes in 1994, in 1995 with Scott Ayakatubby (while
Steffes was out with a shoulder injury), and back with a healthy
Steffes in 1996. There was no AVP stop here last year.
</P>
<P>
   But even the $40,000 in prize money Kiraly and his partner have
taken home from those four wins in Atlanta pales in comparison to
what Kiraly and Steffes did the last time they stopped here. At
Atlanta Beach in Jonesboro, Kiraly and Steffes won the first
Olympic beach volleyball competition in 1996, when they beat Mike
Dodd and Mike Whitmarsh for the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the best moments in my career,'' said Kiraly,
who also won gold in the indoor team volleyball event at the 1984
and 1988 Olympics, in addition to having won 134 AVP events in his
13 years on the tour. ``All I know is that I'm definitely going to
come back here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
