</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-TANZANIA-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMERA MAY PROVIDE CLUES IN TANZANIA BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-VICTIMS, AFRICA-EMBASSY,
AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-EVACUATE) 
(mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania _ A video camera on the roof of the
American Embassy here that points at the entrance gate where a
terrorist bomb went off at 10:39 a.m. Friday may offer clues for
investigators who started piecing together evidence Sunday about
what happened.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that they did not know yet whether the
camera was rolling during the attack, but that the camera seemed to
be one of the few pieces of equipment that remained intact on the
largely devastated three-story building.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion, which left nine dead and more than 70 injured,
appears to have been caused by a bomb attached to a car or truck,
an American official said Sunday. Much of the attention is focused
on a water truck that was at the entrance awaiting clearance to
make a regular delivery when the bomb went off.
</P>
<P>
   An American official said that ``a possible scenario'' _ and so
far, the most likely explanation _ was that a bomb was attached to
the water truck. The blue tanker lay crumpled upside down in the
rubble in the compound Sunday, its undercarriage slammed askew
against the embassy wall and the cabin where a driver and his
assistant sat reduced to a few spokes of black metal.
</P>
<P>
   But there were many questions about how a water truck that
belonged to the embassy's motor pool could have been fitted with a
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the water truck, his assistant and five Tanzanian
security guards at the gate were all killed. The impact was so
severe that it damaged buildings more than a mile away. So far no
witnesses have come forward, the American official said.
</P>
<P>
   Tanzania has been considered a quiet diplomatic post. But while
American officials here puzzled about the physical details of the
bombing, there was less puzzlement about how the nation, with its
large Muslim population, might possibly have been chosen as a site
for an Islamic fundamentalist attack.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the nations in East Africa, Tanzania has the highest
percentage of Muslims. Along the coast, about 60 percent of the
population is estimated to be Muslim; most of the rest are
Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Washington officials have said that they have no clues yet about
who the bombers might be. But one name that officials mention
frequently is that of Osama bin Laden, a wealthy sponsor of
fundamentalist Islamic activities around the world. Bin Laden, who
lives in Afghanistan, is sometimes given protection by the Sudan,
to the north of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   More militant strains of Islam have come to Tanzania in the last
few years, and in February police clashed with protesters, killing
two, outside a mosque in the Mwembe Chai section of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such coincidences, however, there are no real known
clues, and no prominent group has claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects of unearthing vital evidence _ whether from traces
of the explosives or from the video camera _ seems better here than
in Nairobi, where the lengthy and complex work to rescue victims
may have damaged investigative leads.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A longtime personnel assistant in the embassy, Evita Kwimbela,
said the driver of the water truck had been employed by the embassy
for nine years and was ``very calm, very cool.'' Mrs. Kwimbela, who
is recovering from a head wound in the hospital, said she knew the
driver by his last name, Ndange, and said he was in his early 40s.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of about 10 embassy drivers, she said, and had been
assigned on Friday to pick up water from a well owned by the
embassy about four miles from the compound and bring it back. Mrs.
Kwimbela said that because of Dar es Salaam's chronic water
shortage, the tanker went to the well daily and was parked inside
the embassy grounds when it was not in use.
</P>
<P>
   The American official who said the water tanker was considered a
possible vehicle for the bomb also said the bomb might have been
attached to a car. Several charred car skeletons lay almost
directly outside the embassy gates; in all, 22 cars that were near
the building were wrecked.
</P>
<P>
   There was widespread sentiment Sunday that because of its lax
borders, open Indian Ocean sea front and widespread poverty,
Tanzania is a natural place for organizers either to send or to
recruit helpers for a bomb attack. It would not be difficult for a
well-organized effort to penetrate society with bribes and
promises, several Tanzanians said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the people don't have money and need money,'' Mrs.
Kwimbela said.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy in Tanzania was considered a low-risk, low-profile
post, a place where American diplomats administered aid programs
and tried to spread ideas about American democracy. Unlike some
other African countries, Tanzania receives little military
assistance, and few Americans visit, aside from a steady stream of
safari tourists.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no ambassador since January, and the embassy and
its staff of 40 have been managed by the charge d'affaires, John
Lange. The new ambassador, Charles Stith, a political appointee
chosen by the Clinton administration, is to arrive next month.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, American officials said, the embassy security
system worked as it was supposed to because the bomb went off
outside the embassy compound rather than inside. But the building
itself is very close to the narrow street and lacks the setback
required for newly built American embassies.
</P>
<P>
   No American was killed here; one temporary American employee was
evacuated to London on Friday for medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   There was some conjecture Sunday that the Tanzanian guards at
the gate suspected there was something awry with the water truck
and were inspecting it more carefully when the bomb went off.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Marine guards, who are posted at all American
embassies, operate from inside the front door of the building. They
do not typically inspect individual visitors or cars, officials
here said.
</P>
<P>
   A protective green tarpaulin now covers the crater, which is
seven feet wide. Traces of the explosive will presumably be found
in the crater. The embassy compound, flanked by flowering oleander
and frangipani trees, is neatly cordoned off and guarded by more
Marines who flew in Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The building, built of reinforced concrete by the Israeli
government for use as its embassy in the late 1970s, is probably
beyond repair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
