<HEADLINE>
TALKS CONTINUE BETWEEN BELL ATLANTIC, UNION TO END STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: New England, Mid-Atlantic states.)  (nk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bell Atlantic and union officials negotiated through
the day Sunday to end a strike by 73,000 telephone workers that
began shortly after midnight. The immediate impact of the strike
was to inconvenience customers from Maine to Virginia trying to
reach directory assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Company and union officials said they expected the disruption to
be greater Monday, when most Bell Atlantic workers would have
normally reported to work, and scheduled repairs and installations
of phone lines would face inevitable delays.
</P>
<P>
   Talks were taking place in New York and Washington, and
officials from Bell Atlantic and the Communications Workers of
America said they wanted to reach a quick settlement and avoid
all-out-warfare like the 17-week strike by Nynex workers in 1989.
Nynex merged with Bell Atlantic last year, forming the nation's
largest regional phone company.
</P>
<P>
   The communications workers went on strike as soon as the two
sides failed to reach a settlement at 12:01 a.m. when their
three-year contract expired. But 13,500 Bell Atlantic workers in
New England who belong to the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers decided not to go on strike in the hope that a
settlement could be reached in several days.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that the strike could end soon, officials with the
electrical workers said that in separate talks in Boston, the union
and Bell Atlantic had agreed on contract language that would set
stronger limits on the company's use of nonunion workers to do work
traditionally done by unionized phone technicians.
</P>
<P>
   That had become a major issue for both unions, and the
communication workers had demanded limits on Bell Atlantic's
practice of farming out work to the company's new nonunion
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing a concern expressed by workers at many other companies,
union members fear Bell Atlantic's increased use of nonunion
workers will endanger their job security and reduce the union's
bargaining clout.
</P>
<P>
   Communications workers officials said they were studying the
language the company had worked out with the electrical workers and
might want more comprehensive restrictions on the company's moving
work to nonunion employees.
</P>
<P>
   In dozens of cities along the Eastern Seaboard, repairmen,
operators and customer service representatives picketed Sunday in
front of Bell Atlantic buildings, often shouting, ``No Contract. No
Work.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, callers who sought directory assistance were
greeted by an electronic voice, saying, ``We're sorry due to the
work stoppage. We're not able to provide an operator at this time.
Please place your call later. We are sorry about the
inconvenience.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporations in New York said they would not be hurt by a short
strike because it would not make much of a difference if they had
to wait a few extra days to have new lines installed. But a long
strike might be a different story, a Merrill Lynch spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, based in New York City, provides telephone
service, wireless communications, cable and digital TV, and
Internet and data services to close to 27 million customers in 13
states and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials said that to prevent major delays in repairs
and installing phones lines, thousands of managers would pick up
the slack by working 12 hours a day, six days a week.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the day, key officials with the union and company
engaged in informal talks, but occasionally the two sides held
formal sessions with their complete negotiating teams.
</P>
<P>
   Morton Bahr, president of the communications workers' union,
said, ``Our major unresolved issues at Bell Atlantic include
keeping good permanent jobs from being outsourced and converted
into temporary jobs at low pay and minimal benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Kraus, a Bell Atlantic spokeswoman, said the company had
addressed that issue in its proposal. ``All of the union's concerns
are addressed, including outsourcing, overtime and vacations,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from both sides said they were eager to avoid a replay
of the 1989 strike, an especially bitter showdown. During that
strike, workers sabotaged Nynex equipment, customers grew angry
about service delays, the company lost business and a striker was
killed trying to prevent a car from crossing the picket line.
</P>
<P>
   A long strike could hurt Bell Atlantic by encouraging frustrated
customers to turn to its competitors for services like high-speed
Internet connections.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Millions of customers in nine states in the Southeast were
spared disruptions Sunday because the CWA announced shortly before
midnight Saturday that 48,000 workers at Bell South would not go on
strike because the two sides had reached a tentative agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Bell South agreed to increase wages by 12.4 percent over the
three-year contract and to hire additional workers in an effort to
reduce the large amounts of forced overtime that workers had
complained bitterly about.
</P>
<P>
   The strike had far less effect in New England than in New York
and Bell Atlantic states to the south because the electrical
workers, who represent most Bell Atlantic workers in New England,
had not walked out. Most of Connecticut is not affected by the
strike because the phone company that serves most of the state,
Southern New England Telecommunications, reached a contract
agreement on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kraus of Bell Atlantic said outsourcing _ the transfer of
work to nonunion companies _ was only a small percent of Bell
Atlantic's work, asserting that it is used for functions like food
service, cleaning and getting computers prepared for the Year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have the flexibility just like every other business
in America to run our business cost-effectively and to continue to
do this in the future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say their concern is not that Bell Atlantic is
farming out food service and cleaning work to nonunion workers, but
that it is outsourcing work like handling business accounts and
installing high-speed Internet lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether the core telephone work which has
always been unionized will remain unionized,'' said Bob Master, a
spokesman for the communications workers. ``That's the fundamental
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Other issues under negotiation include wages, forced overtime,
increasing pensions for current retirees and the company's failure
to offer early retirement inducements to everyone it said it would
under the 1995 contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
