<SLUG> BC-WYOMING-MISSING-WOMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUES REMAIN ELUSIVE ON WOMAN WHO DISAPPEARED IN 1997
</HEADLINE>
   (ll) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDER, Wyo. _ Time has been standing still for the friends and
family of Amy Wroe Bechtel for more than a year now, since the
endurance runner vanished from this quiet mountain town.
</P>
<P>
   No solid clues have emerged since July 24, 1997, when the
unlocked car belonging to Mrs. Bechtel, a 24-year-old personal
trainer, distance runner and amateur photographer, was found
several miles from town along a road in the Shoshone National
Forest. It is believed that she went there to map a trail for a
race she was organizing. Her keys and sunglasses were on the car
seat, but her wallet has never been found.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the thin leads for her family have slipped from their
grasp _ like the sighting of a homeless woman in Florida who bore a
striking resemblance to Mrs. Bechtel, and the man who was said to
have stalked her while she was in college but turned up with an
alibi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not much farther along than we were one year ago, to be
honest,'' said Fremont County Sheriff Larry Mathews. ``But this is
not at a standstill. It's still moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses have testified before a Federal grand jury,
but Mathews said the major obstacle to his investigation was the
refusal of Mrs. Bechtel's husband, Steve, to take a polygraph test.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to make up a suspect list, he'd probably be the only
one on it,'' the sheriff said. ``Until he'll cooperate, until we
get other evidence that eliminates him, he is a possible suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bechtel has said that polygraph tests are unreliable and
that he has already cooperated by allowing a search of his home and
truck and answering investigators' questions. Mr. Bechtel, a
27-year-old mountain climber, is in Greenland on an expedition for
several weeks and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no basis whatsoever to view Steve as a suspect, not
one shred of evidence,'' said Kent Spence, Mr. Bechtel's lawyer.
``It's time for law enforcement to back off of Steve. It adds
another tragedy to this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Bechtel has said he was mountain climbing about 100 miles
away the day his wife disappeared, then returned home and had
dinner with neighbors while waiting for her. A motive seems
unclear. There was a life insurance policy of $3,400. Mr. Bechtel
pays the mortgage on the house that he and his wife bought and that
he cannot sell without her signature, friends and officials close
to the case say.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Mr. Bechtel's in-laws say his decision not to take the
polygraph test has strained their relationship with him. A few
months ago they changed the 800 number on the posters they have
mailed out across the country and on their Web site so it would
ring at their house and not his. A reward has increased to
$100,000, and new posters are being sent nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's entirely possible that Steve could have done
something,'' said Joanne Wroe, Mrs. Bechtel's mother. ``But we need
to be open to any possibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
