<SLUG> BC-CLIMATE-DISEASE-NEWYORK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK, MOSQUITOES AND TICKS ARRIVED EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (With CLIMATE-DISEASE)  
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The warm, wet winter produced by El Nino, combined
with an on-and-off wet spring, stimulated an unusually early
increase of mosquitoes and ticks that might spread disease in the
New York region. But so far no epidemics have materialized.
</P>
<P>
   In this region, where malaria and many other illnesses borne by
insects and other vectors have long been under control, two
weather-influenced diseases are of special concern: Lyme disease
and Eastern equine encephalitis, the former potentially crippling,
the latter potentially fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Two mosquitoes in particular _ the salt-marsh variety and a
similar freshwater type _ thrive in wet-dry cycles like those that
characterized the early summer in this region, said Dominick
Ninivaggi, the vector-control superintendent in Suffolk County on
Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The common household mosquito known as culex has also been more
abundant than usual this year, but although these insects have made
the summer a misery for some residents, none of them carry disease.
</P>
<P>
   The mosquito to worry about is the freshwater variety Culiseta
melanura. It transmits the encephalitis virus and has been
relatively abundant in places like Manorville, Ninivaggi said.
Measures to control its breeding were taken in the early spring, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the encephalitis virus was detected in some Long Island
mosquitoes; it typically appears in August. No cases have been
recorded on Long Island in recent years, although one person died
from encephalitis in Rhode Island earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, the summer has mostly been dry, and the number of
mosquitoes has consequently dropped, Ninivaggi said.
</P>
<P>
   Lyme disease is spread by the tiny deer tick, and Dr. Richard
Ostfeld, an ecologist at the Institute of Ecosystem Studies in
Millbrook, said the warm and wet winter led to an earlier and
bigger appearance of the ticks than usual in early spring.
Nevertheless, Ostfeld said, studies indicate that the total tick
population over the warm season ``should not be extraordinarily
high'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   In Suffolk County, where the ticks are endemic, disease
statistics seem to jibe with Ostfeld's analysis of the early
season. ``There's no question that there are more ticks around,''
said Dr. David Graham, Suffolk's director of preventive medicine
services.
</P>
<P>
   That has translated to about 250 confirmed cases of Lyme disease
in the county so far, he said. Most of the cases appeared ``a
little ahead of schedule,'' he said, but the total falls within the
range of 600 to 1,200 cases normally expected there each year.
</P>
<P>
   Next year might be different if the predictions of Ostfeld and
his colleagues prove right. They are calling for an extraordinarily
large population of deer ticks for 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
