A5231 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-HASKELL-NYT &LR;      08-09 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HASKELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORONADO'S QUEST HOLDS OFF VICTORY GALLUP TO WIN $1 MILLION
HASKELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCEANPORT, N.J. _ Five months ago, trainer Shug McGaughey left
Gulfstream Park a frustrated and disappointed man, his hopes of
taking Coronado's Quest to the Kentucky Derby in shambles.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he left Monmouth Park with the dream of a championship
for the talented 3-year-old colt very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   Coronado's Quest, whose fractious behavior in the Florida Derby
kept him out of the Kentucky Derby, put himself squarely in the
battle for year-end honors when he held off the stretch run of
Victory Gallop to win the $1 million Haskell, his first Grade I
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Behaving beautifully before a Haskell-record crowd of 40,405
that had made him the 3-5 favorite, Coronado's Quest stalked the
early pace set by the long shot Arctic Sweep and then moved up
quickly to take the lead on the far turn.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the stretch, Coronado's Quest, a chestnut son of
Forty Niner, first shook a strong challenge from Grand Slam and
then turned back the expected bid from the late-running Victory
Gallop, the Belmont Stakes winner. Victory Gallop, who was ridden
by Gary Stevens, charged along the rail to within 1\ lengths of the
winner at the end of the mile-and-an-eighth race.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens lodged an objection against Coronado's Quest, who was
ridden by Mike Smith, for drifting in in the final yards, but it
was quickly disallowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe I bothered that horse at all,'' said Smith.
``It didn't affect the outcome by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   Grand Slam held on for third, a half-length back, and was
followed under the wire by Ian's Thunder, Tomorrow's Cat and Arctic
Sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign started today for him,'' McGaughey said of
Coronado's Quest's chances for a championship. The colt missed the
Preakness and the Belmont because of a minor foot injury but
returned with victories in the Riva Ridge and the Dwyer at Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we had been pointing toward,'' McGaughey said.
``We came up against a horse today who has been to the battles and
we beat him. Now, we have to beat him again.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be in the 1 1/4-mile Travers at Saratoga on Aug. 29,
a race Victory Gallop's trainer, Elliott Walden, believes will be
more to his colt's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along this was a two-race series, the Haskell,
then the Travers,'' said Walden, whose colt finished second in the
Derby and the Preakness to Real Quiet. ``That day will be to our
advantage. He definitely is still in the running for champion
honors. His record speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop has four victories in seven starts, with two
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coronado's Quest was the best one today,'' Walden added. ``He
had some advantages with the track. We knew we were taking a chance
of getting him beat because of how this track plays.''
</P>
<P>
   McGaughey acknowledged that Monmouth's speed-favoring,
tight-turned track was very much to the liking of Coronado's Quest,
who covered the nine furlongs in 1:48 3/5 as he extended his record
to four victories in six starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victory Gallop will be tough coming back at 1 1/4 miles with
those big turns at Saratoga,'' McGaughey said. ``We'll have to be
tough, too. I saw what I wanted to out there today _ he responded
to two good challenges. A good hard race was what he needed and
that's what he got.''
</P>
<P>
   Coronado's Quest returned $3.40 for a $2 bet to win and earned
$600,000 for Stuart Janney Jr., who had concurred with McGaughey's
opinion this spring that the colt was too badly behaved to risk
taking to the carnival-like atmosphere at Churchill Downs. But a
minor surgical procedure performed before the colt left Florida to
correct his breathing, coupled with the extra time McGaughey and
his staff spent with him, all seem to have turned him around.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left the races Florida Derby Day I was a pretty
humiliated guy,'' McGaughey said. ``I was pretty down. I was
disappointed in the horse, second-guessing myself _ I didn't know
what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pretty proud guy,'' he said. ``I think we've got a
contender.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
