<HEADER>
A5236 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BARTLEYS-600&AMP;A     08-09 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BARTLEYS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 BARTLEYS: A FAMILY'S LAST, FAINT HOPE IS EXTINGUISHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-VICTIMS, AFRICA-EMBASSY,
AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-EVACUATE, AFRICA-TANZANIA) 
(mk) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER and JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ She already knew that her son was dead.
</P>
<P>
   But as Sue Bartley and 150 other mourners left a memorial
service here Sunday for the American victims of Friday's terrorist
bombing, they were hoping against hope that Mrs. Bartley's husband,
Consul General Julian Bartley, was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   They listened to a reading from Ecclesiastes, heard a mournful
rendering of taps and then went home to wait, grasping red roses in
trembling hands.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, their wisp of a hope was gone. Using torn
clothing, strands of hair and a ring, doctors positively identified
Bartley's badly disfigured body Sunday evening, adding his name to
a list of 11 dead Americans that included the Bartleys' 20-year-old
son, Jay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the last missing American,'' Chris Scharf, an embassy
spokesman, said of Bartley.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts the father and son were an immensely popular duo
whose headlong embrace of Kenyan life had been lovingly returned by
the people they met and befriended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julian was greatly loved by Kenyans,'' Scharf said, ``not only
because of his respect of them, but also because of his ability to
relate to the person who was trembling in line for a visa. He would
leave his office and go outside the embassy and work the line,
talking to people, asking them about themselves. He was
extraordinarily popular among Kenyans, even those who might be
denied a visa.''
</P>
<P>
   After Bartley was discovered missing, Kenyan soldiers searched
for him in local emergency rooms and the public morgue. But later
his body was found in a private mortuary where a tag misidentified
the body as that of a Kenyan, Scharf said.
</P>
<P>
   At a ceremony at Ambassador Prudence Bushnell's residence
Sunday, colleagues ``spoke about how Julian had touched so many
people,'' said Donald Mackenzie, director of the regional office of
the U.S. Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very special person,'' said Mackenzie, who found it
difficult to talk about his friend and colleague in the past tense.
``When he talks to you, you feel like you are the most important
person in the room, and not that he was looking around to see if
there was someone more important around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great sense of humor. Though I guess it isn't so
funny now, he used to say to people who came to him, `I'll take
care of you from womb to tomb.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bartley, 55, was born in Jacksonville, Fla., according to a
statement released by his daughter, Edith, who lives in the United
States and was en route Sunday night to Nairobi to join her mother.
He grew up in South Jamaica, Queens, where his mother, Gladys
Baldwin, still lives. He worked for the Foreign Service for 24
years, including assignments in the Dominican Republic, Colombia,
Spain, Israel and Korea.
</P>
<P>
   At Sunday's crowded memorial service, held on the porch of
Bushnell's home, Bartley's friends recalled how he once took a
night job to help pay some medical bills for his son Jay.
</P>
<P>
   To people who knew him, Jay Bartley had come to Kenya full of
youthful enthusiasm about Africa about two years ago. And when he
died, he had carved a young man's comfortably frenetic niche for
himself in Nairobi, coaching a girl's basketball team, jet skiing
at African beaches and teaching friends how to ride horses.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the bombing, Jay Bartley was working at the
embassy in a summer job, preparing for his sophomore year at the
U.S. International University in the Kasarani section of Nairobi,
about 12 miles from the city center. The college is based in San
Diego, but has an 1,800-student campus in Nairobi.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an interview, Freida Brown, executive director of the
university's Nairobi campus, said Jay Bartley had planned to spend
one more year in Nairobi before returning to the United States to
complete his bachelor's degree, possibly in international
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the explosion first hit, you felt detached from it,'' she
said. ``But Saturday morning, when they called me and said he had
died, I was totally distraught. Because I knew him and I could just
see him walking across that campus.''
</P>
<P>
   She described Jay Bartley as gentle, outgoing and caring, a
lanky young man with a wide grin and soft voice. He coached the
girl's basketball team at his former high school, the International
School of Kenya, and was known for teaching friends how to ride
horses. ``He was the kind of kid who got up first and made his
parents breakfast in the morning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent trip to Mombassa with some friends, Ms. Brown
recalled, Jay Bartley took it on himself to oversee the welfare of
a female student who had broken her leg after falling off her jet
ski.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took her to the hospital,'' Ms. Brown said. ``Then after
her foot was put in a cast, he piggybacked her to the bus. He was
always looking after other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown said Jay Bartley had a learning disability that made
it difficult for him to complete written tests, but that he had
more than compensated with a buoyant, dogged personality and a
laptop computer provided by his father. ``It was a real struggle
for him, but he never let that stop him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown described Julian Bartley and his wife as similar to
their son: easygoing, upbeat, sociable people. ``Julian always had
a big smile and hug for everybody,'' she said. ``They were three of
a kind.''
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to the Bartley home on Saturday, Ms. Brown
described Mrs. Bartley as being ``in a state of shock.'' Yet she
still had enough presence of mind to ask Ms. Brown whether she had
received a cookbook from the Nairobi American Women's Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's amazing,'' said Ms. Brown. ``She was looking after
people even in this time of sorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
