<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5239 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATINKIN-YIDDISH-SONG     08-09 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATINKIN-YIDDISH-SONGS-930(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOSTALGIA AND INNOVATION IN YIDDISH SONGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: This is the second article in a series describing cultural
events through their audiences' experiences. The previous article
described a performance by the Argentine troupe De la Guarda.) 
(js) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Faye Schutzberger was sitting in a 148-year-old
synagogue that has been turned into an otherworldly performance
space, trying to explain the elusive appeal of the language of her
ancestors and the long-lost music it spawned.
</P>
<P>
   ``S geyt tsu dem hartz; it goes to the heart,'' she finally said
as her eyes swept the faded elegance of the neo-Gothic building,
modeled after the Cathedral of Cologne, on the Lower East Side.
``It's soul music. Yiddish soul music. It affects you the way no
other music can.''
</P>
<P>
   There are times when audiences and performers have different
agendas and times when they are looking for precisely the same
thing. But it's hard to think of a case where the planets are more
passionately aligned than the hyperbolic evocation of Jewish roots,
``Mamaloshen'' (``Mother Tongue''), being performed by Mandy
Patinkin at what is now the Angel Orensanz Foundation and Center
for the Arts at 172 Norfolk St., near Houston Street.
</P>
<P>
   For Patinkin and for his audience, his hour-long concert of
Yiddish songs _ and quintessentially American ones translated into
Yiddish _ is less a performance than a seance, a way to connect
with a past that seems at once both utterly lost and somehow eerily
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the imagined past is wholly consistent with the real one
is open to debate, and it's safe to say an evening of Patinkin's
singing in Yiddish is not everyone's idea of artistic bliss.
</P>
<P>
   But for Mrs. Schutzberger, 80, who has lived her whole life in
the Flatbush section of Brooklyn; for Felice Spector and her
mother, Florey Stein; for Irving Goldberg, Martha Bergman and Roz
Schapira, who are part of a Yiddish club affiliated with the
Woodstock Jewish Congregation, no less than Patinkin, his
performance each night is like peeking into an overflowing chest,
long since discarded, with a combination of wonder and bewilderment
at what might be inside.
</P>
<P>
   So when Sylvia Herscher, 84, found herself standing on the
corner of Norfolk and Houston streets the other day, a few blocks
from the site of the wholesale hardware store her father used to
own, the mere existence of Patinkin's show and the surprising
vitality of the world it evoked was cause for celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' she said to her cousin, Phyllis Schwartz.
``There hasn't been as much action on Norfolk Street in 50 years.
What is this? Remembrance of things past?''
</P>
<P>
   The show's genesis dates back to the beginning of the decade
when Joseph Papp asked Patinkin to record a song, ``Youssel,
Youssel,'' in Yiddish. Given Patinkin's theatrical (critics
sometimes say too theatrical) style, the emotional megatonnage of
the material seemed a good fit.
</P>
<P>
   Papp was so taken by what he heard that he told Patinkin: ``You
have to do this music. This is your job.''
</P>
<P>
   After Papp's death in 1991, the job slowly became a calling, and
then a mission and then an obsession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm freest, I'm most able to express myself when I sing,''
Patinkin said one morning in his study in his Upper West Side
apartment. The study is jammed with family, career, model railroad
and Jewish memorabilia, like a plaque reading ``Dybbuk stops
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And for some reason, singing that song in Yiddish tripled the
experience,'' he continued. ``For all the times I've been
criticized for being over the top, maybe I was drawn to this music
because it invites it. It almost demands it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, I was born singing in the wrong language because the
people who wrote and sang these songs were the greatest
storytellers ever of family and journey, life, birth, death, joy,
sorrow. And I realized that this was where Tin Pan Alley began,
that before there was the music I began singing, before Gershwin
and Irving Berlin and Rodgers and Hammerstein, there was Yiddish
music.''
</P>
<P>
   To do the show, Patinkin immersed himself in Yiddish language,
literature and song, including studying every morning at 7 with
Moishe Rosenfeld, who presides over New York's only daily Yiddish
radio show. The result, first in a Nonesuch CD and then in the
show, is an improbable musical stew that's one part rediscovery of
the lost past and one part reinterpretation of the familiar
present.
</P>
<P>
   So the songs include old Yiddish numbers like ``Belz,'' a lament
for a small town, or ``Papirosin,'' about a poor cigarette seller;
``Unter Dayne Vayse Shtern'' (``Under Your White Stars''), a
Holocaust song, and ``Lid Fun Titanic'' (``Song of the Titanic''),
a Yiddish take on the sinking, pre-Leonardo.
</P>
<P>
   But they also include Patinkin's entirely unlikely Yiddish
versions of familiar songs like ``Maria'' (rendered as ``Mayn
Mirl'' ) from ``West Side Story,'' ``Take Me Out to the Ball Game''
(``Nem Mikh Mit Tsu der Ball Geym'') and ``God Bless America''
(``Got Bentsh Amerike''), replete with an unfurled oversize flag.
All of this provides a vertiginous experience of somehow sounding
unsettlingly right when rendered in Yiddish, as if plucked whole
from a parallel universe.
</P>
<P>
   For Patinkin the music resonates on at least three levels:
first, for its role in the development of American song; second,
for its evocation of his own Jewish past, and third, for its
evocation of the American immigrant experience. But he said the
degree to which the production is both indelibly Jewish and
patently American explains in part the mystery of how listeners
seem both transfixed and somehow comprehending of music in a
language only a small percentage of them understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mystery I can't explain, but I did not grow up with
this stuff, and it speaks to me,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   For much of the audience, it's the specific, not the universal,
elements of the music and culture that mean the most. So for the
mother and daughter, Ms. Spector and Mrs. Stein, the appeal was
very much rooted in the pickles at Gus', the egg creams at Katz's,
the smell and texture of Orchard and Ludlow and Essex streets.
</P>
<P>
   For Goldberg, it was more the survival of Yiddish and what he
saw as a revival of culture he once thought was certain to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how many people listen to klezmer music?'' he said
excitedly. ``Not just among Jews, but even among gentiles? That's
why you see so many young people here.''
</P>
<P>
   At which point he spied three young women walking in together
who turned out to be three Mormon sisters, Christy, Laura and Emily
Summerhays, from Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss, may I see you a minute, please?'' he said to the first
one. ``I don't want to get too personal, but we're doing an
interview here. How old are you?''
</P>
<P>
   He beamed when Christy Summerhays, an aspiring actress, said she
was 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``See,'' he said. ``You get my point?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the point is open to endless interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Schutzberger, who grew up in a Yiddish-speaking home, was
not happy with the English version of Paul Simon's ``American
Tune,'' which Patinkin uses as a bridge weaving through the
performance and as a way to convey a sense of the production to
those who don't speak Yiddish. And she was not convinced the show
was more than a glimpse of a dying culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's like a last gasp,'' she said. ``For those of us
that grew up with it, this is a part of us. It's almost cellular.
But I try to get my daughter interested in Yiddish music or
theater, and she has no interest. It's not part of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   And not everyone was taken with the emotional temperature of the
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little of Mandy goes a long way,'' one woman said.
</P>
<P>
   But the show has been such a success that it has been extended
from its original closing date, last Saturday, to Aug. 22. After
that the Orensanz will not be available, but Patinkin is searching
for another theater. And both for those who lived the vanished
world of the Lower East Side (``Loved it, loved it, loved it,''
Mrs. Stein said as she bounded off for a hot dog and an egg cream
at Katz's) and those, Jewish or not, who knew it third-hand or not
at all, most people seemed profoundly moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the language, but you still understand,'' Christy
Summerhays said. ``I never felt I was missing out.''
</P>
<P>
   How far the show will go toward fostering the embryonic revival
of interest in Yiddish culture is not clear. But Rosenfeld said
Patinkin had fulfilled all his missionary instincts and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the album and the show, more people are being turned onto
Yiddish culture now than at any time in the past 25 years,''
Rosenfeld said. ``It's important for people to know, to have some
respectful acknowledgment of the beauty of this culture. That's
what Mandy's doing. How far it goes, only time will tell. But it's
all good. That's the key. It's all about doing good for the soul.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
