<SLUG> BC-RAC-JIM-DANDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAVORITE TRICK WINS JIM DANDY BY A NOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ In the other half of the day's
sweepstakes for 3-year-old honors, Favorite Trick won the Jim Dandy
Stakes by a nose with a dramatic rally that showed the class of a
Horse of the Year, but not many clues to his future.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the colt's stirring success, it remained most unlikely
that he would go on to the Travers Stakes in three weeks to
challenge Coronado's Quest, who won the $1 million Haskell
Invitational at Monmouth Park, and Victory Gallop, who finished
second to Coronado's Quest. Both races were ranked as preps for the
Travers and the year-end prize, the Eclipse Award for the best
3-year-old colt of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Trick played the starring role in his part of the show
by prevailing in a tight three-horse finish by the length of his
nose over Deputy Diamond, who won second by a neck over Raffie's
Majesty. Then it was only a length and a half back to Scatmandu in
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Jim Dandy also became a personal triumph for Bill Mott,
trainer of Favorite Trick, coming on the day before his induction
into the Racing Hall of Fame. And it punctuated a ringing weekend
for Pat Day, who won the Whitney Handicap on Saturday aboard
Awesome Again and returned Sunday to win the Jim Dandy with
Favorite Trick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He proved that he was a champion last year,'' Mott said of
Favorite Trick, ``and he was named Horse of the Year, and
rightfully so. That was 1997, and he's now shown this year that
he's good enough to win at a mile and an eighth. He's never run a
bad race other than the Kentucky Derby, and that was at a distance
that didn't suit him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Derby, which was run at a mile and a quarter, Favorite
Trick ran eighth. The only other race he lost was the
mile-and-an-eighth Arkansas Derby, when he ran third in a scramble
behind Victory Gallop. His record now is 11 victories in 13 starts,
but Mott again doubted that he could win beyond a mile and an
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Travers, run at a mile and a quarter, Mott said:
``It's probably something we're not planning to do right now. I do
think we'll stay away from that race, but we'd like to discuss it
for about a week or so. Grass is an option for him, and it's
something we may look to do down the line because he's worked over
it and we know he handles it. A flat mile may suit him because we
know if we're thinking about the Breeders' Cup, we obviously are
not going to run him in the mile-and-a-quarter Classic. We'd like
to keep our options open and find out what it is that he does
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Trick ran third much of the way Sunday, stalking the
early speed flashed by Rock and Roll, who led for nearly one mile.
Right on his heels came Scatmandu, who briefly poked his head in
front as they turned for home. At that point, Favorite Trick seemed
to be losing ground. But Day changed paths, found daylight and
raced from fourth place to first in the deep stretch, where he
stuck his nose in front at just the right time in a gutsy
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite Trick ran the mile and an eighth in 1:50 flat, paid
$5.90 for a $2 bet to win and earned $150,000, raising his career
income past $1.5 million. Limit Out, who was one of the early
favorites, was scratched a couple of hours before the race because
he was coughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Favorite Trick has had a pretty good year,'' Day said, ``but
obviously he's not handling the competition with the authority he
did last year. But he's getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   The race was run before 61,190 fans on a sunny afternoon in the
Adirondacks, conditions that helped surpass the attendance record
of 58,269 set last Aug. 3. But the precise number of spectators who
attended on both days was doubtless somewhat lower because both
were promoted with souvenir T-shirts, and many in both crowds went
through the turnstiles several times and willingly paid the $2
admission charge more than once to get more gifts. . . . At 45,
Bill Mott will become the youngest trainer inducted into the Racing
Hall of Fame when he is enshrined at Saratoga on Monday. He was
elected to the Hall of Fame along with Jacinto Vasquez, the jockey,
who rode 5,231 winners and twice won the Kentucky Derby, and Ansel
Williamson, who started training horses during the 1850s while
still a slave and later, after being freed, went on to train
Aristides, the winner of the first Kentucky Derby in 1875.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
