<HEADLINE>
FORMER GREEN BERET SUES OVER CNN-TIME REPORT  
 MILKEN'S LATEST VENTURE: CO-WRITING A COOKBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif.)  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cable News Network and Time magazine have been served with the
first lawsuit filed in response to their joint ``CNN Newsstand''
report in June contending that the U.S. military dropped lethal
nerve gas in Laos in 1970. In what could be a harbinger of
expensive legal bills to come for the two Time Warner companies,
the suit was filed by a man who was never even named in the CNN
report or its companion article in Time.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Plancich, a former Green Beret who was on the so-called
Operation Tailwind mission that day 28 years ago, filed a $100
million lawsuit against Cable News Network and Time on Thursday in
U.S. District Court in Miami, saying he had been defamed by the
June report, even though it was publicly retracted a month later.
</P>
<P>
   Although not named, he appeared in photographs, both on CNN and
in Time, of what Time called a ``hatchet force'' sent to ``wipe out
a Laotian village suspected of harboring American defectors.''
</P>
<P>
   That accusation angered Plancich, said his lawyers, Edward Horan
and Mitchell Cook. ``CNN focused in on the nerve-gas issue,'' Horan
said, ``and the Pentagon got involved investigating very quickly
because of that allegation, plus the question of whether anyone
killed was an American defector. But they all glossed over the
allegations of killing women and children _ crimes punishable by
death under international military law.''
</P>
<P>
   After inquiries by both the Pentagon and CNN's own legal team
found insufficient evidence to support the ``Newsstand''
allegations, CNN and Time executives retracted them and issued
profuse apologies.
</P>
<P>
   The network also negotiated an undisclosed monetary settlement
with retired Adm. Thomas Moorer, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff in 1970, whom CNN had depicted as having confirmed the use of
nerve gas. CNN also offered a settlement to the mission's
commanding officer, Lt. Col. Eugene McCarley, who rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the network said CNN would not comment on
pending legal action. Horan said that Plancich, who lives in Key
West, Fla., was not interviewed by CNN for the Tailwind report.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's own internal investigation of the coverage criticized the
journalists who produced the Tailwind segment _ two of whom were
dismissed _ but took pains to say that those journalists believed
that what they were reporting was true.
</P>
<P>
   That may make it difficult for Plancich to prove the reporters
acted with ``actual malice'' _ a requirement for winning a libel
judgment on behalf of a public official. Some libel experts said a
court would most likely regard an Army sergeant as a public
official.
</P>
<P>
   Although a deliberate effort to avoid the truth can be evidence
of malice, that, too, is difficult to prove. But Horan indicated
that he might try to prove just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hearing two sides all along,'' he said, ``but they
basically chose to discount the versions that didn't go along with
their story line.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   Milken's Latest Venture: Co-Writing a Cookbook
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity cookbooks are nothing new. But now Michael Milken _
the man whose enormous appetite for power, money and junk bonds led
to his conviction for securities fraud _ is serving time as a
recipe monger.
</P>
<P>
   Using the nom de spoon Mike Milken, he is co-author with his
personal chef, Beth Ginsberg, of ``The Taste for Living Cookbook:
Mike Milken's Favorite Recipes for Fighting Cancer.'' The book,
which the Time-Life Books unit of Time Warner will distribute as a
50,000-copy first printing in September, is part of Milken's
personal and public battle against the disease. His prostate cancer
is now in remission.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from California, Milken, 52, said that
when advanced prostate cancer was diagnosed in February 1993 and he
was told he had 12 to 18 months to live, he decided not to follow
the example of his friend Steven J. Ross, the former Time Warner
chairman, who had died of the same disease a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Milken recalled that Ross thought ``the idea of giving up eating
the food you love is the same as giving up life'' _ even though
leading researchers say that a low-fat diet high in fruits,
vegetables and soy products may be an effective tool in combating
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Milken changed his diet as part of his treatment regimen _
although, initially, he said, eating became ``more of a burden than
a pleasure.'' That is, until Ms. Ginsberg, who trained at the
Culinary Institute of America, taught him that ``you could make
healthy food taste like and look like the food you grew up with.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-color, large-format book, which will sell for $27.50,
was designed and edited by the Boston-based book packagers Allen &AMP;
Osborne. It includes a six-page first-person memoir of Milken's
eating life _ although his time in jail is not mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Time-Life will distribute the book for the publisher, Cap Cure,
the prostate-cancer charity that Milken founded. Cap Cure will
receive all the profits from the book.
</P>
<P>
   When Milken goes to New York to publicize the book in
mid-September, he will be eschewing the kind of junk food he once
chewed while standing at his desk trading junk bonds. He now
recommends low-fat or fat-free delicacies like ``Eggs Michael,''
``Vegetable Reuben'' and ``Devil's `Fool' Cake.''
</P>
<P>
   _ GAYLE FELDMAN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
