<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACOB'S PILLOW: TRIUMPH FOR AMERICAN INDIAN DANCE THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BECKET, Mass. _ The American Indian Dance Theater's new
``Kotuwokan'' got off to a slow start on Saturday night at the Ted
Shawn Theater at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival here. But by the
close of the evening, the company had succeeded triumphantly in an
ambitious project, ending in a grand finale with a stageful of
dancers and musicians performing as one vivid whole.
</P>
<P>
   That would have been enough to merit the kinds of cheers and
youthful screams that greeted the company when the curtain rose
again on the bowing ensemble. But those closing moments of the
piece, a suite of dances whose title means ``come celebrate the
dance'' in the Algonquin language, were also extremely poignant. In
trying to suggest the vital survival of tradition, Hanay Geiogamah,
who conceived and directed ``Kotuwokan,'' also suggested that it
was possible to make fresh formal art of age-old ritual, practiced
here by a company founded 10 years ago to preserve and popularize
traditional American Indian dance and music.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of the inclusion in the piece of a dance
created for the company by the modern-dance choreographer Laura
Dean. And Ms. Dean's quartet ``New Dance,'' performed by Rod
Atcheynum, Lisa Odjig-Fisher, Dawn Russell and Dmitri Seth, was a
shimmering little jewel of a piece that took a rather rigidly
circumscribed vocabulary of small walking steps, colored by tilts
and dips of the torso, and turned it into rich, minimalist art. One
thought of Paul Klee's glowing magic-square paintings, watching the
performers move together in a line and then separate for solos
clearly drawn from their individual gifts and styles, waving small
fronds of bright ribbons as they danced.
</P>
<P>
   Even more impressive was the way Geiogamah sewed the piece into
the larger quilt of the new work. A lone traveler's journey through
time and a culture _ a familiar genre in the these multiculturalist
days _ ``Kotuwokan'' incorporated a city street scene, old forms
like the Fancy Shawl Dance, Hoop Dance and a variety of animal
dances, and scenes of hunting and battle. The traveler died and was
brought back to life, borne up by the long wings of attendant
eagles. The piece built into dances that gave the performers a
chance to show off the smooth, quick footwork that moved them into
astonishingly complex jumps and cross-footed travel.
</P>
<P>
   The most affecting moment came toward the end in the ``modern
fancy dance'' performed by Ms. Odjig-Fisher and Shawn Yazzie in
odd-looking black gym clothes, that in its renewing of the
traditional recalled the South African gumboot dance fashioned by
miners from their inherited dance forms. The point was made.
</P>
<P>
   The company, culled from 11 tribes across the nation, also
includes Marty Pinnecoose, Eddie Swimmer, Leslie Barichello, Jason
Daniels, Bronson Haywahe, Kevin Haywahe, Georgena Jones, Isaac
Lehi, Marc Meekis, Dallas Morrison, Elizabeth Olney, Darrell
Paskemin, Sancha Paskemin and Morgan Tosee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
