<HEADLINE>
NO CANDIDATES YET BUT VOTERS PREFER ...  
 FLORIDA: UNITY EVENT EXPOSES RIFT WITHIN RIFT  
 COLORADO: POLITICIANS GALLOP AND RUN FOR VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's early for this sort of thing, but because many of the
presidential candidates, probable candidates and possible
candidates are already out shaking the bushes, here's how the field
ranked when the Harris Poll recently asked 1,011 potential voters
to name their first choice for the Republican presidential
nomination in 2000. The figures following each name represent the
percentage of support:
</P>
<P>
   Colin Powell, the retired general, 25;
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush Jr. of Texas, 16;
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, wife of former Senator Bob Dole, 8;
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kemp, the 1996 Vice Presidential nominee, 7;
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, 7;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the magazine publisher, 4;
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, the commentator and former candidate, 3;
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, 3;
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich, 2;
</P>
<P>
   Former Education Secretary William J. Bennett, 1;
</P>
<P>
   All others, 8
</P>
<P>
   And undecided, 15.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, released last week, was conducted between July 17 and
21 and had a margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   A few words of caution:
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters say Powell runs best in polls if respondents are asked
to pick a favorite from a list that includes his name _ the method
in this poll _ as opposed to respondents' mentioning his name on
their own. Apparently many voters take him at his word that he does
not intend to be a candidate and therefore do not volunteer his
name.
</P>
<P>
   In the current Harris poll, when the poll-takers removed the
retired general's name from the list for a second round of
questioning, the order of finish for the remaining names was
roughly the same as in the first round of questioning, with Bush
getting 22 percent, Mrs. Dole 12 percent and the others ending up
in about the same order as before and with about the same
percentages.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bush, pollsters say his high standing _ he consistently
does well in all polls _ appears to result in part because some
voters confuse him with his father, the former president.
</P>
<P>
   UNITY EVENT EXPOSES RIFT WITHIN RIFT
</P>
<P>
   Racial feuding between white and black Democrats in Florida over
leadership jobs has taken a new and more ominous turn, with blacks
now fighting with blacks over how to end the bitter quarrel.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore flew to Fort Lauderdale over the weekend
in an effort to mediate an end to the squabbling, which is not only
considered a major divisive threat to Democratic election hopes in
this fall's elections, especially the governor's race, but could
also pose a threat to any hopes Gore might have for capturing the
Sunshine State's big trove of 25 electoral votes two years from
now.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president and some of the state's top Democratic
leaders emerged from the meeting talking peace and solidarity. But
they conceded that the rift was by no means totally healed and that
the meeting was, at best, ``a step forward toward unity.''
</P>
<P>
   One major figure in the quarrel, state Rep. Willie Logan of
Opa-Locka, was not at the meeting _ and it was not clear whether he
had not been invited or had spurned an invitation.
</P>
<P>
   As the meeting got under way, some black demonstrators handed
out leaflets that were critical of some black participants,
including Rep. Alcee Hastings of Miramar, perhaps the most powerful
black politician in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The squabbling broke out last spring when white Democrats in the
State House of Representatives decided to oust Logan, who is black,
as their leader. They contended that he was ineffective and chose
state Rep. Anne Mackenzie of Fort Lauderdale, who is white, to
replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings weighed in at that point, declaring that the leadership
change was but the latest proof that Florida's Democratic Party
took the state's considerable black vote for granted. He and Logan
began talking about using the black vote, normally 95 percent
Democratic, as a swing vote, one that could go either Democratic or
Republican in elections, now punishing, now rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ms. Mackenzie has announced that she plans to
retire, and her fellow white Democrats, both in the State House and
within the Florida Democratic Party's top ranks, have been trying
to make amends, including casting about for a black member to
replace her as leader. But their top choices strike Hastings and
Logan as the wrong choices.
</P>
<P>
   They were chosen, Logan said a few days ago, because they would
``do the bidding'' of the white majority in the State House.
Hastings warned of ``sycophantic symbolism.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the black legislators in the running, state rep. Josephus
Eggelletion of Fort Lauderdale, accused Hastings of divisive
political meddling.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the king,'' Eggelletion said.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from the weekend peace talks, Hastings seemed intent on
putting such remarks behind him in favor of building party unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to elect Democrats all over the state,'' he said,
adding that he, for one, intended to work hard this fall for the
Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   POLITICIANS GALLOP AND RUN FOR VOTES
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's primaries in Colorado will be some of the most
important in the country to date, with abortion rights a major
issue in several.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell is favored to be renominated in the
Republican Senate primary, not only because is he an incumbent,
with high name recognition, but also becaise he has a big stash of
campaign cash. Still, his challenger, Bill Eggert, a lawyer and
solid Republican conservative, has run a surprisingly strong race,
constantly hammering on the possibly crucial fact that Campbell was
a lifelong Democrat until he jumped to the Republican fold three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Dottie Lamm, the wife of former Gov.
Richard Lamm, is the favorite, having high name recognition, a big
cash stash and the backing of most party leaders. Yet her opponent,
state Rep. Gil Romero, has hung on doggedly, traveling much of the
state on foot, often running, literally, because he is an avid
jogger.
</P>
<P>
   If the fall race comes down to a Campbell-Lamm contest, current
polls indicate Campbell will win, thereby doing his part to help
retain the Republican majority in the Senate. But national
Democratic leaders have indicated they may pour in help, whomever
the Democrats nominate, because they believe Campbell's party
switching has left him vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   In the primaries for governor in Colorado, abortion is a crucial
issue in the Republican contest, with State Treasurer Bill Owens, a
conservative, opposing it, and the president of the state Senate,
Tom Norton, a moderate, in favor of leaving the choice up to women.
</P>
<P>
   Polls give Owens a slight lead. But he has been slipping a bit
since he acknowledged that he misstated his draft record when he
said did not receive a college deferment during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Lt. Gov. Gail Schoettler is favored to
win over the state Senate's minority leader, Mike Feeley. Ms.
Schoettler has campaigned much of the time by horse, riding more
than 500 miles in a successful search of publicity. Democrats have
controlled the Colorado governorship for the past 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   Two Colorado congressional primaries, both in districts where
incumbents are retiring, merit watching.
</P>
<P>
   In the 6th District, on Denver's western outskirts, the
attention is all on the Republican contest because the district is
so full of Republican voters that, come fall, it probably will not
matter whom the Democrats send into battle. What is worth keeping
an eye on is whether the four Republican conservatives and
moderates running on Tuesday so fragment the vote that an abortion
rights advocate, state Rep. Martha Kreutz, slips in as the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2nd District, northwest of Denver, four Democrats are
vying for the right to try to hold the seat for the party, which
has owned it for the past 12 years. It could be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The likely winner, Boulder's Mayor, Bob Greenlee, is a moderate
who favors abortion rights. Come fall, that kind of political
ideology could make him a real competitor in a district that is
evenly divided among Republicans, Democrats and independents.
</P>
</TEXT>
