<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK AND THE YANKEES BOTH HITS WITH KNOBLAUCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chuck Knoblauch was doing high-step running exercises
in front of the first-base dugout with the rest of the Yankees two
hours before Sunday's game. All the Yankees needed were tires
strewn across the grass to make the drill look even more animated.
Legs churned, arms pumped, faces contorted.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Knoblauch abandoned the routine and zigged and zagged
between and around his teammates like a miniature Jerry Rice. It
was a trivial display, but it looked natural for Knoblauch to
behave expressively, and it made his teammates chuckle. That meant
it was a successful venture for Knoblauch. He looked comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it before, and I'll say it again, this is the most
positive experience I've had in baseball and in my baseball life,''
Knoblauch said. ``Off the field, everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that Knoblauch won a World Series championship with
the Twins as a rookie in 1991 and that his .254 average this season
is a whopping 50 points lower than the career average he entered
the season with, it was an intriguing comment. The Yankees have not
had one post-season game yet, and Knoblauch sounds like a person
who adores New York, or one who really wants everyone to believe he
does.
</P>
<P>
   The always intense Knoblauch loosened up considerably as he
recounted walking through Manhattan recently and being jolted when
a truck driver abruptly stopped a few feet away from him. The
trucker shouted, ``Hey, Chuckie,'' waved his fist, told the second
baseman the Yankees ruled, and rumbled away.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is just different from any other city,'' Knoblauch
said. ``The people, the city, everything is great.''
</P>
<P>
   While it has been thrilling for Knoblauch to be the leadoff man
for a team that is barreling toward the major league record for
regular-season victories, perplexing moments have collided with
positive moments. From the inexplicable throwing troubles he has
endured to the subpar batting average to the dwindling on-base
percentage to the remarkable splurge of homers that exceeds what
Mark McGwire has done since the All-Star Game, this season has also
been a soap opera of sorts for Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Knoblauch has socked 11 homers since July 10, two
more than McGwire in the same period, it has puzzled Manager Joe
Torre. Torre is not sure how to feel about Knoblauch's swinging at
the high pitches he is being fed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' Torre said. ``Again, I'm not sure if it's good
or bad, because he's a get-on-base guy. Turns out he's helped us
win games in other ways, with the home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch helped Sunday by reaching base in three of four
at-bats, including a single in the sixth inning to begin a
three-run rally as the Yankees edged the Royals, 5-4. Still, the
numbers that matter most are 84-29. That is the Yankees' record,
and why Knoblauch said: ``I want to play here. I haven't thought
any differently since I was traded. I can't say how much I enjoy
being a Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Brian Cashman should clip Knoblauch's words out
of the paper and save them as potential bargaining tools. Because
Knoblauch was traded in the middle of a five-year, $30 million
contract, he can demand a trade within 15 days after the conclusion
of the World Series. Knoblauch, who will have three years and $18
million remaining on the deal after the season, does not seem
likely to do that. But Alan and Randy Hendricks, his agents, would
surely like a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   When those discussions happen, Cashman should politely remind
the agents that Knoblauch had a good, not a great, year. Cashman
should also tell them that Knoblauch's $6 million salary would be
more than anyone on the roster who has a guaranteed contract for
1999 except for Paul O'Neill. The general manager should say $6
million is enough. For now, forget an extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only discussion we had was early and how he doesn't want
to go anywhere and we don't want him to go anywhere, so let's not
worry about it,'' Cashman said. ``I'm not worried about it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Yankees traded pitcher Eric Milton and three minor leaguers
for Knoblauch, and that is another reason they do not want to lose
the 30-year-old. ``It's a good relationship,'' Knoblauch said.
``Hopefully, there won't be a problem. I don't foresee any as long
as they want me to play here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch halted his ``I Love New York'' campaign when asked
what he would do if the Yankees sought to honor his current
contract and did not offer him a dollar over $18 million, which is
quite plausible and quite fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I haven't even thought about,'' Knoblauch said.
``It's hard for me to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   It should not be hard. Not for someone who loves New York so
much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
