<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-SEX-SHOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: JUST SHOPPING _ NO SEX, PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was supposed to be a harmless shopping expedition,
aimed at picking up the kind of bargains that a more single-minded
sex-shop patron might easily miss. Where else, after all, but at
the Times Square Book and Video Center, formerly XXXtasy Peepshow
Center, could you find a Thomas the Tank Engine video (``Thomas
Breaks the Rules'') for only $1.98?
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, in the course of an afternoon spent strolling
Eighth Avenue, this columnist did get some swell stuff. For Mom _
happy birthday! _ a bottle of Dolce Vita eau de toilette ($9.99,
tax included, at Show World). For her father-in-law, a Rodale
gardening video, ``Planting, Pruning and Propagating'' ($4.28,
bought at NRS Video, formerly NRS XXX Video).
</P>
<P>
   As for herself, a leering salesman with a Freddy Krueger laugh
recommended a key chain adorned with a diminutive couple who
perform, when properly manipulated, what is now officially known as
a ``specified sexual activity.'' She chose, however, to go with a
classic: a brunet ``tip and strip'' pen ($2 at the Photo Emporium).
</P>
<P>
   But despite the fun and the bargains, the afternoon ended badly,
at least for the cause of free speech. First, an embarrassed but
persistent salesman at NRS Video insisted that this columnist would
have to leave if she continued to write down titles from its new
stock of tapes. (``If you have a question, talk to our lawyer,'' he
kept saying.)
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the Playpen, she was thrown out again for taking notes,
this time by a considerably larger and more intimidating gentleman.
When asked why, he gestured impatiently and said: ``I'm just doing
my job. I'm not giving you any more.''
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the battle over New York's sex shops has
been a game of cat and mouse, with the cat, as usual, heavily
favored.
</P>
<P>
   Since the city passed its new zoning law three years ago, shop
owners, whose business does not actually have much to do with
speech, judging from the sounds issuing from the remaining peep
booths, have sought shelter in the First Amendment. Meanwhile the
Giuliani administration, trying to stay on the right side of the
Constitution, has claimed to be merely regulating the sex shops
while clearly trying to shut down as many as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Now the game has entered a new phase, in which each side has
forced the other into increasingly baroque postures.
</P>
<P>
   The shop owners have spent the last few weeks in hurried
renovations, trying to stock up on enough irrelevant tchotchkes and
remaindered videos to evade the title ``adult establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The city could have simply claimed victory and enjoyed the
spectacle. Instead, it has tried to press ahead with closing the
shops, only to bump up against the mathematics of its own law.
</P>
<P>
   According to regulations issued by the Buildings Department last
month, a sex shop-video store-luggage boutique-perfume counter does
cease to be an ``adult establishment'' once 60 percent of its
accessible floor space is devoted to stuff that no one entering the
shop is likely to be interested in.
</P>
<P>
   So far, neither cat nor mouse can be sure how this latest phase
of the chase will end.
</P>
<P>
   The city has closed down several clubs where real sex seems to
have been for sale, but it has yet to succeed in shutting a shop
where all that was at issue was good clean smut.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Justice Stephen Crane of state Supreme Court in
Manhattan heard many hours of testimony on the precise nature of
the changes at Show World, formerly the city's most extensive sex
shop, now a combination pool hall, ``classic'' movie theater,
bookstore and sex shop. He reserved judgment on the question of
whether the establishment, at Eighth Avenue and 42nd Street, should
be shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   Why some sex-shop owners are so reluctant to allow reporters to
chronicle their transformation is hard to know, but the staff at
Show World could not have been more gracious when this columnist
appeared at its new and totally empty movie theater to sample the
offerings. Behind her, a foreign tourist in a tank top took one
look at what was showing and left in confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Available for viewing were five ``classic'' movies, or more
precisely videos, which were being screened on a continuous basis.
Upon request, one of the staff members obligingly cut off
``Barbarosa'' in favor of ``Of Human Bondage.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Howard limped across the screen in a grainy blur. Sad to
say, even at $5, it wasn't a bargain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
