<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: MAJOR PLAYERS; WORLD'S BIGGEST ARTS FESTIVAL; PEQUOT
MUSEUM TO OPEN; CEREBRAL AUTEURS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., N.Y., Great Britain)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the artistic directors of Summerfest La Jolla in California,
the husband-and-wife team of David Finckel, the cellist, and Wu
Han, the pianist, have banded together their musical cronies in
hope of producing ``the world's best chamber music festival.''
Whether or not that's true, chamber-music aficionados can feast on
performances by some of the biggest names in the business during 10
concerts at the La Jolla Museum of Contemporary Art. Lending a hand
to the newly appointed leaders are the violinists Ida and Ani
Kavafian and the pianist Menahem Pressler. The festival runs
through Aug. 22. Information: (619) 459-3728.
</P>
<P>
   The Jolly What?
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Edinburgh Festival Fringe retained its Guinness Book of
World Records status as the largest arts festival when it opened
Sunday for its 51st season. With 16,141 performances of 1,309 shows
by 9,810 artists, the Fringe is a cornucopia of arts both
traditional and, well, not so. Falling in the former category are
the European premiere of Sam Shepard's play ``Shaved Splits'' and a
tribute to the 1960s balladeer Serge Gainsbourg by '90s rockers
like P.J. Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the ``mad musical mayhem'' of ``The Jolly Folly of
Polly the Scottish Trolley Dolly.'' Just don't ask what it's about.
The festival's organizers aren't sure themselves, though a
spokesman said it had nothing to do with cloning. Information:
011-44-131-226-5138.
</P>
<P>
   Time Travel
</P>
<P>
   The Mashantucket Pequot Tribe of southern New England, the owner
of the Foxwoods Resort Casino, has put its money where it counts
with a $135 million, tribally owned and operated Mashantucket
Museum and Research Center, to open Tuesday. The complex, about a
mile and a half from the casino in Mashantucket, Conn., was
designed to serve as a resource on the history and culture of the
region's tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Combining technology and scholarly research, multisensory
dioramas depict tribal life as it was. Visitors can walk past a
replica of a glacial crevasse to a caribou hunt from 11,000 years
ago and then on to a 16th-century Pequot village, a 17th-century
Pequot fort and an 18th-century farmstead. Information: (860)
396-6800.
</P>
<P>
   Choice Picks
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers convened in upstate New York over the weekend for the
44th Robert Flaherty Film Seminar to explore the weighty topics of
truth and reality in nonfiction films. Beginning on Friday, the
Museum of Modern Art will present a selection of new works by the
directors doing all that heavy thinking in ``Investigating the
Real.''
</P>
<P>
   On view will be Sienna McLean's ``Still Revolutionaries,'' about
women within the Black Panther Party, and Hirokazu Koreeda's
``Kioku ga Ushinawareta Toki,'' about a man suffering from a
syndrome that prevents him from accumulating new memories.
Information: (212) 708-9480.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0176 </DOCNO>
