<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' BID FOR SWEEP FALLS SHORT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ As Mets Manager Bobby Valentine reminded anyone within
earshot this weekend, there is long way to go before the season is
over. But a victory Sunday still would have meant something.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since May 31, the Mets had a chance to pull
into the lead in the National League wild-card race. All they
needed was to beat the Rockies again.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs were on their way to another defeat in St. Louis, as
the Cardinals swept a three-game series and left the door wide open
for the Mets. And, for a moment, it looked as if the Mets might
leave Coors Field with their first series sweep, and their first
victory over Darryl Kile since May 4, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Hideo Nomo took the mound in the bottom of the fourth inning
with a 4-1 lead. But Nomo, who had somehow battled his way through
the first three innings, lost any touch he had left. The
right-hander never escaped the fourth, as Colorado rallied for
seven runs. Before the game was over the Rockies would score 10
unanswered runs for an 11-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   And after the drubbing, the Mets (62-53) had to travel to St.
Louis, still trailing the Cubs by a half-game.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kile (8-14) had improved his record against the Mets
to 9-3, as Dante Bichette, who homered, singled and doubled twice,
drove in 5 runs to reach 100 runs batted in for the fourth
consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long afternoon,'' Valentine said. ``And that fourth
inning was real long.''
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud was the one bright spot for the Mets. He had four
singles to extend his hitting streak to 23 games, one short of
Hubie Brooks' club record. But little else went right for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   And almost everything went wrong for Nomo (5-9), who in three
and two-thirds innings was charged with eight hits, seven runs,
three walks, three wild pitches and one costly balk that forced in
a run. It was Nomo's first loss since June 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dry here, maybe that's why,'' Nomo said through his
interpreter. ``I don't know if it was the dryness or what. It just
feels different pitching at Coors Field.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Valentine: ``He kept fiddling with his grip on the ball. He
was fiddling with it the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   And not like Zero Mostel.
</P>
<P>
   Over his last five starts, Nomo, who is the only pitcher to
throw a no-hitter in this park, had been 3-0 with a 2.37 earned run
average. But Sunday Nomo's lack of control, which had plagued him
earlier in the season, did him in again. Staked to the 4-1 lead
after two and a half innings on the strength of a two-run second
and a two-run third, Nomo walked a pair of Rockies in the bottom of
the third, but escaped unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   But when Nomo allowed back-to-back singles to Todd Helton and
Mike Lansing to open the fourth, he could not escape again. Nomo's
first pitch to Colorado's No. 8 hitter, Kirt Manwaring, was a wild
one that moved the runners to second and third. Manwaring rifled
Nomo's next pitch under the pitcher's glove, off the mound and into
center field to score one run and move Lansing to third.
</P>
<P>
   Before throwing another pitch, Nomo made a move toward first.
But Nomo had missed a sign from his first baseman. Olerud had
broken toward home, anticipating a Kile bunt attempt, and Nomo
balked to score Lansing and give the Rockies a 4-3 lead. Manwaring
took second on the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing shaken, Nomo fell behind Kile, 3-0. After running the
count to full on the pitcher, Nomo walked him. On the next pitch,
Darryl Hamilton pushed a bunt up the third-base line for an infield
hit.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded and nobody out, Valentine went out to the
mound. Nomo responded by inducing Neifi Perez into a fielder's
choice at second, as Manwaring scored to tie the score, 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   Another wild pitch on a 2-2 count to Larry Walker, and Perez
advanced to second as Kile stayed at third. Nomo rallied to strike
out Walker on a full-count forkball. But Bichette grounded a
two-run single between the pitcher's legs for a 6-4 lead, and that
was all for Nomo.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   One day after another strong outing by Armando Reynoso, Mets
Manager Bobby Valentine announced that he will go with his six-man
rotation until a pair of back-to-back doubleheaders with the
Cardinals at Shea Stadium on Aug. 20 and 21. ``It seems like, why
mess with it?'' Valentine said of his six-man experiment. ``This is
the best stretch we've had the whole year. Why should we change
anything?'' ... Greg McMichael left the team to be with his wife,
Jennifer, who is about to give birth to the couple's third child.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
