u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-SEX-SHOPS-NYT &LR;      08-09 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SEX-SHOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SHOWDOWN ON SEX SHOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Aug. 10:
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's crackdown on New York City's sex
industry has met a legal snag. Many adult video stores and strip
clubs are feverishly reconfiguring their businesses to limit the
amount of floor space and inventory devoted to X-rated
entertainment to under 40 percent. They claim that changes their
character enough to exempt them from new zoning restrictions on
pornography shops.
</P>
<P>
   It is a clever strategy. But the constitutionality of the new
zoning ordinance, and its worthy purpose of protecting communities
from the adverse impact of sex-related businesses, has been upheld
by both state and federal courts. It would be absurd to allow
subterfuges like a halfhearted display of suitcases and trinkets to
prevent its enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The new law bars ``adult establishments'' entirely in purely
residential neighborhoods and prevents their clustering into ``red
light'' districts in the commercial and manufacturing areas where
they are still allowed. Such businesses are prohibited from
operating within 500 feet of each other or within 500 feet of
residential buildings, schools and churches.
</P>
<P>
   The law defines a business as an ``adult establishment'' if it
devotes a ``substantial portion'' of its operation to adult
entertainment. Citing language in a City Planning Commission report
and court papers filed by the city to help the statute pass
constitutional muster, the pornography shops argue that they can be
treated as X-rated enterprises only if 40 percent or more of their
business is in adult materials.
</P>
<P>
   But, clearly, the 60-40 ratio was meant only as a general
guideline, not a mechanical test. It was intended to show that the
rules pose no threat to general interest book or video stores with
a relatively modest section of adult materials. Notably, the City
Planning report says a store should not escape regulation as an
``adult establishment'' simply by moving a large amount of adult
materials into a smaller amount of floor space.
</P>
<P>
   The city's authority to zone has firm constitutional standing.
If the courts find problems with the way this particular law is
being enforced, these problems can be remedied with appropriate
amendments by the mayor and City Council. Meanwhile, neither the
existing law nor the First Amendment should preclude city
inspectors from considering factors other than square footage in
determining whether a business is an adult establishment.
Meaningful enforcement calls for common sense, not just a tape
measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
