<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LEGAL-SERVICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LEGAL SERVICES IN JEOPARDY AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Aug. 10:
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the House Appropriations Committee might be
annoyed if you told them that they cared nothing for equal justice.
But there is no other way to explain their obsessive drive to
destroy the federal Legal Services Corp. and its ability to help
impoverished Americans with civil legal problems. For the third
consecutive year, the committee voted to cut the Legal Services
budget in half.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, a sufficient number of lawmakers rallied last week
to block the devastating cut on the House floor, as they have in
the past. Even so, the budget approved by the House includes just
$250 million for the program.
</P>
<P>
   That figure is less than the inadequate $283 million Congress
allocated for Legal Services last year and far short of the $340
million sought by the administration. The money is needed, among
other things, to help protect victims of domestic violence and
enforce child support orders against an absent parent.
</P>
<P>
   The House also made no move to repeal a ban on class-action
suits and other congressionally imposed restrictions that hinder
efficient and effective representation of Legal Services clients.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Legal Services decry its ``liberal agenda.'' But
its actual docket is dominated by cases involving housing,
benefits, consumer-credit disputes and domestic relations issues.
The purpose of this program is not to promote a political
philosophy but to broaden access to the justice system for indigent
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, at least, was more generous. Last month, it voted to
budget $300 million for Legal Services in the next fiscal year. The
issue now goes to a House-Senate conference committee. To provide
anything less than $300 million would harm both Legal Services and
the Republicans' reputation for fairness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0187 </DOCNO>
