u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BUS-'97CRASH-300&AMP;A     08-09 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUS-'97CRASH-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUS DRIVER IN FATAL 1997 CRASH WAS UNFIT TO DRIVE, PANEL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Transit officials knew that the bus driver involved
in a fatal crash on Fifth Avenue last year had a long history of
seizures and alcoholism but failed to take him off the road, in
violation of state law, a state panel has concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, Charles Alston, suffered a seizure moments before
the Oct. 2 crash, doctors have said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any serious review of his medical records should have resulted
in the conclusion that he was not medically qualified to drive a
bus,'' the State Public Transportation Safety Board said in a
report issued last week.
</P>
<P>
   The board urged New York City Transit and its parent agency, the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority, to review the medical
records of all bus drivers and subway and train operators, a
process that had already begun shortly after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The report, based on a review of New York City Transit's thick
medical file on Alston, found references to at least three
seizures, dating back to 1991. In all, Alston had missed 470 work
days from 1992 to 1997 due to illnesses ranging from cancer to
asthma to glaucoma.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the report said, the agency's doctors ignored an
internal order in 1994 to make sure that Alston was treated for
alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   State motor vehicle law forbids anyone suffering from alcoholism
or ``any condition which is likely to cause loss of consciousness''
to drive a bus.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 2, Alston lost control of his midtown bus for seven
blocks, plowing into several cars, critically injuring a bicyclist
and killing a foot messenger before crashing into a building. He
died 20 days later of illnesses unrelated to the crash, shortly
after a neurologist diagnosed epilepsy, which in adults is often
triggered by alcoholism.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After the accident, transit officials said that although Alston
had been suspended in 1983 for using morphine and in 1985 for using
alcohol, he had not tested positive for drugs or alcohol since
then. They added that he had denied having any seizures in his last
three annual physical exams.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board, however, found that New York City Transit had
extensive knowledge of Alston's health problems but followed a
disturbing pattern of taking him off the road for a while, then
declaring him fit to drive. From 1992, when Alston was treated for
a seizure attributed to alcohol withdrawal, until July 1997, he was
placed on restricted duty five times due to either seizures, losses
of consciousness or alcohol-related problems. But he was always
allowed back behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   If the agency had simply followed its own internal guidelines,
the report stated, ``this bus operator should have been removed to
a nonsafety-sensitive position, with a diagnosis of
alcoholism/alcohol dependence _ a diagnosis indicated in New York
City Transit medical records at least four times.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City Transit officials declined to comment on the
report Sunday, saying they had not finished reviewing it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-AR     08-09 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES PULL OUT ANOTHER WIN, 5-4, OVER ROYALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trying to teach instincts to a baseball player is
like trying to eat a bowl of soup with a fork: basically
impossible. You can try and try, but you will almost always be
unsuccessful. You have a spoon, or you do not. You have instincts,
or you do not.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter has excellent base-running instincts, and Ramiro
Mendoza has excellent pitching instincts. Because Jeter never
stopped running as he tried to steal second base in the eighth
inning, and because Mendoza has never treated his switch to the
bullpen as a demotion, the Yankees managed to steal a 5-4 victory
over the Royals on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The march toward history continued for the Yankees, who do not
think they should ever lose a game, and usually do not. Andy
Pettitte was listless in his first start in 10 days, following a
muscle strain in his left shoulder, and he dumped the Yankees in a
4-1 ditch after five and a half innings. The Yankees yawned,
realized they still had a game to win and delighted a Beanie Babies
crowd of 55,911 at Yankee Stadium by doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to win every time out,'' Jeter said. ``We know it's
not going to happen, but that doesn't mean we don't think we can do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, they did it again to sweep the four-game series from the
Royals while outscoring them, 41-9. The Yankees improved to a
ridiculous 84-29 for the season and a just-as-ridiculous 42-8 at
home. If anyone definitely expected the Yankees to rally against
Hipolito Pichardo and Kansas City's bullpen, it was the 25 Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along that we're not satisfied to just play
pretty well,'' said Scott Brosius, who homered for New York's first
run. ``There's a desire in all of us to win every game.''
</P>
<P>
   That desire manifested itself with one out in the eighth, after
Jeter walked on a 3-2 pitch with the score tied, 4-4. Jeter bolted
for second base on Scott Service's 1-0 pitch to Paul O'Neill, and
shrewdly looked back at the plate twice. He saw a wild pitch whiz
by Royals catcher Sal Fasano when he was about 20 feet from second,
so he never hesitated and cruised into third easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people said we were fortunate or lucky when we were
winning earlier in the season,'' Jeter said. ``I think you make
your own breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre raved about the critical play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got such great instincts,'' Torre said. ``Those are
things you can't teach. I'm sure that put pressure on. Now they
weren't allowed to allow us anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely. Service intentionally walked O'Neill to set up a
double play. But Bernie Williams looped a single to left center.
Had Jeter only taken second, he probably would not have scored on
the hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little things like that can win you a game or two during the
season,'' O'Neill said. ``Today, it did that for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Jeter's dash, Mendoza had replaced Pettitte with two outs
in the sixth inning and the Yankees behind, 4-1. After the Yankees
scored three runs in the bottom of the sixth on O'Neill's two-run
double and Williams' sacrifice fly, Mendoza was unhittable.
Mendoza, who was pushed to the bullpen by Orlando Hernandez's
success, was terrific in retiring seven of eight batters and
permitting only one ball to reach the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel mad about going to the bullpen,'' said Mendoza
(8-2). ``I'm still going to do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis will take batting practice at Yankee Stadium on
Monday before continuing his rehabilitation assignment at Class AAA
Columbus on Tuesday. . . . The crowd of 55,911 was the second
largest of the season, behind the 56,717 on opening day, and was
the 10th largest in the 23-year history of the remodeled Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
