<HEADER>
A5282 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROLLINS-MUSIC-REVIEW-     08-09 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROLLINS-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONNY ROLLINS: DISCOURSE WITH TANTALIZING TANGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sonny Rollins could hardly wait to start improvising
when he arrived with his tenor saxophone onstage at the Damrosch
Park Band Shell on Saturday night. Before Rollins finished his
first tune, ``Biji,'' he was already darting away from it with
quick asides and looping runs, following impulses he was eager to
share.
</P>
<P>
   Commanding, whimsical, unpredictable and telling, those impulses
made for a set that transcended jazz factionalism through sheer
force of personality.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins was mainstream and avant-garde, abstruse and basic,
conservative and anarchic, uncompromising and crowd-pleasing. The
free concert, presented by Lincoln Center Out of Doors, drew an
audience that overflowed the park.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins' structures were old fashioned. The set included
standards, modal tunes, altered blues and calypsos, and each
selection used the theme-solos-theme form.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Anderson on trombone and Stephen Scott on piano played
their solos with urbane intelligence, swinging over the beat and
tracing linear narratives, keeping the music tonal and genial. Bob
Cranshaw on electric bass, Perry Wilson on drums and Victor
See-Yuen on percussion provided sure, easygoing support, despite
some clutter from See-Yuen.
</P>
<P>
   And while the rest of the group played within mainstream rules,
Rollins rocketed past them. Jazz is often compared to conversation,
but Rollins had two discussions simultaneously: a witty discourse
on the tunes and, bursting out between the lines, all kinds of
alternatives and extrapolations and tangents, the stream of musical
consciousness behind a typical solo's judicious phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins kept touching down on the melodies, as if knocking on
wood, then streaking out to the further reaches of harmony and
speed. He played breakneck lines that zigzagged through all kinds
of chordal convolutions; he skipped up to high, hooting notes and
an occasional overblown squeal, then dived down to foghorn honks.
Unlike David Murray, whose solos turn into ecstatic glossolalia,
Rollins made his seem like spectacular introspections and private
dares.
</P>
<P>
   Rollins treated standards, including ``They Say It's Wonderful''
and ``More Than You Know,'' with jocular affection. He moved the
original melodies around the beat and gently mocked romantic
declarations with exaggerated vibrato or an extra edge in his
sound. His saxophone crooned the melodies of his own ballads,
including selections from his latest album, ``Global Warming''
(Milestone), and a new song written for the concert,
``Homecoming.'' The bluesy ``Clear-Cut Boogie'' ended with a
repeated riff in a decrescendo until Rollins, true to the
ecological titles on the album, declared, ``And then there were no
more trees left.''
</P>
<P>
   But the tours de force were the calypsos: just three chords and
endless possibilities. Rollins put dissonant tags on cheerful
melodic hooks; he toyed with snake-charmer scales and nasal bagpipe
tones; he cartwheeled through arpeggios and spiraled through
harmonic transformations; then returned to the tune as if nothing
had happened. It was the sound of a master deep in thought and
equally deeply at play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
