<HEADER>
A5285 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOXWORTHY-COX     08-09 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOXWORTHY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Foxworthy at peace with God
 &HT;    Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Comic Jeff Foxworthy confided before a throng of 4,000
Sunday night, including Gov. Zell Miller, that talking about his
faith was outside his ``comfort zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The nationally-known comic who's trademark ``redneck'' humor has
made him rich and famous said he discovered after returning home to
Georgia that what was missing in his life was ``inner peace,'' and
no amount of fame and fortune could make up for that.
</P>
<P>
   In a 45-minute address at Roswell High School in north Atlanta,
laced with Bible verses and spiced with his trademark crackerbelt
humor (''When I was a kid one of my uncles wrote on our mailbox the
word M-A-L-E. About the time I was a junior in high school I
thought ``You know, that ain't right. The ``M'' should be
capitalized''), Foxworthy talked about his conversion that, he
said, was really more like ``coming home again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was seven years old I gave my life to Christ,'' said
Foxworthy, who now lives in Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never turned my back on him. But I didn't walk with him... I
started drifting away because I didn't have momma waking me up on
Sunday morning making me go to church.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the crowd _ which ranged in age from infants to seniors,
and from devoted Christians to devoted Foxworthy fans _ didn't
quite know what to expect from the comic who had yet to talk
publicly about his newfound faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen him perform,'' said Karen Sledge, 30, of
Marietta, Ga. ``I came out here expecting to laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Miller, his arms propped on a bannister in the back of the
high school's gym, and without his usual entourage, said he's
always been a fan of Foxworthy and wanted to bring his grandson
Justin Miller along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff's one of Georgia's greatest treasures,'' said the
governor. ``I like all of his stuff . . . I 'm glad that he's back
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Foxworthy, wearing a beige golf shirt, black jeans and cowboy
boots, appeared nervous at first, but quickly loosed up as he began
discussing his life and career and his connection with God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to say if I could make $100,000 a year, I wouldn't have
a problem in the world,'' he said. ``I had nights where I've made
that much. But I found out I wasn't a bit happier than when I
started out and was making $20 a month . . . Since I have decided
to walk with God, it has changed my entire life,'' he said. ``It
has helped me curb my anger, it has helped me live my life with
more ease.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech was sponsored by Fellowship Bible Church in Roswell.
``He just wants to tell people some of what god's doing in his
life,'' said the church's assistant pastor, Paul Pridemore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to do a lot of it because he wants his privacy.
But he loves God and he wanted to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Foxworthy revealed that after his sitcom was cancelled and he
was preparing to return to Atlanta, he told his wife Gregg, ``I
might be a preacher.'' She was dumbfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``She looked at me kind of like a cow looks at a new gate,'' he
said, ``and said that great Southern word: 'Dowhat?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
