<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-O'MEARA-830&AMP;ADD-N     08-09 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-O'MEARA-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNINTIMIDATED BY SUCCESS, O'MEARA TAKES AIM AT THIRD MAJOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winning the Masters and the British Open in the same year should
at least make you the most recognized golfer in your city. But Mark
O'Meara is not even the most recognized person in his neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara lives in Windemere, Fla., outside Orlando, in the same
community with Tiger Woods and Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   But while Woods and Griffey are better at making headlines,
O'Meara has quietly been making history. He enters this week's PGA
Championship at Sahalee Country Club in Redmond, Wash., with a
chance to win three majors in the same year. No man has done that
since 1953, when Ben Hogan won the Masters, the U.S. Open and the
British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Golf's spotlight has finally found its way to O'Meara, an
unassuming 41-year-old family man who has replaced Woods as the
neighborhood's hottest golfer. The turn of events was unexpected.
O'Meara had enjoyed a solid career before this year, winning 14
tournaments on the PGA Tour and 20 tournaments worldwide. But he
had never won a major.
</P>
<P>
   Now, O'Meara has reached his peak at an age when others are
reaching for Nuprin. His success is testament to what can happen
when talent, temperament and experience merge. Yet, if someone had
told O'Meara in January that he would have a chance to win his
third major by August, what would he have said?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have believed it,'' O'Meara said last week in a
telephone interview from his home.
</P>
<P>
   He believes it now. And despite his modesty, O'Meara is not
intimidated by the attention he will face this week as he tries for
a triple-major year, something that such great golfers as Jack
Nicklaus and Arnold Palmer never achieved. To prepare for the PGA
Championship, O'Meara spent the weekend in Park City, Utah, with
his longtime coach, Hank Haney, golfing, fishing, and fine-tuning
his game. O'Meara has never seen Sahalee, a picturesque course
outside Seattle featuring narrow, tree-lined fairways that put a
premium on accuracy off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara has been cautious not to let the anticipation hurt his
preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm approaching this the same way I always do, wanting to play
well enough to give myself the opportunity to win,'' O'Meara said.
``If I don't play well, I can live with it. It has already been a
special year. And I think it's pretty neat that a 41-year-old guy
is showing that the older guys can still play the game a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo was the last man who arrived at the PGA Championship
with a chance to win his third major in one year. But after winning
the Masters and the British Open in 1990, Faldo finished tied for
19th at the PGA. O'Meara hopes to do better, and he will be
well-rested. He has not played in a tournament since last month's
British Open at Royal Birkdale, when he won a four-hole playoff
against Brian Watts.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara's success does not surprise Haney. Their relationship
started in 1982, when O'Meara was a young golfer from southern
California, struggling to make a living. It was late in the season,
and O'Meara was 124th on the money list, needing to finish in the
top 125 to keep his tour card. After working with Haney, O'Meara
made the next three cuts and kept his card. Haney said that 16
years later, O'Meara remains as dedicated to the game as he was the
day of their first lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing that makes Mark special is that his mental
attitude is as good as it has ever been,'' Haney said. ``That's
pretty impressive, when you're talking about a guy who's 41.
Hanging around guys like Tiger and Ken Griffey is a part of that.
You can learn a lot hanging around champions, guys who are that
competitive, guys who are pushing you. Tiger and Mark played golf
in Orlando before the British Open, and Mark shot a 63. He lost.
Tiger shot a 62. That's not a bad way to get ready.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that O'Meara has played the best golf of
his career since Woods joined the tour in the summer of '96. Woods
and O'Meara, who are both represented by International Management
Group, became fast friends. Woods, who won the Masters at age 21,
was looking for a place to live after turning professional, and
O'Meara sold him on the Orlando area, with its warm climate and
lack of state income tax. Other tour players, such as Scott Hoch,
Payne Stewart and Lee Janzen, the reigning U.S. Open champion, also
live near O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   Woods looks up to O'Meara for his experience, and O'Meara is
fueled by Woods' fire. The day after the British Open, O'Meara and
Woods flew home together, and as soon as it was safe to take off
their seat belts, Woods wanted to see the claret jug, the trophy
given to the British Open winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Tiger he'd have his name on that trophy one day,
probably a few times,'' O'Meara said. ``He's got plenty of time.''
</P>
<P>
   But for O'Meara, that chance was a long time coming. ``I finally
realized I didn't have to play perfect golf to win a major.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Haney believes O'Meara has always had the game for a major
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hardly anybody has a game suited for all four majors, and it's
hard to win any of them,'' Haney said. ``I always thought Mark
would win a British Open, because his lower ball flight and
accuracy are suited for playing over there. But Mark always had
what it takes. He doesn't have too many easy victories in his
career, but when he has a chance to win, he usually closes the
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, O'Meara has been a better deal-closer than Donald
Trump. He did not lead the Masters until the final hole, but he
rallied from three strokes down with four holes to play to defeat
Fred Couples and David Duval by one stroke, clinching the victory
with a 20-foot birdie putt on No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Only certain players make putts like that. Ask players on tour
to name the game's best pressure putters, and it will not be long
before you hear O'Meara's name. That ability to find the bottom of
the cup makes O'Meara extremely dangerous when he is in contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say I was certain I'd make that putt at
Augusta, but I had a pretty good read on it, and I felt
confident,'' O'Meara said. ``That was quite a way to win my first
major.''
</P>
<P>
   But the British Open was just as dramatic, as O'Meara prevailed
over a world-class field in windy, chilly conditions that tested
every part of a player's game. Once again, O'Meara never led until
the final round. Then, after finishing the 72d hole at even par, he
waited behind the 18th green with his wife, Alicia, and their two
children, Michelle, 11, and Shaun, 8, as Watts played the final
hole. It was great theater, as Watts made one of the great shots in
British Open history to force a playoff with O'Meara, hitting a
difficult greenside bunker shot to within six inches of the cup to
save par.
</P>
<P>
   Showing his class, O'Meara applauded the shot. Showing his
toughness, O'Meara dominated the playoff, setting the tone with a
birdie on the first hole and winning by two strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But just because nobody expected him to win two majors this
year, O'Meara says he see no reason to be intimidated by the
magnitude of what he could accomplish this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to have a chance to win three majors in the same year is
pretty special,'' O'Meara said. ``When the year starts, you really
can't expect anyone to be in that position. I'm just happy to have
the chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
