<HEADLINE>
IN BROOKLYN, LONGTIME FRIENDS BECOME POLITICAL ADVERSARIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They were not merely up-and-coming officials from the
same Brooklyn neighborhood, but kindred politicians close enough to
have been the best of friends for years. Over nightcaps in
neighborhood bars, they planned their political futures. They
worked on each other's campaigns. They went to family reunions
together and even, at times, vacationed together.
</P>
<P>
   But now, in one of the odd twists that are often part of
politics, the two officials, Assemblyman Darryl Towns and City
Councilman Martin Malave Dilan, have become political adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   Towns, 37, is in a heated Democratic primary for re-election to
a seat he won in 1992, representing the northern Brooklyn
neighborhoods of Bushwick and Cypress Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Dilan, 47, who was elected to the council in 1991, is running
against him. It is a race in which Towns has had to defend his
record, presenting himself as a vigilant advocate for his district
as Dilan has offered a dissenting view and the promise of ``a more
active presence in Albany and in the district.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The current Assemblyman has been an absentee Assemblyman,''
Dilan said of his former confidant. ``Many of the people in the
district, if they were to see his face, would not know who he is.
In fact, I think he has been in a holding pattern waiting for Daddy
to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Towns' father, U.S. Rep. Edolphus Towns. The
younger Towns' relationship with the Democratic Party organization
in Brooklyn adds another layer of complexity to the race for the
Democratic nomination for the Assembly seat. The contest between
Dilan and Towns is widely seen as an extension of a feud between
Assemblyman Clarence Norman Jr., the Brooklyn Democratic chairman,
and the younger Towns.
</P>
<P>
   Norman and the elder Towns, once close friends themselves, have
become bitter political adversaries, a result of disagreements over
endorsements. When the younger Towns decided to support Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, a Republican, in last year's mayoral contest,
Norman announced that the Democratic organization would no longer
support the congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Dilan had planned to run for Congress,
against Rep. Nydia Velazquez, a fellow Democrat. But last month,
Dilan, a close ally of Norman, announced that he could not raise
enough money to topple the popular congresswoman. Instead, he
announced his candidacy for the Assembly seat held by the younger
Towns.
</P>
<P>
   Both Norman and Dilan say they are not involved in any plan to
injure the Towns family.
</P>
<P>
   ``One might have that perception,'' Norman said. ``But I want to
make it perfectly clear that the county organization is neutral.
Despite the fact that I have some differences with the father, it
has nothing to do with my relationship with the son. There is no
backdoor support to Darryl's opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all are convinced, however. ``He's neutral against an
incumbent?'' the younger Towns asked. ``I find that strange,
because the incumbent usually enjoys the Democratic organization's
support.'' The race in the 54th Assembly District is also marked by
ethnic issues. Towns, who is black, and Dilan, who is Puerto Rican,
are running in a district that is predominantly Hispanic. And one
of Dilan's campaign themes is that it is time for the district to
send a Hispanic Assemblyman to Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 census showed the Assembly district as 66 percent
Hispanic, 24 percent black, 5 percent white and 3 percent Asian,
and demographers say the Hispanic population has since grown to
more than 70 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
