<SLUG> BC-PBP-SMOKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Truth Train' pulls into South Florida
 &HT;    By Mary Warejcka
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, FLA. _ Rebellion isn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   After all, not long ago teens were defying authority by
``smokin' in the boys' room,'' instead of applauding an
anti-smoking campaign, as a couple hundred teens did in West Palm
Beach Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They call it a rebellion against corporate tobacco. The fight
against cigarette makers is literally rolling through the state on
a train from Pensacola to Miami. They call it a campaign for
``truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Their message is simple: Smoking kills so don't start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoking just draws too much from the heart and what you love
to do,'' explains Joshua Johnson, a West Palm Beach 18-year-old who
got on the train at Tampa. ``Like they say, kissing a smoker is
like kissing an ashtray.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also denounces smoking in TV and radio ads that are part
of the statewide effort to curb smoking in teens. The campaign is
being paid for with part of the $11 billion settlement that tobacco
companies offered last year.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 kids got off the train at the West Palm Beach station
at 201 S. Tamarind Ave. Some will stay and others will jump on the
train to travel south to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Lawton Chiles also has popped on the train for parts of the
trip. He rode from Okeechobee to town Saturday. As he gave credit
to the teens for coming up with the campaign, a petition for movie
executives was passed around.
</P>
<P>
   It asks movie makers to stop glamorizing cigarette smoking,
saying that while only 25 percent of ``real people'' smoke, 75
percent of TV characters light up.
</P>
<P>
   Another anti-smoking organization GROSS, Get Rid of Student
Smoking, had an early afternoon outpost at Boynton Beach Ocean
Park. The organization is midway through a two-week campaign of
daily stops from Miami to Vero Beach aboard a retired fire engine.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsors paid for giveaways at the truck including
Surge soft drinks, water bottles, drink holders and stacks of
T-shirts that read, in part: ``Surgeon General's Warning: Smoking
won't make you sexy or rich. Smoking won't make you cool. Smoking
makes you die.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to get teenagers not to smoke,'' said 12-year-old
Nick Banko of Boynton Beach after coming up to the fire engine and
putting on a free T-shirt. ``I hate smoking. My dad smokes. I bug
him about it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
