<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WEIL-631-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDRE WEIL, 92, MATHEMATICS PIONEER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa., Ill, Japan, Brazil)  (ll) 
 By FORD BURKHART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andre Weil, a former professor at the Institute for Advanced
Study in Princeton, N.J., whose work in algebraic geometry and
number theory recast the basics of mathematics, died on Thursday at
his home in Princeton. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   At the institute, Weil was considered an intellectual peer of
colleagues who were among the century's most influential scholars:
Albert Einstein, J. Robert Oppenheimer, the mathematician John von
Neumann and the logician Kurt Godel among them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Weil (pronounced VAY) won the equivalent of the Nobel
Prize, which is not awarded in mathematics, when he received the
Kyoto Prize in Basic Science from the Inamori Foundation of Kyoto,
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   That award honored the part of his work known as the Weil
conjectures, which provided the principles for modern algebraic
geometry. The patterns of numbers that Weil discovered are now
applied, for example, in writing almost-unbreakable secret codes
and in enhancing the accurate transmission of computer data.
</P>
<P>
   Other applications of his work can be found in elementary
particle physics and in encryption and computer security.
</P>
<P>
   But such practical applications were far from Weil's mind, said
Phillip Griffiths, director of the institute and a mathematician.
Griffiths said Weil had provided answers to some of the most subtle
questions about ordinary numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will certainly be remembered as one of the giants of
mathematics of all times,'' Griffiths said. Beyond that, he added,
Weil was a scholar and historian and was fluent in languages _ ``in
Sanskrit, in Persian, you name it.''
</P>
<P>
   He introduced ideas of topology _ the study of geometric figures
_ into arithmetic, permanently changing the way scholars study the
science of computing by numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Weil, born in 1906 in Paris, became devoted to mathematics in
his early teens and received his doctorate from the University of
Paris in 1928. His thesis solved a problem concerning elliptic
curves that had been posed by the mathematician and philosopher
Henri Poincare.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, Weil rejected the avant-garde circles of Paris and
instead went off to India to study its culture and to teach. In
India, he taught at Aligarh University from 1930 to 1932, then
returned to France to teach at Marseille University and Strasbourg
University until 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Weil was a founder of the influential Bourbaki, a group of
French mathematicians who rebelled against the French establishment
and whose original writings from the 1930s unified all of
mathematical knowledge for the first time. The Bourbaki remain
highly influential in the field to this day.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the draft, he went to Finland. ``As a soldier,'' he
said, ``I would be entirely useless, but as a mathematician I could
be of some use.'' The Finns returned him to the French, who
imprisoned him for six months.
</P>
<P>
   In prison, he created the Riemann hypothesis _ named for a
German mathematician _ and it became a basic element of number
theory and is regarded as one of his most insightful mathematical
achievements, Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Weil later joined the French Army to earn his release from
prison, then came to the United States to teach at Haverford
College in Pennsylvania. He taught at the University of Chicago
from 1947 to 1958, and at the University of Sao Paulo in Brazil
from 1945 to 1947.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Institute for Advanced Study in 1958. After he
retired from there in 1976, he wrote on mathematics and edited
works by Jacques Bernoulli and Pierre de Fermat, two French giants
in mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Eveline, died in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Weil is survived by two daughters, Nicolette Schwartzman of
Princeton and Sylvie Weil Weitzner of New York City, and three
grandchildren. His younger sister, the philosopher Simone Weil,
died in England in 1943.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
