<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWESTERN-RUSSELL-ACQUIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHWESTERN MUTUAL LIFE DEAL EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Wash.)  (lb) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Northwestern Mutual Life Insurance Co. of Milwaukee, the United
States' fourth-largest mutual insurer, is expected to announce as
early as Monday that it will acquire Frank Russell Co., one of the
nation's largest pension-fund advisory firms and the compiler of
the widely followed Russell 2000 index of small-company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern is expected to pay about $1 billion for Russell,
based on recent prices for asset management companies, but
spokesmen for the two companies declined to comment on the
transaction Sunday night. According to people close to the
companies, negotiations had continued through the weekend and were
close to completion Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern, which is owned by its policyholders and dominates
the personal life-insurance market, has been on the sidelines in
recent years as other insurance companies have expanded into
broader areas of financial services. But it had hinted for months
that it was seeking an acquisition that would extend its reach
beyond its basic business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most big life-insurance companies have bought into asset
management,'' said Michael Frinquelli, a partner in Renaissance
Fund Advisors, a hedge fund specializing in insurance stocks.
``This is Northwestern's initial shot, and it is a big one.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Russell, a family-controlled company based in Tacoma,
Wash., would certainly offer Northwestern a broad footprint in the
financial services field. Besides its pension advisory work, it
markets mutual funds, private investment advisory services and
institutional brokerage services, in the United States and 25 other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which had revenue of $305 million last year, is
controlled by George F. Russell Jr., its chairman and a grandson of
its founder, and members of his family.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell family owns approximately 60 percent of the company,
with the remaining 40 percent owned by its approximately 1,400
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the deal were first published on the World Wide Web
site of The Financial Times over the weekend. But some transaction
involving Russell has been expected since early this summer, when
Russell confirmed that the company had engaged Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
to advise it on estate-planning options.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Bloomberg News in June, Russell, 65, said
that the company's fortunes had risen sharply in recent years and
that he wanted to make sure that no crisis would arise if something
should happen to him or his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The company, founded in 1936 as a small mutual fund and
brokerage company, is a brand name in the lucrative but highly
competitive pension-fund world.
</P>
<P>
   Besides managing about $40 billion directly, it advises a long
list of blue-chip corporate pension funds, including those of AT&AMP;T
and J.C. Penney, on asset allocation and the selection and
evaluation of money managers.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition would give Northwestern, which has assets of $71
billion, an overnight presence in foreign markets. Russell has been
aggressive in forming joint ventures to develop and market mutual
funds to serve specific foreign markets. In March, for example, it
announced that it had joined with Societe Generale in Paris to
market mutual funds to its European customers. It has similar
relationships in Australia, Canada and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Russell created and maintains the Russell
stock-market indexes, the best known of which is the Russell 2000
index of small-company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also created market indexes for investors in
Australia, Canada, Japan and Britain. Worldwide, more than $850
billion is invested in index funds that track these Russell market
benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, if completed, would be the third acquisition of an
asset management company by a financial giant in recent months,
coming on the heels of Mellon Bank's purchase of Newton Investment
Management and Merrill Lynch's acquisition of Mercury Asset
Management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
