<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-VICTIMS-U.S.-2     08-09 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-VICTIMS-U.S.-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFILES OF 6 AMERICAN VICTIMS OF THE KENYA BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Ga., Fla., Va., Ind., Ala., Mo., Calif.)  (See also: AFRICA-BOMBINGS, AFRICA-VICTIMS, AFRICA-EMBASSY,
AFRICA-U.S., AFRICA-EVACUATE, AFRICA-TANZANIA) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They hardly thought of themselves as heroes. Some were clerks,
some were service personnel. Others were specialists in politics,
health or international aid programs. But they were also people who
loved music or dance, appreciated exotic lands and cultural
differences, liked tending a garden or studying Swahili. They were
sons and daughters, parents and siblings.
</P>
<P>
   And on Sunday the families, friends and colleagues of some of
the 12 Americans who died in the bombing of the American Embassy in
Nairobi, Kenya, spoke of them as heroes of a sort: They had come
from Georgia and Missouri, Indiana and Florida and other places,
and they were in Nairobi as Americans who wanted to work for their
country. As Kenneth Hobson Sr. said of his dead son: ``Anybody who
wears the uniform is a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the six victims profiled here, the victims included
Prabhi Kavaler, a Foreign Service officer; Julian Bartley, the
American consul general in Nairobi;, his son, Jay Bartley; Tom
Shah, of the embassy's political section; Jean Dalizu, of the
defense attache's office, and Michelle O'Connor, of the general
services office.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Louise Martin, epidemiologist
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mary Louise Martin, 45, an epidemiologist who had worked for
the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta for more
than a decade, had been in Nairobi for three years and had recently
begun work on a pilot project there to treat children suffering
from drug-resistant strains of malaria.
</P>
<P>
   Like many expatriates in Kenya, Dr. Martin went regularly to the
U.S. Embassy in Nairobi to change money and shop at the commissary
for hard-to-find American products. She was there on Friday when
the bomb exploded.
</P>
<P>
   A native of New Orleans and the mother of three children, aged
14, 11 and 10, Dr. Martin studied veterinary medicine at Louisiana
State University, but friends and associates said she found her
true calling in research to improve the well-being of children.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985 she joined the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, and after two years of epidemiological training, she
embarked on eight years of research on birth defects, particularly
congenital heart defects, officials of the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Martin's husband, Dr. Douglas Klaucke, also was employed by
the Atlanta centers. Associates said both stood out for their
commitment and empathy. ``These are kind, loving, warm people,''
said Dr. Stephen Blount, the agency's associate director for global
health. ``They're not just regular doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jose Cordero, deputy director of national immunization
programs at the centers, said of Dr. Martin: ``She was very bright
and was always willing to step in when there was a challenge. She
was very, very outgoing, always happy, had a wonderful smile. She
was born in New Orleans and had this combination of Southern charm
and grace.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Douglas Klaucke was assigned to Kenya to work in a
polio immunization program for the World Health Organization. Dr.
Martin gave up her job with the Atlanta centers and the family
moved to Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Martin concentrated at first on resettling her children,
then did volunteer veterinary work at an animal orphanage and field
work for the World Health Organization as it battled an outbreak of
fever in northern Kenya. An avid reader and kayaker, Dr. Martin
also acquired a working knowledge of Swahili.
</P>
<P>
   Klaucke recently signed up for another tour of two to three
years in Kenya, and Dr. Martin resumed the career she had set aside
to move to Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   She began working several months ago for the Atlanta-based Task
Force for Child Survival and Development, becoming associate
director of a program that provides a new drug, Malarone, for
victims of malaria who have shown resistance to other drug
therapies.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had enormous drive and the interpersonal skills and talent
to work with anyone,'' Walter Dowdle, director of programs for the
task force, said. ``She had this incredible ability to get down on
the level of children and relate to them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't believe it's real,'' said Dr. Martin's sister,
Susan Bryson, of Lawrenceville, Ga. ``The only thing, she died in a
country she loved. She died doing the things she liked. She's left
behind so many people who loved her.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Nathanael Aliganga, Marine sergeant
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Nathanael Aliganga had left his Florida roots far behind.
At only 21, he was a U.S. Marine security guard at the embassy,
where he was on duty Friday morning when the bomb blast took his
life. ``He died serving his country,'' said Capt. Landon Hutchens,
a Marine Corps public affairs officer.
</P>
<P>
   Aliganga had been at the embassy since late February, when he
completed Marine Security Guard School at Quantico, Va. The three
years since he enlisted, in January 1995, had been a whirlwind of
constant motion: recruit training at Parris Island, S.C.; combat
training at Camp Lejeune, N.C.; training as a communications
specialist at the Marine Air Ground Combat Center in Twenty-Nine
Palms, Calif.; Keesler Air Force Base in Biloxi, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   From there, he had gone on to postings in Okinawa, Japan and
Camp Pendleton, Calif., where he was selected for guard duty.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Lynn Olds, Air Force master sergeant
</P>
<P>
   Following in her father's footsteps, Sherry Lynn Olds had
enlisted in the Air Force right out of high school, hoping to see
the world, and she did.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Sgt. Olds, 40, spent two months in
Birmingham, Ala., taking courses to qualify for a promotion to
chief master sergeant. She was expected to receive her promotion in
a few months.
</P>
<P>
   During her course work in Alabama, Sgt. Olds also spent a week
at home in Panama City, Fla., with her parents, Delbert, now a
retired civil servant, and Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a beautiful girl,'' said her aunt, Pat Casey. ``She
was very special to her parents.''
</P>
<P>
   After she went to Nairobi, she shipped African jewelry, amber,
carved wooden games and other presents home to her family.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the day two Air Force officers arrived with the
devastating news of their daughter's death, her parents received a
flimsy letter from Sherry in Africa. Inside the envelope was a
Post-It sticker. It said, ``Will e-mail you soon.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
