<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5306 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-VICTIMS-U.S.-2     08-09 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-VICTIMS-U.S.-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: you soon.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Molly Huckaby Hardy, administrative worker
</P>
<P>
   Molly Huckaby Hardy, 51, a career State Department employee from
Valdosta, Ga., had worked in Foreign Service posts around the world
_ in Asia, South America and Africa _ for more than 25 years.
Friends said she had always loved the adventure of life abroad, of
tasting other cultures and traveling to exotic places.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department described her only as an ``administrative
worker,'' and friends and family members said they never knew what
she actually did for the government. ``We never pried, we never
asked,'' said Marsha Bates, a longtime friend. ``She could have
been doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Divorced and the mother of a grown daughter, Ms. Hardy was
keenly interested in theater and dance, and involved herself in
community theater projects at many of her overseas postings, which
included Laos, Vietnam and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Not long before her death in the terrorist explosion at the
embassy, Ms. Hardy sent home letters and photographs detailing her
work remodeling her home there and turning a small plot of ground
into a beautiful garden. ``She just loved being there, I think,''
Ms. Bates said. ``She found East Africa a beautiful place.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were also hints in recent letters to friends and
relatives that her wanderlust was waning. She said she planned to
return to the United States, possibly next June, to work as an
instructor for State Department employees.
</P>
<P>
   A 1964 graduate of Valdosta High School, Molly Huckaby worked
for several years as a clerk at a local newspaper, where her father
was the advertising manager. She then attended Valdosta State
College before completing her undergraduate studies at a college in
the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, while working in Washington, she married
William Hardy of Jacksonville, Fla., who worked for the State
Department. Soon Ms. Hardy, too, was employed in the Foreign
Service. In Laos in 1973, Ms. Hardy became pregnant and was ordered
home, and her daughter was born in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The couple divorced in the late 1970s. Ms. Hardy continued her
Foreign Service career. About eight years ago, she bought a home in
McLean, Va., now occupied by her daughter, Brandi Plant.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hardy was last in the United States in April 1997, to attend
the funeral of her sister, Patti Sanders, 46, who was killed in
Georgia in a head-on collision with a truck. She also visited her
newborn and only grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Hardy had occasionally had brushes with danger _ a
plane she missed went down in South Africa several months ago _ her
posting in Nairobi was not considered perilous. ``It was not a
high-risk facility,'' Ms. Bates said. ``And it was not a high risk
job. We never dreamed _ and she never dreamed, I'm sure _ that it
would come to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Arlene Kirk, Air Force budget officer
</P>
<P>
   After 25 years in Africa, Arlene Kirk, 50, a native of South
Bend, Ind., who flew into Nairobi early Friday morning after a
six-week stay in the United States, had been looking forward to
going home for good next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bitter pill to swallow,'' said her sister, Katherine
Wright, from South Bend.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of six children, Ms. Kirk attended business school
at Indiana University, where she met her husband, Robert. After
graduation, the two moved to South Africa, where Kirk taught
democratic principles to township mayors. Later, the couple worked
for the federal government in various positions in Botswana and
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Kirks moved to Nairobi with their son
Robbie Jr., now 14. Ms. Kirk was a budget officer for the Air
Force. Her husband, 50, is a project development officer for the
U.S. Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
   Their oldest child, Maisha, 23, attends Tuskegee University in
Alabama. The couple lost a young daughter, Kamilah, to cancer in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   While at home in South Bend, Ms. Kirk cared for her parents,
Frederick Arthur, 84, and Mary, 83, taking them to the doctor and
trying to enroll them in exercise classes. She and her husband had
planned to extend their stay at home for several days, Ms. Wright
said, but Ms. Kirk worried that her bosses wanted her back at work
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   En route to Nairobi, their flight from Amsterdam was overbooked,
and the Kirks decided to give up their seats in exchange for some
money and a free night's stayover. But they were too late; other
passengers had volunteered. They got on the flight, arriving early
Friday morning in Kenya. Ms. Kirk rushed to get to work.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hobson Jr., Army sergeant and aide to defense attache
</P>
<P>
   In the two small Missouri towns where he grew up, Sgt. Kenneth
Hobson Jr., 27, an aide to the defense attache at the embassy, was
remembered Sunday as a young man with a dream.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives said the sergeant regarded military life as an
adventure and intended to make a career of it.
</P>
<P>
   In Nevada, Mo., friends remembered Kenny Ray Hobson as a
talented and popular high school youth who played tennis, went
hiking, appeared in school plays, cooked gourmet meals, loved to
debate world affairs and had a taste for adventure that could not
be slaked in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   He was the son of a Vietnam War veteran, and after graduating
from Nevada High School in 1989, he joined the Army. What followed
were assignments to various posts in the United States and abroad:
to Germany, to the Persian Gulf during the 1991 war with Iraq and,
after Arabic language school in California, to Kenya last winter.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Deborah, a fellow Army enlistee, was mustered out
after their daughter, Meghan, was born two years ago. When Hobson
went into military intelligence training at Fort Gordon, Ga., and
in Washington, his wife and child lived for a time with his parents
in Lamar, Mo. But they accompanied him to Nairobi when he was
posted there last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Lake Tahoe, Calif., on May 1, 1971, he was taken to
western Missouri by his parents when he was small. He attended
schools in Lamar, a town of 4,000, until the fourth grade. Then the
family moved to Nevada, 25 miles away, a community of 9,000, where
he finished secondary school.
</P>
<P>
   The family moved back to Lamar after he graduated. His father is
now a dispatcher in the Barton County Sheriff's Department.
</P>
<P>
   Before going to Africa, said his mother, Bonnie Hobson, Hobson
was given a choice of four other assignments, all close to home.
But he chose the more exotic assignment in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   While he was listed as an administrative specialist at the
embassy, he told his parents he was not allowed to talk much about
his job, and they did not press him. They said he planned vaguely
to retire after 20 years of service, and then to attend culinary
school and perhaps open a bed and breakfast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
