<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5307 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMB-NAIROBI-BOS &LR;      08-09 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-NAIROBI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUE EFFORT CONTINUES IN NAIROBI, DAR ES SALAAM
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS   AND ANDREA USEEM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI _ While US officials tried to quell speculation about
who launched attacks on two American embassies in Africa, a tense
drama played out in Nairobi Sunday as Israeli soldiers and Kenyan
volunteers tried to extricate a dying woman from rubble at the site
of the more powerful bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
   As the rescue effort in Tanzania and Kenya entered its third day
and the official death toll climbed to 210 _ 200 in Nairobi and 10
in Dar es Salaam _ the Israelis, trained to deal with urban
terrorist attacks and equipped with hydraulic lifts, tried to free
a woman known only as Rose from the wreckage of Ufundi Cooperative
House, which housed a secretarial school and small offices.
</P>
<P>
   The effort was complicated by the need to use heavy earth-moving
equipment to excavate blocks of concrete without toppling the
remaining portions of the unstable building, and by the late
afternoon the woman had not been saved.
</P>
<P>
   The dead included 12 Americans, all in Nairobi. The 12th
American victim was identified Sunday as Consul General Julian
Bartley, whose son, Jay, a university student, also was
killed. &UR;  &LR; Dozens more people are believed missing and probably dead
in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   In both cities, the rescuers used bulldozers to clear debris,
pausing at times to let technicians with sensitive devices listen
for the cries of anyone trapped amid the jumble of cement, glass,
wires, and metal pipes.
</P>
<P>
   There was a rare moment of joy in the cordoned-off rescue area
in Nairobi when Israeli soldiers emerged from the twisted metal and
shattered glass of the Ufundi building with two survivors, a woman
and her son, who had escaped the blast unhurt. The two, who were
not immediately identified, had been too shocked and frightened to
walk down the 21 flights.
</P>
<P>
   On the eastern side of Ufundi house, a bulldozer scooped
concrete and loose papers and dumped the loads into a truck. At
first glance, it could have been a construction site in a crowded
downtown, but along with the detritus, several mangled bodies were
pulled from the wreckage and loaded into a Red Cross truck.
</P>
<P>
   Among those survivors watching with a mixed sense of relief and
unease was Aurelio Rebelo, a lawyer who barely escaped from his
office in Ufundi Cooperative House when it collapsed Friday
morning. ``I lost everything,'' said Rebelo, who escaped by
squeezing out of a first-floor balcony and scaling blasted-out
windows of a neighboring building. ``My entire library, all my
records.''
</P>
<P>
   His personal assistant remains buried in the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   In their Sunday sermons in downtown Nairobi, clergymen called
for forgiveness. At the city mortuary, where families lined up to
identify bodies of missing relatives and friends, the talk was of
vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we forgive people we don't even know?'' said Zablon
Obengo, 31, as he stood with other red-eyed relatives of his
cousin, a bank manager killed in the blast. After searching
hopefully but fruitlessly at one hospital after another, the group
had arrived at the last stop, the mortuary. The body was there.
</P>
<P>
   The mortuary _ where 48 corpses awaited someone to claim them _
was a scene of horror. Most lay on the bare cement floor, bloody,
half-naked and contorted. One man's skull was ripped open,
another's face was split in half. Several bodies were burned black.
</P>
<P>
   A horrific stench hung in the air.
</P>
<P>
   John Kamau Mwangi, leaning on his walking stick, bent over to
inspect the waxy bare foot of a corpse with half a head. His search
had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' he said, his eyes wide, ``is my son.''
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey Gatitu Matu, who found his dead brother at the morgue,
spoke for many. ``If it is possible for those who did this to be
punished, that would be a good resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   In both Nairobi and Dar es Salaam, police and rescue workers
said they will continue working around the clock to pull more
survivors from the ruins. But they admitted that their hopes are
dimming as time passes.
</P>
<P>
   In Nairobi, the specially trained 64-member Fairfax County, Va.,
Fire and Rescue team was searching the embassy with four teams of
dogs that look for bodies and body parts. The team took with it
55,000 pounds of preassembled gear, including concrete-piercing
drills, torches capable of cutting through steel beams, and
fiber-optic cameras.
</P>
<P>
   At both bombing scenes, the rescue workers balanced the need to
look for bodies and the need to preserve shards that might help
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets difficult to protect the integrity of a crime scene
when you've got bodies there,'' said the Rev. Charles R. Stith of
Boston, who will take his post as US ambassador to Tanzania next
month. He arrived in Washington Sunday for briefings at the State
Department with the emergency task force overseeing the rescue and
the investigation. ``You've got to get people who still might be
alive in the midst of the rubble, and that has to be the
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-story embassy building was so badly damaged that it
probably will have to be razed and rebuilt, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In both Kenya and Tanzania, most of the evidence technicians,
explosives specialists, terrorism analysts, and other investigators
from the FBI and other agencies had arrived by last night. While
the government refused to divulge exact numbers, officials said
that nearly 200 were working in Dar es Salaam and more were in
Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators might get a boost from video shot by two
closed-circuit cameras atop the embassy in Nairobi. One of the
cameras was blown off the roof, but US officials suggested that the
images of cars and pedestrians just before the blast might have
been preserved. In Dar es Salaam, a security camera remained on the
roof of the embassy, pointed at the heavily damaged gate.
</P>
<P>
   Top officials publicly and privately refused to name a top
suspect, or even to reveal what is known about the type and the
quantity of explosive used in the simultaneous explosions 450 miles
apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not the act of some isolated individual, a madman,''
Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen said. Appearing on ABC's
``This Week,'' he called the attacks ``long in the planning.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said that while some
Americans may want to retaliate, it is too early to talk about
striking back. ``While there might be an instant gratification to
do something about an attack on us, we have to be absolutely sure
we have the facts straight,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The memory of the United States is very long, and our reach is
very far,'' she said on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Arlen Specter, a Pennsylvania Republican, said too
many terrorist attacks have gone unsolved and unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
David L. Marcus reported from Washington and Andrea Useem reported
from Nairobi. Material from the Associated Press was used in this
report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
