<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SCHARAGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRY SCHARAGA, 88, HAILED AS SANITATION HERO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By ROBERT McG. THOMAS Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harry Scharaga, who did such a good job clearing snow off the
streets of Queens, N.Y., in 1968 that he may have helped doom Mayor
John Lindsay's presidential aspirations in 1969, died on July 28 at
his home in Lauderdale Lakes, Fla. He was 88 and had retired as
first deputy sanitation commissioner in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Lindsay would have otherwise made a viable presidential
candidate after what happened _ or rather, didn't happen _ in
Queens in February 1969, he had about as much chance of winning the
1972 Democratic presidential nomination as a snowball in the hands
of an irate Queens resident picketing his campaign in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   As many Queens residents still recall with rancor, when 15
inches of snow fell on New York on Feb. 9, 1969, cleanup proceeded
apace elsewhere in the city, but in Queens, where Scharaga had
recently been the Sanitation Department's borough superintendent,
the cleanup was so sluggish that some streets were impassable for a
week and Lindsay was widely and extravagantly blamed.
</P>
<P>
   Various administrative lapses were singled out for blame, but
Scharaga's wife, Mildred, knew immediately and exactly what the
underlying problem was.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter from The Long Island Press called her at 3 a.m.
the night of the snowstorm to find out why the cleanup in Queens
was going so slowly, as she recalled last week, she gave him an
earful:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because my husband has been promoted to Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Scharaga, who had a recognized talent for planning,
organizing and directing complex operations, did such a good job
with snow removal and everything else in Queens that his promotion
seemed only reasonable, even if it did leave Queens residents with
what turned out to be unrealistic expectations for continued
administrative efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   That his promotion may have inadvertently left an administrative
vacuum that contributed to the dismal snow cleanup in Queens a
short time later was an irony not lost on the Lindsay
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Within months of the 1969 Queens debacle, and with Lindsay in a
tight race that preceded his narrow re-election as mayor that
November, Scharaga had been promoted again, to chief of staff of
the Sanitation Department's bureau of cleaning and collection, and
put in charge of citywide snow removal operations.
</P>
<P>
   He planned so well and so thoroughly that in what became known
as the Christmas Night snowfall of 1969 so many snowplows and salt
spreaders were deployed so rapidly that the city was hardly
affected. And with the February storm still a raw memory, Scharaga
was hailed as a municipal hero.
</P>
<P>
   A few months later he tackled another festering problem that was
generating a wave of complaints. Finding that many city
neighborhoods ostensibly scheduled for three garbage pickups a week
were actually averaging only two _ and these so haphazardly that
residents never knew when the next one would be _ Scharaga came up
with an ingenious solution: He cut the number of scheduled pickups
in the affected neighborhoods to two a week but put them on regular
fixed schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay was so grateful that in August 1970, Scharaga was
promoted to the newly created post of first deputy commissioner for
operations. It was the first time in 28 years that a uniformed
Sanitation Department employee had made it to the commissioner
level, and Scharaga promptly earned his keep championing the
introduction of plastic garbage bags, which sharply reduced the
number of injuries to collectors.
</P>
<P>
   For Scharaga, who was born on the Lower East Side and dropped
out of high school to help support his family, the job and the
title were a culmination of a career of steady advancement.
</P>
<P>
   After joining the Sanitation Department in 1930, he rose rapidly
through the civil service ranks, his ambition fueled in part by
memories of his first sanitation job: shoveling refuse down a chute
into an incinerator, work so dangerous he had to wear a chain
around his waist to keep from falling in.
</P>
<P>
   Scharaga, a close friend of John DeLury, the longtime president
of the Uniformed Sanitationmen's Association, was active in forming
the union in 1936 but elected to stay on the job rather than join
the union staff.
</P>
<P>
   After his retirement, Scharaga fared somewhat better in Florida
than Lindsay had when his presidential campaign collapsed after
Queens residents followed him to Florida and jeered him in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   After four restless years, Scharaga became director of community
service for the Broward County tax assessor's office and did such
an acclaimed job that he held it until a few months before his
death.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Scharaga is survived by a daughter,
Arlene Eisenberg of New York City; a son, Victor Schargai of
Washington; three grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
