<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colbrunn content with second tour
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Greg Colbrunn has a career .278 batting average
with sporadic power (61 career homers) but respectable
run-production (one RBI per 6.9 at-bats). A first baseman, he had
played the outfield this season and can still play catcher, his
original position, if required. He plays hard. He is still just 29.
</P>
<P>
   This is not exactly the profile of a journey man. Yet, here he
is, in his second stint with the Braves, one of five teams to have
employed him. He is no closer to a multi-year contract now than he
was when he broke into the majors with Montreal in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the two decent seasons in Florida when I played every
day,'' he said. ''You like to think it would happen. But on the
other hand, I've had two major elbow operations. I mean, I'm happy
to have a job. There's two sides to every story.''
</P>
<P>
   Colbrunn's first 10 days back with the Braves have been a smash.
Entering Sunday's game, he had three hits with a double and a home
run in his first six at-bats with five RBI. And he may well be the
best bargain on the team. The Braves are paying just $200,000
remaining from his $600,000 minor league contract he signed with
Colorado, in addition to a modest $30,000 bonus for each 25
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves obviously covet his services, having traded twice (at
the cost of three minor leaguers) to obtain him. This time, he
would like to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everything goes right, yeah, that Braves are one of the
best teams to play for,'' he said. ``Bobby's (Cox) a heck of a
manager. They're built to win games. It's nice to be here for a
full year instead of coming in part-time. It's nice to be here but
it'd also be nice to be here from day one. I come in and they're 14
games up. They're going to win the division with or without me.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss out again
</P>
<P>
   Cox had Walt Weiss in the lineup until trainer Dave Pursley came
in early Sunday afternoon to suggest the shortstop be given a
second day off to rest his left quad. Weiss sat out Saturday's game
just to give him a break after a night game but he reported to the
clubhouse Sunday with some soreness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other guy (Ozzie Guillen) just went 4-for-4 and Walt gets
almost four days off,'' Pursley said. ``It's not like he couldn't
play today.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuck on track
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tucker would like to think his slump is over. If hitting
safely in five of his seven starts didn't persuade him, Saturday's
4-for-4 performance finished the job. Tucker opened Sunday's play
with a .262 average, after leaving Atlanta at .253. He hit .180 in
July, his worst month as a Brave, but has gone 9-for-28 (.321) in
his last nine games and with his two doubles Saturday, he continues
to lead the club in that category (along with Andruw Jones) with
24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been swinging pretty good for two weeks,'' Tucker said.
``A 1-for-4 doesn't do a thing. I need a few 2-for-3s and 3-for-4s
before anyone takes notice of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc. ...
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, when the Braves caught San Francisco on the last day
of the season to win the NL West, Atlanta has used 14 different
starting pitchers. The Giants have used 36. The Braves have won 93
more games than the Giants since then. ... The Giants wore red
ribbons on their jerseys as a part of the team's ``Until There's A
Cure Day,'' an AIDs salute.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
