A5313 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHR     08-09 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PRIVACY RIGHTS WHEN IT COMES TO YOUR E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 Q:   Someone in my company sent me an e-mail with confidential
information by mistake. While I was gone, my boss got into my
computer and deleted the e-mail without informing me. I found out
anyway, and feel this was an invasion of my privacy. Was this
legal?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Your computer and software is company property, just like
your desk and chair. And just as your company has a right to
examine the drawers of your desk, it has a right to go into your
computer and browse through your e-mail files.
</P>
<P>
   Savvy companies make sure their employees realize this, so there
aren't any unwelcome surprises in situations like yours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I advise my clients to clearly state in their personnel
policies that computers are provided for business use, and
employees have no expectation of privacy,'' said Patrick Flynn, a
consultant with HR Management Solutions in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But even without a written policy, the company has a right to go
into your computer _ especially when there's a legitimate business
reason like deleting a misdirected memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one caveat would be looking at personal documents that
might be on the computer,'' Flynn said. ``If the company is doing a
search and comes across personal things, it's an open question
whether it has the right to copy them or delve into them.''
</P>
<P>
   The lesson here should be clear. Think of your office computer
as a glass box, with all its contents potentially visible to your
employer.
</P>
<P>
   Your boss may never need to look inside. But to be safe, don't
keep anything there that you wouldn't want the company to read.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;   &LR; I soon will be leaving a major international firm after
one year due to a change in my husband's job location. Because this
is my first job after college, I asked my supervisor for a letter
of reference. She replied that it is against company policy. I
respect her position, but how can I prove to prospective employers
that I did a good job? I don't think a character reference from a
friend will sway anyone to hire me.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  I've written before about how sad it is that many companies
no longer feel free to give job references, because they're afraid
of lawsuits. Here's a perfect example of the damage that does _ a
good young employee who may have trouble getting work because of a
lack of references.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Mandel, director of counseling at Alumnae Resources in San
Francisco, has a couple of suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Get a copy of your most recent performance evaluation, and
provide that in lieu of a reference letter. If your company doesn't
do evaluations as a matter of course, ask if you can have one
before you leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Performance evaluations sometimes carry more weight with
employers than references, since they figure it wasn't done just
for the sake of impressing someone,'' Mandel said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to get a personal note or letter that can serve as a
reference from one of your co-workers, another manager, or a
manager who has left the company. If they don't want to put
something in writing, ask if you can have potential employers give
them a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't worry too much about references. Many of the other
applicants you'll be competing against face this same hurdle. And
prospective employers usually give much more weight to other
factors _ such as applicants' experience, skills and how they
present themselves in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   So focus your energy on writing a dynamite cover letter and
resume, and then acing your job interviews.
</P>
<P>
   And be sure to network, especially since you're moving to a new
city. ``Develop a strategy for how you're going to network,''
Mandel said. ``Use your husband's contacts and whatever career
centers are available. Call in favors from everyone you know here,
asking if they know people in your new city. ... I haven't seen any
change in networking being the most effective job-search
technique.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;   &LR; I run a small business and have a client who isn't paying
their bills. I've sat down with them and worked out plans to pay on
an installment basis, but they don't follow through. They owe me
about $8,000. Should I hire a lawyer and sue them, or what?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Free-lancers and small-business people with a
bill-collection problem have several options that are less drastic
than suing their client, according to David Perlstein, the San
Francisco author of ``Solo Success: 100 Tips for Becoming a
$100,000-a-Year Freelancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Some ideas:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure you're dealing with the appropriate member of the
client's team _ the person with the power to sign checks. ``You may
have worked things out with your client contact, but you may not
have gone up the ladder to the head of accounting or the CEO,''
Perlstein said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have a lawyer write your next letter asking for payment. It
may cost $200 in legal fees, but that's a worthwhile investment if
it shakes loose an $8,000 payment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a deal to accept even a small amount of money as an
initial installment to get the repayment ball rolling. Consider
dropping by the client's office to pick up the check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it helps to say, `If you can cut me a check right
now, I'll come pick it up,'' Perlstein said. ``Don't wait for the
client to say `The check is in the mail.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ You may also be able to sell this debt to an outside company
that makes money by buying and collecting people's receivables. You
can find such firms in the yellow pages under ``factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Factors pay a discounted rate for receivables _ for instance,
you might get $4,000 for selling them this $8,000 bill, Perlstein
said. The factor would get to keep all the money it manages to
collect from your client. You wouldn't have recouped the full
$8,000 you were owed, but at least you'd have gotten something.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might only get 50 cents on the dollar, but you'd get rid
of this matter,'' Perlstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways,
San Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or
send e-mail to workways &LR; sfgate.com. Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query in person, but we will answer as many
in print as we can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
