<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5314 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONTHEMONEY-COLUMN--SF     08-09 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONTHEMONEY-COLUMN--SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T PANIC ABOUT ELECTRONIC PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY DOAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
As I reported in the July 27 column, most federal payments will
soon be made electronically in lieu of paper checks under the
Electronic Funds Transfer '99 Act. The change doesn't take effect
until January, and the Treasury Department says it will grant
waivers for certain people who want to stick with the
check-in-the-mail method.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But some unscrupulous financial service companies are telling
consumers that their payments will be delayed or halted immediately
if they don't sign up for expensive payment access services with
them, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what these businesses say, the government has not
started delaying or withholding any payments because of this
change. And it is still considering setting up low-fee
``limited-purpose'' bank accounts for people who aren't granted a
waiver.
</P>
<P>
   You can get more information on the government's electronic
payment plans by calling the federal agency from which you receive
payments or by visiting this Web site www.fms.treas.gov/eft/.
</P>
<P>
   CPA LOCATOR: If, like hundreds of thousands of Californians, you
opted to extend the filing of your 1997 tax return, the August 15
deadline is coming up. If you need to track down an accountant in a
hurry, you can find one in your area by using a new service called
``Find a CPA'' at www.calcpa.org, the home page for the California
Society of CPAs.
</P>
<P>
   You can research CPAs by specialty, location and language. The
service, which doesn't charge CPAs to join, offers a broad range of
listings.
</P>
<P>
   SAVINGS WORKSHEET: The American Savings Education Council, a
coalition of private and public groups trying to raise public
awareness of financial planning, has a basic savings worksheet
available for free on its Web site. Called the ``Ballpark
Estimate,'' it can give you a rough idea of the savings you'll need
when you retire. You can download it from www.asec.org or have it
mailed to you by calling (800) 732-0330.
</P>
<P>
   USED VS. NEW CARS: Cars purchased when they're 1 to 3 years old
cost their owners an average 9.5 percent less to own and operate
over their lifetimes than do new cars, according to a study by
Intellichoice. The study looked at more than 2,500 cars, trucks and
sports utility vehicles (SUVs). It factored in depreciation costs,
financing, insurance and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The study also notes used SUVs cost 11 percent less to own and
operate than new ones, while pre-owned trucks cost only 6.2 percent
less than new trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle staff writer Amy Doan can be reached at
doana &LR; sfgate.com or by calling (415) 536-5134.
</P>
</TEXT>
