<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUMMER-CAMP-ACADEMIC-967-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER CAMP COMBINES NATURE AND ACADEMICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ll) 
 By MACARENA HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mamasa Njie, 11, knew all about the mosquitoes,
poison ivy, uncomfortable mattresses and occasional homesickness
that awaited her at camp. But she had not counted on three hours a
day of reading, social studies and math and science classes.
</P>
<P>
   Mamasa, a sixth-grader from P.S. 64 in the South Bronx, is one
of the 1,300 New York City public school students attending summer
school at camp under a program started this summer by Schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were just coming here and we'd pick what we
wanted to do, like in other camps,'' Mamasa said of her experience
at Camp Vacamas, near Butler, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not what Crew had in mind. The chancellor, who
attended a summer camp in Maine when he was a boy in Poughkeepsie,
N.Y., persuaded the board of education to help finance the program,
called Break-Aways Camp, not only to help improve schoolwork but
also to broaden the experience of inner-city children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exposing them to an entirely new perspective and their
understanding of life is just what a lot of our kids need,'' Crew
said. The camping courses, which carry no academic credit now, will
be evaluated, he said, and he hopes that the four-year pilot
project can be expanded and eventually involve 10,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to work very hard in being able to demonstrate that
this model has tremendous power,'' crew said.
</P>
<P>
   The program's start was touch and go because the board did not
approve the pilot project until late May, with an estimated annual
cost of $15 million to $20 million, which is supplemented by
private donations.
</P>
<P>
   The city contracted with 25 independent camps, some day camps
and others residential, ranging from the Brooklyn Center for Urban
Environment, which held sessions in Prospect Park, to Camp Ohnehtah
in the Catskills community of East Windham, N.Y. The Board of
Education provides the teachers, and the camps provide counselors
and other support workers. Tuition averages $400 for the sessions,
which run two or three weeks. The first camp sessions started in
June, and some camps have held more than one session.
</P>
<P>
   The board had planned for a program with 52 teachers and a class
average of 20 students, but was able to recruit only 39 teachers,
so classes are larger than planned.
</P>
<P>
   Some teachers had already made vacation plans; others complained
that the pay was not enough. (At Camp Vacamas, it was $1,000 for a
three-week session.) Some of the 15 participating residential camps
threw in special privileges, like letting teachers bring their own
children at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   It proved easier to find students than teachers. Principals from
27 of the city's 32 community school districts selected candidates
from fourth through eighth grade, and then sought parental
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Mamasa and 20 other students from P.S. 64 were sent to Camp
Vacamas for three weeks. The three general school areas _ reading,
social studies and science and math _ are covered in two
hour-and-a-half classes a day, which frequently cover material in
more than one area.
</P>
<P>
   One reading assignment was to write a daily journal entry. After
three days, Mamasa wrote: ``Camp is all right so far. I am having
fun. We go swim everyday and go to classes. At rest hour I write
letters to my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Roser, 28, a teacher from Australia who was recruited by
Camp Vacamas for the summer as a counselor, said the students
envied the nonacademic campers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for them combining academics and camp activities,''
she said. ``You are combining two atmospheres.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to classes, students swim and take nature walks.
After two weeks, Mamasa and other campers could walk the trails and
call out oak, sassafras and pine trees by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mosquitoes are afraid of smoke, and I like that,'' wrote Lanna
Wilson, 12, in her journal. ``We lifted up rocks and we saw a lot
of nasty insects. I was the only girl who did not scream. I was the
brave one.''
</P>
<P>
   One city teacher who took a camp job, Linda Silverberg, a
computer teacher in Middle School 319 in District 9 in the South
Bronx, said she was concerned about the responsibility. ``I was a
little leery because I didn't know what exactly I was going to be
doing,'' she said. ``We thought we were going to have to cover
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The three teachers at Camp Vacamas chose to concentrate in one
of the course areas but to cooperate in planning and coordinating
lessons. Journal entries were used in social studies, for example.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon Mrs. Silverberg's social studies class was
presenting ``It's All About the Environment, Baby,'' a play
written, directed and performed by the students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more here than what I have in my regular classroom,''
she said, ``They are touching and observing'' the trees and insects
and nature, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers were not the only ones who needed persuading. A few
parents were reluctant. Ydalia Perez, 40, did not like the idea of
having her daughter, Jessenia Liriano, 13, away for three weeks and
reachable only by mail, not telephone. It took a meeting with
teachers and a visit to the camp to persuade her to allow Jessenia
to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can have more knowledge of what nature is,'' Ms. Perez
said. ``And she can become more responsible and take care of her
things. Over there she had to do her bed and wash her clothes. I do
all of that for her.''
</P>
<P>
   At Camp Vacamas, Jessenia had other responsibilities, like
writing and directing the play in Mrs. Silverberg's class.
</P>
<P>
   After the first run-through of the play, Jessenia, the actors
and the extras walked down to the lake for a quick swim before
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Break-Aways is the bomb,'' she said, using a current term
according it the highest praise. ``We have school and camp all at
the same time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
