r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IPO-SMALLINVESTORS-SF     08-09 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPO-SMALLINVESTORS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL INVESTORS JUMPING ON IPO ROCKET 
</HEADLINE>
   By ARTHUR M. LOUIS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
After years of sitting on the sidelines, individual investors are
actively participating in the wild and woolly market for initial
public stock offerings.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Surprisingly enough, they are getting a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   IPOs, formerly monopolized by institutional investors, were made
available to customers of such leading retail brokers as Charles
Schwab &AMP; Co. and Fidelity Investments starting last year.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, retail customers can't always get as many shares as
they want. They can't always sell their stocks when they want, and
sometimes, the stocks they buy don't perform well.
</P>
<P>
   And when IPO shares are in hot demand, many customers can't get
them at all.
</P>
<P>
   But those who do participate in IPOs have made out well on
average. The IPO shares sold to retail customers have performed
better, by and large, than the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index _ the
leading stock market benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle examined 102 IPOs that have been sold to customers
of Schwab, Fidelity, E-Trade and a New York-based online broker
called Wit Capital since February 1997. A $1,000 investment in each
of them _ $102,000 all told _ would have grown to $117,675 at the
end of last month.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, a hypothetical $1,000 investment in the S&AMP;P 500 at
the time of each IPO would have risen to just $111,231.
</P>
<P>
   Investors covet IPOs because they tend to be underpriced.
``Investment bankers usually do that as a reward for their best
customers,'' says Richard Shaffer, editor of Venture Finance
magazine in New York.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, once trading begins, most IPOs rise in value.
</P>
<P>
   A recent, spectacular example was Broadcast.com Inc., a Dallas
company that offers sporting events, music and news over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It went public at $18 per share on July 17, traded as high as
$74 that day and closed at $62.75. It since has tailed off to
around $50.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Broadcast.com was not among the IPOs that have
been made widely available to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Before last year, the only individuals who could get their hands
on IPO shares were those with lots of money and special ties to the
investment bankers that underwrote new issues.
</P>
<P>
   But in response to requests from its customers, Schwab wrangled
a deal last year with three leading investment bankers _ CS First
Boston, J.P. Morgan Securities and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist _ to
distribute shares in the IPOs they underwrite.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity struck a similar deal with Salomon Smith Barney, while
E-Trade now gets IPO shares from BancAmerica Robertson Stephens.
Wit Capital, which is not only a broker, but an investment bank,
gets IPOs from numerous other investment banks with which it does
business.
</P>
<P>
   The firms advertise their IPOs through selective mailings to
customers and by posting information on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, IPOs are in such heavy demand from so many quarters that
retail brokers usually can't get enough shares to meet the demand.
</P>
<P>
   At Schwab, which has distributed shares from 39 IPOs, only the
most-active and richest traders may participate. The IPOs are
reserved for those who place at least 24 trades per year with the
firm or who have account balances of at least $1 million, says Bob
Hannan, director of the syndicate department.
</P>
<P>
   That works out to just 3 percent of Schwab's 5 million
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stocks have a certain level of risk,'' Hannan explains.
``We have to make sure the customers we offer them to are
sophisticated, so we focus on our more-active traders.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity, which has participated in 29 IPO deals, has more
nebulous standards. The firm favors customers with ``long tenure''
who ``do much of their business with us,'' says Bob Mazzarella,
president of Fidelity Brokerage Services.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, the only broker that makes IPOs available to all its
customers on a first-come, first-served basis is Wit Capital.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``We're trying to serve issuing companies by opening up their
lines of distribution,'' says Andrew Klein, Wit's founder and chief
executive. He says he hopes that this will persuade the nation's
big underwriters to give his firm still more investment-banking
business.
</P>
<P>
   Since last September, Wit has offered shares in 22 IPOs
underwritten by prominent investment bankers such as Goldman Sachs,
Lehman Brothers and Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   To buy IPO shares from Wit, you must open an account with the
firm, which you can do electronically through its Web site, at
www.witcapital.com.
</P>
<P>
   Klein says that while the firm will sell IPO shares to any
customer, it is careful not to let customers get in over their
heads. ``If you have a net worth of $10,000, we would permit you to
buy maybe $1,000 of an IPO,'' he remarks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Most of the IPOs sold to Wit customers are not exactly
household names. The better-known ones include Rollerball
International, which makes in-line skates, and Cleveland Indians
Baseball, which owns the 1997 American League champions.
</P>
<P>
   All the brokerage firms ask their customers to refrain from
unloading their IPO shares quickly _ a tactic known as
``flipping.''
</P>
<P>
   The brokers do this at the demand of the underwriters, who are
committed to maintaining a stable market in IPO stocks during the
early trading days. If the customers flip shares, the underwriters
sometimes retaliate by withholding the commissions they normally
pay the broker for participating in the IPO.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-flipping dictum often conflicts with the interests of
investors, many of whom are drawn to IPOs because of the potential
for quick, large, in-and-out profits. If the profits aren't grabbed
quickly, they may evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, Box Hill Systems, a New York-based maker of
data-storage systems, whose IPO was offered to Fidelity customers
last September at $15 per share. The stock surged to $20.06 on the
first trading day, but within less than two months, it had fallen
below the IPO price.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, it was trading at around $6.
</P>
<P>
   Wit Capital asks its customers to hold IPO shares for at least
60 days, and will hit those who disobey with an extra-large
commission on the sale. Normally, Wit charges $14.95 per trade, but
it imposes a surcharge equal to 5 percent of the transaction price
on a flip.
</P>
<P>
   If a customer flips 100 shares at $30 per share, for example,
the surcharge will amount to a stiff $150. Of course, that probably
won't bother customers who bought the stock for $10 per share. Even
with the surcharge, the net profit would come to $1,850.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab customers are asked to hold their IPO shares for at least
30 days. If they sell earlier, they don't suffer a money penalty
but they may not be allowed to buy shares in future IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   The same rules apply to customers of E-Trade Group, which has
sold shares in a dozen IPOs since last November.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity asks its customers to hold their stock for at least 15
days, and it, too, may restrict their participation in future IPOs
if they flip.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of flipping gets done anyway, much of it by institutional
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The underwriters ask the institutions not to flip, but the
biggest institutions can get away with it because of their
importance to the underwriters. No underwriter in its right mind
will cut off its nose by refusing to sell shares in future IPOs to
a giant mutual fund family.
</P>
<P>
   This disparity between the treatment of institutional investors
and small, individual investors recently prompted a multistate
group of securities regulators _ the North American Securities
Administrators Association _ to launch a formal investigation. The
investigation is still in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hurdles, hassles and obstacles, individual investors
seem pleased at the opportunity to get in on IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab customer Jack Diamond, a retired casket salesman in
Carrollton, Texas, has bought 500 to 2,000 shares each _ ``not as
much as I wanted'' _ in four IPOs: Blue Rhino, Capstar
Broadcasting, Keebler and USWeb.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask, Schwab will send you prospectuses,'' Diamond says.
``After reading them, I decided to try a little. It's up to you
because Schwab won't tell you whether a stock is good, bad or
indifferent. They only say that some go down and some go up.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``I'm happy with my choices'' _ as well he might be.
All but Keebler have performed far better than the overall market,
and even Keebler shows a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity customer Joseph Lupo Jr., a full-time investor in
Franklin Lakes, N.J., says he has gotten into ``a bunch'' of IPOs,
not all of which he could remember by name. His allotments have
ranged from a couple of hundred shares to several thousand per IPO.
</P>
<P>
   He says there have been ``some good deals,'' such as Qwest
Communications, whose stock has more than tripled since the IPO in
June 1997, and ``some down deals,'' including Earthshell Container,
which has lost more than half its value since going public last
March.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to take the bad with the good,'' Lupo says. ``I'm
pretty happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-09-98 2238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
