<DOCNO> NYT19980809.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5328 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ACURA-LADN     08-09 0320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ACURA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT GLAD TO BE PLAYING IN BACKYARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lindsay Davenport will try to win her third consecutive Corel
WTA event this week at Manhattan Beach in the $450,000 Acura
Classic, which starts today at 10 a.m. The Newport Beach resident
won the Toshiba Classic in Carlsbad on Sunday and will be one of 28
players in the Manhattan Beach singles tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve matches, including four qualifiers, are set for today at
the Manhattan Country Club's stadium and court four. The fourth
match in the stadium between Los Angeles' Kimberly Po and France's
Julie Halard-Decugis highlights the first day. The winner will face
Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, the second seed, has a bye with Nos.1, 3 and 4 seeds
Martina Hingis, Arantxa Sanchez Vicario and Monica Seles. At
Carlsbad, Davenport said she may play better in Southern California
because she receives more fan support than at other Corel WTA
events. She also said she looks at the events in Southern
California as tune-ups for later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to play near home, on the hard courts,'' she
said. ``For me, it's the perfect preparation for the U.S. Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Irina Spirlea, the sixth seed, will be the highest seed to play
today. She takes on China's Fang Li in the stadium at 7 p.m. Two of
the eight opening-round doubles matches also are today in the
tournament that runs until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Many eyes will be on Davenport this week because she is close to
home and is coming off two wins. Even though she is ranked second,
she does not receive as much attention as others on the women's
tennis tour because she is not outspoken. Staying in the
background, however, is a role that she wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the position I'm in,'' she said. ``It's easier to stay
focused on your game when you're not in the spotlight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
