<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 8/9/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 9, 1998 -- BBA-YANKS-ROYALS, 8-9 -- The
Yankees' Orlando Hernandez pitching against the Royals on Sunday.
Hernandez allowed just four hits in eight innings and improving his
record to 7-3. The Yankees swept the four-game series from the
Royals while outscoring them, 41-9. The Yankees improved to a
ridiculous 84-29 for the season and a just-as-ridiculous 42-8 at
home. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MASHANTUCKET, Conn. -- Aug. 9, 1998 -- INDIAN-MUSEUM, 8-9
-- A re-creation of life in a 16th-century Pequot village at The
Mashantucket Pequot Museum, which opens on Tuesday, celebrates the
Mashantucket Pequot Tribal Nation's resurrection. The museum has
been able to draw on resources that many other museums can only
dream of. Foxwoods Resort Casino, now Connecticut's largest
individual source of revenue and that which allows the Pequots to
live like sheiks, supplied $193 million -- roughly four months'
take from the slot machines -- for the museum. (George Ruhe/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) STAMFORD, Conn. -- Aug. 9, 1998 -- PRICELINE-INTERNET,
8-9 -- Jay Walker, chairman of Priceline.com LLC, a small online
start-up company. Priceline has been awarded a broad
Internet-related business patent, protecting not just the virtual
nuts and bolts of its electronic commerce system, but also its
entire business model for buying and selling goods and services on
the Internet. ``Investors expect revenue from Priceline's business
operations, but the real payoff will come from the licensing of its
methods to other electronic commerce companies,'' says Walker.
(George Ruhe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SANTA CLARA, Calif. -- Aug. 9, 1998 -- CELLPHONE-CHIPS,
8-9 -- Kanwar Chadha, founder of Sirf Technology Inc., a
three-year-old Silicon Valley start-up, with a 1996 global
positioning system chip, left, and the newest 1998 chip. Nokia of
Finland is set to announce a $3 million investment in the start-up,
Sirf Technology Inc., to produce GPS chips inexpensive enough to be
installed in cellular telephones. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) MILL VALLEY, Calif. -- Aug. 9, 1998 --
MARKET-SMALLSTOCKS, 8-9 -- Max Rodel, a 55-year-old chemist and
investment fanatic, is agonizing over his stock portfolio and
feeling a bit rotten about the way his small-company stocks have
cratered in the last few weeks. ``It's been absolutely miserable,
not only for the last few weeks but for the last few years,'' says
Rodel. ``I'd invested in small caps for years and done well. But
I'm having a very bad year investing, one of the worst in 25
years.'' (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
