<SLUG> BC-BELL-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEPHONE STRIKE ENTERS SECOND DAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A strike against Bell Atlantic Corp. by 73,000
telephone service workers enters its second day Monday after
negotiations last night failed to resolve a contract dispute that
focuses on the company's use of outside contractors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The walkout by the Communications Workers of America threatens
to disrupt installation, repair, and, in some cases, operator
services for the company's 27 million customers from Maine to
Virginia. However, only minor delays were reported Sunday. Most
phone calls are routed automatically, and New York-based Bell
Atlantic said managers were filling in for striking employees.
</P>
<P>
   The CWA, which represents 2,800 customer service representatives
in New England, said it would &UR;  &LR; set up picket lines at Massachusetts
sites this morning. Protesters hit the streets Sunday in New York,
New Jersey, and West Virginia after the union's contract expired at
12:01 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're hung up over work being moved to nonunion
subsidiaries,'' Melissa Morin, president of New Hampshire-based CWA
Local 1400, said last night. ``We thought the issue had been
resolved because the company made certain commitments. Then, at the
last minute, it reneged. That's why we struck.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  In New England, most Bell Atlantic workers are represented by
the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers. &UR;  &LR; This union
appeared to be near an agreement on its own contract but
negotiations were continuing. Even as negotiators continued to work
toward an IBEW accord, union officials said their members would
honor CWA picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we felt there was a major stumbling block, we wouldn't be
talking right now,'' said Edward Fitzpatrick, president of IBEW
Local 2222 &UR;  &LR; in Boston. The IBEW represents about 17,000 technicians
and operators in New England, including 4,000 in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Hoey, a Bell Atlantic spokesman in Boston, said the company
has introduced a comprehensive offer that addresses all union
concerns, including temporary jobs, outsourcing, vacation policies,
and the expansion of high-technology union jobs in the company.
``From our point of view, the CWA strike is regrettable and, we
think, unnecessary,'' Hoey said.
</P>
<P>
   Morin, a member of the regional bargaining committee, said
workers were prepared to remain out ``until they have job
security.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, tempers flared in New York over a proposed
pension enhancement package that was to be offered to all customer
service employees before the Aug. 8 contract expiration deadline.
The package allows eligible workers who are near retirement to add
six years to their age and six years to years of service for
purposes of calculating their pension.
</P>
<P>
   According to the CWA, 13,000 employees, many of them based in
New York, did not receive the package as promised, prompting the
union to file a charge of unfair labor practice with the National
Labor Relations Board. Union officials representing more than 130
Massachusetts employees are expected to either join the complaint
filed in New York or file a separate charge in Boston today.
</P>
<P>
   Hoey said he could not comment on specific contract issues. He
noted, however, that the IBEW has negotiated an agreement with a
provision for the pension enhancements and with language on use of
outside contractors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The most recent CWA strike against Bell Atlantic took place in
1989 and lasted about three weeks. The CWA also walked out in 1989
at Nynex Corp., acquired last year by Bell Atlantic. That strike
lasted two months. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Material from the Associated Press was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
