<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-FIRE-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
5 DIE IN A FIRE AT A HIGH-RISE IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five people died, including an elderly woman lunging for a
rescue ladder, after a fire broke out in a 20-story apartment tower
in North Bergen, N.J., Sunday afternoon and burned for more than
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The fire started on the fourth floor of the building, which
houses mostly elderly people and low-income families, said Lt. Neil
D. Sanzari of the North Bergen police.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 residents, some in their 80s and gasping for air,
were taken to hospitals. At least seven firefighters were hurt,
including one who suffered second-degree burns on the back of his
neck and on his ears, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   A few residents fled through the building's garage. Others
rushed out the front door, some limping and others using canes.
Rescuers carried some residents in wheelchairs down several flights
of stairs filled with smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Sanzari said one woman fell to her death as she was about to be
rescued.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just jumped the gun,'' he said. ``They were bringing the
ladder right up to the balcony. But she didn't wait for them to put
the ladder on the railing. She grabbed it too quick and pulled it
right down.''
</P>
<P>
   The other four victims were found in the building and probably
died from smoke inhalation, Lieutenant Sanzari said. The
authorities had not released the names of the victims by late
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the fire was reported at 4:48 P.M. and
eventually was upgraded to five alarms.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials said they did not know the cause of the blaze.
But they said several oxygen tanks were found in the apartment
where the fire started, and the police said they received many
calls from residents and neighbors of the building who said they
heard a huge explosion about the time the fire started. Some
rescuers speculated that a cigarette could have touched off the
oxygen tank.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   John A. Caballero, who lives three blocks away and raced to the
building when he heard the explosion, said smoke quickly engulfed
the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big cloud of black smoke around the third and fourth
floors, and then it just kept going up and up and up,'' he said.
``It looked like a battle between the fire and the water. The water
was going in and the flames were coming out, but mostly it was just
smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   The building, Westview Towers, is at 6115 Granton Avenue, near
61st Street, on the town's western slope in a neighborhood that
includes a number of buildings housing the elderly. The building
was evacuated, but the police said that it was not immediately
declared uninhabitable. Sunday night, the authorities were still
going door to door to check on residents.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers and firefighters converged on the scene from
throughout northern New Jersey. ``It looks like a firemen's
convention,'' Caballero said. ``Anywhere you are in North Bergen,
you can hear the sirens.''
</P>
<P>
   Police detectives and investigators were at the building in what
authorities called a standard response to such a huge blaze.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll approached that of a fire in Passaic, N.J., in
May 1997 when six young children were killed in a blaze that tore
through their three-story wood-frame apartment house. All the
children were members of the same extended family.
</P>
<P>
   Heat and smoke _ but not flames _ spread through the tower, fire
officials said. More than 30 residents and at least seven
firefighters were hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the North Bergen Fire Department said the building
had no sprinklers, and was built about 20 years ago, when only fire
alarms were required. Battalion Chief Charles J. Severino said the
building _ made of concrete, steel and bricks _ is designed to
contain a fire in the unit where it starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The down side of that is that the building holds a lot of
heat,'' he said. Chief Severino said firefighters were unable to
get down some halls because of the heat.
</P>
<P>
   North Bergen is a town directly across the Hudson River from
Manhattan, with what residents often call ``million-dollar views''
of the city. The building is in a working-class neighborhood with
narrow streets that quickly jammed with rescuers and panicked
residents when the fire broke out.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the scene said the building is a privately owned,
federally funded center for the elderly, although some younger
people live there as well. Around 400 residents live in 285 units
on 20 floors.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christine Todd Whitman rushed to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a question of flames spreading throughout the
building,'' Governor Whitman said. ``It was intense heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Renee Palumbo, who has lived in the building for 22 years, said
she was in her apartment when firefighters told her she had to
leave. As she was being escorted out, she saw flames shooting out
of one of the apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very scary,'' she said. ``I've never seen a fire like
this here before.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she left her two cats behind, but late Sunday night she
was told she would be able to return to her one-bedroom apartment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
