<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JEWISH-RAVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEPHARDIC SANTANA' HAS JEWISH ROCK FANS DANCING 'TIL DAWN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODBOURNE, N.Y. _ Jewish teen-agers with yarmulkes stuck firmly
to their heads were diving off the stage in the Ali Baba room at
the Aladdin Hotel, their fringes flying and their fists raised in
joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome!'' shouted one, falling into the melee of dancers
below.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, Yosi Piamenta and the Mizrahi Rockers were ripping
through what they billed as their first ``all-night rave,'' a
marathon self-promoted concert for which they charged $12 a head.
It drove hundreds of their fans into a frenzy of whooping,
stomping, rock-and-roll ecstasy that lasted until 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders _ and plenty of older-generation insiders _ might well
be puzzled at the partying in the heart of this Orthodox Jewish
community in the Catskill Mountains. But for those familiar with
Piamenta's heavy metal Hebrew jams, the music is a natural
outgrowth of their religious exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's a rabbi in Denver, and he's cool with this,'' said
Basi Twerski, 25, an elementary-school teacher in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Piamenta, an Israeli-born rock guitarist who became a Hasid,
shrugged at the notion of a conflict between an all-night rave and
his Orthodox faith, which prohibits women from joining their
boyfriends on the dance floor or even from moving to the music by
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   This was, he said, not a rave in the typical drug-induced,
dance-party sense. There were no blinding strobe lights or bumping
and grinding couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, you can't wear the tsitsith and say, `Come on, baby,'''
Piamenta said, laughing and pointing at the fringes worn to remind
Orthodox Jews of God's commandments.
</P>
<P>
   Widely acknowledged by rock critics as a guitar virtuoso,
Piamenta, who now lives in Brooklyn, delights in swinging his
Fender Stratocaster behind his head and playing backward, a la Jimi
Hendrix, while he sings in Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   His set list ranges from Hebrew versions of popular hits like
the 1980s tune ``Down Under'' by Men at Work to his own religiously
themed jams. ``The music is maybe a little scary to some people,
but the message is kosher,'' said Rebecca Lillian, 39, a rabbi from
Skokie, Ill., who has been a Piamenta fan since the 1970s, when she
heard him in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday happened to be the first Sabbath, known as Shabbos
Nachamu, after a three-week period during which Orthodox Jews do
not eat meat, drink wine, celebrate in any way or listen to music.
Now they were ready to cut loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss it?'' said Michelle Newman of Brooklyn. ``It drove me
crazy not hearing music for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not surprising to see this,'' said a 36-year-old
diamond dealer from Great Neck, N.Y., who was watching the frenzy.
``The Orthodox are not afraid to be spiritual.''He added, ``And
hey, it's as close to Jerry Garcia as Orthodox Judaism's going to
get, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Mentioning the late guitarist and leader of the Grateful Dead
appears to be unavoidable at Piamenta's concerts. With his full
beard, tie-dyed shirt (adorned, of course, with religious fringes)
and a psychedelically embroidered skullcap, the ``Sephardic
Santana,'' as he is sometimes called, makes no apologies for
embracing the trappings of the counterculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 20 years I've been doing concerts for Jews, when really my
thing is rock-and-roll,'' Piamenta said. ``I'm a Jewish
rock-and-roller.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Piamenta, 46, who has six children, admitted to feeling
``dead'' the morning after his all-night show. His working weekend
was not over yet. In the afternoon he would be back in Brooklyn to
play another concert, and in the evening, a bar mitzvah in New
Jersey. (For years, weddings and bar mitzvahs have been Piamenta's
main means of support, though he recently broke into the New York
City club scene with gigs at the Knitting Factory and Wetlands,
both in TriBeCa.)
</P>
<P>
   ''He's good, real good,'' said Police Officer Jason Berger, 28,
of Fallsburg. ``I'm the only Jewish cop anywhere around here, so I
had to stop by and check it out.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no hint of marijuana in the air, no underage drinking,
and other than hundreds of fans smoking cigarettes, no evidence of
any typical rock show vices.
</P>
<P>
   Rock fans will be rock fans, however, even here. Though skirts
hung properly long, some were more revealing than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our culture,'' Ms. Newman said, ``we can't really go out
there, but we love the music.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
