<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-09 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-LOUIMA-745(     08-09 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-LOUIMA-745(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR OF LIVING WITH THE LOUIMA CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GARRY PIERRE-PIERRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Abner Louima bowed his head Sunday as he stood in
front of the Club Rendez-Vous in Flatbush, Brooklyn, where on a
steamy night exactly a year ago, prosecutors say, he became the
victim of a sequence of brutal acts at the hands of police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   A small gathering that included Louima's family and friends and
the parents of people who had died while in police custody were led
in prayer by the Rev. Al Sharpton. ``We come not to rally today,
but to pray,'' Sharpton said. ``We gather where Abner's blood began
to flow a year ago. A year ago, he was alone. Today, the whole city
stands with him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the year that has passed, doctors operated on Louima three
times to repair the injuries from that night. And at the same time,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and police officials have made changes in
the department to try to repair relations with the community and to
eliminate the climate that they feared could have allowed the
incident to take place.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say those changes have been largely cosmetic and
have not been felt throughout the department. More important, they
say, the mayor lost a golden opportunity to make much-needed and
systemic change.
</P>
<P>
   Louima was arrested a year ago during a brawl outside the Club
Rendez-Vous, at 1438 Flatbush Ave. Prosecutors say that four
officers beat him in a police car on the way to the 70th Precinct
station house, and that two of the four tortured him after arriving
there.
</P>
<P>
   One officer, Justin Volpe, is accused of ramming a stick into
Louima's rectum and then into his mouth, inflicting major internal
injuries; and a second, Charles Schwarz, is accused of holding
Louima down during the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The case put a bright light on the Police Department and its
relationship with the people it patrols. In ethnically diverse
neighborhoods like those of the 70th Precinct, many residents,
especially Caribbean immigrants, said they had seen a pattern of
rudeness, rough treatment and abuse against black residents,
particularly from the largely white police force.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the Police Department's first steps after the
incident, in each of the city's 76 precincts lieutenants replaced
young and inexperienced sergeants as desk officers, the ones who
most commonly deal with the public.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also allocated $1.5 million to the Civilian Complaint
Review Board to hire a dozen senior investigators, people with
prior experience in law enforcement. That change was intended to
strengthen the police watchdog group, which has been widely
attacked by critics saying its investigations of police actions
have been shoddy.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also created a 31-member task force, made up of
community advocates and leaders, to examine relations between
residents and the police.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the substantive changes occurred at the 70th
Precinct itself. A few days after the incident, officials replaced
the precinct's chief with Inspector Raymond Diaz, a popular
commander with extensive background in community policing who had
been in charge of precincts in East Harlem and in Williamsburg,
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz transferred about 24 officers and recruited more black
officers. Three of the last five new officers assigned to the
precinct are of Caribbean ancestry and live in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 35 percent of the 270 officers in the precinct are
black, including Capt. George Clouden, one of the executive
officers. Diaz said that the precinct was designated as a place
where immigrants can be fingerprinted for their naturalization
applications. So far, more than 1,000 people have used the service.
That, Diaz said, gave residents a different view of the station
house.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Diaz has attended and held scores of meetings
with various community groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can knock on the door and come to see me,'' said Diaz,
who added that he has given neighborhood residents his direct phone
number at the station house. ``And it doesn't have to be a
community leader; it can be anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday at least one critic said nothing had changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city's outrage of a year ago has abated,'' said Public
Advocate Mark Green, who is seeking the Democratic nomination for
the U.S. Senate. He spoke to an assembly at the Evangelical Crusade
of Fishers of Men Haitian Pentecostal Church in Flatbush. ``City
Hall has taken next to no action, and Mayor Giuliani has denigrated
his own civilian task force,'' he told the assembly, which included
Louima.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In March, the mayor's task force issued a report asking for
tougher screenings for police cadets, suggested that new recruits
be required to live in the city, and asked for bigger salaries for
officers who agree to continue on patrol duty. But Giuliani
dismissed most of its findings, saying that some of them ``are
unrealistic and make very little sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, said in an interview that a year later there was
still no special prosecutor for police brutality, and there were no
residency requirements for police officers and no end to the
so-called 48-hour rule, which gives patrolmen involved in an
incident two days before they must talk to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   There have been few efforts to increase the number of captains
who are members of minorities, critics said. Of the 371 captains in
the department, 10 are black, six are Hispanic and one Asian. It is
widely believed that captains set the tone for a precinct more than
anyone, much the way that midlevel managers do in an office.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago he was in a jam,'' said Siegel, a member of the
mayor's civilian task force, which has not met since March. ``He
came to some of his critics and said he was open to change. He
really wasn't at all. He simply wanted to manage the crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Requests for comment from the mayor's office were referred to
Diaz.
</P>
<P>
   For Haitian residents, the Louima incident exposed the
vulnerability of a group that had had a closely held belief that
they could move into the mainstream by keeping to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to draw out a lot of Haitians into the fold,''
said Tatiana Wah, chairwoman of the Haitian-American Alliance, a
community group. ``These are people who had been away from the
community and are coming back saying, `How can we really help?'
This thing had shocked a lot of us.''
</P>
<P>
   After several protests and rallies, more and more Haitians are
getting involved in politics, including Samuel Nicolas, Louima's
cousin, who gained prominence as the family spokesman after the
incident. He is running for the Democratic nomination for
Brooklyn's 42nd Assembly District, an area that includes Flatbush
and parts of Crown Heights. There are now Haitians on the city's
community and school boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for a long time we've isolated ourselves,'' said Ms.
Wah, whose organization and others like it have increased the
number of citizenship and voter-registration drives in Queens and
Brooklyn, where some of the largest Haitian enclaves are located.
``We're a young immigrant group. We didn't know better. It's
finally sinking through that there are things we must do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
