<HEADLINE>
DRY SPELL THREATENS CROPS IN NEW JERSEY
</HEADLINE>
   (ll) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey farmers are facing drought conditions as the New York
City region contends with one of its driest summers in years.
</P>
<P>
   It has yet to rain in August in New York City or in most of New
Jersey. July brought a mere drip of water, compared with normal
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a wet spring, rainfall for the year is actually above
normal, according to meteorologists, and reservoir levels are high.
The early part of this week may bring scattered showers and even
thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   But the wet spell likely will be short-lived, and a few moist
days may not be enough to help farmers whose crops have been
damaged by high temperatures and drought conditions on the heels of
an unusually wet spring.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, ``much of the state has been bone-dry in
August,'' following a below-normal July, said Art Kraus, a National
Weather Service meteorologist based in Mount Holly, N.J. In July,
rainfall in Atlantic City was 2.41 inches below normal; in Newark,
it was 3.18 inches below normal.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey farmers are pouring money into irrigation and
anxiously watching their crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been irrigating around the clock,'' said Peter Demarest
of the Demarest farm in Hillsdale, after a half inch of rain in 39
days.
</P>
<P>
   His peaches are small but sweet, he said, but his pumpkins are
imperiled. He already replanted an entire pumpkin field after an
excess of rain in June. Now, he said, ``If I don't get water in
there in the next week or two, I'm in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Demarest said, is the sharp change from an
especially wet spring, which was preceded by an ``ultramild''
winter. ``I've seen more severe droughts,'' he said, ``but I've
never seen a season like this.''
</P>
<P>
   In the southern part of New Jersey, the story is much the same.
Bill Brooks Jr., who runs Dusty Lane Farms in Elmer, N.J., and is
the president of the State Board of Agriculture, said his potato
yields were above average, thanks to a rainy May and June, but his
grain crops were being hit hard by the subsequent dryness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our yields will be off substantially,'' he said, adding that a
depressed market for corn and soybeans will exacerbate the wounds
inflicted by weather.
</P>
<P>
   Central Park's average rainfall for July is 4.35 inches; this
July brought only 1.09 inches. It was the seventh-driest July since
record-keeping began in 1869, said Joe Koval, a meteorologist with
the Pennsylvania State University department of meteorology. Based
on the average for years past, August should have brought a
``little over an inch by now,'' Koval said. Instead, the month's
first nine days have yielded not even a drop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
