<SLUG> BC-GLF-METRO-AMATEUR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURVILLE WINS SECOND STRAIGHT METRO AMATEUR CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALAX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCARSDALE, N.Y. _ Jerry Courville Jr. lived up to his reputation
as one of the New York metropolitan area's most prominent amateur
golfers Sunday when he captured his second consecutive Metropolitan
Golf Association Amateur Championship with a 1-up triumph over Jeff
Putman at Quaker Ridge Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Courville and Putman were the last two players left from the 715
who entered the 96th edition of the oldest regional amateur event
in the country. They went into the 35th hole of today's 36-hole
match-play final even, and both found the fairway with their drives
on the 364-yard hole. But only Courville hit his approach onto the
green after a shift in wind cost Putman dearly.
</P>
<P>
   A light wind was behind Putman just before his shot on the
course's 17th hole, but it shifted during the shot and forced his
sand wedge from 115 yards to fall into high rough near a greenside
bunker on the left side. He ended up with a bogey-5, while
Courville made par to break the tie in a roller coaster of a match
at the 6,835-yard, par-70 course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fooled on 17,'' Putman said. ``I was 115 yards away and
I thought a wedge was OK with downwind, but it went 85 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit two clubs wrong, on 16 and 17, and I gave it to him,''
said Putman, who also made a bogey-5 on the 16th when his approach
flew past the green.
</P>
<P>
   Both players parred the 440-yard 18th hole, and Courville won
the Met Amateur for the third time in the last four years. It was
his second title this season at Quaker Ridge, where he captured the
Hochster Memorial in June.
</P>
<P>
   Courville also won all his three matches in last year's Walker
Cup here to lead the United States to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a comfort factor to know the course,'' said Courville,
39, a member of Shorehaven Golf Club in East Norwalk, Conn., where
he works as an office manager. ``Knowing where to hit and where not
to hit helps, but Jeff knows this course, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Putman, 31, an investment banker in Manhattan and a member of
Somerset Hills Country Club in Bernardsville, N.J., captured the
tournament title in 1993 shortly after he regained his amateur
status. He played well enough to win all week, except on two of the
final three holes.
</P>
<P>
   Putman eliminated Greg Rohlf, the low medalist, in 24 holes in
the first round of match play and Ed Gibstein, who won a match in
this year's British Amateur. Hitting the wrong clubs in two of his
final three approaches cost him this tournament, however, because
Courville's play was slightly below his usual high level as a
result of back pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have to defend, I wouldn't have played because of
my back,'' Courville said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
