<HEADLINE>
AUGUST PRONOUNCEMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN BEENE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's August, so of course we're talking NBA....
Hoop fans, if they can stand any more abuse after the Karl
Malone/Dennis Rodman rasslin' match, are in for a long winter.
</P>
<P>
   Early indications are the NBA owners and players are prepared to
act like babies and make everyone think Jerry Reinsdorf knew what
he was doing with the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern and several team owners on Thursday
abruptly walked out of the first meeting between league and the
players' union since June 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got up and walked out. It seemed more feigned than
anything else. It looked like a charade,'' NBA union director Billy
Hunter said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   This is all just posturing. The owners are prepared to see this
out to the bitter end, and the players _ for now _ are united.
Don't expect any meaningful negotiations to begin until at least
October and don't be surprised if the season doesn't start on time.
Count on watching the Rose Bowl before seeing any Lakers game this
season.
</P>
<P>
   _Let's see if we've got this right. You are in the middle of a
pennant race. You need pitching but fail to acquire any before the
trading deadline. Less than a week later, you designate one of your
leading RBI and homer guys for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   You are the Angels. You are now two games out of first place in
the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it makes perfect sense.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Cecil Fielder looked like Cecil B. DeMille on a few
at-bats this year. And his days of hitting as many homers as his
pants size are long gone. Still, Fielder was on pace for 24 homers
and 98 RBI when the Angels said, ``See ya.'' The club treated him
like he was Jeff Manto instead of the established, respected
veteran that he is.
</P>
<P>
   I guess it makes as much sense as trading for Jeff Juden.
</P>
<P>
   _Quick: How are the Angels like Venus de Milo?
</P>
<P>
   No arms. Oh, where have you gone Mike Witt, Kirk McCaskill?
</P>
<P>
   _It's August, so of course we're talking hockey.... So Disney
wants the NHL so badly it's willing to shell out $600 million for
five years just to televise the one sport that is so much better to
watch live.
</P>
<P>
   By the way it has handled the Ducks/Paul Kariya situation/Ron
Wilson fiasco, you would have thought it did not care much at all
for the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Disney can do something for the league whose TV ratings
last season were lower than rhythmic gymnastics'.
</P>
<P>
   _Just wondering. Who's running things at Disney: Huey, Dewey and
Louie?
</P>
<P>
   _It's August, so of course we're talking college football....
Don't send in any more ballots, the voting's over. The quote of the
year _ yeah, we know there's four months to go _ goes to Texas A&AMP;M
football coach R.C. Slocum.
</P>
<P>
   Said Slocum on losing prized recruit Chip Ambres, who signed a
professional baseball contract with the Florida Marlins for $1.5
million: ``I have a lot of rules and no money. Baseball has a lot
of money and no rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Slocum has forgotten the reign of Barry Switzer at
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   _I didn't vote in the recent Pac-10 media poll, but if I had, I
woulda picked 'em in this order: UCLA, Arizona State, Washington,
USC, Oregon, Arizona, Washington State, Stanford, Oregon State and
Cal.
</P>
<P>
   _It's August, so of course we're talking about another Dodgers
collapse.... This quote by Dodgers pitcher Chan Ho Park pretty much
summarizes the whole season, from the Mike Piazza contract squabble
to the firing of Fred Claire and Bill Russell to the botched trade
of Randy Johnson, etc., etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was stupid,'' was Park's response to blowing a 4-0
eighth-inning lead to the Montreal Expos (team motto: We'll trade
you anything. Just ask.) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   No, Chan Ho, you're being too hard on yourself. Inept is the
word you were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   But give some credit to Park. At least he answered for his poor
performance and in English, no less. Can you interpret that, Hideo
Nomo?
</P>
<P>
   _And finally, this is what Wilt Chamberlain had to say about all
this NBA foolishness:
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball should have taught all these leagues a lesson, but
apparently it hasn't. I hope I don't reflect the entire population
of basketball fans, because if I do, the league is in big trouble.
I have no patience for this.''
</P>
<P>
   And neither do we. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
