<SLUG> BC-CAR-CUP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKINNER UPSTAGES TEAMMATE EARNHARDT
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ The hottest driver at Richard Childress
Racing is not seven-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion Dale
Earnhardt. And ``The Intimidator'' knows it.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Mike Skinner stamped himself as an emerging road-racing
ace Sunday with a career-best third-place finish in The Bud at The
Glen, an event that continued to showcase a run of success for RCR.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner was in contention for his first Cup victory until passed
by eventual race-winner Jeff Gordon on lap 87 of the 90-lapper over
the 2.45-mile Watkins Glen International road-course. Earnhardt,
whose year was made by his victory in the season-opening Daytona
500, finished 11th to preserve his top-10 standing (ninth) in the
points chase.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner and Earnhardt finished fourth and fifth, respectively,
in the Brickyard 400 at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway last
weekend. And Skinner posted a fifth-place result at the New
Hampshire International Speedway on July 12.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's race was the seventh for Skinner and respected crew
chief Larry McReynolds, who left Earnhardt's team and swapped
places with Kevin Hamlin in mid-June in an effort to rejuvenate
both underachieving teams.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, who made his last pit stop on lap 51 of 90, said
McReynolds instructed him to conserve fuel in the waning stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably had enough gas left to win the race, but I didn't
know it,'' said Skinner, the 1997 Cup rookie of the year and driver
of the No. 31 Lowe's Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``I couldn't see inside
that gas tank. We've had some great strategy, and we've kept the
fenders on the cars. That's how we've got three top-fives in the
last four races.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt also was playing the fuel-mileage game to gain
critical track position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving the right way. We were just out of the top 10,''
said Earnhardt, driver of the No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus
Chevy. ``Congratulations to Larry McReynolds and Mike Skinner and
that RCR team. They were on the same strategy we did _ and they
pulled it off.'' NUTS AND BOLTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Gordon is the only driver to lead at least one lap in 16
of the 20 races this season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Martin has been running at the finish of the past 36
races.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dale Jarrett, who finished fifth, scored his second top-five
finish at The Glen, but remains winless in 12 races here. It was
his eighth top-10 finish in the last 10 races.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeremy Mayfield, considered among Gordon's championship
threats at midseason, has posted five consecutive finishes of 18th
or worse since his first career victory at Pocono Raceway on June
21. He finished 31st here.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kyle Petty, who finished sixth in the No. 44 Mattel Hot Wheels
Pontiac Grand Prix, made the best points move of the race by
climbing from 31st to 27th.
</P>
<P>
   _ Petty, Sterling Marlin (seventh, second time) and rookie Jerry
Nadeau (15th) joined Skinner in posting season-best finishes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ricky Craven has finished 29th, 41st, 17th and 35th since
qualifying on the pole in his return to the series at New Hampshire
International Speedway on July 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
