<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martinez overtakes Marichal as winningest Latin American
pitcher; Braves win 7-5
 &HT;    By Tom Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Working on the mound that Juan Marichal once
called home, Dennis Martinez, replaced the Giants great in baseball
history Sunday night. He won No. 244.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez worked a scoreless eighth inning and was the pitcher of
record when Chipper Jones' two-out, two-run single broke a tie in
the ninth and gave the Braves a 7-5 victory, making the 43-year-old
Nicaraguan the winningest Latin American pitcher of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Andres Galarraga both hit two-run homers as the Braves
swept the Giants. Atlanta hit 11 homers in the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, Gerald Williams legged out a swinging bunt, which
Ozzie Guillen followed with a double, his third in two games. After
Tony Graffanino struck out, Chipper Jones, who hit a two-run homer
in the first, drove a 2-2 pitch into center to score both runners.
</P>
<P>
   Starter John Smoltz struck out nine while allowing six hits and
took a 5-4 lead into the seventh but did not figure into the
decision. The Giants put two men on with Barry Bonds, who had
already homered twice, coming to the plate. John Rocker walked
Bonds on a full count to load the bases for Jeff Kent and, with
Rudy Seanez replacing Rocker, Kent lifted a sacrifice fly to right,
tying the score 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   Seanez was charged with his first blown save as a Brave. The
five earned runs charged to Smoltz were the most he has given up in
eight starts. He had yielded five runs in his last four games
combined.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, who had homered in the seventh for a short-lived Braves
lead, spoiled a second chance to play hero when he came up with the
bases loaded in the eighth. But Julian Tavarez induced a fielder's
choice to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker put the Braves ahead 5-4 when he led off the seventh with
his 12th homer of the year, tucking the ball just inside the
right-field foul pole. Tucker had not homered since June 27 but the
Giants could hardly be surprised. Five of his 12 home runs have
come against San Francisco pitching and his career average versus
the Giants was .647 entering the game.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz got into trouble in the third after retiring the first
two men he faced. He allowed a single to Stan Javier, then walked
Ellis Burks, who opened the night with a career .400 average
against Smoltz. That brought up Bonds, who drove the first pitch
far over the right-field fence for his 23rd of the year to tie it
4-4.
</P>
<P>
   This was Bonds' first multi-homer game of the season but the
32nd of his career. The two homers gave him 397 in his career,
leaving Bonds three short of becoming baseball's first 400-400
player (home runs-stolen bases). He already has 417 steals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
